<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PAPER TRAIL TO LOCAL GUN DEALERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The punk on the phone is laughing as he tells me he's only 17
but still was able to buy a sweet semiautomatic pistol through one
of the most accessible gun brokers in town &UR; _ The Arizona Republic.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's funny, man, is that on one page of the paper they got
your whiny (expletive) &UR; anti-gun column and a few pages back there's
classifieds where I can get anything I need,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got one a few weeks ago. Called up a dude and went to his
house and paid my money. He didn't ask me how old I was and I
didn't say and everything was cool. So, &UR; you're one of those guys
who talks but then, you know, makes money off guys like me. That
makes you . . . what?''
</P>
<P>
   A hypocrite.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' he said, hanging up just as I was about to tell him he
was a foul-mouthed sonnyboy with no understanding of free
enterprise, no knowledge of journalism, no manners, and only one
little thing going for him:
</P>
<P>
   He's right.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The same day Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were massacring
classmates at a Littleton, Colo., high school, weapons ranging from
9mm pistols to antique Lugers to Winchester rifles were available
for purchase _ without restriction _ through the Republic's
classifieds.
</P>
<P>
   It happens every day.
</P>
<P>
   Would-be Rambos can buy firearms through the East Valley's
Tribune, through Tucson's Arizona Daily Star, through just about
every newspaper or classified publication in the state. &UR; Not to
mention Web sites, gun magazines and gun shows.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy, anonymous and hair-trigger quick.
</P>
<P>
   There's no background check required in person-to-person sales,
as there is for someone walking into a gun shop. It's a deal with
no questions asked, except maybe, ``Cash or check?''
</P>
<P>
   The Arizona law defining who can buy a weapon and who can't
includes a passage reading, ``This section does not apply to
private firearm sales or transfers which are not subject to any
federal law or any other law of this state.''
</P>
<P>
   In this state, any Tom, Dick or Harry can sell a weapon to any
Eric Harris or Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   (Technically, it's against the law to sell weapons to minors
without the written consent of a parent or legal guardian. But as
the smart-mouth on the phone told me, if nobody asks . . .)
</P>
<P>
   This loophole was brought to you by the Arizona Legislature, the
same caring, thoughtful people who _ on the day of the Littleton
killings _ passed a law that would have prohibited Arizona cities
from enacting gun control ordinances.
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Jane Hull vetoed it. For now.
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, newspapers throughout the state happily take the money
of small-time gunrunners, then squawk on their editorial pages
about the proliferation of violence.
</P>
<P>
   Republic advertising director David Alley told me, ``What we try
to do is to allow the law to be our guide. Our motive there is that
it's a lot cleaner. If it's legal, then we'll do it. If it isn't,
we won't.''
</P>
<P>
   Most other publications in Arizona seem to agree, happily
serving as a middleman in the gun business at a time when kids are
killing kids and two local cops have been shot down in a month.
</P>
<P>
   Some papers turn down ads for cigarettes, topless bars and other
things they find objectionable. Why not guns? At least when it
comes to personal sales.
</P>
<P>
   Pawnshops and retailers are different. At least they need to do
background checks. It's not much. But it's something.
</P>
<P>
   After a bloodbath like the one in Colorado, newspaper writers
want to explain what happened.
</P>
<P>
   We point the finger at TV and movies and video games. We blame a
lack of parental supervision and the absence of school discipline.
We try to pin it on music videos or the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end, the punk on the phone was right. Until we take a
long hard look at our own industry's participation in the gun
trade, we've got no business shooting off our mouths. &QL; 
E.J. Montini can be reached at (602) 444-8978 or at
ed.montini &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
