<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by New York Times News Service clients) 
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The following Arizona Republic story has been added for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Sunday, April 25. If you
have any questions, please contact the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
SHERIFF (Phoenix, Ariz.) _ It was a sculpture when it was outside
the artist's home. But when the metal spider was plopped outside
Maricopa County Sheriff Joe Arpaio's front door Saturday, it turned
into a possible bomb and needed to be blown apart. ``It's not a
bomb, but it's still a threat, and I'm getting tired of these
threats,'' an angry Arpaio said. By RICHARD RUELAS. Story will move
in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
LITTLETON (Littleton, Colo.) _ Rusty Schlyer cannot sleep. Every
time he closes his eyes, the image comes back. He is alone in the
main hall of Columbine High School. In slow motion, a boy wearing a
black trench coat and a black mask rounds a corner. He has a rifle
on his hip. Then the rifle coughs. ``That's when I always wake
up,'' said Schlyer, 16, who dodged the shots by leaping behind a
pillar. By BILL
</P>
<P>
   MULLER. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   JONESBORO (Jonesboro, Ark.) _ March 24 came and went in this
still shellshocked town of 50,000, and folks sighed with some
relief. They had survived the first anniversary of what had been
the nation's deadliest school massacre. Then the Littleton, Colo.,
shootings came last week and set back the fragile healing, sending
shock waves through this pretty little section of northeast
Arkansas. By STEVE YOZWIAK. Story will move in the ``A'' category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
