<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 01:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2310 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN     04-25 0675
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON TO TEAM: DON'T TRY TOO HARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson called a
team meeting prior to Saturday's game against St. Louis to tell the
players to relax and not try to do too much.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The Dodgers entered the game against the Cardinals
hitting .190 with runners in scoring position. The Dodgers lost
three of their first four games on the six-game homestand and were
9 of 43 (.209) with eight RBI with runners in scoring position.
</P>
<P>
   ``The battle isn't getting a hit, it's getting a good pitch,''
Dodgers hitting coach Rick Down said. ``You can't get yourself out.
You have to be patient and swing at a pitch you can hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Johnson: ``The pitchers are trying to be too fine, the
hitters are trying to shoulder too much of the burden. I'm learning
about the makeup of the team, but everyone in the lineup wants to
do it. Sometimes you can put too much on yourself. Then, it's not
much fun.''
</P>
<P>
   Osuna update: Right-handed reliever Antonio Osuna arrived at
Dodger Stadium and said he was experiencing no pain in his elbow.
He'll start a rehab assignment today at Single-A San Bernardino.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers aren't all that happy about Osuna's decision to put
off surgery to remove a bone spur in his right elbow.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it would have been my choice, in my opinion, I would have
it done and he'd be back in six to eight weeks,'' Dodgers general
manager Kevin Malone said. ``All we can do is recommend what to do.
I wish he would have told us before he changed his mind (about
having surgery). If he does (wind up needing surgery) we probably
backed (his return) up two weeks, but you have to give the player
the option.''
</P>
<P>
   Before Osuna returns (he's eligible May 3) you can bet the
Dodgers will make sure he's thrown and thrown and thrown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to increase the work load for him and see how he
holds up,'' Malone said.
</P>
<P>
   Souvenir trade: Michael Lerner of Simi Valley, who caught the
second grand-slam home run ball by St. Louis' Fernando Tatis in the
third inning Friday, met the third baseman after the game and
traded the ball for a signed game-worn jersey.
</P>
<P>
   According to Lerner, Dodger Stadium officials ushered him out of
the left-field pavilion as fans mobbed him with monetary offers. He
was escorted to meet Tatis, telling the Cardinals slugger he
``wanted the ball to go to the Hall of Fame where it belongs,''
Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   Tatis took off his No.23 jersey and gave it to Lerner, who said
it would be on display at Lenny Dykstra's Car Wash in Simi Valley
beginning Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Lerner almost didn't make it to the game. He discovered he
accidentally brought tickets for Sunday's game and considered
driving home, but didn't want to deal with the traffic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running around the parking lot and this guy sold me
these tickets,'' Lerner said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the jersey,Tatis autographed a half-dozen
baseballs for Lerner and his three children. In the end, the balls
may be his only memento from the experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The next stop after the car wash will be Cooperstown,'' Lerner
said. ``I will gladly give it up if they ever call me and want to
put it in the Hall of Fame.''
</P>
<P>
   Balks, walks and chalk: Free agent right-hander Mike Maddux was
at Dodger Stadium for the second day in a row and is hopeful the
Dodgers will offer him a contract. ``I get a good feeling. If I
didn't have a good feeling, I have two kids at home who enjoyed
having daddy around last week,'' said Maddux, a former Dodger who
was released by Montreal 11 days ago.... For the sixth straight
game in which a left-hander started against the Dodgers, Paul
LoDuca started behind the plate. The switch-hitting Todd Hundley
hasn't started against a lefty-hander since facing Randy Johnson
opening day.... Shortstop Mark Grudzielanek was in the starting
lineup for the first time in four games.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Alissa Caciola contributed to this report.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
