<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 01:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2317 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LITTLETON-AZR &LR;      04-25 1465
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LITTLETON-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME MAY NOT HEAL ALL WOUNDS IN LITTLETON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BILL MULLER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Rusty Schlyer cannot sleep. Every time he
closes his eyes, the image comes back.
</P>
<P>
   He is alone in the main hall of Columbine High School. In slow
motion, a boy wearing a black trench coat and a black mask rounds a
corner. He has a rifle on his hip. He looks at Schlyer. ``Through''
him.
</P>
<P>
   Then the rifle coughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's when I always wake up,'' said Schlyer, 16, who dodged
the shots by leaping behind a pillar. ``I've had about one solid
hour of sleep in the last three days.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been less than a week since two heavily armed students
burst into the school with guns and bombs, killing 13 and wounding
23 before they took their own lives.
</P>
<P>
   For the survivors, the healing could take a lifetime.
</P>
<P>
   Sorrow and grief are pouring in from all over the world, from
President Clinton to the pope. Money is being raised, blood donated
for the wounded. Armies of counselors have descended.
</P>
<P>
   But mainly it will take the power of time to soothe the
wrenching pain. The tragedy has ripped ragged holes in people's
everyday lives. There are also smaller tears, little things that
mean a lot.
</P>
<P>
   For one family, it's a guitar that may never be played again.
For another, it's the red Acura with the dented door, which must be
driven home from the parking lot by someone else, since the young
girl who owned it is among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The school play has no star, the girls' basketball team no
coach, the volleyball team no captain. The football team has lost
No. 80, whose jersey was placed among the flowers and notes that
littered the ground near the scene of the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will never be 100 percent,'' said Jerry Parmer, a local
crisis counselor. ``There is a certain element in Dallas that has
not recovered from the Kennedy assassination. Littleton is always
going to be the city where they killed 15 people in a school.''
</P>
<P>
   They'll be reminded at anniversary time. Or by another school
shooting in some other innocent town.
</P>
<P>
   Littleton is an Anywhere, USA, in the shadow of the Rocky
Mountains, dominated by bike trails, housing tracts, strip malls
and office parks.
</P>
<P>
   The gunmen's dark trappings _ swastikas, the ``Goth'' scene and
electronic blood sports _ seem out of place in the affluent
community nestled against rolling foothills and built on old
farmland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to take some time to sink in for a lot of
people,'' said Doug Holden, a local attorney and spokesman for
Foothills Bible Church. ``It's hard to believe that something like
this can happen here in this community. This is something that will
never go away.''
</P>
<P>
   Some say one way to start the healing process is to bulldoze the
school and start over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them to knock down the school,'' Schlyer said. ``If
they don't . . . I can't go back in there. I want them to knock
down the school and build a memorial right on top of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another student, 16-year-old Ben Oakley, wants exactly the
opposite.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go back as soon as possible,'' he said. ``I want
them to clean up all the blood, but I want to see the damage. I
want to see the holes in the walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know. It's something I really want to face. It's
something I really need to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Reminders of the shooting are everywhere. Blue and silver
ribbons _ the colors of Columbine High. Black umbrellas. Closed
schools. Canceled sporting events. A crush of TV satellite trucks
and other media at a corner near the school.
</P>
<P>
   And there are more sinister reminders.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley said he was in nearby Southwest Village mall Wednesday
night when a teen in a black trench coat looked at him _ and
laughed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was wearing my soccer shirt, he knew I was in sports,'' he
said. ``I just couldn't believe it.''
</P>
<P>
   The school assailants, known as the ``Trench Coat Mafia'' for
the black trench coats worn by them and their friends, targeted
athletes especially. Oakley is on the Columbine varsity soccer
team.
</P>
<P>
   In dealing with his grief, Oakley has clung to his friends. He's
only been home long enough to tell his parents he's OK.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Parents) don't know what we feel,'' he said. ``They didn't go
through it.''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hohn, a 17-year-old student, said she was doing fine, but
her calm ``pops in and out.''
</P>
<P>
   She saw a picture of a slain friend on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was something I did not need to see,'' Hohn said. ``I
just totally broke down and started crying. He had a chance, and
they took that chance away.''
</P>
<P>
   Hohn said they should gut the school, replace the carpeting, the
lockers, everything. She believes the library, where much of
carnage occurred, should be razed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think any kid is going to be able to set foot in
there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Another student, Kenny Castro, looked almost dazed as he
discussed the death of his best friend, Matt Kechter, a football
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``It makes you wonder,'' Castro said. ``He wasn't doing anything
to anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Castro said he's angry at the gunmen, Eric Harris and Dylan
Klebold, and part of him wants revenge. But he would never carry it
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you do that, it would mean that they would have won,''
Castro said, adding that the shooting will bring the school, and
its sports teams, together as they never thought possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to keep saying it,'' he said, wearily repeating the
school's sports chant. ``We are Columbine. We are Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   As a late spring snowstorm blanketed Littleton, students and
parents braved the weather to return to the site of the massacre,
to lay flowers, teddy bears and posters on growing makeshift
memorials to 12 dead students and one dead teacher.
</P>
<P>
   Tents were erected to protect the memorials from the steadily
falling snow. ``In The Arms of Angels,'' one sign read. Nearby were
13 small crosses, 9 blue and 4 pink, representing the nine males
and four females killed.
</P>
<P>
   Dianne Oliver and her church members made blue and silver
ribbons and a 20-foot poster signed by the congregation. When they
brought the poster to the site, it was snowing, so they needed a
plastic cover.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went to Kinko's, and it should have cost $40,'' she said.
``They wouldn't let us pay for it.''
</P>
<P>
   The pilgrimage has deeper meaning to counselors, who say it's a
healthy part of grieving. People must band together, talk about the
tragedy, and work their way through it.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting the site means ``that it happened,'' Parmer said. ``It
is not a bad dream. It is happening.''
</P>
<P>
   Just like a person, a community goes through the stages of
grief: denial, acceptance, anger and resolution. In the days after
the shooting, many are just in denial.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to believe that things like this can happen,''
he said. ``This is outside our reality. Most kids live in worlds of
their own, and that world has been shattered.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people ask counselors the same thing: ``Why did it happen
here? Why did it happen anywhere?''
</P>
<P>
   The best thing they can do, Parmer says, is to talk about what
happened. And stick together.
</P>
<P>
   While district officials repair the school, plans are for the
Columbine students to return to school Thursday at nearby Chatfield
High School, which will house Chatfield students in the morning and
Columbine students in the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County School District officials said they have no
intention of tearing down the school, though it might take some
time to repair it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I met with eight or nine hundred of the students last night,
and they said, `Do not let them take Columbine from us,' ''
Columbine Principal Frank DeAngelis said.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis goes beyond the students and their parents. The whole
community is recoiling.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people are very upset about it,'' said Rochelle
Brunsdon, a Jefferson Center for Mental Health counselor. ``The
first thing we want to do is normalize these feelings. To tell
them, in general, strong feelings are a normal response to strong
situations.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the first task of counselors is to help people regain
control of their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first question to ask is `What do I need to do myself
right now? What will make me feel better?' ''
</P>
<P>
   That helps in the short term, Brunsdon said, but only the
passing of the seasons will help in the long term.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be changes forever. How can a place that lived in a
sense of safety and security . . . ever regain that sense of
permanent security?''
</P>
<P>
   Penny Hohn has an idea. It starts with students going back to
school.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let us go in and put new memories in there,'' she said, ``and
cover up the bad ones.'' &QL; 
Bill Muller can be reached at (602) 444-8178 or bill.muller &LR; pni.com
via email. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
