<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GEN-VOLLEYBALL-USC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
USC BEATS PEPPERDINE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MALIBU, Calif. _ Trevor Julian likes Provo, Utah. Honest.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot to do there,'' the Harvard-Westlake High
graduate and USC volleyball player said seriously. ``We can go see
the Mormon Tabernacle.''
</P>
<P>
   The best reason to love Provo is because that's where the
Trojans are heading after beating George Roumain-less Pepperdine
15-7, 11-15, 15-9, 15-6 Saturday in a Mountain Pacific Sports
Federation first-round playoff match at Firestone Fieldhouse.
</P>
<P>
   The MPSF tournament continues Thursday at the site of the
highest remaining seed, which is Brigham Young University.
</P>
<P>
   Roumain, the reigning national Player of the Year, sprained his
ankle in practice last week and watched as the Waves beat Loyola
Marymount to secure a home playoff match.
</P>
<P>
   But Roumain, sitting on the bench, was unable to cheer the Waves
back this time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're definitely a different team,'' Julian said. ``They
don't have their go-to guy. They need that big go-to guy. Our game
plan was to let Roumain get his kills and shut down the other
guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The difference was evident. With Roumain, Pepperdine swept USC
in three games March 2. Without Roumain, the Waves were outhit by
USC 88-67.
</P>
<P>
   The Trojans (16-10) have plenty about which to celebrate. Brook
Billings led everyone with 36 kills and then received a large
wrapped box afterward that was his birthday gift.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, USC coach Pat Powers was gushing about Billings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We put a saddle on Brook and rode him,'' Powers said. ``He's
got saddle sores.''
</P>
<P>
   Julian and Eli Fairfield got 14 kills apiece, and they ran
around hugging everyone in sight. Not a good idea, Fairfield said
afterward, because he and Julian have head colds and sore throats.
</P>
<P>
   ``You forget about it once you're out there,'' Fairfield said.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, they get another chance to play healthy. The Trojans,
who hadn't made the playoffs in four years, move on to Thursday's
semifinal against Long Beach State, which has defeated the Trojans
all three times they have faced this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been defeating ourselves,'' Powers said. ``We played
our last five matches on the road (actually seven counting
Saturday), and we won four out of five.''
</P>
<P>
   Pono Kahale, playing in Roumain's place, led with 20 kills,
followed by Pierce College graduate Keith Barnett with 16 kills and
Scott Wong with 15 kills.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got down in this game and didn't have George to bring us
back,'' Kahale said.
</P>
</TEXT>
