<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2319 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JONESBORO-AZR &LR;      04-25 1396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JONESBORO-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACRE DISRUPTS MENDING IN JONESBORO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE YOZWIAK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   JONESBORO, Ark. _ March 24 came and went in this still
shellshocked town of 50,000, and folks sighed with some relief.
</P>
<P>
   They had survived the first anniversary of what had been the
nation's deadliest school massacre, when two boys with high-powered
rifles murdered five and wounded 10 at the local middle school.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Littleton, Colo., shootings came last week and set back
the fragile healing, sending shock waves through this pretty little
section of northeast Arkansas where folks pepper their talk with
quotes from the Bible.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Lord is dragging his feet about getting down here and
fixing it,'' said Cookie Kinman, a waitress at a local waffle house
where the motto is ``People make the difference.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just awful. People are pretty tore up all over again.''
</P>
<P>
   The Littleton killings resurrected Jonesboro's ongoing mystery:
How could something so bad happen in a place so good?
</P>
<P>
   The killers in Littleton killed themselves, leaving no
opportunity to question them.
</P>
<P>
   Here in Jonesboro, the killers _ Andrew Golden, then 11, and
Mitchell Johnson, then 13 _ were so young, so emotionally and
mentally immature, that they still have not answered why they did
it.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, now 12 and 14, will remain in an Arkansas youth prison
until they are at least 18, when they will be eligible for release.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Golden has been described as a troublemaker. Folks say
Johnson is a choir boy who may have been upset over the breakup
with a girlfriend or angry with a teacher.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no end for us. There is no closure at all,'' said
Gretchen Woodard, Johnson's mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the pain, all the tragedy, all the heartache just comes
again in waves,'' said Woodard, who visits her son every chance she
is allowed: two hours every second and fourth Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ``My son can't tell you why. It's his burden for the rest of
his life. The (March 24) anniversary devastated him. No one
understands the guilt that Mitchell deals with.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodard is still raising Mitchell's brother, Monte Johnson, 12,
and stepsister, Jessie Woodard, 3. She is married to a
heavy-equipment operator.
</P>
<P>
   The family still lives in the same double-wide mobile home and
keeps the same phone number as before the shootings. They have not
been hit with threatening mail or phone calls.
</P>
<P>
   The media are ``a double-edged sword'' to Gretchen Woodard. The
notoriety left her deluged with thousands of well-wishing letters
from around the world. At the same time, she winces every time she
sees some commentator ascribe a new theory to her son's crimes.
</P>
<P>
   In the wake of the Jonesboro shootings, the Arkansas Legislature
lowered the age at which a child can be prosecuted as an adult to
10, from 18.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, a 10-year-old child can spend his life in prison. Are we
going to give up on our children after age 10? That breaks my
heart,'' Gretchen Woodard said.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Golden, who pleaded innocent, was silent at his
sentencing, and has not publicly commented about the killings.
Mitchell Johnson pleaded guilty and said he was sorry for what he
did.
</P>
<P>
   Many Jonesboro residents remain bitter and confused over the
pair's failure to explain themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Ruby McCluskey, whose daughter, 14-year-old Crystal Barnes, was
among those wounded in the Jonesboro shootings, cried in front of
her television Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The girl, who last year was shot in the back and leg and
confined to a wheelchair, refused to watch as events unfolded in
Littleton. After an hour, McCluskey switched it off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm angry that it happened again,'' McCluskey said. ``I don't
know why they're doing this; that when they get mad, they go out
and shoot somebody. I don't understand it.''
</P>
<P>
   During the summer, Crystal Barnes worked hard to rehabilitate
her broken body. By the time school started in the fall, she was
out of her wheelchair and even off her crutches.
</P>
<P>
   McCluskey, who works at a local uniform company, said she talks
with her children every day.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't talk to your kids on a day-to-day basis, if they
aren't comfortable talking to you about normal things, they aren't
going to come to you with their problems.''
</P>
<P>
   Off U.S. 63, on a shady lane past groves of pines, churches,
cemeteries and the ``fancy pigeon'' farm, news reporters are
greeted at the Westside School with a warning sign, threatening
them with prosecution and directing them to the office.
</P>
<P>
   Bullet holes are no longer visible. A fence now separates the
school from the woods where the boys fired their rifles.
</P>
<P>
   A memorial garden, pavilion and amphitheater will be completed
this fall. Inscribed will be the names of the dead students _
Brittney Varner, Natalie Brooks, Stephanie Dawn Johnson, Paige Ann
Herring _ and the teacher, Shannon Wright, who shielded other
students from being shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a setback for all of us,'' said Dick Young, the
no-nonsense superintendent of the Westside Consolidated School
District.
</P>
<P>
   Young rejects how school shootings in recent years have been
characterized.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not `school violence,' but the violence of our
communities coming into our schools.'' If society fails to deal
with violence, crime in the schools ``will occur over and over and
over again,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Like others here, Tim Morgan, pastor of the First Free Will
Baptist Church, is struggling to find meaning in the killings.
Quoting the Bible, he said, ``All things work together for good to
those who love God.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is the good?
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Hubert Brodell, a 70-year-old former insurance salesman
who has led the Jonesboro community for 12 years, said his town of
50,000 people is closer than ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we had the healing ceremony (two weeks after last year's
shootings), it was one of the best things that ever happened to
us.''
</P>
<P>
   Two ministerial alliances merged into one. Security and
counseling were increased at the schools. More police patrol the
neighborhoods. Crisis intervention teams were formed for other
emergencies in a town that lies along ``Tornado Alley.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Our town has handled it exceptionally well,'' said Brodell,
who keeps a photo of himself and President Clinton, sports a tie
with donkeys and gold stars and posts a sign on his door that says
``Please come in.''
</P>
<P>
   Brodell remains mystified how Andrew Golden, whom he had known
since the boy was knee-high, could pull a trigger on other
children.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor stopped for a cup of coffee early Wednesday with the
boy's grandfather, Doug Golden. But the two old friends don't talk
about the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't discuss it. It's hard enough for everybody,'' Brodell
said.
</P>
<P>
   Thursday night, Jonesboro hosted a nationally televised
town-hall meeting for ``Nightline.'' Emotions ran high during the
two-hour show, which drew more than 300 people, including Gretchen
Woodard.
</P>
<P>
   Despite prompting from host Ted Koppel, she declined to
apologize to Mitchell Wright, widower of murdered teacher Shannon
Wright, for her son's actions. Ballistics tests showed the teacher
was killed by Woodard's son.
</P>
<P>
   Woodard said that it was not her intention to cause anyone any
pain but that she had already repeatedly apologized to the
community at large.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last week, life was getting back to normal,'' said Wright, who
this month married a local TV news anchor. The two met during news
interviews following last year's shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``This week, we got a reality check. There are people who think
I shouldn't have gotten married again. But God brought us
together.''
</P>
<P>
   Superintendent Young, who remained silent during the program,
said as he left the church that he was disappointed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It stirred up emotions that were becoming lightened. We'll
have to deal with that tomorrow. But they (ABC-TV) made their
money,'' Young said.
</P>
<P>
   Even before the program, Mark Stebnicki, professor of psychology
at Jonesboro's Arkansas State University, said his community had
been ``re-traumatized'' by the Littleton shootings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our community will never be the same. We can't make Littleton
or Jonesboro go away,'' Stebnicki said. ``But what people do is
learn how to adapt and cope.'' &QL; 
Steve Yozwiak can be reached at (602) 444-8810 or at
steve.yozwiak &LR; pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
