r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN     04-25 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-SPURS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS STORM PAST FADING LAKERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Not that anyone needed another indicator of how
far the Los Angeles Lakers have fallen, but the San Antonio Spurs
happily provided an up-to-date perspective Saturday on The Decline
of '99.
</P>
<P>
   It's this simple: No Lakers team with Shaquille O'Neal in the
lineup had ever lost to the Spurs, home or away, in good times or
bad, in sickness or in health, since O'Neal donned the purple and
gold. Never.
</P>
<P>
   Until Saturday. And oh, did the Spurs make up for lost time and
lost games.
</P>
<P>
   It was a dominating performance, netting a lopsided result, the
Spurs embarrassing the visitors 108-81 in front of a raucous 31,972
at the Alamodome. San Antonio got 21 points from Tim Duncan, 16
from the usually dormant David Robinson and 36 points from the
bench to expose all the reasons why these teams are moving rapidly
in opposite directions.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs won for the 25th time in their past 29 games. The
Lakers lost their fifth in the past seven games and fell to 12-12
since the Eddie Jones-Glen Rice trade that reshaped the team at
midseason.
</P>
<P>
   The contrast was startling.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's an indication that they're playing very good
basketball and we're still in a learning process with this
ballclub,'' coach Kurt Rambis said of the 27-point loss, which tied
for worst of the season (see Trail Blazers, Portland, April 13).
``We were doing a few good things the last couple ballgames. We
took a step back today.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe more than a step. The Lakers surrendered 69.2 percent
shooting in the first half and fell into a 15-point halftime
deficit, and the defense never did arrive as the margin grew larger
in the final two quarters.
</P>
<P>
   It's in vogue now for the Lakers to cite their countless roster
moves this season as the source of their disarray. It's a valid
argument to a point, and they've decided to concentrate on simple
improvement, rather than wins and losses, over the waning days of
the season.
</P>
<P>
   But after a shellacking by a team they've owned for the better
part of two seasons, the excuses were pointless. They just owned up
to the obvious deficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was disappointed with our effort,'' Rambis said. ``They
outworked us tonight. We're not going to go anywhere or do anything
if we get outworked.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal, unaccustomed to losing in his hometown, gave his usual
26 points and 12 rebounds and even made 6 of 8 foul shots. But
after Glen Rice's 19 points, there was little support.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're the hottest team in the league right now, and they
just played with more urgency than we did, more determination,''
O'Neal said. ``Once again we had a lot of turnovers, they had a lot
of easy baskets. The first half they shot 70 percent. A team shoots
70 percent, you have to step it up on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it's difficult to defend against turnover-fueled
fast-break layups, of which there were many. The Lakers committed a
reasonable 13 turnovers, but they went for 14 points, and the Spurs
converted eight turnovers into 12 points in the first half.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers stuck around for only the first quarter, trailing
25-23 heading into the second period. They tied it at 25-all, but
never got that close again. With the Spurs leading 31-30, San
Antonio launched a 14-2 run that provided a permanent cushion and
played stifling defense the rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs wound up scoring 16 points above their average while
holding the Lakers to their fourth-lowest output of the season, and
18 points below their average.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, the Lakers were faced with the irritating question.
Are they really 27 points behind the Western Conference's elite, a
group of which they are supposed to be a part?
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't really use points for a barometer,'' Derek Fisher
said. ``The way that we play shows us how far, even if we lost by
one.''
</P>
<P>
   But the gap is clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think right now they're at the highest level of
confidence,'' Fisher said, ``and we're somewhere in the middle or
maybe the lowest. That has a big effect on the way you play when
you're out there on the floor.''
</P>
</TEXT>
