<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 01:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2322 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS     04-25 0647
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-CARDINALS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VALDES' OUTING BLISTERS CARDINALS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Team meetings in April are rare, but these are the
Los Angeles Dodgers and the expectations are enormous. And they've
been playing dreadful lately, culminating in Friday's loss to St.
Louis in which the Cardinals' Fernando Tatis hit two grand slams.
In the same inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't sleep too good,'' Dodgers manager Davey Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Suffice to say, Johnson should be refreshed today.
</P>
<P>
   His pep talk worked, at least for a day, as the Dodgers beat St.
Louis 6-1 Saturday in front of a soldout crowd of 53,964 at Dodger
Stadium. And they did it the way it was diagrammed on the
blackboard during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Ismael Valdes (2-0) allowed one run on six hits in
tossing the Dodgers' first complete game of the season. He struck
out 10 and walked two and got offensive support from Eric Karros
and Eric Young, who each hit first-inning homers.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers also got key hits from Gary Sheffield and Devon
White to pad their lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had good control and I was getting ahead of the hitters, in
and out,'' Valdes said. ``I was feeling pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   The only obstacle for Valdes may have been Johnson, who thought
about yanking him in the eighth inning because of a blister
problem. Valdes left his last start with a blister on the middle
finger of his pitching hand. This one was closer to his nail and
had little affect on his pitches.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the mound and I said, `Nice going,''' Johnson said.
``He pleaded with me, `No, let me finish.' The trainers, he must
have them in his pocket, because they said it was the normal thing
he got.''
</P>
<P>
   It was such a night for the Dodgers that catcher Paul LoDuca can
again sleep comfortably. After beginning the season without a hit
in 19 at-bats, he broke through with a seventh-inning single.
</P>
<P>
   The only downer for the Dodgers was third baseman Adrian
Beltre's failure to get a hit. His hitting streak stopped at 11
games.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals left-hander Donovan Osborne (0-2) was the losing
pitcher, giving up four runs in five innings. Tatis homered again,
his seventh, but it was a solo shot in the seventh inning and had
little bearing on the outcome.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think meetings are more therapeutic for the manager than
they are for the players,'' Johnson said before the game.
</P>
<P>
   The dividends were on display early, beginning with the fifth
pitch Young saw from Osborne. The second baseman, who went 3 for 4,
drilled his first homer of the season to give the Dodgers a 1-0
lead. It was the 10th time he's led off the first inning with a
homer.
</P>
<P>
   Sheffield then drew a one-out walk and Karros hit an 0-1 pitch
over the left field fence as the Dodgers went ahead 3-0. It was
Karros' fourth homer.
</P>
<P>
   Entering the game the Dodgers (9-9) had scored four runs in the
first inning all season. It was also the first time they scored
more than one run in the first inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``Valdes did a good job,'' Cardinals manager Tony La Russa said.
``He was sharp and he pitched up and in and out. He mixed it up
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Valdes retired the first seven Cardinals, allowed a
double to Joe McEwing and then didn't allow another hit until Ray
Lankford led off the sixth with a pinch-hit double.
</P>
<P>
   But Valdes wasn't bothered by it. He struck out Darren Bragg and
Edgar Renteria and retired Mark McGwire (0 for 3, walk) on a fly
ball to center.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first five innings he was painting inside, outside, and
throwing strikes on anything he wanted to,'' LoDuca said. ``He
painted McGwire on one. To be honest, he threw one bad pitch, and
that was the one Tatis hit out. It seemed like with two strikes we
could have called any pitch we wanted because he was throwing
strikes with everything.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
