<SLUG> BC-SOC-GALAXY-CLASH-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GALAXY HOLDS OFF CLASH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By FRED J. ROBLEDO  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PASADENA, Calif. _ It had been a long five-game season for the
Los Angeles Galaxy, punctuated by the dismissal of coach Octavio
Zambrano on Wednesday. But at last, the free-flowing Galaxy machine
that notched record after record last season made its 1999 debut
Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Newly hired UCLA coach Sigi Schmid asked assistant Ralph Perez
to handle the match against San Jose, opting to observe this one
from a Rose Bowl suite high above the field.
</P>
<P>
   After the Galaxy failed to get a shot on goal in the first half,
Schmid couldn't take it any longer. He made his sideline debut in
the second half and his presence was more than enough to spark Los
Angeles to a 1-0 victory over the Clash.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first regulation victory for the Galaxy this season
and ended its three-game losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   Galaxy president Tim Leiweke made the coaching change because he
said fans in Los Angeles deserved ``instant gratification and
results.''
</P>
<P>
   For a day at least, Los Angeles had both.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Caligiuri scored the game-winner in the 58th minute, ending
a 183-minute scoring drought for Los Angeles, which had only scored
three goals in its first five games.
</P>
<P>
   Midfield playmaker Mauricio Cienfuegos slipped a pass down the
right side for Caligiuri, who was finishing an overlapping run down
the flank. Caligiuri settled the ball softly in front, then
finished to the left side past San Jose goalkeeper David Kramer.
</P>
<P>
   Los Angeles had a chance to make it 2-0 in the 75th minute, but
Cienfuegos missed a penalty shot after Kramer guessed correctly to
his right.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the fact the Galaxy didn't manage a shot on goal in the
first half, it appeared more spirited from the opening whistle.
</P>
<P>
   The only changes Perez made to the starting lineup involved
moving midfielder Clint Mathis to the front line with Cobi Jones
and starting Ezra Hendrickson in place of struggling Daniel
Hernandez.
</P>
<P>
   In the 15th minute, Jones turned on Clash defender Mauricio
Wright, then dropped a beautiful pass in front of the net to
Caligiuri, but the former UCLA graduate couldn't direct his shot on
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Caligiuri showed his playmaking skills minutes later. Settling
outside the penalty box, he saw Greg Vanney sneaking behind San
Jose's defense toward the penalty spot. He rewarded Vanney with a
beautiful pass behind the defense, but Vanney missed an easy
opportunity 8 yards straightaway, spraying his shot to the right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
