<HEADER>
A2324 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OUT-TROUT-OPENER-LADN     04-25 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TROUT-OPENER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TROPHY TROUT EASE THE CHILL OF OPENING DAY IN EASTERN SIERRA
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(EDITORS: Brett Pauly is the Daily News Outdoors Editor. Daily News
staff   writer Jeremy Bagott contributed to this story.) 
By BRETT PAULY  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. _ It wasn't the prettiest thing, with
light snow and near freezing temperatures dampening some spirits
throughout much of the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a lot warmer in the car,'' Jeffrey Puerto, 8, said
Saturday as his father, Dan, targeted trout _ outside _ at Crowley
Lake. ``I'm waiting for the sun to come out.''
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey got his wish for only short periods during the first day
of trout fishing in the Eastern Sierra, as the sun broke through
mostly overcast skies and windblown snowflakes at the popular
fishing site north of Bishop.
</P>
<P>
   But a propensity of trophy trout seemed to erase any
cold-weather worries. No fewer than four trout topped the 7-pound,
10-ounce heaviest trout weighed in during the 1998 opener, and a
glut of rainbows and browns were caught in the 5- to 7-pound range.
The day's whopper was a 10.41-pound rainbow landed at Convict Lake
by L.A.'s Charles Hennessey, according to early reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best part of the day is all the good fishing,'' said Mike
Thompson of Riverside, as he dangled Power Bait beyond a stringer
of three 15-inch rainbows at Bridgeport Reservoir. ``The worst part
is a little bit of snow and the temperature. I like it when I get
up and it's 80, not 30.''
</P>
<P>
   The annual angling extravaganza attracts throngs of visitors,
long estimated at 30,000 to 40,000 or more, some 80 percent of whom
are thought to be from the Southland. It is a celebration of the
end of a six-month seasonal closure of trout fishing in creeks,
rivers and lakes from Independence in Inyo County north to
Bridgeport and throughout the remainder of Mono County.
</P>
<P>
   While fishing is the common thread between visitors and regional
anglers alike, it also serves as a springboard to camaraderie and
social gatherings, some of which have been put on hold since last
fishing season _ or even last year's Eastern Sierra trout opener,
always slated the final Saturday in April. It's about swapping
stories, family time, making new friendships and rekindling old
ones.
</P>
<P>
   Married 10 years, Deborah and Ron Paules of Simi Valley
northwest of Los Angeles have enjoyed the last six trout openers
together. They usually ice-fish with a group in the Mammoth Lakes
Basin, but some in the party canceled and the couple found
themselves casting bait at Upper Twin Lake.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like to fish, but I probably like sitting here reading a
book better,'' said Deborah Paules. ``It's like everybody else; you
think you are going to catch the big hungry one who has been
waiting all season to eat !ital!my!off! Power Bait.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part is, we haven't got a fish yet.''
</P>
<P>
   At least they don't get their fishing tackle mixed up.
</P>
<P>
   Nearby a family was still chatting about a fishing pole that was
lost hours earlier when an overzealous trout took off with the
hook, line and sinker; the outfit was caught a short time later by
another angler ... with the offending trout still hooked.
</P>
<P>
   The weather was mild in mostly windless but cloudy Bishop and
the Owens Valley, with a high of 59, a low of 41 and scattered
rain. At higher elevations, including Crowley Lake, Mammoth Lakes
and the Mono Basin, highs ranged from 36 to 45 and lows 16 to 23;
it snowed lightly for much of the day, with an inch sticking in
Mammoth Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   At Crowley, the most popular of all opening-day destinations,
fireworks were set off at 5:10 a.m. to signal the season's start,
replacing the traditional pre-dawn flare. The weather apparently
had little impact on safety issues, as the sheriff's offices of
Inyo and Mono counties reported no boating incidents or
fishing-related emergencies.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless of the weather and the slow early-morning fishing he
experienced at Grant Lake, Monte Rompal of North Hollywood said,
``I like it up here, just to get out of the Valley. It's the
atmosphere. It doesn't matter what size fish or how many you
catch.'
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
