<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-REDWINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DETROIT DEALS HAVE MADE THE DIFFERENCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ The Detroit Red Wings are certainly sitting
pretty with a 2-0 series lead over the Anaheim Mighty Ducks heading
into today's game at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   But the Wings weren't flying nearly so high until they acquired
Wendel Clark, Chris Chelios, Ulf Sammuelsson and Bill Ranford at
the NHL trading deadline. Detroit was 3-7-2 in the 12 games before
the blockbuster deals were made on March 23. The Red Wings had only
74 points at the 70-game mark _ the Ducks were one back with 73.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Nicklas Lidstrom said the deals were crucial if the
Red Wings were going to be legitimate contenders for a third
consecutive Stanley Cup title.
</P>
<P>
   ``We knew we weren't going anywhere if we kept playing like we
did in January and February,'' he said. ``I didn't think our team
was peaking like it had the last two years. (After the trades)
everybody was more excited again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those four guys came in and our team really got re-energized,
got our jump back. Everybody started playing better.''
</P>
<P>
   Detroit captain Steve Yzerman knew the team wasn't going well,
but he'd like to believe the Red Wings weren't a bunch of dead
Ducks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to think so,'' he said when asked if Detroit would
have been one of the favorites without making the deals. ``But the
trades have improved the team.''
</P>
<P>
   No question about that. The Red Wings won their first eight
games after the trading deadline passed and are now 11-2-1 since
the new players were added.
</P>
<P>
   Not so special: The Ducks' special teams carried them during the
regular season, so it figured special-teams play would be crucial
to any success Anaheim might have against Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   So far the Red Wings are winning the battle. Detroit is 4 of 15
on the power play, while the Ducks are 2 of 10 with the man
advantage, and one of Anaheim's goals was scored in garbage time of
Game 2. Meanwhile, Detroit was 3 of 6 in the first 30 minutes of
Friday night's game before finishing 3 of 9.
</P>
<P>
   Early signs: Today's opening period figures to be crucial once
again. In the first period of the first two games the Red Wings
have outshot the Ducks 35-16 and outscored them 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   No blame game: Ducks defenseman Kevin Haller wasn't about to
bad-mouth fellow defenseman Ruslan Salei, who was on the ice for
all five Detroit goals Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been in the same situation,'' said Haller. ``A couple
were just bad luck. You've just got to forget about it. He's a good
player. I'm not going to worry about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim coach Craig Hartsburg tried to take the diplomatic route
as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wasn't at his best, he made some mistakes that cost us,''
said Hartsburg. ``But he's young and you've got to coax him along.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's gotten better all year, but this is a new step.''
</P>
<P>
   Fighting mad: After watching the Ducks sit back and take Detroit
abuse for almost 2{ periods on Friday, Stu Grimson finally went out
of his way to stir something up with Chelios and then Darren
McCarty.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit coach Scotty Bowman thought the Ducks were trying to
send a message, but Hartsburg acted as if that wasn't the way to
send it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure if that's what we needed,'' he said. ``We just
need more guys to compete.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
