<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, RED SOX HAVE ENOUGH PUNCH 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There was the smell of blood in the air when Rheal
Cormier emerged from the Red Sox bullpen Saturday to face Cleveland
Indians strongman Jim Thome, whose ribs had been visited by a
Cormier fastball the night before. That pitch, thrown in
retaliation after Darren Lewis had been plunked by Jaret Wright,
touched off the second of two bench-clearing brawls between the
teams Friday night and resulted in the ejection of both players.
</P>
<P>
   Was another round of mayhem on deck?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the fans were (thinking that),'' Cormier said with a
smile after the Sox beat the Indians, 9-4, to end a three-game
losing streak. ``I was thinking, `Oh, God.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Unbeknownst to the Fenway Park crowd of 29,481, any hint of
hostilities already had ceased between Thome and Cormier, hours
before the lefthander retired Thome on a liner to shortstop Nomar
Garciaparra, then induced Wilfredo Cordero to tap into a force
play, ending the seventh inning and preserving what at the time was
a one-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   The night before, Cormier had given Thome a ride back to the
Indians' hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was walking out to my car,'' Cormier said, ``and (Thome) was
waiting for a cab. He came over to me and said, `No hard feelings,
it's part of the game.' So yeah, I gave him a ride back to his
hotel.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier had become hunting buddies with Thome a year ago in
spring training with the Indians, the first team to give him a
chance after he underwent tendon-transfer surgery on his left
elbow. Cormier, who pitched only once in 1997, never made it to the
big leagues with the Indians last season, as he hurt his left
shoulder overcompensating for his surgically repaired elbow.
</P>
<P>
   But on his second go-round with the Sox, who three years ago
traded Cormier to the Expos for Cordero, of all people, then
re-signed him this winter for a modest $500,000, Cormier so far has
exceeded expectations out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   On a day that starter Bret Saberhagen experienced a recurrence
of his own shoulder miseries, Cormier rescued the Red Sox in a game
in which they'd seized leads of 3-0 and 4-1 against Cleveland
starter Dave Burba, only to see rookie Tim Harikkala give it right
back after Saberhagen departed at the start of the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   A double by Jose Offerman and a two-out RBI single by
Garciaparra, one of 10 two-out hits that produced seven Boston
runs, had restored the Sox to the lead in the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   But Cormier's fellow lefty, reliever Mark Guthrie, allowed an
infield hit to Robbie Alomar and walked Manny Ramirez in the
seventh before manager Jimy Williams called for Cormier to face
Thome, who already had doubled and scored Cleveland's first run and
had singled home the tying run off Harikkala in the fifth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a situation where he's such a good hitter, and such a
tough out, because he stands right on the dish,'' Cormier said. ``I
threw him a fastball inside, and he hit it to Nomar, who was
playing in the right spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier, whose off-field glasses make him an unlikely-looking
combatant for the farm-grown Thome, grinned as he noted that he'd
thrown a fastball to Thome Friday night, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``This one wasn't as far inside,'' Cormier said. ``That one got
away from me. This one had a little better location. It didn't move
as much. I think I'll leave it at that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who sent more runners across the plate Saturday
than they have all season, weren't satisfied to leave their lead as
it was. They added three runs in the seventh, which began with a
home run by Mike Stanley and also featured an RBI double by Darren
Lewis and a run-scoring single by Offerman, and one more in the
eighth, when a sure-handed fan leaned over the center-field wall
and gathered in Troy O'Leary's sixth home run and third in five
games.
</P>
<P>
   Stanley, who also singled and scored in the first, broke an
0-for-22 slump. O'Leary's six home runs leave him second only to
Jose Canseco in the American League. He had 12 home runs by the end
of May last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a good team we're facing,'' said Saberhagen, who said a
knot in the back of his shoulder stiffened in  &UR; yesterday &LR; 's cool
wind, prompting him to pull himself out of the game three outs from
being eligible to be the winning pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``To score nine runs against them is a good feeling. Especially
after a tough one like  &UR; last night &LR; , and all the b.s. that went on,
to come out and swing the bats early.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
