<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-ANALYSIS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SCORING STARS NEED TO FIND WAY TO NET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The Bruins got their satisfactory split here,
heading home in a 1-1 series tie with the Hurricanes.
</P>
<P>
   But why doesn't that seem more troubling than satisfying?
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't depend on Tim Taylor's line and Ken Belanger, and
Byron Dafoe every night,'' said a shrugging Pat Burns, after his
club lost hold of a 2-1 lead in the third period and went on to
suffer a 3-2 loss in OT. ``Guys like (Jason) Allison and (Sergei)
Samsonov, we need those guys to score some goals for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Remember that two-line offense that was all the hubbub in the
Hub as the regular season ended? There were only traces of it here
in the first two games _ traces that could end up the root cause of
defeat unless some of the Boston shooters wake up and smell the
net.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, Rob DiMaio and Belanger were the unassuming scorers.
In Game 2, the names were more customary _ Samsonov and Steve
Heinze _ but the Boston attack that showed some serious bite down
the stretch showed up here with much of that bite missing.
</P>
<P>
   Allison has to play better, and his game showed some signs of
reviving in Game 2, but he is by no means alone. Wingers Dmitri
Khristich and Anson Carter have been non-factors. The Bruins need
Khristich cranking off his sizzling slapper. They need Carter
driving to the net, following up for rebounds. In 137 minutes 5
seconds here, those two key wingers barely could be found in the
Boston attack.
</P>
<P>
   The two biggest surprises in the first two games, from Boston's
perspective, were Belanger and Landon Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   Belanger was a brute force in the opener, a powerful forechecker
and hitter, and it earned him a spot at left wing on the opening
line Saturday &UR;  &LR; night. In the end, he received fewer minutes that he
did in Game 1, but that was, in part, because Burns was trying to
kickstart his more offensive-minded shooters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Eventually, skill comes out,'' Burns said after the morning
workout. ``It's your skilled players that win series.''
</P>
<P>
   Of all the Boston forwards, it was the 24-year-old Wilson who
looked the most comfortable in Game 2. He had presence. Shift to
shift, he finally was showing reason why the Bruins gave up a
first-round draft pick to bring him to Boston. Samsonov scored the
first goal, but it was a brilliant move by Wilson on the right
wing, pulling up on a dime to elude ex-Bruin Glen Wesley, and then
snapping off a hard wrister at Arturs Irbe, that set up Samsonov
for the gimme.
</P>
<P>
   Save for the always-dependable checking lines _ DiMaio with
Taylor and P.J. Axelsson, Wilson's performance was the most
outstanding thing in a Black-and-Gold uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He gets his nose dirty and plays playoff hockey,'' said Burns,
matter-of-factly, as if Wilson always rolls out that kind of game.
``That's why he's playing. I'm not going to put guys on the boards
who aren't doing anything.
</P>
<P>
   Sooner or later you've got to do something.''
</P>
<P>
   Runner-up on the standout list was DiMaio, who looks like the
little John Hancock building when standing next to the big John
Hancock building that is Keith Primeau. DiMaio almost looked happy
getting smacked by Primeau, because it gave him added license to
smack back. On one shift, the powerful Primeau trapped DiMaio near
the Carolina bench and kept him pinned unnecessarily against the
boards. DiMaio kicked and fussed, and then swatted at Primeau,
almost following him right on to the Carolina bench as the 'Canes
captain left the ice. As the series continues, that Mutt-and-Jeff
matchup should grow even more intense. Primeau is the big man on
campus and DiMaio keeps cutting holes in his varsity sweater.
</P>
<P>
   But the chore for Burns and his Bruins now is to get back the
touch of the first two lines, with Allison and Joe Thornton as the
pivots. The coach was rolling numbers to the end here, looking for
the right combination of wingers to package around his two big
centers and revive an offense that earlier this month looked
playoff primed and ready. Suddenly, the big shooters are popguns.
</P>
<P>
   It got slightly better as Game 2 progressed. The Bruins landed
only three shots in the first period, only Carter and P.J. Axelsson
hitting the net among the forwards. They managed a total 18 shots
over the rest of regulation _ less than a shot every two minutes _
and then landed three in OT. Khristich, a huge key to the offense,
didn't land a single shot in Game 2 and squeezed off only one in
Game 1. He only seemed to find his legs late in the third period,
with OT approaching.
</P>
<P>
   Two games gone and the Bruins are even in the series, playing
with an offense that is more wrong than right. That is both the bad
news and the good. Turn it around now and it's only a forgotten
footnote. Fail to get it going and it will be their signature to a
disappointing season.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
