</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-BRUINS-HURRICANES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAROLINA IS FINER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY L. MARRAPESE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ Their season series was even. Their play in
most of Game 1 was even. So it seems appropriate that the Bruins
and Carolina Hurricanes are dead even in their Eastern Conference
quarterfinal round as the games move to Boston.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sheppard was the difference Saturday night as he scored his
second goal of the game, beating Byron Dafoe at 17:05 of the first
sudden-death overtime period to lift the 'Canes to a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Steve Chiasson took the first shot and Dafoe made the
save. Then Martin Gelinas's shot rapped off the post and Sheppard
banged it home from the edge of the crease, sending the
disappointed Bruins home with a split.
</P>
<P>
   ``The D-man on the point took a shot and I made the save,'' said
Dafoe. ``I went to cover it and (Gelinas) chipped at it. It went
through and hit the post and then (Sheppard) got the rebound and
put it in the open net.''
</P>
<P>
   The good news is that Boston's stated goal was to win one game
on Carolina ice heading back to the FleetCenter. The bad news is
that they had a 2-1 lead midway through the third period but
couldn't keep a lid on it.
</P>
<P>
   ``They played us hard  &UR; tonight &LR; ,'' said coach Pat Burns. ``We
had them, 2-1, then we turned the puck over and it was 2-2 and we
got ourselves in a dilemma. We give them credit. Our guys tried
hard, we just couldn't find a way. No excuses, no blaming. We get
back home and it's our turn.''
</P>
<P>
   Early in the second, the Bruins broke through on their fourth
shot of the contest. Just before the Boston goal, the Hurricanes
had a great scoring chance when Primeau drilled a shot from the
left circle that bounced up in the air. Dafoe tried to bat it with
his stick but missed and the puck fell to the ice. With the
Hurricanes coming after it, defenseman Darren Van Impe cleared it
out of the zone and the Bruins took off.
</P>
<P>
   Right wing Landon Wilson, who played only four shifts for a
total of two minutes in the first period but was one of Boston's
best players the rest of the way, fired a shot from the left circle
as he was falling forward. Carolina goalie Arturs Irbe made the
stop but left wing Sergei Samsonov was there on the doorstep for
the rebound and Boston had a 1-0 lead at 2:56.
</P>
<P>
   That didn't seem to take any steam out of the persistent
Hurricanes' attack. In fact, Boston's advantage lasted less than
five and a half minutes when the Hurricanes put an end to Dafoe's
playoff shutout streak at 88:23.
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Paul Coffey, who didn't play in Game 1 because of a
strained hamstring, started the play and Gelinas took it from
there, backhanding a short relay over to Sheppard. Sheppard,
gunning down the right side of the slot, blasted the puck over the
glove of Dafoe at 8:24 to pull Carolina even, 1-1.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, the Hurricanes played most of the game with four
defensemen because Marek Malik (quadriceps contusion) and Nolan
Pratt (groin strain) were injured.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Heinze, who had been benched for more than 19 minutes of
the third period in Game 1 because Burns didn't think he was
getting enough from his second-line left winger, vowed to do
something about it.
</P>
<P>
   His goal at 8:32 of the third period gave Boston a 2-1 lead.
Heinze scored his first goal in eight postseason contests dating
back to the six-game series against the Washington Capitals when he
didn't register a point.
</P>
<P>
   Center Jason Allison dished a pass to right wing Anson Carter in
the slot. Carter fired a shot that trickled through Irbe's pads.
Heinze charged into the crease and rapped it into the net inside
the right post.
</P>
<P>
   At 14:28, the Hurricanes pulled even when Robert Kron scored.
Kron, who had been a healthy scratch for Game 1, filled in for
injured center Ron Francis, who sprained his ankle in Game 1.
Heinze said Kron's goal was his fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a short trip from being a hero to a goat in the
playoffs,'' said Heinze. ``I make a mistake on the boards, a
giveaway, and they come right back and tie it up, 2-2. (Kron)
tipped it. I lost my stick and couldn't get to his hands. He just
redirected the puck between (Dafoe's) legs.''
</P>
<P>
   In overtime, the 'Canes nearly scored on a fluke at the 1:55
mark when former Bruins' defenseman Glen Wesley, taking a page out
of Ray Bourque's book, gunned the puck at the net from center ice.
It nearly went through Dafoe's legs but he got to it in time.
</P>
<P>
   Rob DiMaio nearly won it at 5:48 when his shot ricocheted off
the right post. Then, Sheppard did win it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unfortunately,'' said Dafoe, ``we gave them life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
