<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-WOMEN'S </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOMEN'S WORLD CUP GETTING SERIOUS 
</HEADLINE>
 WORLD CUP-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Joy Fawcett remembers coming home from
China with her teammates eight years ago, World Cup trophy in hand,
and realizing that nobody but the federation, family, and friends
knew they had been over there.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was only one reporter at the airport when we got off the
plane,'' she says. ``I thought, `Did we really do this? And what
does it mean?' ''
</P>
<P>
   Nobody on the US women's soccer team is wondering this time.
More than 400,000 people will buy tickets to this summer's
quadrennial tournament in seven American cities, with an aggregate
billion worldwide likely to watch on TV and 1,200 media
representatives on hand. And this time, Fawcett &AMP; Co. are expected
not only to win but to ``leave a legacy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of the role model aspect involved and we
understand that,'' says keeper (and University of Massachusetts
grad) Briana Scurry. ``We'd be a bit naive not to believe that.''
</P>
<P>
   All the US women need do is glance at the tournament advertising
(``THIS IS MY GAME. THIS IS MY FUTURE. WATCH ME PLAY'') or the Nike
ads pushing female self-confidence and empowerment through sports
or listen to the mob of girls (and, increasingly, boys) screeching
for postmatch autographs to know what their role is. To not merely
win _ but inspire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes high expectations can undermine performance, but I'd
like to think that the expectations are realistic and obtainable,''
says coach Tony DiCicco, whose squad takes on top rival China again
Sunday at Giants Stadium in a tuneup. ``Everyone on the team has
bought into what we have to do. So we're taking all this as a
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   High expectations are flattering, but the Americans have come to
realize there is pressure that comes with them. It means they've
been noticed. When they beat the Chinese for the Olympic gold medal
before 76,000 spectators three years ago, NBC didn't televise the
match. This time, ABC will air both the US-Denmark opener here and
the final in the Rose Bowl and ESPN will show the other 30
tournament matches, all but five of them live.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Watch Me Play'' slogan comes with an unspoken subtext: And
See How Far I've Come. The women's game has evolved dramatically
since the inaugural Cup in 1991. It's faster, more skilled, more
physical, more tactical. And the Americans, who are 111-14-7 over
the past eight years and unbeaten in their last 50 at home, are the
world's dominant side.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we don't win,'' says Fawcett, ``you can see it in our
faces.''
</P>
<P>
   But the winning is only one part of their mission, and the
players accept that. If women's soccer is to keep growing here, if
a top-level professional league is to get off the ground, the US
squad also has to entertain, to play a bold and inventive and
stylish game that will fill seats and keep the sport on TV.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we step on the field,'' says Mia Hamm, ``we want to
put on a show.''
</P>
<P>
   So the nine-match ``Road to Pasadena'' exhibition series has a
barnstorming flavor to it, with the Americans turning up everywhere
from Orlando to Portland, Ore. During the Cup, they'll play in six
cities, including Foxborough. And they won't be performing in
small-college or municipal stadia but in Soldier Field, Jack Kent
Cooke Stadium, and the Meadowlands.
</P>
<P>
   The women's game has come to full flower in America, and the
stars _ Hamm, Michelle Akers, Kristine Lilly, captain Carla
Overbeck, Fawcett, and Scurry _ have marquee status.
</P>
<P>
   Longevity, admittedly, has much to do with that. The 33-year-old
Akers scored the US team's inaugural goal in 1985, and she still
starts in the midfield. Lilly holds the world record for caps
(172), and Hamm is only four goals short of setting a global mark
of 108.
</P>
<P>
   The Americans can put eight women on the field who have 100 or
more caps. No other country can do (or ever has done) that. Ten
players competed in the 1995 World Cup, and seven played in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to duplicate that experience,'' concedes DiCicco,
whose toughest decision is usually whom to leave on the bench.
</P>
<P>
   The US reserves probably could have qualified for the tournament
on their own. And except for their duels with the Chinese and
Norwegians (the defending Cup champions), the Americans' most
demanding tests usually come in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``We play us every day,'' says Scurry. ``You couldn't face a
more difficult team.''
</P>
<P>
   Scrimmages tend to be cutthroat, with the 100-cappers not just
having to fight to retain their spots _ but expecting to.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the best qualities about our veterans,'' says
DiCicco. ``They do expect to start, but they don't expect to be
given anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Hamm may have hundreds of thousands of age-groupers wearing her
jersey, but she knows that some fellow Carolina alumna will be
right at her ankles as soon as she touches the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to expect that someone's going to come at you with a
hard tackle,'' Hamm says. ``They won't let you have a free ball,
and that's the way it should be. We understand that it's not
personal when we're out there on the field. We're just trying to
make each other better.''
</P>
<P>
   This isn't 1991 anymore, and the road to Pasadena is no victory
tour.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can see the other countries getting better,'' says Fawcett.
``We don't have to be told what it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   The gap between the Americans and the rest of the world has
narrowed markedly, and they know that better than anyone. ``The
Brazilians weren't a good team eight years ago,'' says DiCicco.
``Now, they're a very good team. North Korea, where did they come
from? We'd never heard of them, and suddenly they're right with the
Chinese.''
</P>
<P>
   Since they didn't have to qualify for the Cup as hosts, the
Americans haven't had to go play a win-or-go-home match since the
Olympic final. When the Chinese knocked them off for the Algarve
Cup in Portugal last month, it was a ringing reminder that they
still have to be at the top of their game to stay on top of the
world.
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Yanks sought to drive home a point to the Chinese
three nights ago in Hershey, when they stormed downfield and scored
the winning goal three minutes into added time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Chinese were ready for the tie,'' said Scurry. ``That's
the difference between them and us. We don't play for ties.''
</P>
<P>
   The US women don't have that luxury. The men, who finished last
in last year's World Cup in France, have a timetable that has them
being a ``legitimate contender'' by 2010. The women's timetable
calls for them to win here and now. It doesn't say anything about
putting on a show or leaving a legacy. This time, it's assumed.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 0213EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
