<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 02:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2333 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-MCDONOUGHCOLUMN-B     04-25 1661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-MCDONOUGH </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PEERS CALL ELWAY ONE OF NFL'S BEST EVER 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By WILL MCDONOUGH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It is fitting that he is going out on top, because that
is where John Elway belongs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If anyone had any doubts about John being ranked up there with
the best that have ever played this game,'' said his former coach,
Dan Reeves, Saturday, ``then the last two Super Bowls should have
washed all of that away.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had proven that he could win the biggest games of them all,
so there was nothing left to prove. He has done it all. The
National Football League will miss him. And fans in Denver, and all
around the country, will miss him. He was an incredibly exciting
player.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway will make it official in the next few days that he will
retire from the Denver Broncos after a glorious career in the NFL,
with five Super Bowl appearances, two world championships, and a
Most Valuable Player award from last January's win over Reeves's
Atlanta Falcons.
</P>
<P>
   He has had one of the greatest careers of anyone who ever has
played the game, and he will have a special place in the Hall of
Fame in Canton, Ohio, five years from now, the first year he will
be eligible to be voted in.
</P>
<P>
   ``John deserves to be ranked up there with the very best ever,''
said Jets coach Bill Parcells, who lost the AFC Championship game
last year in Denver. ``He is certainly in the top four or five
quarterbacks of all-time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the first time I saw him. It was his rookie season
and we were on the field before the game for warmups. He threw a
couple of deep comebacks and I said to myself, `Gee whiz, this kid
looks like he is going to be special.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He had one of the best arms I've ever seen, and a great
combination of talent. He had size, strength, durability, and
courage. I always told our players when we went up against him, `If
you just let him stand in the pocket, and we don't get anyone in
his face, we are going to lose.'
</P>
<P>
   ``When I saw him playing a game, and if the other team wasn't
doing anything to stop him from stepping up and throwing in the
pocket, I knew they were going to lose. If you just let him stand
there and freeze, it was all over.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first Super Bowl and his first Super Bowl, he had a great
first half against us, but then our defense got after him, flushed
him out of the pocket, and allowed us to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the championship game we did a good job of shutting him
down in the first half, but then he did a good job of beating us in
the second half. But he's had a whole history of bringing his team
back to beat people in games.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway seemed born to play football. His father Jack, now
retired, was an outstanding college coach. Young John could do
anything athletically. Coming out of high school, he had a football
scholarship to Stanford, and signed a baseball contract with the
New York Yankees. He played baseball in the minors for the Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recruited John out of high school and coached him all four
years at Stanford,'' says Jim Fassel, the New York Giants' coach
who has remained close to Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``John is a great competitor. In college I knew he was going to
be a great player in the NFL. He had incredible talent and a great
desire to compete. In 1994, I was asked to come back to present
John into the Stanford Hall of Fame. Someone asked me what I
thought was the greatest play I had ever seen John make. They all
thought I was going to say this unbelievable throw he made against
USC one day when he threw a rocket from his own 40-yard line, on a
line, over Ronnie Lott's head to our receiver, Kenny Margerum. Lott
was on the 10. Margerum was in the end zone. You should be able to
run 20 yards in the time it takes a football to travel that far.
But John threw it so hard, Ronnie could not respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them, though, that was not my favorite John Elway play.
It came in baseball. He was a sophomore playing right field against
Arizona State. They had a man on second and the batter hit a single
down the right-field line. Just inches inside the line. John raced
to the line, gloved the ball, turned and threw a strike to home
plate to get the runner. I have never seen anything thrown as hard
as that ball was. It was so stunning the players on both sides came
out of the dugout, and the fans came right out of their seats.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think John is the greatest quarterback ever to play this
game, and he's just as great as a person. We still talk on the
phone a lot. I spoke with him the Tuesday morning after the Super
Bowl and he was totally relaxed, as if nothing great had happened.
It's a tribute to him and his family, and the way he was raised,
that John has conducted himself the way he has on and off the field
throughout his entire playing career.''
</P>
<P>
   ``During that first year,'' says Reeves, who coached Elway for
most of his career, ``we played the Colts in Denver. We were behind
by two or three touchdowns in the second half, and he brought us
back to win. And then I was lucky enough to be part of most of
those incredible comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``John has great leadership qualities. He does not ask anyone,
like another player on the team, to do something he would not do
himself. He had tremendous focus. He was like Michael Jordan. When
the game was on the line, he wanted the ball. He lived for those
moments. That's why he has more comeback victories than anyone
else.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could write a book about all of the memories I have of him
as a player. He did something special in almost every game he ever
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know why he is retiring now, but my guess is that he
just found it too difficult to keep getting himself ready to play
the season, the way he did in the past. It was the same way with
Roger Staubach. Roger and John both were great workout guys in the
offseason. Tremendously dedicated. At the end, Roger told me he
just couldn't make that commitment anymore, and if he couldn't, he
didn't think he could play up to the standards he set for himself.
My guess is this is what has happened to John.''
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, after he won his first Super Bowl, most thought
Elway was going to retire. But he came back with the hopes of
winning back-to-back Super Bowls, and creating an atmosphere to
help get his good friend, Broncos owner Pat Bowlen, a new stadium
in Denver. Both happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been talking with John about retiring,'' his agent,
Marvin Demoff, one of the very best and a solid guy, told me in
March at the annual league meetings. ``John is very tempted to go
back and try for three in a row. No one has ever done that. That is
the temptation. But I've been telling him there is also a
possibility that won't happen, and not to go out on top would be a
shame. Now would be the perfect time. He doesn't need any money. He
is in good health, and not beat up. There is nothing left to
prove.''
</P>
<P>
   Beyond being a great player, Elway is also quite a guy. I
remember asking linebacker Bill Romanowski, when he first joined
the Broncos three years ago, what he thought of Elway, and Saturday
he said the same things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't act like John Elway,'' said Romanowski. ``He
doesn't act like a star. He's just one of the guys like everyone
else in the locker room. There is no pretense. No big ego. All the
players like him because they know how much he wants to win. John
is just one of the guys. I've been with him when people asked him
for autographs and he never turned one down. Never. He would stand
there and sign for hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our team is really going to miss him in the locker room. He
had great leadership ability. He was so intense. Before his last
Super Bowl, I never had seen him that intense. I've been with him
for three years and he wanted to win that one more than any other
game. We had two weeks of practice before the game, and at the
beginning, he was too fired up. He was overthrowing everything in
practice. You could see he wanted that game too much. But on about
Wednesday before the game, he settled down, and everything was
great after that. It was really great playing with the guy, he's a
super person.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday I asked Jim Saccomano, the public relations director of
the Broncos and a man who has been by Elway's side throughout his
career, for his favorite memory.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to understand first what a nice person he is,''
Saccomano said. ``John does not like to hurt people. He wants to be
nice to everyone. Sometimes we have to hold him back from doing too
much.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into Green Bay a few years back to play the Packers,
and we stayed in a hotel in Appleton, Wis. There was a wedding in
the hotel the same day. We came from the airport to the hotel, and
John went right into production meeting with the television crew
doing the game. When it was over, we came through the lobby, and a
bridesmaid from the wedding party stopped John and asked if he
could take a picture with the bride and groom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kept saying he couldn't, he hadn't been to his room, it was
just impossible. John said he was sorry, but he couldn't. He
stepped into the elevator and closed the doors. Six seconds later,
the doors opened and John said `OK, let's do it.' They went right
to the bride and groom, took all of the pictures they wanted to
take, and then left. Years later, some writers heard the story,
found the couple, and asked them about it. They said it was one of
the greatest moments of their lives. That was John just being
John.''
</P>
<P>
   Personally, and I said this a few years before he ever won a
Super Bowl, John Elway is the best quarterback I have ever seen,
and that covers almost 40 years in this business. If you put Elway
on the same team with the others considered as the greatest, he
would have had them beat in size, arm strength, mobility,
durability, and courage. If they were all young, and in their
prime, trying out for the same team, Elway would be the starter.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
