<HEADLINE>
IT'S A FIRST FOR REVOLUTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Revolution's fortunes appear to have changed.
Not only did their 3-2 victory over D.C. United Saturday night keep
them unbeaten in regulation time this season, they won for the
first time at RFK Stadium since Major League Soccer started in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   This game was a redemption after three seasons of mistakes and
misfortune. Player-coach Walter Zenga provided a dominant presence
in goal, and the Revolution battled for two first-half goals by
Ivan McKinley and one by Giovanni Savarese, then held off a
desperate D.C. rally in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution had displayed defensive organization and Zenga
had been spectacular in four previous games. This time, though, New
England also kept possession in midfield and dictated some of the
tempo, signaling a major change in the team's comportment _
especially significant since D.C. United previously seemed to be
able to score at will against the Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``For us, this is very good because, for me, D.C. is the best
team in the league,'' Zenga said. ``We are starting over, and
tomorrow we will go back and keep trying to improve our team.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga and assistant coach Giuseppe Galderisi are providing a
positive influence, even overcoming a 10-hour trip caused by flight
delays at Reagan National Airport, which Zenga said allowed them
``many more hours to talk about the game.''
</P>
<P>
   A revamped midfield with Jair and Kris Kelderman flanked by Mike
Burns and McKinley provided much more composure than the Revolution
had shown. This poised approach limited the effectiveness of
United's Marco Etcheverry. And the Revolution, though without Edwin
Gorter (food poisoning), Imad Baba (groin), and John Harkes (knee),
took advantage of the absence of United defensive midfielders
Richie Williams (ankle) and Geoff Aunger (suspension).
</P>
<P>
   United took the lead as Etcheverry outmaneuvered Dan Calichman,
then Richard Goulooze slipped in the recently resodded goal area,
and Roy Lassiter took Etcheverry's pass and rounded Zenga in the
27th minute.
</P>
<P>
   Five minutes later, McKinley volleyed a Kelderman pass from the
left into the top of the net to tie. Then, the Revolution gained
momentum as Savarese made a sliding, left-footed finish of a Ted
Chronopoulos cross for a 2-1 edge in the 37th minute. McKinley
headed over Brian Kamler in the 45th minute, and United seemed
dispirited at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   United remained in first place with 7 points in the Eastern
Conference and the Revolution moved into second place with 6
points. The Revolution improved their record to 2-12-2 against the
two-time MLS Cup champions.
</P>
<P>
   Though the Revolution's midfield game disintegrated in the
second half, their defensive determination kept them in command
until A.J. Wood's 87th-minute score.
</P>
<P>
   By then, the Revolution had striker Tony Kuhn and defender Manny
Motajo in the midfield, but the only fatal defensive breakdown
occurred when Brian Dunseth missed a sliding tackle on Wood in the
penalty area, allowing him an open blast past Zenga.
</P>
<P>
   McKinley (stomach muscle tear), Jair, and Savarese had been
benched as the Revolution reverted to a siege mentality. Johnny
Torres provided some spark, though, as he was fouled from behind by
Carlos Llamos, who was ejected by referee Rich Grady in the 76th
minute, and eventually dribbled out the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could feel that we were going to win before the game in the
locker room,'' Calichman said. ``There was an electricity.
Sometimes, you can just feel it.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, when we got behind, we still kept playing good football,
we kept fighting.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
