<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREAM STARTING TO RISE IN EUROPE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Mark James told reporters not to get excited. Things
would be back to normal, he said, and there would be no need to
even talk about a playing captain for the 1999 Ryder Cup matches.
</P>
<P>
   Well, he probably doesn't want to say he told us so, but . . .
he told us so.
</P>
<P>
   James is 45 and still plays full-time on the European PGA Tour.
He'll also captain the European team at The Country Club in
September, so when he somehow put together a few good tournaments
and jumped to 19th in the standings, reporters got interested.
</P>
<P>
   The Englishman stopped them short. It is impossible to be a
playing captain with the pressure involved these days, he said. The
last playing captain was Arnold Palmer in 1963. Besides, said
James, he hadn't a clue as to why he had shot the scores he had.
</P>
<P>
   He had a second-place finish in the Madeira Island Open a few
weeks ago, which, coupled with a third at Dubai and a 20th at
Qatar, gave him three strong finishes in six starts.
</P>
<P>
   But last Thursday, James perhaps showed why we won't see him
playing come September. He made double-bogeys on two par-5s, tossed
in six bogeys, made just one birdie, and ended up dead last with an
81 in the first round of the Spanish Open. All of that on a course
that yielded 43 scores of 69 or better.
</P>
<P>
   On the bright side, James's team has a better feel to it than it
had a few weeks ago. Thanks to strong efforts in the Masters, Jose
Maria Olazabal (a win) and Bernhard Langer (T-11th) have jumped
into the top 10 in the European standings, at least for now putting
a halt to talk of rookies that was dominating Ryder Cup
discussions.
</P>
<P>
   James faced the questions when he came to Boston: How did he
envision working with a team with so many rookies in the mix? And
this was last November. The same questions were posed to Tony
Jacklin, a former European captain, when he was in Boston in March.
They answered politely, but they had every right to laugh and say
there was a long, long way to go.
</P>
<P>
   There still is, but Europe is looking at a better veteran
presence than it was a few weeks ago. Not only has the number of
rookies dropped to five in the top 10, but veterans Per-Ulrik
Johansson (21st), Costantino Rocca (28th), and Ian Woosnam (30th)
have given a little kick-start to their games and moved up in the
standings. With a stretch of big events on the horizon _ Benson &AMP;
Hedges, Deutsche Bank, Volvo, English Open, German Open _ don't be
surprised if some big names come through and give the European team
even more of an experienced face by mid June.
</P>
<P>
   But short of an amazing rebound, don't figure on Nick Faldo
being in the picture. He has been a European fixture since making
his Ryder Cup debut in 1977, but he is a shattered shell of what he
once was _ the most feared match-play competitor in the world.
Though he does not hide his desire to be on the 1999 Ryder Cup
team, Faldo understands his work is cut out for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have too much strength in depth for me to hand a wild card
to someone playing on a wing and a prayer,'' James told Golf World.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, Nick, you want a spot on the team? You'd better
earn it. Which is what Faldo intends on doing. He missed the cut at
this week's Spanish Open, but will be at the Benson &AMP; Hedges,
Deutsche Bank, and Volvo.
</P>
<P>
   ``One really good week and I'm right back in it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   It figures that one of James's captain's picks will go to Jesper
Parnevik, so he would prefer to see his veteran players
automatically qualify so that he would have more latitude. Perhaps
to pick Sergio Garcia?
</P>
<P>
   Sure, that seems a long shot, but the kid has plenty of flair
and he's proven tough anywhere he has played, not just in Europe.
He nearly won a couple of Nike events in 1998, and he made it to
the semifinals of the US Amateur at a grueling course (Oak Hill)
last summer. Garcia's performance at the Masters (low amateur at 7
over) and his impressive pro debut at the Spanish Open (67-73)
began with birdies on three of his first four holes.
</P>
<P>
   Like his idols, Seve Ballesteros and Olazabal, Garcia has a feel
for the short game that you cannot teach. Unlike his idols, Garcia
can hit it into the next ZIP code without trampling through woods.
</P>
<P>
   And Garcia, unlike James, is someone the captain would probably
want to play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Lanzetta is the head professional at Rockland Golf
Course and a senior rules official with the PGA of America. At last
week's PGA Seniors Championship, Lanzetta had the unhappy task of
approaching John Bland after the final round. Bland had just shot
71 to finish at 7-under 281, good enough to tie for seventh.
``John, can I ask you about the 11th hole?'' asked Lanzetta. As
Bland related the sequence of shots, Lanzetta cringed. So, too, did
Bland, for the South African realized he had goofed. Big time.
Bland had hit his second shot into a hazard guarding the green and
after searching unsuccesfully, he took a drop and played his fourth
shot onto the green. Then he found his original ball and played
that one through, recording that as his score. Chalk it up as
another serious example of a player not knowing the rules _ or at
least drawing a blank when it comes to exercising judgment. Once
you put another ball in play, you cannot play the original. Credit
Bland for at least owning up to the gaffe. ``My fault,'' he said.
``I know better.'' When told it was a very costly ruling, Lanzetta
held up his hands and said, ``I don't want to know, don't tell
me,'' and walked away. Despite what some players may think, rules
officials do not enjoy this part of the job. For the record, the
mistake cost Bland $52,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   If you caddie on the PGA Tour, be advised not to make travel
plans too far in advance. Certainly, this has been the season of
breakups, starting with Tiger Woods's firing of Mike ``Fluff''
Cowan. Next, Mark O'Meara canned longtime caddie Jeff Higginbotham,
and that was followed by the unsettling episode at the MCI Classic
at Hilton Head, S.C., last week when Parnevik released Lorne
Duncan. What is bothersome about the latest move is that it came on
the heels of Parnevik's disqualification at Harbour Town amid
reports that he blamed Duncan. A spectator reported that he saw
Parnevik remove his glove and use it to wipe his line on the green,
which is a violation. An official approached Parnevik, who said he
couldn't remember doing that, but Duncan confirmed it had happened.
Parnevik, who would have missed the cut anyway, was immediately
DQ'd for signing an incorrect scorecard and Duncan was quickly
fired. After shooting 65 Thursday to take the lead at the Greater
Greensboro Chrysler Classic, Parnevik denied that he had fired
Duncan for that reason, though his explanation rang hollow.
``Sometimes, even though you're very good friends with someone,
it's better to just part,'' Parnevik told reporters. ``You're
always looking for a change.'' Even if the change means punishing
an honest man . . . So who is carrying for Parnevik at Greensboro?
Lance Ten Broeck, who has been on and off the Tour for about the
past 100 years, it seems. Parnevik and Ten Broeck are good friends
. . . Don't be alarmed if you don't see Cowan with Jim Furyk at
Greensboro. When they agreed to a partnership just before the
Masters, Cowan informed Furyk that he had already planned a
vacation to Scotland. Furyk's caddie at Greensboro is Jeff Manson,
an old friend from college . . . Then there's Jeff Maggert, who
gave some time off to his regular caddie, Brian Sullivan, and did
what could be considered a very dangerous thing: He hired his
girlfriend, Michelle Austin, to carry for him at Greensboro . . .
And who says Faldo doesn't have a heart? When he discovered that
his caddie, Fanny Sunesson, had a sore back, Faldo jumped into
action. No, he didn't volunteer to lug the bag himself. He ordered
a lighter bag, one with a pop-up stand; it was delivered in time
for this week's Spanish Open. Now, if he could only cut down five
or six shots a round to lighten her workday . . . His swing has
always been a curious one, but after winning the PGA Seniors
Championship last week, Allen Doyle knows he'll be asked about it
even more, and most in the media will fall back on the story line
that he's a former hockey player with a slapshot golf swing. ``I
should have brought a damn hockey helmet and put it on coming down
the 18th hole,'' said Doyle after his major triumph. ``Then I'd
really be known for something.'' . . . He shows up to socialize,
see some old friends, and get in two rounds of golf. That's why
Freddie Haas attends the PGA Seniors Championship. Last week, he
opened with a 95 (ouch), but came back to shoot his age _ 83 _ at
PGA National's Champions Course in Palm Beach Gardens, Fla. ``I
felt like 83,'' said Haas after 36 holes on a grueling course.
``Most of the time I feel 75, except on this course. When we go to
other courses I would have broken 80.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Some would say that the first taste of serious local competition
takes place May 3-4 with MGA State Four-ball qualifying, but it
would be a gross oversight to ignore the recent Seagulls Tournament
at Hyannisport. The annual event was won by the teen-age stars from
Dennis Pines, Kenny Lewis and Michael Carbone, who prevailed in a
stellar field. Lewis, it seems, is quite comfortable at
Hyannisport, with victories in last year's Seagulls and the 1997
and 1998 Cape Cod Amateur. He is 18-0 in matches at Hyannisport in
that stretch. In the final, Lewis-Carbone defeated Joe Keller and
Paul Heffernan, 4 and 2. In the semifinals, they beat their Dennis
Pines mentors, Joe Walker and Kevin Carey, 1 up. Brendan Hester and
Chris Tufts teamed for a 64 to win medalist honors.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 0231EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
