</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SLAP IN THE FACE FOR E.J. 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENSBORO, N.C. _ The Flyers, as expected, opened the playoffs
without their behemoth team captain, Eric Lindros. A collapsed lung
earlier this month led him to two surgeries within a week and the
need to regenerate nearly half his blood supply.
</P>
<P>
   Lindros says he is thinking about a possible second-round
return, which for anyone who has had a severe chest cold _ never
mind a collapsed lung _ sounds like either unbridled optimism or a
death wish. If there had been a team flight after the Flyers' game
that night in Nashville, Lindros has told friends, he likely would
have been aboard and might not have been able to make it to a
hospital. As it was, he nearly had to be dragged from his hotel
room, crumpled over in pain, to seek life-saving medical assistance
in the middle of the night.
</P>
<P>
   Ex-Bruins netminder Eddie Johnston, now scouting the
Bruins-Hurricanes series for the Penguins, recently recalled his
own tap dance with the undertaker.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was off to the best start of my career,'' EJ recalled,
thinking back more than 30 years ago. ``I had three shutouts, and
my (goals-against) average was under 1.00. I couldn't have been
playing any better than that.''
</P>
<P>
   But during warmups one night at the old Olympia in Detroit,
Johnston was dropped by a Bobby Orr slapper. After a brief visit to
a local hospital, he hopped a flight home a couple of days later,
unaware that Orr's shot had fractured his skull. He believes the
flight came close to killing him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in tough shape when I came off the plane,'' recalled
Johnston, a noted workhorse in his day, an era when injury was a
badge of honor, stitches were military-like stripes of honor. ``A
friend was at the airport to pick me up, and he didn't even
recognize me. I was a mess. Luckily, he took me right to the
hospital.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Johnston, doctors at Massachusetts General Hospital
quickly diagnosed that he had a blood clot in his head, and surgery
was avoided only when, after 10 days, medication helped dissolve
the clot. His hospital stay lasted nearly six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have been out sooner than that,'' recalled Johnston.
``But some of the guys, (Phil) Esposito, (Gerry) Cheevers, came in
to see me one day and I got all messed up again. I don't know what
happened, I got excited or something. Whatever it was, I needed two
more weeks to get better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was different back then. A guy got a concussion, came back
to the bench looking goofy, didn't know where he was, and just took
a seat. He kept playing. The next day, he didn't know what
happened, couldn't remember anything, but that's just the way it
was _ no one thought anything about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Midway through Johnston's hospital stay, Hall of Fame netminder
Glenn Hall (in the Blues net in '70 when Orr scored the Cup winner)
stopped in for a visit. Seeing his pal in the hospital bed gave
Hall reason to reconsider the way he was doing business.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put a mask on that night,'' said Johnston, ``and he never
took it off.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The betting around Los Angeles is that Kings general manager
Dave Taylor, who canned Larry Robinson as head coach last week,
will plant a familiar face behind the bench. If so, that probably
would give ex-Bruins coach Butch Goring, once a key King, the edge.
Other names in the mix: Dave Lewis (two Cup rings as Scotty
Bowman's understudy in Detroit) and Ted Nolan, last seen getting
the hook in Buffalo after winning Coach of the Year honors. Keep in
mind, if the 'Canes don't make it out of the first round vs. the
Bruins, or don't make a respectable show of it, Nolan's name could
pop up as a possible replacement for Paul Maurice. Nolan was once a
Whalers assistant . . . Someone must have put too much spice in
Owen Nolan's tomato juice. Once thought to be an Avalanche
cornerstone, drafted first overall in '90 when the franchise was in
Quebec, the San Jose right wing fired off a couple of beauts last
week as their playoff series approached. Nolan: ``We definitely
have more character on this team. (The Avalanche) have two solid
lines, maybe the top two lines in the league. After that they don't
have anything.'' On one Patrick Roy: ``He's either unbeatable or
things just go flying by. He's either on top of his game or lets in
the weakest goals.'' Nothing like needlessly firing up the enemy .
. . Kudos to the Avalanche, Sharks, and the NHL front office for
postponing the start of the series last week, following the horror
in Littleton, Colo. For those who missed it: The series was
switched to a 2-3-1-1 format, opening in San Jose rather than
Denver. Avalanche GM Pierre Lacroix lives only a half-mile from
Columbine High and, in days past, often took strolls to the
schoolyard with his wife in the evening . . . Just as the season
was ending, Nashville came to terms with its prized draft pick,
center David Legwand, the No. 2 pick overall in last year's draft.
The deal is worth just short of $3 million over three years, as
allowed by the Collective Bargaining Agreement, but he could bank
$8.9 million if he hits all of the incentives. He played in
Nashville's last game of the season. ``You watch the way he
plays,'' said Nashville coach Barry Trotz, ``it looks like he's
floating around the ice. Once he gets stronger . . .''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Lords of the Boards consider getting
the season off to an earlier start. Today's player is typically in
exceptional shape and doesn't need three weeks of training and
exhibition games. A Sept. 30 start would guarantee that Game 7 in a
Cup final wouldn't go past June 9 or 10. Game 7 could be June 19
this year, which is less than a week before the June 25 expansion
draft to stock Atlanta . . . Chicago center Alexei Zhamnov, among
those Blackhawks who came to life (25 points over 18 games) after
Dirk Graham got canned as head coach, will switch from No. 36 to
No. 13 next season. It will be his third number since going to
Chicago in the Jeremy Roenick swap. Question is, no matter what
number he's wearing, will he ever show up as a No. 1 center? Look
for head coach Lorne Molleken to try career center Doug Gilmour as
one of Zhamnov's wingers next season . . . The final tally in D.C.:
The Capitals lost no fewer than 511 man-games to injury. Said
another way, that's akin to having six guys missing from the lineup
every game. The injuries, said coach Ron Wilson, ``poisoned our
season.'' After making it to the finals last spring, the Capitals
now are faced with a huge rebuilding project, similar to the youth
movement the Bruins embarked on two years ago . . . Not everyone is
convinced that Mario Lemieux's group has the money to carry the
Penguins, but the league believes the group is fiscally viable. The
NHL needs to know soon, if only for the sake of scheduling, whether
the Penguins are going to be in Pittsburgh next year, a matter
that, in part, rests with US bankruptcy court. The court already
has prohibited Roger Marino from shopping around for a possible
out-of-town landing spot for his debt-ridden club . . . Islanders
netminder Wade Flaherty made his way into the trivia books with
Wayne Gretzky's retirement. He gave up the Great One's final goal.
``I guess if your name is down as a trivia answer,'' mused
Flaherty, ``that's the name you want beside it.'' Former Vancouver
netminder Glen Hanlon let up Gretzky's first NHL goal. ``Someone
had to get him on his way,'' said Hanlon . . . A couple of weeks
before making up his mind to retire, Gretzky made a point of noting
to John Davidson, his pal on the Rangers' broadcast team, that next
season's training camp will start before Labor Day. Initially, J.D.
took that as a positive sign that No. 99 would return. In
reflection, he saw it was just part of the thinking that went into
Gretzky's decision-making process . . . Walter Gretzky, Wayne's
dad, hung outside the Ranger dressing room prior to his son's last
game. Now retired at age 60, the senior Gretzky keeps busy in
Brantford, Ontario, helping to coach a 12-year-old traveling team.
``A lot of times, coaches on the other clubs ask if I'll say a few
words to their kids,'' said Walter. ``I always tell them the same
three things: 1. listen to your coaches; 2. play as hard as you
can, because then, no matter what, no one can criticize what you
did out there _ because you did your best; 3. enjoy yourself, have
fun . . . because if you're not having fun then you're not going to
get better.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Word around campus is that North Dakota coach Dean Blais decided
to stay put for a four-year deal worth upwards of $1 million, which
included annual pay of $150,000 and the university paying off his
mortgage . . . On the subject of debt load, don't you love it when
arena owners who are also club owners (like here in the Hub)
dismiss the revenue from luxury box sales, lamenting that those
dollars go directly to the bank to pay off the arena mortgage?
Eventually, the building gets paid off, and it's the arena/club
owner who is left holding that equity. Ignoring that revenue would
be like the Average Joe telling the IRS each year that a huge chunk
of his annual pay should be disregarded because that money went to
pay a mortgage. No wonder the Players' Association rolls its eyes
every time players and owners get around to money talk . . . When
Ranger captain Brian Leetch took center ice last Sunday in the
Gretzky ceremonies, the sold-out crowd at Madison Square Garden
bellowed a thunderous, ``Sign him! Sign him!'' As of July 1, the
31-year-old Leetch is an unrestricted free agent, and New York Post
hockey columnist Larry Brooks recently mused that the Bruins might
take a run at the ex-BC Eagle. Seems like a real stretch, because
when the smoke clears, Leetch's deal figures to be worth $8
million-$10 million a year. The Bruins still smart from the harsh
reality of paying old guys big bucks back in the Kevin Stevens-Adam
Oates era and they're not about to go down that path again . . .
Montreal assistant coach Dave King has a two-year offer on the
table to coach Jokerit, the elite Finnish club in Helsinki where
the likes of Jari Kurri and Teemu Selanne spent their youth. ``I'm
not coaching there unless Jari and Teemu are playing there,'' joked
King. If King leaves the Habs, look for ex-Bruins coach Rick
Bowness to take his spot in Montreal. Alain Vigneault, the Habs'
head coach, was an assistant in Ottawa when Bowness was head coach
. . . In Games 1 and 2 of the Senators-Sabres series, both won by
Buffalo, Sabres netminder Dominik Hasek stopped 85 of 88 shots for
an eye-popping .966 save percentage. And after missing Game 1 of
the series with the lingering effects of a concussion, ex-Bruin Joe
Juneau collected a pair of assists in Buffalo's 3-2 win in overtime
Friday night . . . Mike Smith, the associate GM in Toronto, still
hasn't heard what Ken Dryden, the Leafs' president and GM, has
planned for him next season. Smith's deal is up when the season
ends, and with jobs such as the Minnesota Wild front office
available, he'll have to move promptly if Dryden isn't quick to
extend his deal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
