<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK CIRCULAR FILE A NOT-SO-MERRY GO-ROUND 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ There's a recent but nevertheless rich history of
corporate intrigue in the New York Knicks organization. This past
week's dismissal of Ernie Grunfeld was simply the latest chapter.
If Claude Rains were still around, he'd say he was shocked,
shocked, to see such a thing.
</P>
<P>
   Coaches come and go. General managers come and go, albeit at a
less rapid clip. Coaches and general managers go at each other in
New York _ and then they go, or at least they have in the last
dozen years. That's why the next hire Dave Checketts makes has to
be someone who not only has the cachet, but also can handle both
jobs. (M.L. Carr is available.)
</P>
<P>
   By all accounts, Grunfeld and Jeff Van Gundy are good, earnest
men who simply were not entirely sympatico. The most visible source
of their contretemps probably was the Charles Oakley-Marcus Camby
trade, but it has to be deeper than that. One is now gone and the
other is likely to follow.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of teams have coaches who don't like their general manager
or vice versa. George Karl was just fined $25,000 for his incessant
trashing of Seattle GM Wally Walker. Jerry West was happy to show
Pat Riley the door when Riley's act began to wear thin in Los
Angeles. Chris Ford made no secret of his total disillusionment
with Carr, even though he never publicly said a word.
</P>
<P>
   Most general managers, however, seem to stick around. Witness
Elgin Baylor and Wes Unseld, two terrific players whose
off-the-court records are lamentable. Willis Reed survived for
years in New Jersey with a mediocre record. He's still there,
albeit without the power he once wielded.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks, it seems, have had more than their share of
dirty laundry airings; it is ever thus in the Big Apple. In the
last 12 years, there have been four public, bitter fights between
the Knicks coach and general manager.
</P>
<P>
   In 1986, the coach was Hubie Brown. He and GM Dave DeBusschere
were always at each other's throats and their mutual distrust and
contempt was an open secret. Hubie, of course, wanted to trade
every guy on the roster, was rarely happy, and was fond of saying,
``Potential will get you fired.'' DeBusschere eventually fell in
January 1986 after four forgettable years. His successor, the
hapless Scotty Stirling, lasted only a year and change.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the 1986-87 season, Stirling agreed to exchange the
Knicks' No. 1 pick in 1987 for Seattle's No. 1 pick and Gerald
Henderson. Brown, whose team was going down the tubes and certain
to get a high pick, went ballistic. Brown also was dismissed three
weeks later after starting out 4-12.
</P>
<P>
   The irony is that the designated Sonics pick (which belonged to
Milwaukee) turned out to be No. 18, which was used to select Mark
Jackson, who went on to become Rookie of the Year. Seattle drafted
Scottie Pippen with New York's pick in a prearranged deal with the
Bulls.
</P>
<P>
   Stirling was history in May 1987, and that led to the next big
dust-up. The Madison Square Garden suits wanted Jimmy Rodgers as
the coach, but Boston wouldn't let him go without compensation. So
the Knicks turned to Rick Pitino, who was hired even though general
manager Al Bianchi was not the man who made the choice. There
almost instantly was friction between the two.
</P>
<P>
   Bianchi, an old-schooler, was a frequent critic of Pitino's
system, saying it was great for the regular season but would get
exposed in the playoffs. He was correct. Pitino felt his system did
work _ and that he couldn't work with someone who openly questioned
it. He was correct. He left for Kentucky after two years. Bianchi
eventually got buddy John MacLeod into New York, but both soon
flamed out.
</P>
<P>
   The last big blowup, while technically not a fight between coach
and general manager, was nevertheless a classic power struggle.
Riley wanted more power. Checketts wanted things to remain as they
were. The two, once pals, turned into mortal enemies when Riley
bolted for Miami. Grunfeld was technically the general manager, and
this was before Checketts started to spread himself so thin that he
now worries about things like ``The Scarlet Pimpernel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks haven't been the same since. Since Riley left, New
York has had three second-place finishes and has not gotten past
the second round of the playoffs. The Knicks will be lucky to even
make the playoffs this year, a staggering thought for a team with a
$68 million payroll.
</P>
<P>
   The next guy will inherit a train wreck. The Knicks are old,
capped out, and have few desirable players who aren't dramatically
overpaid. Things may actually get worse before they get better.
Whoever the next guy is, he must get along with the boss. With
Checketts's hand in so many pies, the new guy would be wise to look
in the mirror when he looks for his boss.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   More than a few people in Cleveland are watching the Celtics'
late-season slide with great interest. While the Cavs haven't
announced officially that they will take Boston's pick in this
year's draft, it's all but a done deal with the Celtics'
plummeting. ``I would say yes,'' Cavs GM Wayne Embry said this past
week when asked if he'd take the pick if things continued along
these lines. Folks in Cleveland feel they got the better of the
Andrew Declercq-Vitaly Potapenko deal. First, they basically
exchanged one backup center for another. The one they got may not
be as talented, but he's the perfect backup and he's cheap by NBA
standards. They also got out of adding another fat contract to the
mix. ``Affordability was a key for us,'' Embry said. ``We've got
two big ones already (Shawn Kemp and Zydrunas Ilgauskas) and some
more ahead.'' Now, you add a top six pick and it makes it look like
larceny from Cleveland's point of view. The Celtics, meanwhile,
undeniably have a better presence in the middle. Time will tell on
the pick. This will be the first time since 1979 that the Celtics
will not have a first-round pick (unless they trade for one). The
only other team with a longer track record of having a
first-rounder each year is Sacramento, which has had one every year
since 1972 . . . Observation of Patrick May, age 10, upon getting a
copy of the Celtics' team picture last Wednesday at the
76ers-Celtics game: ``They left out the guy with the best name
(Popeye Jones) and the best hair (Pervis Ellison).'' We know why
Pervis wasn't there; he's been diligently rehabbing in Washington
all season. But where was Popeye? . . . If, as expected, Paul Silas
has the ``interim'' tag removed from his job description, it will
mean that he has gone 16 years between official gigs. (He coached
the Clippers from 1980-83.) We checked and couldn't find anyone who
waited longer between head jobs, with one interesting exception:
Silas's last boss in Charlotte: Dave Cowens. You may recall, though
most of us would like to forget, that Cowens was the Celtics'
player coach for the final 68 games of the 1978-79 season. He
resurfaced in Charlotte in 1996, a stretch of 17 years between head
jobs. The only other ones who come even close are the late, great
Red Holzman, and the equally great Bill Russell. Holzman left the
Hawks in 1957 and didn't surface again until he took over the
Knicks in 1967. Russell left Seattle in 1977 and returned 10 years
later for a brief, ill-advised, and wildly unsuccessful stint in
Sacramento. Pitino went eight years between NBA jobs . . . The
Players Association will hold its nose as it moves to stop the
ridiculous $25,000 fine levied on Latrell Sprewell for remarks made
by his agent. First, like everyone else, they've had it with
Sprewell. Second, Sprewell's new agent, Bob Gist, isn't thought of
highly in the union offices; they feel he's a bit of a hanger-on.
But there's a much larger issue at work. ``This is unprecedented,''
said union attorney Ron Klempner. ``It's a lot more than just the
fine.'' The union just got through resolving grievances for two
players (Pooh Richardson, Stanley Roberts) who were fined for
ripping their coach. But to fine a player for something his agent
said? Most players would be broke if that were standard procedure.
``We've never had anything like this before,'' Klempner said. ``The
player disavowed the remarks unequivocally. I would hope the Knicks
would work it out themselves.'' The union also is going to closely
watch the Celtics' ``voluntary'' summer workouts and see whether
players who show up do so ``voluntarily.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Tyus Edney was named MVP of the recent European Final Four in
Munich after leading his team (Zalgiris Kaunas) to an 82-74 victory
over Kinder Bologna. In 35 minutes, Edney had 14 points, 6
rebounds, 6 assists, and a steal. Why can't the Celtics get guys
like that? Zalgiris, which is sponsored by Lithuanian stars Arvydas
Sabonis and Sarunas Marciulionis, qualifies for the McDonald's Cup
next October in Milan . . . The battle has begun. The Raptors sent
out a video touting Vince Carter for Rookie of the Year. Don't they
know that writers are immune from such blatant bribery attempts?
(Next time, make it a coffee cup, T-shirt, or mouse pad, guys.) Via
faxes to writers, agent Mark Bartlestein is promoting client Randy
Brown for Most Improved Player . . . Amazing to see Rick Mahorn not
only play, but play important minutes last week against the
Celtics. He's 40 years old. He said he thought the Celtics might
have interest in him this year, but there were no calls. That's a
shame. He would be a perfect fit on the Celtics, although he did
admit that he'd have trouble adjusting to Pitino's frantic coaching
style. Mahorn also is reminded of how old he is every time he sees
teammate Allen Iverson. He went to high school with Iverson's
parents.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 0235EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
