<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIME FOR CARROLL TO BECOME AUTHORITY FIGURE 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ The scene looked the way it's supposed to
look.
</P>
<P>
   There was Pete Carroll huddled with Bob Kraft and Bobby Grier in
the war room on draft day, exposed to ESPN cameras, apparently
fighting for the Patriots to select Ohio State linebacker Andy
Katzenmoyer with the 28th pick in the first round instead of
filling another need, running back.
</P>
<P>
   If Carroll is indeed fighting for what he wants and needs to
lead the Patriots out of their two-year slide, then he's doing the
right thing. Kudos to Grier and Kraft if they went along with their
coach's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   It must be, after all, Carroll's team. It can't be Bobby Grier's
team. It can't be Bob Kraft's team.
</P>
<P>
   It will be, after all, Carroll's neck on the line if the players
others have recommended falter next year.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this outward show of authority by Carroll _ and the
toughness he has shown with players not attending the strength and
conditioning program _ happens more than we think it does, but it
appears to have happened all too little the past two years.
</P>
<P>
   Some of it is understandable.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, he was a young coach getting his second chance at
the big time, put in an absolute no-win situation replacing Bill
Parcells. There was reason for him to stay within the parameters of
the system Kraft created: personnel director Grier ran the show and
Andy Wasynczuk was in charge of the money, salary caps, etc.
Carroll's job was to coach the players Grier got for him.
</P>
<P>
   So maybe what we're seeing is not what is happening. Maybe
Carroll is still coaching Grier's players. The Patriots will tell
you it's a committee decision every time they draft a player or
sign a free agent. That may be true, but it's also evident that
Carroll never wanted to lose his starting center (Dave Wohlabaugh)
and his starting weak-side linebacker (Todd Collins). And as much
as he spoke of Tedy Bruschi being able to fill in for Collins and
Heath Irwin for Wohlabaugh, draft day proved that really wasn't the
case. The Patriots needed to draft Damien Woody, and Carroll knew
he needed Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   With the coach entering his very critical third year, management
needs to empower Carroll. Just letting him stay on one more year is
not enough. If they don't let the coach have a major say in
personnel, letting Parcells go to the enemy will look even worse in
time.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll needs to work with players he's comfortable coaching,
hire and fire his own staff, and put together his program, not
someone else's. He needs to operate in his own style.
</P>
<P>
   He can no longer afford ``evaluations'' of his performance,
especially by his own players. That fiasco at the end of last
season showed a lack of respect from management.
</P>
<P>
   Some who left the organization felt that Carroll was not acting
like a coach who had a guaranteed five-year deal. If he didn't, one
could see why Carroll would be handcuffed. After all, take the
guarantee out of Rick Pitino's deal with the Celtics and his power
is taken away and he has no spaghetti sauce to sell. Take the
guarantee out of Pat Burns's deal with the Bruins, and he's going
to do things to please Harry Sinden and Jeremy Jacobs rather than
doing things his way.
</P>
<P>
   If the committee approach is to work in New England, Grier and
Wasynczuk must answer Carroll's calls if they are within reason.
That's the way it is around the league where the committee approach
is successful. When Mike Ditka wanted Ricky Williams and said he'd
be willing to give up all of his draft, Bill Kuharich sprang into
action. When Dennis Green wants something, he gets it. When Mike
Holmgren asked for something in Green Bay, Ron Wolf got it done if
he could. Even in the days when Parcells had to answer to George
Young in New York, Young faithfully executed his coach's wishes.
</P>
<P>
   There are many examples of the committee approach working.
Carroll knows X's and O's as well as anyone. He knows talent. Now,
he needs complete authority and respect to do his job.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots are telling all who will listen that Terry Glenn
was not involved in trade talks during the draft. The Patriots have
to be very careful about Glenn's confidence level, especially after
Glenn and his agent, Jim Gould, had a big powwow with Carroll last
week concerning a plan to keep Glenn healthy through the season.
Glenn recommended ways to be used in practice that will keep his
legs fresh. Whether Carroll goes along with it is another issue . .
. Troy Brown, who never used to miss offseason workouts, is staying
away this offseason. The receiver, who missed six games with an
ankle sprain and was never right the second half of last season,
isn't pleased that the team has not addressed a contract extension.
Brown may be supplanted from punt-return duties by rookie Kevin
Faulk . . . Not only is the draft itself competitive, but the
aftermath can get nasty, with teams vying for free agent rookies
among the undrafted players. Bonuses last year got up to $40,000,
which is more than what many seventh-round picks get. And every
team likes to claim it found a prize that slipped through the
draft. The Steelers think they got a player who could be Slash II:
South Carolina quarterback Anthony Wright. ``He may be the next
Randall Cunningham,'' said former NFL quarterback John Reaves, who
was Wright's coach at South Carolina two years ago. ``He's got a
great arm. He can throw a ball 70-75 yards on the run.'' . . . Just
a few days before drafting Akili Smith in the first round, the
Bengals called in quarterbacks Jeff Blake, Neil O'Donnell, and Paul
Justin for physicals, an unusual request for this time of year. A
day after Smith was drafted, O'Donnell was cut, and two days later,
Justin was gone. Justin is scheduled to visit with the Washington
Redskins Sunday . . . Carl Pickens is still out there, saying he
will sit out the year rather than play for the Bengals as their
franchise player. Pickens had some interest from the Dolphins, but
they have backed off and signed Tony Martin, who may be on trial
for laundering drug money before the season is over . . . The meat
of Lamont Warren's contract with the Patriots is backloaded. The
first two years of the five-year deal are worth about $1.5 million,
which is about all the Patriots will spend for Warren . . . Ditto
Larry Whigham. While the deal is worth $4 million over four years,
Whigham received a $650,000 signing bonus . . . The veterans are
starting to fall around the league, and this is where the Patriots
could pick up some defensive line help in the coming weeks. The
Colts are talking as though defensive end Al Fontenot could be on
the streets soon. Fontenot makes $900,000 . . . Jevon Kearse, who
is projected by many as a linebacker in the NFL, will start his
career as a defensive end for the Titans. The Titans see him as the
next Willie McGinest.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Jets seriously considered former Rams quarterback Chris
Miller, who has been out of football three years, and Eric Zeier
(who signed with Tampa Bay) to be their backup before settling on
Scott Zolak. Word is Parcells got a little sick of trying to find
Mr. Perfect for the job and decided to go with the devil he knew.
Zolak is driving up from Florida and should be on Long Island
Tuesday to sign his incentive-laden deal . . . The Patriots would
have loved to take Temple quarterback Shaun King in the third
round, but Tampa scooped him in Round 2 . . . The Patriots are one
of the teams keeping a close eye on Lawrence Phillips in NFL
Europe. Phillips is playing for former Boston College coach Jack
Bicknell in Barcelona. So far, Phillips has run well and has
behaved himself . . . Bill Walsh had questioned backup quarterback
Jim Druckenmiller's arm strength and the decision to take him in
the draft a year ago and had already decided to give the backup job
to Jeff Garcia, the Canadian Football League star QB in the
post-Doug Flutie era. Walsh had tried unsuccessfully to trade
Druckenmiller, and now that is impossible, as Druckenmiller was
charged last week with raping a Virginia Tech coed . . . Once the
Los Angeles Whatchamacallits are named the 32d NFL team, each of
the other 31 will get about $20 million in franchise fees. On top
of $18 million per team when the Browns were born, it's a nice deal
for a little competition and having to go through an expansion
draft to give up players you don't want anyway . . . If Ben
Coates's contract isn't redone by the Patriots, don't be surprised
if he finishes his career in Los Angeles . . . Bobby Ross wanted
Barry Sanders to take part in the Lions' minicamp this weekend, but
Sanders, a 10-time Pro Bowler, stayed consistent with his policy of
not attending voluntary workouts . . . If teams value offseason
strength and conditioning programs so much, why don't some of the
colder-climate teams _ New England and Green Bay, for instance _
get together and set up a training site in Florida? Run it from
mid-March through the end of May and see how many players show up.
If a lot do, then the expense is worth it; if not, then close it
up. For years, it has been the teams in warm-weather situations _
Tampa, Miami, Arizona _ who get the best attendance . . . Ricky
Williams is going to be a very high-priced spokesman for Puma,
which is getting back into the sports marketing business with a
bang . . . Look for Irving Fryar to sign with the Oakland Raiders
within a month. Fryar would like to be reunited with Jon Gruden,
who was a coach in Philadelphia when Fryar was there . . . Miami
coach Jimmy Johnson has said he wouldn't be against going into the
season with two rookie running backs. Rob Konrad of Syracuse and
North Andover has an excellent shot at starting at fullback, along
with Mississippi State's J.J. Johnson. A camp full of running backs
could mean the end for Karim Abdul-Jabbar, Stanley Pritchard,
Roosevelt Potts, Tyrone Wheatley, and perhaps even John Avery . . .
Former Patriots offensive coordinator Larry Kennan said one of the
most common concerns scouts had in Tim Couch's workouts was how he
threw the ball out of the shotgun because Couch was strictly a
drop-back guy at Kentucky. Couch more than answered those questions
. . . Grey Ruegamer was the second center taken in the draft by the
Dolphins, in the third round. The Arizona State tough guy has a
little Conrad Dobler in him. In fact, he's so tough his mother told
the Miami Herald that he castrated sheep on his friend's farm with
his teeth. Ruegamer allegedly helped in the castration of 800 sheep
over a three-day period last May. This guy is playing alongside
Kevin Gogan? It might be worth the price of admission to see Chad
Eaton vs. Ruegamer in those Dolphins-Patriots games.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
