<SLUG> BC-RAC-RACING </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BAFFERT CAN FILL IN WITH EITHER FILLY 
</HEADLINE>
 NOTEBOOK-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON INDRISANO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Silverbulletday or Excellent Meeting? Excellent Meeting
or Silverbulletday? What's trainer Bob Baffert to do?
</P>
<P>
   Baffert not only has the top two 3-year-old colts in General
Challenge and Prime Timber _ co-favorites at 7-1 to win Saturday's
Kentucky Derby in the advance wagering sponsored by Churchill Downs
_ but also the top two 3-year-old fillies mentioned above.
</P>
<P>
   While traveling the long road to the Derby, Baffert has wandered
all over the place when it comes to the fillies. First, he said he
would run neither filly in the Derby if his colts came through.
Then, he pointed Excellent Meeting toward Friday's Kentucky Oaks,
which left the question open about the Derby chances of
Silverbulletday, who won the Eclipse Award as the top 2-year-old
filly of 1998. Then, he began talking about how small
Silverbulletday is, and, all of sudden, Excellent Meeting became a
Derby candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, Baffert can do what he wants. The two fillies lead all
of the colts in money earned in graded stakes, which determines
entry into the Derby (Silverbulletday with $1,721,170 and Excellent
Meeting with $1,164,224). He knows he needs only one of them to win
the prestigious Oaks; to run them both would be classic overkill.
</P>
<P>
   The egos of owners may come into play here. Silverbulletday is
owned by Mike Pegram, who also owns Real Quiet, last year's Derby
winner, and Excellent Meeting is owned by the Golden Eagle Farm of
John and Betty Mabee, who also own General Challenge. Pegram has
said that Silverbulletday belongs in the Oaks, but she has been
working sensationally at Churchill, and Pegram loves publicity. So,
who knows? The Mabees sold Worldly Manner, who was trained by
Baffert, to Sheik Mohammed al Maktoum of Dubai for $5 million when
Worldly Manner was a 2-year-old. Worldly Manner is now 9-1 in early
wagering to win the Derby, but the Mabees could form a powerful
entry with their colt and filly, who is the only one to defeat
Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, who likes to act a little wacky at times, surprised
trainer Nick Zito at Churchill last Monday when he suggested that
Zito send Wood Memorial winner Adonis, a Derby hopeful, out to work
with Excellent Meeting. Thoroughbreds work with members of their
own stable, they don't fraternize with the enemy. Zito was stunned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him they don't pay off in the morning,'' said Zito.
``He was serious. He said, `Let's work them together. I want to see
if I have a Derby horse.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Excellent Meeting went out and blazed 5 furlongs in :59 4/5,
while Adonis went the same distance on his own in 1:04 1/5. Using
the ancient standard that a fifth of a second equals 1 length,
that's a difference of 22 lengths. Adonis was only out for an
airing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just wanted him to get a feel for the track and make sure
he came out of the Wood OK,'' said Zito. But it was an audition for
Excellent Meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a good thing that Adonis didn't go with her,'' said
Baffert. ``She did it real easy. The mile and one-quarter (the
Derby distance, while the Oaks is a mile and one-eighth) with
Silverbulletday might stretch her a little bit, but Excellent
Meeting, well, she was really good today. I have to see what
develops.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Baffert's colts, who ran 1-2 in the Santa Anita
Derby, with General Challenge defeating Prime Timber, are also
doing great at Churchill. On Thursday, General Challenge, whose
sire, General Meeting, is also the sire of Excellent Meeting, went
6 furlongs in 1:12, while Prime Timber went 1:12 3/5.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner and Aljabr, who will represent the Godolphin
Stable of Sheik Mohammed in the Derby, cleared quarantine and got
their first feel of the Churchill surface Thursday, as each took a
casual gallop of 1 1/4 miles over the oval. ``They both went very
well,'' said Tom Albertrani, assistant to head trainer Saeed bin
Suroor. ``They went out a little bit on their toes, but they did
better than expected for the first day. I'm sure that, in another
day, they will be more relaxed.'' . . . Trainer Elliott Walden, who
will saddle Blue Grass winner Menifee in the Derby (8-1 in the
advance betting), hopes to have Ecton Park start, too. Ecton Park,
who has been working with the addition of blinkers, has $100,400 in
graded earnings but needs a couple of defections to get into the
projected field, which is limited to 20. If Ecton Park, a son of
Forty Niner, does start, he will be ridden by Robbie Davis, ``If he
doesn't get in, we'll probably go in the Illinois Derby (May 8),''
said Walden . . . Trainer D. Wayne Lukas announced that Chris
Antley, who has overcome personal problems to begin riding again
this year, will handle Lexington Stakes winner Charismatic in the
Derby. Antley won the 1991 Derby aboard Strike the Gold, who was
trained by Zito. Charismatic will give Lukas two entrants, with Cat
Thief considered the stronger of the two.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Suffolk Downs will open its gates at 10:30 a.m. on Derby Day,
with the simulcast of the first race from Churchill at 11:30, and
the Derby set for 5:37 p.m. Suffolk will run its first live race at
noon. With a paid admission, patrons will receive a souvenir Derby
glass and a pass valid for the month of May. Suffolk will accept
advance Derby wagers starting Friday . . . K One King, who was
purchased for $1.7 million by Allen Paulson so his wife, Madeline,
could run a horse in the Derby, worked five panels in 1:02 at
Churchill Monday under Alex Solis. ``He relaxed the first part of
it, and then picked it up around the turn,'' said Solis. ``I was
impressed with him.'' . . . Epic Honor, fourth in the Lexington,
has $180,000 in graded earnings and could have qualified for the
Derby, but his connections have sensibly decided to take him to the
Illinois Derby.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
