<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS BEAT GRIZZLIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the NBA equivalent of high noon between computer nerds.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so Saturday's official starting time was more like 8 p.m. -
the extra half hour had been tacked on in case any basketball fans
who were avoiding the Sports Arena decided to change their minds.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, at one end of the street, sporting a pocket protector
autographed by Bill Gates, we introduce the Vancouver Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   And ... staring back from the home end of the street through
eyeglasses held together by masking tape ... give it up for the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   Two teams parked in the lottery. The loser would be sitting in
the driver's seat for the homestretch of the NBA Draft derby and
the opportunity to select yet another college prospect who - at
best - may be the poor man's answer to Class of '97 valedictorian
Tim Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers - seemingly unconcerned with courting lottery
Ping-Pong ball disaster - recovered from a catnap at the start of
the second half, and defeated Vancouver, 105-96, in front of 13,493
on ``ROTC Night.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Personally, I hit the wall,'' said Clippers forward Maurice
Taylor, who added a few bricks (he missed 15 of 24 field-goal
attempts), but finished with a team-high 25 points. ``I was dead
tired, but coach got on us, told us we had to fight for this
game.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor had enough haymakers left to knock down eight
fourth-quarter points, as the Clippers (9-35) earned the decision
in the fifth game for each team over a seven-night span. His
driving layup with 4:44 left to play but the Clips up for good at
95-93, and dropped the Grizzlies to 8-37.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we came on in the fourth quarter showed that we really
wanted this game,'' Taylor said following the Clippers' sixth win
in their last 11 games.
</P>
<P>
   Just call it draft dodging.
</P>
<P>
   A truly madhouse ride to the rescue was provided by Clipper
forward Rodney Rogers. The Clippers' swing forward escaped from the
bench to score a season-high 19 points and collect seven rebounds.
He also provided enough defensive sinew to slow down Vancouver star
Shareef Abdur-Rahim, whose game-high 27 points included just seven
in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to always be ready to play,'' said Rogers, whose
minutes have been trimmed by the meteoric rise of forwards Maurice
Taylor and Tyrone Nesby. ``From the first guy, to the last guy ...
you never know when you're going to be needed.''
</P>
<P>
   Rogers' heroics included the second of back-to-back 3-point
flips that pulled the Clippers even at 93 with 5:15 left to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to do something,'' he said. ``We had blown the lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, there's a stunner.
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers usually play hard and mean well, but their 58-52
halftime lead completely vanished in about two-and-half minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers bailed out his pals, while backup point guard Troy Hudson
filled in for Sherman Douglas, who was chugging around the court on
fumes.
</P>
<P>
   Hudson had just enough in his playmaking tank to get everyone
home safely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
