<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-IRWINDALE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WOOD WINS AT IRWINDALE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRWINDALE, Calif. _ Persistence finally paid off for Timmy Wood.
</P>
<P>
   The Chino Hills resident, who had been involved in some untimely
incidents during his first two races at Irwindale Speedway, more
then made up for it by winning the NASCAR Super Late Model feature
before 2,500 Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   Other winners included Jim Smith in Legends, North Hills T.K.
Karvasek in Super Stock and Troy Decuir in Mini-Stockars.
</P>
<P>
   Wood, who started on the pole, is the fourth different winner in
Super Late Model, joining Winston West regular Brendan Gaughan,
Greg Pursley and track points-leader Rod Johnson of Chatsworth. It
felt great, especially after crashing two weeks ago and having a
tire go flat (last week), said Wood, who held off second-place
Brian Barron by .163 seconds at the stripe. We felt if we could
just get some luck we had the car to win.
</P>
<P>
   It was close for Wood, who led all 50 laps of the feature race,
which included 16 caution laps that effected seven cars.
</P>
<P>
   Barron, who at one point slipped several car lengths behind
Wood, made several challenges over the final four laps. He got
within the Wood's back bumper but could never get around, failing
on his final attempt coming off turn four on the final lap.
</P>
<P>
   He put a lot of heat on me, Wood said. My tires were starting to
go away. I was concerned. I'm just glad we were able to hold him
off.
</P>
<P>
   Duarte's Dennis Arena, who began the race in fifth place in the
track's point standings, finished 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Decuir had a much easier time, winning the 20-lap Mini-Stockar
feature by 3.557 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Decuir, who started third, grabbed the lead on Lap 5 and
stretched his advantage to nearly 500 feet before coasting well
ahead of Bory Molina and Rudy Flores.
</P>
<P>
   The Legends feature was one of the most exciting races of the
evening.
</P>
<P>
   The 25-lap event featured four lead changes, including two over
the final five laps.
</P>
<P>
   Escondido's Seth Hicks, who finished fourth, controlled the race
from the start. He took the lead on Lap 3 and held the advantage
until lap 18.
</P>
<P>
   Riverside's Randy Anderson, who started eighth, drove to the
inside of Hicks on turn 3 and outraced him to the start-finish line
for the lead.
</P>
<P>
   Anderson was unable to hold off Smith, however.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who started second, slipped by Anderson on the back
stretch of Lap 22 before holding off Andderson by .474 seconds at
the finish.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan Schug, who won the trophy dash, was third.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
