<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-PADRES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PADRES' POWER BEATS D-BACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DON KETCHUM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Which team led the major leagues in home runs and
which was barely in double figures?
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks were the club hitting the ball out of the yard
with regularity, and the San Diego Padres were not. On Saturday
night, their roles were reversed.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres sent five into the outer reaches of Qualcomm Stadium,
four on first pitches, and coasted to a 7-2 victory over Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The sellout crowd of 61,674, lured in part by free T-shirts
marking the Padres' 1998 National League championship, was the
biggest regular-season draw in Padres history.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona, whose five-game winning streak ended, fell to 10-8. The
defending National League champion Padres improved to 8-9. The
teams will wrap up their three-game series at 1 p.m. today. The
Diamondbacks then will travel to Houston, the next stop on their
13-game, four-city trip.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie Sanders hit two homers for the Padres, and Tony Gwynn,
Phil Nevin and Greg Myers hit one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Third baseman Matt Williams continued his early season surge for
Arizona, collecting two hits, including his league-leading seventh
of the season and third in three games. He has 306 for his career,
tying Fred Lynn for No. 78 on the all-time list.
</P>
<P>
   Arizona has 34 homers, San Diego 16.
</P>
<P>
   Left-hander Omar Daal was the initial target of the San Diego
sluggers, giving up two home runs. He also walked three in five
innings, throwing 108 pitches. He was charged with the loss, his
first after two victories.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been spoiled by the way Omar has been pitching,''
Diamondbacks Manager Buck Showalter said. ``He got deep in a lot of
counts, and that can force you to give the hitters good pitches to
hit.''
</P>
<P>
   Daal acknowledged that his con trol wasn't at the level he
desired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was behind in the count to about every hitter,'' he said.
``I only walked three, but I've walked too many this season (13 in
26 innings). I will cut down on those, there's no question about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks lit the board first in the first inning against
right-hander Woody Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Right fielder Tony Womack singled to right, stole second (his
sixth steal of the season), moved to third on a groundout to second
base by Jay Bell and scored on a wild pitch.
</P>
<P>
   The lead didn't last long.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn, who would probably win by a landslide if he decided to
run for mayor, ignited the groundswell of support from the packed
house with a two-out homer off Daal in the first inning to tie it
at 1.
</P>
<P>
   Another two-out homer, this one by Sanders, gave the Padres a
2-1 lead in the third inning. Sanders also hit a homer in the
eighth off right-hander Darren Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   The Diamondbacks answered in the fourth when third baseman Matt
Williams out-Williamsed right-hander Woody Williams by hitting a
1-1 pitch into the left field stands with two outs.
</P>
<P>
   San Diego got help from its former center fielder, Steve Finley,
to take a 3-2 lead in the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin singled up the middle with one out, but the ball went
under Finley's glove. It didn't roll too far away, but it was
enough for Nevin to take second. Finley's successor in center for
the Padres, Ruben Rivera, doubled past a diving Matt Williams at
third to bring Nevin home.
</P>
<P>
   Daal held the Padres scoreless in the fifth. Showalter called on
right-hander John Frascatore to start the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Nevin wasted no time with Frascatore, hitting his first pitch
over the fence in center field for a 4-2 lead. Rivera hit his
second double of the night into the right-field corner, and Myers
hit the first pitch from Frascatore for his first homer of the
season and a 6-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Padres came perilously close to increasing their lead in the
seventh off right-hander Vladimir Nunez.
</P>
<P>
   Gwynn led off with a double to left-center, giving him 4,001
career total bases. He is the 54th player in major league history
to accomplish that feat. He also has hit safely in 16 of the club's
17 games.
</P>
<P>
   With two outs, Rivera beat out a slow roller down the third-base
line for his third hit. Nunez walked Myers to load the bases but
got Chris Gomez on a swinging third strike to get out of trouble.
</P>
<P>
   Right-hander Dan Miceli entered the game for the Padres in the
top of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   He gave up a one-out single to Kelly Stinnett and a two-out
single to pinch-hitter Greg Colbrunn but struck out Tony Womack for
the third out. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
