<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 02:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2353 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR     04-25 0841
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BLUES-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOAN PLAYS HERO IN OT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - You couldn't see him, but he was out there. In fact,
he was smack dab in the middle of the circus at center ice. Buried
beneath flailing arms and waving sticks, he was in the epicenter of
the celebration.
</P>
<P>
   Shane Doan couldn't believe it. Probably still can't. Not even
today.
</P>
<P>
   But the hard-luck forward for the Coyotes, the kid with the
candy store smile and altar boy personna, will never forget it. And
neither will his teammates, his coaches or another wild Whiteout
crowd at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Doan delivered in the biggest way imaginable Saturday, reaching
into the crease to sweep in a dramatic, game-winning goal in
overtime as the Coyotes beat the St. Louis Blues, 4-3.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was pretty lucky,'' said Doan, who finished the
regular-season with only six goals. ``The puck just happened to be
sitting there. (Dallas Drake) did all the work and threw it in
front, and I only had to move it an inch to get it over the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was great to be out there when it happened, though. It's
huge. It's hard to explain the way that you feel when you get the
opportunity to play in overtime and you get the opportunity to
score. It's pretty exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   And so, too, is this Western Conference first-round playoff
series. Had the Blues taken this game as they did the opener, it's
likely that the Coyotes' 12-year streak of first-round exits would
continue. Especially with the team lacking the services of injured
star Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   Forget it. Game 5 is here next Friday night. The Whiteout will
live at least for that long.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're right back in this thing now,'' Drake said. ``It's all
tied up and anything can happen. They got a split, and now we go to
St. Louis for two games, but home ice doesn't mean a whole heck of
a lot in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   It meant something Saturday. All you had to do was look up into
the rafters of the arena and watch the streamers float down from
upstairs the second Doan scored at the 8:58 mark of OT.
</P>
<P>
   During the celebration at mid-ice, something else came from
upstairs. A phone call from the video review booth. Officials
needed to confirm that Doan wasn't in the crease when he tapped it
past Grant Fuhr. After a few anxious moments on the Coyotes' bench,
referee Dave Jackson signaled goal and the place went nuts again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew it was good when (Jackson) skated away from the box and
was getting ready to throw his arm out to call it,'' said Coyotes
left wing Keith Tkachuk, who again didn't score but set the tone
with tough-as-nails play.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had my head down, just praying to hear the whistle,'' Drake
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes, who were outshot, 34-28, headed straight to St.
Louis after the game for Game 3 at noon today in the Kiel Center.
Game 4 is there Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get reset and refocused,'' said Blues defenseman
Chris Pronger. ``We've got to get ready for (today) because it's
going to come along pretty quick.''
</P>
<P>
   Nikolai Khabibulin, who came up with some mammoth saves among
his 30-stop performance _ including a point-blank stop from former
Coyote Mike Eastwood early in overtime _ will be back in nets for
Phoenix today if he's able.
</P>
<P>
   Once again, Blues defenseman Al MacInnis almost fractured the
entire bunch himself. His slap shot knocked Juha Ylonen out of the
playoffs with a broken right foot. He had another early goal on the
power play and set up two other scores, giving him two goals and
four assists in two games. But Drake, dropping to the second line
with Ylonen and Doan, countered with a goal and two assists.
</P>
<P>
   Teppo Numminen also stepped up with a power-play goal, ending an
0-for-10 skid in the postseason for the maligned, man-advantage
unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``We changed something from Game 1 to Game 2, and it did afford
us some more scoring opportunities,'' Coyotes Coach Jim Schoenfeld
said of the power play. ``Hopefully, it will get us some more goals
going into Game 3.''
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes thought they had won in regulation. Defenseman Keith
Carney gave them a 3-2 lead with 5:34 left, when he wristed in a
long shot from the high boards, scoring unassisted on the play.
Drake thought it was over. Otherwise, he wouldn't have taunted
Pronger, who has been a 6-foot-6 thorn in this series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just jabbering,'' Drake said, ``I don't even know what I
said to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Drake had to eat those words with 3:18 left in regulation as
Pavol Demitra's goal tied the score at 3 and sent it into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   But, thanks to Doan, now Drake can tell Pronger that he'll meet
him in St. Louis, that the series isn't over and the short-handed
Coyotes aren't dead yet. Anything can happen. Roenick, for example,
was seen scarfing down a plate of food with his teammates after
Saturday's game _ and he was supposed to be sucking his meals
through a straw for the next month.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm doing a lot better,'' JR said. ``We all are right about
now.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 0259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 03:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2354 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-A     04-25 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-COYOTES-BICKLEY-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPTAIN COYOTE, TEAMMATES DIG DEEP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN BICKLEY  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - They pounded away at the ghosts and, in the end, came
up with a gut-wrenching exorcism in the face of impending failure.
An afternoon when the inner substance of a hockey team came alive,
prevailing over injury and logic and creeping death.
</P>
<P>
   And so a series is saved, and a series is born.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes have clawed back into the playoffs. Resisting defeat
because defeat would have meant the end. Winning because there was
no other choice. Led by a man who has moved past the numbers and
finally assumed the mantle of leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Go ahead, exhale. Has any victory been more rewarding?
</P>
<P>
   ``No, no, no,'' Keith Tkachuk said. ``This is it. This is the
win we needed, the one we haven't had in this organization. The
game where everyone put aside everything else and did whatever it
takes to win.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ever wanted to gauge the maturity of a hockey team, this
was the moment. An afternoon when they survived another quick
deficit. A second period when they offered up two shots on goal,
with another bad goal surrendered by Nikolai Khabibulin. An
afternoon when they finally grabbed the lead after 114 minutes of
playoff hockey, only to give it back immediately with alarming
generosity.
</P>
<P>
   An afternoon when they grinded to victory in spite of their
past.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, this doesn't mean that a stigma has been jettisoned
back to Winnipeg. But it does mean that a much-maligned
organization is learning a thing or two about survival.
</P>
<P>
   ``We dug deep,'' Dallas Drake said. ``We dug all the way to our
toes.''
</P>
<P>
   If you ever wanted to gauge the maturity of Tkachuk, if you ever
wanted proof that his new priorities are more reality than
rhetoric, this also was a defining moment.
</P>
<P>
   When the Coyotes left the ice after regulation, they sat in
silence, catching their breath, trying to focus on the moment. Not
a word was said, but when they came back on the ice, the
determination spewed from the captain. Held to one shot on goal
over the first three periods, Tkachuk was everywhere, flying around
the ice, blasting shots at Grant Fuhr.
</P>
<P>
   ``Still couldn't get one to go in, though,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   No, but he led the way. And everyone else followed. An afternoon
when the ``C'' on his sweater never fit better.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to explain the feeling out there,'' said Shane
Doan, author of the game winner. ``Every shot, you could feel your
heart pounding. Every time the puck landed on your stick, you felt
like you had a chance. One time, Niki was on his back making a
save. Unbelievably intense. But we just had to have it. And Keith
set the tone for us.''
</P>
<P>
   You wouldn't know it by the numbers, but Tkachuk is in the midst
of a wonderful series. The match-up with Chris Pronger is already a
classic, but Pronger has landed in the penalty box three times
while Tkachuk has kept his cool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three years ago, it probably would've been different,''
Tkachuk said. ``But you get older, you grow up.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. Three years ago, the numbers would've mattered to a
scoreless Tkachuk. Now, he understands that it's all about winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a force in overtime,'' Keith Carney said. ``He set an
example, and guys followed. And that's just what we need from
Keith.''
</P>
<P>
   Amazing how quickly the course of a series can change. For most
of the game, it was evident that the Blues had found a comfort
zone, skating with little fear of the Coyotes, gaining more and
more confidence with each shift. Before Saturday, the Coyotes had
lost four of their last five playoff games at America West Arena,
and the ``Whiteout'' had no effect on the visitors.
</P>
<P>
   But they weren't ready for the team that took the ice in
overtime.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was the Coyote team we need the rest of the playoffs,''
Tkachuk said.
</P>
<P>
   And now the pressure has shifted. There is a 19-hour turnaround
until Game 3. And a St. Louis team that must regroup with a
36-year-old goalie and two defenseman who logged a combined 77
minutes of ice time on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, they came in here and stole home-ice advantage,''
Drake said. ``But hopefully, we have a little momentum now.''
</P>
<P>
   A little momentum. And a much-needed burst of life. &QL; 
Dan Bickley can be reached at (602) 444-8253 or at
dan.bickley(at)pni.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
