<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 03:01 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2355 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FBN-ELWAY-APPRECIATIO     04-25 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-ELWAY-APPRECIATION-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NO FINAL COMEBACK FOR ELWAY  
 LAST-MINUTE HEROICS MADE HIM A LEGEND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE Schoenfeld  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For years, Art Modell sat on his perch atop Cleveland Stadium
and watched Denver Broncos quarterback John Elway make his life
miserable.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the authority on John Elway,'' said Modell, owner of the
Cleveland Browns until moving the franchise to Baltimore in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Modell was there in 1987 when Elway and the Broncos took over on
their 2-yard line, trailing, 20-13, late in regulation of the AFC
championship game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, they were on the 1{-yard line in the mud,'' Modell
said Saturday. ``He takes them 98{ yards to tie the game. He just
killed us.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen every quarterback ever produced of note _ Sid
Luckman, Sammy Baugh, Johnny Unitas _ and nobody impressed me as
much as John Elway, especially his ability to come from behind.
He's the best two-minute quarterback I've ever seen. He's the
all-time comeback king.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who directed 47 game-saving drives, decided on Friday to
retire after 16 seasons. A formal announcement will be made early
this week at a news conference in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   Three times in the 1980s, Elway broke the Browns' hearts with
late comebacks.
</P>
<P>
   His 98-yard, game-tying drive in '86 still is known
affectionately as ``The Drive.'' The Broncos then won in overtime
to advance to Super Bowl XXI.
</P>
<P>
   ``His presence, his ability to run out of the pocket, his
ability to see the field was remarkable,'' Modell said. ``It was
third and long, he'd find a way to get that first down. He'd stop
the clock. He'd get everyone in the right position. He had so much
confidence in his ability to move the team.''
</P>
<P>
   Bob Ferguson, vice president-player personnel director of the
Cardinals, spent three seasons with Elway in Denver from 1993 to
1995. But before that, he competed against him when Ferguson worked
for the Dallas Cowboys and Buffalo Bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a threat from the day he walked on the (NFL) field,''
Ferguson said. ``It wasn't beating the Broncos. You had to beat
Elway.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody (in scouting) used to say, `Is he an Elway-type
player?' That was the ultimate compliment. You were describing the
best. Not many can say they are an Elway-type player.''
</P>
<P>
   Elway finished his career with more victories (148) than any
quarterback in NFL history. He threw for 51,475 yards and accounted
for 54,882 yards, second only to Miami's Dan Marino.
</P>
<P>
   He was the first quarterback to start five Super Bowls, winning
the last two, including a 34-19 victory over Atlanta last January.
He completed 18 of 29 passes for 336 yards and a touchdown, earning
the Most Valuable Player Award.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you take everything in consideration, he's the best to play
the position,'' said New York Giants Coach Jim Fassel, the former
Cardinals offensive coordinator, who coached Elway for two years at
Stanford and then again in Denver from 1993-94.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy had an unbelievable career. I don't know if anyone
went to the Super Bowl more and he won two titles. He has done a
lot for the game and is a great example, a role-model type guy.
That's why I always admired him. His comebacks, durability,
competitiveness, arm strength . . . you put all that package
together with longevity, I think you can build a strong case that
he's the best to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Few athletes have ever been more popular in the town in which
they played.
</P>
<P>
   Elway, who will be 39 in June, gets about 4,000 letters from
fans each month.
</P>
<P>
   When he was a rookie, Denver newspapers tried to follow him into
a barbershop to photograph him getting sheared. It was big news in
Denver each October what Elway gave out on Halloween.
</P>
<P>
   A Denver woman once called Elway's secretary and asked if her
husband, who was about Elway's size, could borrow some of his
clothes for their trip to Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   ``My daughter, Vanessa, worked for John Elway Nissan,'' said
Ferguson of the seven car dealerships in Denver Elway once owned.
``His businesses were so successful. He wasn't afraid to do what it
took to be the best in whatever he did.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was just a tremendous honor to be in the same locker room
with him. I lived with his dad (Broncos director of pro scouting
Jack Elway) when I first got to Denver, and I got to know John
personally. He's a great competitor and a fun guy to be around. The
leadership role people wanted from him was not his cup of tea. He
just wanted to play.''
</P>
<P>
   Many forget the Broncos didn't draft Elway. The Baltimore Colts
did, but Elway refused to play there, so the Colts traded him to
Denver for quarterback Mark Herrmann, rookie offensive lineman
Chris Hinton and a first-round pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was one of the worst mistakes the Baltimore Colts ever
made, and they know it,'' Ferguson said.
</P>
<P>
   Elway's NFL career didn't start out great. He completed only 1
of 8 passes, was sacked four times and intercepted in his first NFL
game, a season-opening loss at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, a national TV commentator said, ``I don't care
how hard it is to adjust to the NFL, that is pathetic.''
</P>
<P>
   He led the Broncos to Super Bowls following the 1986, '87 and
'90 seasons, but they were routed each time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took so much criticism from the media and others,''
Ferguson said. ``People in Seattle called him, `Mr. Ed,' for his
toothy smile. For him to roll most of that off his shoulders, he's
just a really, really class person.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in 1997, Elway won a Super Bowl crown in the Broncos'
31-24 victory over the Green Bay Packers, ending a 13-game AFC
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   The Broncos won again the next year and some thought Elway would
want to return to try to help them become the first team to win
three consecutive Super Bowl crowns.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, he decided he needed to spend more time with his wife
and four kids.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad to see him go out on top,'' Ferguson said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
