r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SUNS-ATTENDANCE-A     04-25 0907
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SUNS-ATTENDANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUNS GRATEFUL DROP-OFF IN TICKET SALES MINIMAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By NORM FRAUENHEIM  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The predictions promised nothing. There would be no
Antonio McDyess. There would be no visit from Michael Jordan. There
would be only echoes and empties. Empty seats. An empty arena. And,
eventually, empty coffers.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't quite worked out that way in the NBA's post-Jordan,
post-lockout, air ball era. In fact, the Suns are surprised _
probably relieved _ that the America West Arena box office hasn't
suddenly turned into a temple of doom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Candidly, the fallout is less than I thought it would be,''
Suns President Jerry Colangelo said. ``The whole league was
predicting doom and gloom.''
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, the number of empty seats at America West Arena and
elsewhere are enough to signal an alarm. There is no disaster. But
one looms if complacency is the response to a mere decline.
</P>
<P>
   First, the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns averaged 18,885 in ticket sales through their first 21
home games. For the first time since 1990, they fell 138 short of
averaging a sellout. Their decade-long string was broken on Feb. 9
against Sacramento.
</P>
<P>
   Going into today's game against Houston, six other games fell
short of a sellout _ Cleveland, Vancouver, twice against Dallas and
twice against Golden State.
</P>
<P>
   The Suns have climbed a couple of spots in attendance rankings
to seventh from ninth last year. Translation: The Suns haven't
slipped as much as the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   But there's another important factor. Unlike the National
Football League, the NBA does not include no-shows in the crowd
figure that is at the bottom of box scores each day. That number
simply represents the number of tickets sold. Nonetheless, no-shows
have been evident all season at America West Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo says the no-show count is up about 100 a game from
last season. In the Suns' heyday six years ago, no-shows amounted
to a handful of people, who always could get a premium price for
their tickets on the streets outside the arena.
</P>
<P>
   The no-show count is important because it indicates the level of
interest. Corporations own many of the season tickets, but if they
can't give them away, the product might have a problem.
</P>
<P>
   For the Suns, there are reasons specific to themselves and the
Valley, as well as to the league.
</P>
<P>
   Here are just a few:
</P>
<P>
   All Suns home games have been televised by Cox, Channel 45 or
Channel 12. Pay-per-view, as we remember it, is dead. Why purchase
a seat in the upper deck if you can watch the game, up close and
personal, from the comfort of your living room couch for free or
for the cost of basic cable?
</P>
<P>
   Competition for the sports dollar never has been so intense with
the Diamondbacks, Cardinals, Coyotes and Arizona State.
</P>
<P>
   ``The landscape continues to evolve,'' said Colangelo, who added
to the competition with the introduction of the Diamondbacks.
``There is the advent of hockey, but that has really had no impact
on the Suns. That's a cult following, a very loyal and vocal one.
But there's little crossover between NHL and Suns fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``Baseball presents another interest, and there's the resurgence
of the Cardinals. But they play eight home games. It's limited.
With the Diamondbacks, there's annual attendance of 3 million.
That's a different factor. The Suns recognize that the competition
is keen.''
</P>
<P>
   In the seats themselves, differences have been noticed. In part,
the crowd has changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been a lot of no-shows,'' said Irving Shuman, who
purchased the first block of season tickets for the franchise's
inaugural season, 1968-69, at Veterans Memorial Coliseum. ``Also, a
lot of people around me are strangers. I think there were some
people who gave up their tickets because they were frustrated by
the greed exhibited by the players and owners during the lockout.''
</P>
<P>
   Shuman wasn't exactly an ardent fan in the season's early weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was very disenchanted,'' he said. ``I was one of those who
thought that the season shouldn't be played at all. But now, I'm
beginning like what I see. I'm still a basketball fan.''
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo and the rest of the league are counting on customers
such as Shuman, who said his interest was reignited by the
consistently brilliant play of Suns guard Jason Kidd. A slight
increase in television ratings from last season indicates a loyal
fan base that missed the game during its absence.
</P>
<P>
   The concern, now, is not to turn off those customers with a
ragged style of play. It has bogged down into a half-court,
post-up, stand-around, slam-dunk, two-man game. On some nights,
field goal percentages look like mortgage rates.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo has noticed. He said he already is asking for change
in informal talks with NBA Commissioner David Stern. The old city
game is in need of urban renewal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to quicken the game, we need to bring back more
freedom in the open court,'' said Colangelo, a former chairman of
the Competition and Rules Committee, whose suggestions include a
wider lane, more vigilance on the three-second call and a quicker
shot clock. ``Coaches with lesser talented teams are able to keep
scores down with a half-court style.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has diminished the beauty of the game. I'm pushing for
immediate change. We don't need to experiment.''
</P>
<P>
   The empty seats may provide the evidence. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
