<HEADER>
A2357 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DBACKS-ATTENDANCE     04-25 0763
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DBACKS-ATTENDANCE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
D-BACKS DISAPPOINTED IN EARLY ATTENDANCE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By LES POLK  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - While the Diamondbacks have been getting into a good
groove on the field this season, BOB has a touch of the blues.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance at Bank One Ballpark for Arizona's first 10 games of
the 1999 season is off 25 percent from last year's inaugural season
_ or 11,815 fans per game.
</P>
<P>
   The average per game has dropped to 34,370 this year, compared
with 46,185 for the first 10 games last year when BOB and the team
were brand new _ and ticket prices were lower.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dropoff, going into this weekend's games Arizona was
ninth in the major leagues in average attendance per game and sixth
in the National League. Leading the major leagues was the Colorado
Rockies, at 43,021 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Attendance figures are somewhat difficult to compare this early
in the season because of the disparity in the number of home games,
and because some teams may have had more attractive opening
homestands than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been somewhat surprised and disappointed by the numbers
to date,'' said Jerry Colangelo, managing general partner of the
Diamondbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Officials knew attendance would be off because season-ticket
sales fell by about 9,000 to 27,000 in the wake of a 12 percent
rise in prices. But they hadn't planned on this much of a decline.
</P>
<P>
   Theories explaining the dropoff range from the Cactus League's
banner March to season-ticket prices to school being in session and
the novelty of Major League Baseball wearing off.
</P>
<P>
   The Cactus League drew nearly a million fans this spring, and a
baseball burnout factor may be at work.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo said no other major league team is in a market that is
exposed to so much baseball in the month leading up to the season.
While Florida has more teams training there overall, they are
scattered around the state. The Valley alone has seven teams for
spring and Tucson three.
</P>
<P>
   Colangelo also is disappointed in attendance for games when
Randy Johnson is the starting pitcher. Part of the attraction in
signing Johnson to a lucrative contract was a projected spike in
ticket sales for his games, but that hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the smallest crowd in last season's first 10 home games
was 42,876. This season the team has drawn only one crowd over
40,000, and that was on opening day when the announced attendance
was a sellout of 46,929, but empty seats were evident in the upper
deck corners.
</P>
<P>
   The franchise attendance low was set against the Phillies on
Monday, when the announced attendance was 29,704.
</P>
<P>
   For Johnson's first outing, against the Los Angeles Dodgers on a
Thursday night, the attendance was announced at 36,105. His second
start, on Tuesday against the Phillies, drew 30,546.
</P>
<P>
   Total attendance for the season so far is off more than 118,000.
That's a lot of $8 beers.
</P>
<P>
   But the price of concessions can't really be blamed for an
attendance decline. Prices remain the same this year as last, and
more items are available. Fans are still free to bring in their own
food and non-alcoholic drinks.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the paying customers grumble about the ushers and their
supervisors' strict policies around the concourse and attitude
toward fans who might want to just hang out by the railing or in
center field for an inning. But Colangelo and others say those fans
are a tiny part of the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Director of Security George Bevard said it's a ``double-edged
sword'' when you have policies that please most fans but not all.
</P>
<P>
   At the Team Shop, the paying customers are still in a buying
mood.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Namberg, vice president of the shops, said business is good
and the sales are way ahead of projections.
</P>
<P>
   Namberg had figured sales would be off about 18 percent this
season because attendance would fall, but total sales haven't
dropped at all, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously we couldn't meet opening day last year, but this
year's opening day was the third biggest retail day we've ever
had,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Weekends are as good as last year, but weekdays have been soft
with school still in session.
</P>
<P>
   And Colangelo thinks it will be children and families sitting in
$10 seats who deliver higher attendance figures as school winds
down and the season evolves _ perhaps into the Diamondbacks
contending in a pennant race.
</P>
<P>
   The vast majority of tickets remaining for games this season are
in the $10 range.
</P>
<P>
   ``The numbers are going to get better,'' he said. ``The team is
competitive.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
