<HEADER>
A2358 &Cx1f; tic-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZ     04-25 1072
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-YOUNG-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS JOB IS BEST BET FOR JACKSON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB YOUNG  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Nothing was surprising about the demotion last week of  &UR; Ernie
 &UR; Grunfeld from Knicks general manager to a post as assistant to
 &UR; Dave
 &UR; Checketts, president of Madison Square Garden, which controls the
Knicks.
</P>
<P>
   But the timing was curious.
</P>
<P>
   Grunfeld has made some bad personnel decisions, including the
trade of forward  &UR; Charles Oakley to Toronto, which removed all the
toughness from the once-feared Knicks. But why not wait until the
end of the season?
</P>
<P>
   Here's why: Checketts became the acting general manager, and
he's going to travel with the team and stay in close contact in the
remaining weeks of the season to determine for himself whether
 &UR; Jeff
 &UR; Van Gundy is going to be the head coach beyond this season.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the rumblings have begun again about  &UR; Phil Jackson, who
is practicing his Zen on the presidential campaign trail for former
Sen.
 &UR; Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Could Jackson be the new coach? The new GM? Both?
</P>
<P>
   Don't bet against it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no change in Phil's schedule,'' Jackson's agent,
 &UR; Todd
 &UR; Musburger, told the ``Chicago Sun-Times.'' ``He continues with his
(corporate motivational) speaking engagements and he continues
working for his good friend, Senator Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   The coaches of Los Angeles Lakers, New Jersey Nets, Washington
Wizards and Charlotte Hornets all have interim tags.  &UR; Rick Pitino
in Boston and  &UR; Brian Hill in Vancouver also could be in trouble, so
Jackson will be back.
</P>
<P>
   But the Knicks job always has been the one coveted by Jackson,
who played there.
</P>
<P>
   For now, though, Checketts wants to see the Knicks in the
playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``This organization has to be completely focused now on (the
last) eight games and on making the playoffs,'' Checketts told New
York reporters upon announcing Grunfeld's reassignment. ``The
reason I did what I did was, frankly, so that for those eight games
and hopefully the playoffs, I can be involved in a day-to-day way,
and this summer, understand fully what the issues of this club are
and where we go next.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts dropped several hints in his comments about the mess
that suggest Grunfeld and Van Gundy weren't on the same page.
</P>
<P>
   He was asked whether Grunfeld should be held accountable for the
club's struggles.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you mean the dynamics of what an organization can go
through in a season _ not just player moves, but everybody having a
mission, a strategy, agreeing on where we're headed, and supporting
decisions and making them together _ yes, I would hold him
accountable.''
</P>
<P>
   But he isn't clearing Van Gundy just yet, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll only say the organization has not functioned very well
together,'' he said when asked about Van Gundy's role. ``It was
just more like a continued direction with critical people
throughout the organization (who) did not support the mission. And
there was division, clearly. For that, I hold him and myself
responsible.''
</P>
<P>
   Checketts said he'll reserve judgment on why the Knicks have
foundered until the season is over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I know, but the ma[QQreason I did this (demote
Grunfeld) was so that I really know,'' he said. ``I've been
watching this team just like you. But now I want to be close, and
in the circle of what's going on before I make any more
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   Doing the job &QL; 
Is there any doubt that  &UR; Paul Silas has earned a contract from the
Charlotte Hornets?
</P>
<P>
   The club was 4-11 when  &UR; Dave Cowens quit in frustration. The
team's second-best player,  &UR; Anthony Mason, was out for the season.
And the club's star,  &UR; Glen Rice, was milking an elbow injury in
hopes of being traded.
</P>
<P>
   Granted, the deal that sent Rice to the Lakers for  &UR; Elden
Campbell and  &UR; Eddie Jones made Silas a better coach right away. But
he used that deal as the impetus to turn the club around.
</P>
<P>
   The Hornets are 17-10 since then, and they had a nine-game
winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   Detroit's  &UR; Alvin Gentry, a friend of Silas' who went through the
same `interim'' situation and earned the Pistons job, can relate to
what Silas is going through.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's obvious to anyone he can manage players,'' Gentry said.
``Three weeks ago, no one in this league thought they'd be (.500).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough (being in an interim position). The way you walk on
the court, the way you sit on the bench, the way you call timeouts
_ you know everything is being evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to just do the job, but there's never a comfort
level.''
</P>
<P>
   Silas, who has been down this route before, said he's doing the
job just as he would if he had a 10-year contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``I expect people to respect me,'' he said. ``I give it, and I
expect it in return.''
</P>
<P>
   He's getting it from around the league. And since owner  &UR; George
Shinn and prospective co-owner  &UR; Michael Jordan reportedly have
agreed that Silas should get a new contract, what's the holdup? &QL; 
He's back &QL; 
Nets center  &UR; Jayson Williams, who underwent 4{ hours of surgery to
repair his fractured right leg, getting a metal plate, four screws
and a bone graft from his hip, is a long way from playing again.
But at least he has had time to work on his comedy routine.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was hurt when he collided with teammate  &UR; Stephon
Marbury, who also hit the floor. Marbury's mom,  &UR; Mabel, rushed onto
the court to check on her son.
</P>
<P>
   Williams had heard his leg snap, but that wasn't his first
concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to move out the way and not get stepped on by Mrs.
Marbury,'' he said. ``That was my first reaction,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And he had thoughts on the wheelchair he was in, which was
rigged to hold his leg straight out.
</P>
<P>
   ``This contraption was just invented. We didn't have a
wheelchair long enough for my leg, so my brother, Victor, told me
to sit on the crutch, so that's what this is.
</P>
<P>
   ``It ain't no modern science. Victor's not that smart. He only
got out of the seventh grade.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Williams recalled his propensity for predictions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember telling you (media) guys that an ambulance would
have to take me out of here. And it did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The one prediction I predicted right in eight years here. I
picked championships, a playoff series over the Knicks, and that an
ambulance would take me out of here before I give up. And sure
enough, here come the sirens.'' &QL; 
Bob Young can be reached at (602) 444-8271 or at
bob.young(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
