<SLUG> BC-HKN-NOTEBOOK-MCMANAMAN-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POSTPONING SERIES WAS CORRECT MOVE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB MCMANAMAN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The NHL did the right thing by postponing the Colorado
Avalanche-San Jose Sharks series in the wake of last week's
shooting tragedy at Columbine High School in Littleton, Colo.,
which killed 15 people and left more than 20 wounded.
</P>
<P>
   The series began Saturday, four days after it was scheduled to
open in Denver. It also was moved to San Jose for the first two
games, another wise move, considering the circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Colorado fans weren't ready to celebrate playoff hockey.
Avalanche players weren't into it, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The tragedy got to us,'' Colorado Coach  &UR; Bob Hartley said.
``There are many dads on our team. I'm a dad, and it's been pretty
tough to focus on hockey. . . . But we want to dedicate our games
to Columbine High School.''
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche players will wear school patches on their sleeves
throughout the playoffs, a nice move as well.
</P>
<P>
   On not playing at home until Games 3, 4 and 5, Hartley said,
``Looking at what this community has gone through, I think worrying
about home ice would be very selfish.'' &QL; 
Trivia time
</P>
<P>
   Pitcher  &UR; Guy Bush served up the last home run to  &UR; Babe Ruth on
May 25, 1935. Any idea who the goalie was when  &UR; Wayne Gretzky
scored his last goal?
</P>
<P>
   It was  &UR; Wade Flaherty of the New York Islanders.
</P>
<P>
   ``If your name is going down as a trivia answer, that's the name
you want it beside _ Wayne Gretzky,'' Flaherty said. ``It's pretty
cool. You're like the guy who gave up  &UR; Mark McGwire's 62nd home
run. You're one of those guys who most people ask about but don't
remember. But I will.'' &QL; 
Bubba in Nashville
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's true. The expansion Nashville Predators, who have done
virtually everything right in their first season, went above and
beyond the call of duty by acquiring a hockey player who's name is
Bubba.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday,  &UR; Andrew ``Bubba'' Berenzweig, a senior defenseman and
captain at the University of Michigan, went to Hockey Tonk town
from the Islanders in exchange for a fourth-round pick in the June
NHL entry draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I had to pick a team to play for, it would be Nashville _
and my name definitely has something to do with that,'' said
Berenzweig, who helped Michigan to two NCAA championships. ``It
almost seems like destiny.''
</P>
<P>
   Berenzweig, a fifth-round pick by the Islanders in '96, said
he's gone exclusively by the first name of Bubba since he was a
toddler. Good thing, too, seeing as how the Predators actually have
a ``Bubba-cam'' during home games, when they periodically scan the
crowd searching for a face to fit the name.
</P>
<P>
   Said Bubba: ``The only one who still calls me Andrew is my
grandmother.'' &QL; 
Who are you?
</P>
<P>
   Mighty Ducks of Anaheim goalie  &UR; Guy Hebert must hate to see
 &UR; Brendan
 &UR; Shanahan in the playoffs. Two years ago, Hebert ripped a groin
muscle making a save on the Detroit Red Wings forward and was lost
for the rest of the second-round series.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1 of this year's first-round match-up, Shanahan got
shoved from behind and his skate whacked Hebert in the face mask.
After 10 minutes, Hebert had to leave the game because of
grogginess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I walked into the locker room, and I wasn't sure who I was,''
Hebert said. ``Guys were telling me I was  &UR; Dominik Hasek.''
</P>
<P>
   Hebert returned, only to lose both Games 1 and 2, allowing a
playoff-high eight goals _ two by Shanahan. &QL; 
Loose pucks
</P>
<P>
   San Jose forward  &UR; Owen Nolan got the Sharks' series with the
Avalanche off to a flying start by taking several pre-playoff
verbal shots at Colorado players. Among other things, Nolan said
the Avalanche ``don't have anything'' on the third and fourth lines
and that  &UR; Patrick Roy isn't so great.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's either unbeatable or things just go flying by him,''
Nolan said. ``He's either on top of his game or he lets in the
weakest goals.''
</P>
<P>
   Roy wasn't about to let Nolan get under his skin.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get involved in that,'' Roy said. ``For me,
it's extremely important to focus on what I have to do and play
well. There's no need for me to answer back. I don't feel you start
things like that before a series starts. I don't feel I have to
prove anything to Owen Nolan whatsoever.''
</P>
<P>
   The four players Detroit picked up at the trading deadline _
 &UR; Chris Chelios, Ulf Samuelsson, Wendel Clark and  &UR; Bill
 &UR; Ranford _ entered the postseason having played in a combined 414
playoff games. The entire roster on the Mighty Ducks had appeared
in just 399.
</P>
<P>
   A couple of surprise scratches early in the postseason saw
Carolina sit veteran defenseman  &UR; Paul Coffey and Buffalo park
assistant captain  &UR; Rob Ray.
</P>
<P>
   Former Coyote  &UR; Jim McKenzie has been sporting painted toenails
lately _ a dark shade of purple _ courtesy of his 5-year-old
daughter,  &UR; Taylor. She wanted to pain them pink for the Ducks'
playoffs, but the big fella thought that was pushing it just a bit.
</P>
<P>
   The three-year deal Nashville gave to prospect  &UR; David
 &UR; Legwand, the second overall pick in last year's draft, is
potentially worth $9 million _ the second-biggest entry-level
contract ever in the NHL. The largest deal belongs to Tampa Bay's
 &UR; Vincent Lecavalier, the No. 1 pick last year, who can conceivably
earn as much as $15 million if certain incentive clauses are
reached.
</P>
<P>
   Sly move by Sabres Coach  &UR; Lindy Ruff, having the team blow off
morning skate on the day of Buffalo's playoff opener at Ottawa.
Instead, he gathered everyone and they went for a walk along a
canal to talk about the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted them out of their rooms and thinking about the team
and each other,'' Ruff said. ``We just walked and talked about
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Right now, they're talking about a possible sweep after grabbing
a 2-0 series lead over the favored Senators. &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Bob McManaman can be
reached at (602) 444-8326 or at bob.mcmanaman(at)pni.com via
e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
