<HEADLINE>
SURPRISE SCORERS GIVE COYOTES TIE IN SERIES  
 USUAL OFFENSE EITHER HURT OR HEAVILY GUARDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By TIM TYERS  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Keith Tkachuk wore St. Louis defenseman Chris Pronger and his
friends on his shoulders like an oversized, bargain basement suit.
The combination was so ill-fitting that Tkachuk couldn't make his
usual fashion statement on ice: Racking up lots of points.
</P>
<P>
   Plus, two of the Coyotes' top five scorers were out _ Greg Adams
because of a strained groin, along with Jeremy Roenick.
</P>
<P>
   To say the Coyotes needed scoring help to maintain serious
playoff hopes went without saying. The answer came from four
unexpected sources.
</P>
<P>
   The Coyotes received goals from Dallas Drake, defensemen Teppo
Numminen and Keith Carney and forward Shane Doan to win, 4-3 in
overtime, and even the playoff series at one apiece.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, the combined total for this quartet over the
82-game regular season was 27 goals. Drake had nine, Numminen 10,
Carney two and Doan six. Saturday's output was manna from heaven.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what it takes in the playoffs,'' said Carney, whose
slapper from the point gave Phoenix a 3-2 lead with 5{ minutes left
in regulation. ``Of course, you need your top scorers on their
game, playing their game and providing offense, but it takes
everybody in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, their best defensive people were on our best, like
we tried to do. If you look at your successful teams in the
playoffs, it takes more than your first-liners. It takes your
second-, third- and fourth-liners to chip in.''
</P>
<P>
   Adams' injury caused Phoenix Coach Jim Schoenfeld to move
second-liner Robert Reichel to center the first line between
Tkachuk and Rick Tocchet, which created a second line of Drake,
Doan and Juha Ylonen.
</P>
<P>
   Drake produced a tie at 1 at 5:53 of the second period, scoring
on a beautiful cycle of passes from Ylonen and Doan. Doan produced
the game winner at 8:58, banging home a rebound on which Drake and
Ylonen, who had just six goals all season, assisted.
</P>
<P>
   ``Me, Juha and Doaner realize a lot of pressure is put on Keith,
Tocchet and Robert to score, and we came out and got a couple,
which is what we have to do,'' Drake said. ``I knew our line
combination on Friday, and it was fine with me.
</P>
<P>
   ``Put your three top guys on the Number 1 and let them bang
away. That's how it should be. But me, Juha and Doaner stepped up
to the plate today. It was a huge win. We couldn't go to St. Louis
down 2-0. This gives us a little confidence against a good team.
Hopefully, we can bang a few more off from here.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan said he had divine help on his game winner. He played with
a biblical verse _ Romans 8:28 _ on the blade of his stick, which
reads, ``In all things God works for good for those who love and
believe in him and seek his purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   He said playing with his new linemates was exciting, adding,
``Juha, Dally and I all play the same style, really. Dally and Juha
are a little more offensive, and Dally is so physical and he
creates so much room with his hits.''
</P>
<P>
   Numminen's goal, which tied the game at 2 at 2:15 of the third
period, was huge for a couple of reasons. First, it was a
power-play goal, the Coyotes' first in 11 chances in the series,
and slowed a special-teams trend that had been, and still is,
lopsided in the Blues' favor.
</P>
<P>
   Second, it came early in the period and gave Phoenix new life
and offset a potentially backbreaking second-period goal by Pierre
Turgeon that put the Blues up, 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been getting shots, but they haven't gone in,'' Numminen
said. ``It was good to get a power-play goal. We can relax now and
gain confidence from that. Going on the road, we have to be even
stronger defensively, especially on our penalty kill.
</P>
<P>
   ``Getting goals from the players we did is good. That's playoff
hockey. Everybody has to be playing at the top of their game, and
everybody has to contribute. That's what wins.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
