<HEADLINE>
YLONEN'S RIGHT FOOT IS BROKEN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By REPUBLIC STAFF  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - The Coyotes suffered another injury to a key player,
learning after Saturday's 4-3 overtime win over St. Louis that
center  &UR; Juha Ylonen will miss the remainder of the playoffs because
of a broken right foot.
</P>
<P>
   Ylonen, the hard-working Finn who had two assists in Saturday's
Game 2 of the first-round series, including an assist on the
game-winning goal by  &UR; Shane Doan, suffered the fracture when he was
hit in the ankle area by a slap shot from Blues defenseman  &UR; Al
MacInnis.
</P>
<P>
   The team said he will be sidelined for four to six weeks. The
injury to Ylonen, one of the team's best defensive forwards and
penalty killers, comes on the heels of injuries to star center
 &UR; Jeremy
 &UR; Roenick and second-line left wing  &UR; Greg Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Roenick is out indefinitely because of a broken jaw and a
fractured right thumb. Adams missed Game 2 because of a groin pull
and will miss Game 3 today in St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big loss, but you have to just keep right on going,''
General Manager  &UR; Bobby Smith said. ``Juha's a very valuable player
who will come back and play for us, but we've got a guy in  &UR; Bob
Corkum who can step up and fill that role, and hopefully, we'll
have Adams back for Game 4 (on Tuesday).''
</P>
<P>
   Ylonen is the third Phoenix player to suffer a broken bone this
season because of a slap shot from MacInnis, who possesses the
hardest shot in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not enough you have to worry about him shooting it in
your net or faking it and setting up a guy for a goal,'' Smith
said, ``but he breaks an important player's foot.'' &QL; 
Injury update &QL; 
Adams, who pulled himself from Game 1 on the final shift, missed
six games because of a similar groin injury in late February and
early March.
</P>
<P>
   Also, the team reduced the recovery time of defensemen  &UR; Deron
Quint (concussion) and  &UR; Gerald Diduck (broken foot) to one week,
which means both could be available by Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Quint has set his sights earlier, saying he hopes to return by
Game 4 on Tuesday in St. Louis. &QL; 
High-stick anxiety &QL; 
Intensity in Game 2 picked up a notch Saturday, and so did the
chatter.
</P>
<P>
   Coyotes right wing  &UR; Dallas Drake and Blues defenseman  &UR; Chris
Pronger were among the players trading words. After Coyotes
defenseman  &UR; Chris
 &UR; Carney scored an unassisted third-period goal to give his team a
3-2 lead, Drake was in Pronger's face.
</P>
<P>
   But just over two minutes later, St. Louis tied the score on a
 &UR; Pavol
 &UR; Demitra goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Drake's talking) sure came back to haunt him pretty quick,
didn't it?'' Pronger said. ``That's what you get for being a
moron.''
</P>
<P>
   Pronger also said he was high-sticked by Drake earlier in the
period and it wasn't called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Name any play and I got high-sticked,'' he said. ``Apparently,
it's not a penalty to get high-sticked. Only if I do it. I've got
the reputation, so . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The prognosticator &QL; 
Maybe  &UR; Charlie Simmer should book a flight to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   During the intermission before the Coyotes' game-winning goal,
the Fox analyst told partner  &UR; Doug McLeod that Doan would be the
one to score it.
</P>
<P>
   Sure enough, Doan did, 8:58 into overtime.
</P>
<P>
   McLeod credited Simmer on the air after it happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you get a feel just from how guys are playing,''
Simmer said. &QL; 
A small change &QL; 
Coyotes Coach  &UR; Jim Schoenfeld removed center  &UR; Robert Reichel from
the No. 1 power-play team after its first chance came up empty. The
coach elevated forward  &UR; Dallas Drake to the first unit.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looked to me like Dallas was having a game,'' Schoenfeld
said. ``It was nothing against Robert at all. But we had  &UR; Keith
( &UR; Tkachuk) and  &UR; Rick ( &UR; Tocchet), who are our 1-2 right now, and it
looked like Dallas was going to have a night. He was getting some
loose pucks, and that's what you need on the power play.'' &QL; 
Republic writers Paola Boivin, Bob McManaman and Tim Tyers
contributed to this article. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
