<SLUG> BC-HKN-BLUES-SIDER-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACINNIS SHOWS WORTH TO BLUES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PAOLA BOIVIN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHOENIX - Al MacInnis made a beeline for St. Louis' massage
therapist after Saturday's 4-3 overtime loss to the Coyotes. He
should have requested additional treatment for his ego.
</P>
<P>
   It can't be easy carrying a team on your back for two games and
have only a 1-1 split to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   How big an impact has the defenseman made in this Western
Conference quarterfinal series? He has played a role in all six St.
Louis goals.
</P>
<P>
   ``His two games have reflected his play all year,'' Blues Coach
Joel Quenneville said. ``He has been outstanding for us. He likes a
lot of minutes; he controls the puck. He's got that weapon and he's
willing to shoot it. Nobody can shoot it like that. It's got
eyes.''
</P>
<P>
   His power-play goal 5:31 into the first period Saturday gave the
Blues a 1-0 lead, and his two assists contributed to St. Louis'
other two scores. His first was a feed to Pierre Turgeon in the
second period that Turgeon let fly over goalie Nikolai Khabibulin's
right pad, and the second was a perfect pass to Pavol Demitra, who
was wide open on the power play.
</P>
<P>
   In Thursday's opener, he scored on a first-period slap shot from
the blue line and added two assists.
</P>
<P>
   Six St. Louis goals, six MacInnis points. Not bad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, he's been in on all the goals, but sometimes we'd like
to spread it out some more and get more guys involved,''
Quenneville said.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis said, ``I'm not concerned about the others. It's only
been two games. Obviously, we have to rely on other guys as well,
and I'm sure they'll step up in Games 3 and 4.''
</P>
<P>
   The most telling moment of Saturday's game came when MacInnis
wasn't on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   Less than two minutes into the third period, he was sent into
the penalty box for tripping. It took only 38 seconds for the
Coyotes to score what was the biggest goal of the day (until the
game winner): a shot by Teppo Numminen that tied the score at 2 and
seemed to turn the momentum the Coyotes' way.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the loss, St. Louis players are optimistic about their
chances in this series. And why not? They've come a long way.
</P>
<P>
   When the Blues didn't bring back Brett Hull and Steve Duchesne
before the season, many feared the worst, especially for the team's
power play. Instead, they are ranked No. 2 in the NHL this season.
</P>
<P>
   MacInnis, whose shot is the equivalent of a Nolan Ryan fastball,
is a big reason. Ask the Coyotes.
</P>
<P>
   Center Juha Ylonen is out four to six weeks because of a broken
right foot that had an up-close-and-personal meeting with a
MacInnis shot Saturday. Mike Sullivan and Dallas Drake suffered
broken toes in earlier meetings with MacInnis' slap slot.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents will tell you it's a no-win situation covering
MacInnis. ``He's difficult to handle, no doubt about it,'' St.
Louis defenseman Chris Pronger said. ``You want him on your side.
</P>
<P>
   ``He plays a lot of minutes and he's always coming up with big
plays. I think that's been pretty evident by what he's done in two
games.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
