r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZ     04-25 2664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-GOMEZ-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BETTER THAN '95  
 INDIANS ADD PITCHING TO HEFTY HITTING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By PEDRO GOMEZ  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the final weeks of spring training, Cleveland Manager
 &UR; Mike
 &UR; Hargrove issued a challenge to his club, telling them simply
winning the American League Central would not be enough.
</P>
<P>
   Hargrove wanted the Indians to be the very best they could for
each of the 162 games, wanting to reach 100 victories in the
process. A little less than three weeks into the season,
Cleveland's players seem to be taking the matter seriously.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians entered the weekend as the hottest club since the
start of the season. Their .326 team batting average entering the
weekend was 20 points higher than anyone else in the majors.
</P>
<P>
   More impressive, the Indians' 3.94 ERA was the third-best in the
AL. And until  &UR; Charles Nagy lost Thursday night, Cleveland starters
were 7-0. The bullpen had a combined ERA of 1.13 entering the
weekend series against Boston, and the club had outscored its
opponents 101-59 in its first 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the best team I've ever been on,'' said reliever  &UR; Paul
 &UR; Shuey, who has been on each of the Indians division-winning clubs
of the past four years. ``That (1995) team was awesome. It was an
unreal experience being on that team. But I think this one is
better. I think we have better pitching than the '95 team, and
we've got guys on this staff that haven't even reached their
potential. When that happens look out!''
</P>
<P>
   Shuey's sentiments are equally being tossed around by baseball
people who know such things. This club is showing it may be capable
of anything, including winning the franchise's first World Series
since 1948.
</P>
<P>
   Don't forget, this Indians club is winning big without much help
from
 &UR; David Justice, who has been injured and was the only starter with
an average under .300 before the weekend series. Also, the
uncharacteristic defensive lapses of Gold Glove shortstop  &UR; Omar
 &UR; Vizquel, who has three errors already after committing five all of
last season, have not helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team has the same belief in itself as the '95 team,''
Hargrove said. ``The difference is that this team is not as
arrogant as the '95 team.''
</P>
<P>
   The 1995 Indians posted an absurd 100-44 record during the
strike-shortened season, winning their division by 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   This club is getting tremendous power from right fielder  &UR; Manny
 &UR; Ramirez, who led the majors in RBI with 23 entering the weekend
series. He was also batting .369 with five home runs and is
apparently unhappy with his contract status, which will pay him $4
million this year and in 2000, when the club has an option.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez, who turned down a $56 million seven-year extension
recently, has taken to wearing white spikes with messages scrawled
on them during batting practice. So far, the rest of the club is
not allowing his behavior to affect them. &QL; 
Trivial question &QL; 
 &UR; Roger Clemens ended his distinguished career with the Boston Red
Sox more than two years ago. Before he left, though, he managed to
share two of that franchise's most cherished pitching records with
a certain Hall of Famer. What are the records and who is the other
pitcher? &QL; 
Too big a rift? &QL; 
Judging by the way his teammates and club officials are talking, it
doesn't look as if two-time Gold Glove outfielder  &UR; Jim Edmonds will
be back with the Anaheim Angels next season.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds underwent surgery last week to repair a partial labrum
tear in his right shoulder, an operation that will sideline him for
up to four months. The problem stems from the acknowledgment that
Edmonds could have had this procedure done last October and been
fully recovered by now.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not pleased,'' Angels General Manager  &UR; Bill Bavasi said
when asked about Edmonds' delaying the surgery until now. ``But we
can't do anything about it. We just have to react to the pitch
that's been thrown at us and go from there.''
</P>
<P>
   Angels Manager  &UR; Terry Collins, when asked the same question,
said: ``I can't answer that.''
</P>
<P>
   Can't or won't, he was then asked. ``Both,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds' $4.65 million option kicks in automatically if he
reached 320 at-bats this season, now an impossibility. The club
will now have the choice of picking up that option or letting
Edmonds, who has at least 25 home runs in each of the past four
seasons, become a free agent.
</P>
<P>
   Even his teammates are stepping gingerly when the subject is
broached, although new leader  &UR; Mo Vaughn leaped into the fray.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some guys want to get better, some don't,'' said Vaughn, who
returned two weeks after suffering a high ankle sprain that at
first was believed would keep out the former MVP as much as six
week. ``Some play with pain, some don't. The bottom line is, you
have an obligation _ to the guys who are paying you and to the guys
who are playing _ to get better.'' &QL; 
Never say never &QL; 
Houston's outspoken center fielder,  &UR; Carl Everett, is up to his old
tricks of sticking his foot in his mouth again. This time the
subject was Chicago's Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate coming here,'' Everett said. ``To me, it's the worst
park in baseball other than the one in Detroit (Tiger Stadium). As
far as I'm concerned, they can stick some dynamite in it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a career-ending park. I almost broke my leg on those
(drainage) gutters they have out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Some may recall during last season's playoffs that it was
Everett who said  &UR; Kevin Brown was ``nothing until he gets me out,''
during the first round when Houston eventually lost to San Diego.
Brown, by the way, struck out 16 Astros the day after Everett made
his ridiculous statement. &QL; 
Welcome to the club &QL; 
When Seattle's  &UR; Ken Griffey Jr. was drilled by a pitch last week in
Anaheim, Mariners rookie  &UR; Brett Hinchliffe immediately retaliated
by drilling Angels designated hitter  &UR; Todd Greene. The move
eventually led to a bench-clearing brawl between the clubs and a
three-game suspension for Hinchliffe.
</P>
<P>
   But Seattle's veterans were so impressed with the rookie, that
they invited him to ride on the veteran's bus from the stadium to
the airport, a move that usually requires more than two years of
big league service time since rookies and young players usually
must ride on the same bus as the coaches. &QL; 
Schott in the dark &QL; 
Quietly last week,  &UR; Marge Schott stepped away from the Reds, ending
her 14-year reign as the Cincinnati president and CEO.
</P>
<P>
   Schott finally agreed to sell 5{ of her 6{ shares of the club to
Cincinnati billionaire  &UR; Carl Lindner, who plunked down $67 million
for the controlling interest. Schott will retain one of the 15
shares but now has no say in anything the club does.
</P>
<P>
   Major league owners are expected to easily accept Lindner's bid.
During Schott's time as the Reds' point person, the club won a
World Series championship (1990) and two division titles (1990 and
'95). &QL; 
Trivial answer &QL; 
Clemens finished his Boston career with 192 victories, tying him
with &UR; Cy Young for the most in franchise history. His 38 complete
games also tied Young in that category. For the record, Clemens
pitched 2,776 innings for the Red Sox, while Young pitched 48 fewer
innings for Boston. Young had 112 losses with Boston while Clemens
had 111.
</P>
<P>
   THE HIT LIST &QL; 
 &UR; Whose line is it anyway?: ``How did I feel about it? Nervous.
Scared. Excited. Sad. All the emotions and feelings mixed in.''
That was reliever  &UR; Mark Wohlers, not Cincinnati's catchers, after
learning he had been traded from Atlanta, the only organization he
had ever known, to the Reds.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Holy elusive aura!: One school of thought believed that once
 &UR; Cal Ripken Jr.'s consecutive-games streak ended, it would be the
equivalent of  &UR; Batman being stripped of his mask, there would be no
there, there anymore. Ripken was hitting just .179 with no home
runs and two RBIs in eight games when he landed on the DL for the
first time in his career.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Flashback: Floyd Youmans.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Wonder if Mayor Rudy can parlay this into votes for
 &UR; his probable U.S. Senate race against current first lady Hillary?:
Following the orders of New York City Mayor  &UR; Rudolph Giuliani, the
city that never sleeps will honor Mets reliever  &UR; John Franco with
his own day. Franco recently joined  &UR; Lee Smith as the only
relievers with 400 saves.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Go back to using white at home and gray on the road
 &UR; and this would never happen: Half of the Milwaukee Brewers emerged
from the clubhouse for pre-game stretching last Monday wearing blue
tops while the other half was in white. Blue was the color of the
night, and the others had to switch. &QL; 
EXTRA BASES &QL; 
Longtime veteran  &UR; Gary Gaetti of the Chicago Cubs played in his
2,212th game at third base Tuesday, pushing him ahead of  &UR; Mike
Schmidt and into sole possession of third place on the all-time
list behind &UR; Brooks Robinson (2,870) and  &UR; Graig Nettles (2,412).
</P>
<P>
   Now that  &UR; Barry Bonds is on the disabled list for at least two
months, it underscores just how durable the three-time NL MVP has
been. Out of a possible 920 games he could have played for San
Francisco since joining the club before he landed on the DL, he had
played in 900, which translates into 97.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Texas'  &UR; Rafael Palmeiro, a designated hitter only until his knee
heals enough for him to return to first base, entered the weekend
with zero hits in 14 at-bats against left-handed pitchers. Palmeiro
hit .317 against lefties last season when he was with Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   New Atlanta hitting coach  &UR; Don Baylor wanted  &UR; Chipper
 &UR; Jones to start believing he could hit for power from the right
side. So far, Jones is believing. He had three home runs as a
right-hander in his first 14 games after hitting just two from that
side all of last season. Jones entered the season with 12
right-handed home runs in 677 at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   The St. Louis Cardinals, in first place for the first time since
winning the NL Central in 1996, have just two players _  &UR; Donovan
Osborne and  &UR; Willie McGee _ on their active roster who were with
them when they came within one game of reaching the World Series.
</P>
<P>
   Former Diamondbacks catcher  &UR; Jorge Fabregas, now with the
Florida Marlins, has four hits in five starts since an eye doctor
told him his contact prescription was incorrect. Of course,
Fabregas has only been able to lift his average to .194 entering
the weekend. &QL; 
THE RUMOR MILL &QL; 
As difficult as it may be to believe right now,  &UR; Darryl &UR; Strawberry
could have been back in left field for the Yankees by the end of
the month if he hadn't fallen into trouble two weeks ago.
Collectively, Yankees left fielders entered the weekend with two
home runs and seven RBI. In the end, though, these are the Yankees
and anything can still happen, including seeing Strawberry somehow
return later this season.
</P>
<P>
   Texas pitcher  &UR; John Burkett, who has not had a winning record
since posting 20 victories for the Giants in 1993, will miss his
scheduled start today and probably land on the disabled list at
some point soon. His ERA since opening day last year is 5.96. His
2000 option worth $4.2 million automatically vests if Burkett
starts 30 games.
</P>
<P>
   It seems  &UR; Paul Spoljaric's time as a starter for Philadelphia
ended Tuesday after allowing eight runs on nine hits in two-plus
innings against the Diamondbacks. The career reliever was being
auditioned as a starter this season, but it seems he and his 13.00
ERA will now return to the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of losing their spot in a rotation,  &UR; Masato
 &UR; Yoshii, who had a successful rookie season with the Mets last
season, appears to be in danger of doing the same. Yoshii allowed
six runs on six hits with three walks Wednesday and is 1-2 with a
7.47 ERA. ``He'll have to do better than that,'' New York Manager
 &UR; Bobby
 &UR; Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Mark Mulder, Oakland's first-round pick (the second overall) in
last June's draft, has allowed just one run in 12 innings at Triple
A Vancouver. With the big club's need for pitching help, the
left-hander from Michigan State may make his big-league debut
within the next month. &QL; 
THE RANKINGS &QL; 
 &UR; TOP OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
1. ClevelandEven  &UR; Manny Ramirez's antics aren't enough to distract
this club.  &QL; 
2. NY YankeesEntered the weekend 10-5, same as they were after 15
games last year.  &QL; 
3. St. LouisIn first place for the first time since winning
division in 1996.  &QL; 
4. TorontoManager  &UR; Jim Fregosi walked into a great situation with
this brimming club.  &QL; 
5. AtlantaWelcomed the third new member of the bullpen since the
season began.  &QL; 
6. NY MetsEven without  &UR; Mike Piazza, the Mets aren't missing a
beat.  &QL; 
7. ArizonaThe plan was simple: give themselves a chance to win
every night.  &QL; 
8. Houston &UR; Ken Caminiti is predicting he will be back to his old
self soon.  &QL; 
9. San FranciscoCan the other players pick up the slack for the
injured  &UR; Barry Bonds? &UR; BOTTOM OF THE ORDER &QL; 
 &QL; 
30. BaltimoreSimply pathetic. A new manager is almost a certainty,
but is it enough?  &QL; 
29. FloridaA new season, but it appears the same old results are on
the way.  &QL; 
28. Chicago CubsAnother week, another starter on the DL. Where will
they turn next?  &QL; 
27. MontrealThe results are in and  &UR; Dustin Hermanson appears to be
the real thing.  &QL; 
26. Kansas CityThe auditions for pitcher  &UR; Kevin Appier's services
remain a hot topic.  &QL; 
25. MilwaukeeWorkhorse starter  &UR; Cal Eldred returns to one hurting
rotation.  &QL; 
24. CincinnatiSo &UR; Mark Wohlers only had a mechanical problem? It
goes deeper than that.  &QL; 
23. OaklandThis is a division where the A's might find a way to
squeeze into the race.  &QL; 
22. ColoradoScored at least 10 runs for the 75th time in 320 games
at Coors Field. ON THE RISE &QL; 
 &UR; Pittsburgh Pirates: Two years ago they surprised the baseball world
by remaining in contention until the final two weeks of the season.
The Pirates have much bigger plans this season, considering
themselves the most improved club in the NL Central. Even though
it's just three weeks into the season, the Pirates find themselves
in the thick of the divisional race with good things, like a 4-2
road trip last week, happening. ``Without a doubt, it's a totally
different attitude than last year,'' first baseman
 &UR; Kevin Young said. ``We have guys who want to win ... It's what we
expect.'' &QL; 
GOING SOUTH &QL; 
 &UR; Anaheim Angels: The offense is averaging 5.5 runs per game, which
certainly should be enough to have a better record than the Angels
entered the weekend with. The problems with this club stem from its
starting rotation, where only  &UR; Omar Olivares has an ERA under 5.87
among the starters entering the weekend series in Kansas City.  &UR; Ken
 &UR; Hill (5.87),  &UR; Chuck Finley (7.94),  &UR; Tim Belcher (8.53) and  &UR; Steve
Sparks (9.42) are dragging down the overall ERA, which stood at
4.92 before the weekend. &QL; 
OVERHEARD &QL; 
 &UR; First-year Colorado Manager Jim Leyland after watching the
 &UR; Rockies score three runs in the bottom of the ninth twice in a
 &UR; three-day span to win games: ``I'm going to look like  &UR; Don Knotts
and
 &UR; Telly Savales rolled into one. Look at me now and I've only been
here five games.'' &QL; 
OUT OF LEFT FIELD &QL; 
Tampa Bay pitcher  &UR; Tony Saunders made a name for himself after
helping the Florida Marlins to the 1997 World Series title. He then
became the first player selected in the 1997 expansion draft, taken
by Tampa Bay, but has struggled mightily since then. Three starts
into the season, Saunders appeared on the verge of losing his spot
in the Devil Rays rotation. But after coming within four outs of
throwing a no-hitter last week, it seems Saunders has straightened
out what was ailing him. Instead of relying solely on his breaking
pitches, Saunders went back to having a good mix of fastballs
thrown in to his pitches and had his best performance in 56 major
league starts. ``I know it's early and everyone says it's a long
season, but I don't see me going out there every fifth day and keep
putting that product up,'' Saunders said before his start
Thursday. &QL; 
