<HEADLINE>
MAYOR SPURRED MCNABB PROTEST 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE SCHOENFELD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Philadelphia Mayor  &UR; Ed Rendell wasn't on the bus with Dough Boy
and the three dozen other drunken Eagles fans, but he gets much of
the blame for the anti- &UR; Donovan  &UR; McNabb faction embarrassing itself
at last week's NFL draft.
</P>
<P>
   It was Rendell who went on Philadelphia radio and encouraged
people to call the Eagles' office and say they wanted the team to
draft Heisman Trophy winner  &UR; Ricky Williams.
</P>
<P>
   He gave out the Eagles' private phone number on the radio,
causing the switchboard at the team's offices to overload. These
weren't nice folks who called. Many were rude and obscene.
</P>
<P>
   Philadelphia radio station WIP then organized a bus trip to the
draft in New York City, where the fans could yell, ``We want
Ricky.''
</P>
<P>
   Dough Boy, a 400-pound Eagles fanatic, apparently had a few too
many drinks during he trip, because when the bus reached New York's
Lincoln Tunnel, he mooned a bunch of senior citizens, breaking a
window in the bus.
</P>
<P>
   The fun continued when the bus arrived at Madison Square Garden.
The partyers gave a homeless guy an Eagles shirt. He was taken
inside the arena and fed and then they booed the pick of McNabb,
the Syracuse quarterback taken second overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donovan is a guy with a terrific personality,'' McNabb's
agent,
 &UR; Fletcher Smith, said of the booing. ``He can handle this, and I
think the Eagles understand he can handle this.''
</P>
<P>
   McNabb said he didn't care about the fan reaction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I worry about what's on the inside, with my new family here,''
he said of the Eagles.
</P>
<P>
   Syracuse offensive coordinator  &UR; George DeLeone said he cringed
each time he heard that the Eagles had drafted a former option
quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a pro-style quarterback who happens to run some options
in a very limited fashion,'' DeLeone said. '`It makes me very angry
to see that kid characterized as an option quarterback. It makes me
angry to have our offense characterized as just an option offense.
It's like we run the wishbone. That's not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``Donovan McNabb has been checking protections, hot-reading,
throwing a five-step, three-step, seven-step passing game since
he's been here. It's been a tremendous injustice created by the
media.''
</P>
<P>
   To make amends to McNabb for the drunken fans' behavior, the
Philadelphia Chamber of Commerce had a luncheon in his honor last
week. McNabb gave Rendell an Eagles jersey with Williams' No. 34 on
one side and McNabb's No. 5 on the other. &QL; 
Love that draft
</P>
<P>
   How big is the draft?
</P>
<P>
   ESPN2's TV ratings of rounds four through seven on Sunday blew
away future NHL Hall of Famer  &UR; Wayne Gretzky's last game.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle, a Seahawks season-ticket holder,  &UR; Don Hopkins Jr.,
split a $24 million lottery prize and used some of his winnings to
take a trip to New York to the draft.
</P>
<P>
   He said the NFL gave him the red-carpet treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is first cabin,'' Hopkins said. ``What they did for us is
beyond words.
</P>
<P>
   ``Actually, seeing it in person is something. . . . Everybody is
friendly and talking football.'' &QL; 
Paper Cowboy
</P>
<P>
   Five months after suffering a foot injury against the Cardinals
at Sun Devil Stadium, Cowboys cornerback  &UR; Deion Sanders still is
bothered by the injury.
</P>
<P>
   He was examined by a Tennessee foot specialist last week and
will consult another expert later this week in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought we were on a week-to-week to two weeks deal,''
Cowboys owner  &UR; Jerry Jones said of the injury. ``But when the final
deal tolled, we didn't have Deion for the last five games. Now,it's
week-to-week to five months later. Rest didn't heal it.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question this was a serious injury and (still) is a
serious injury.'' &QL; 
Dirt duo
</P>
<P>
   Former Arizona State center  &UR; Grey Ruegamer, a third-round draft
pick of the Dolphins, is looking forward to lining up next to
veteran guard
 &UR; Kevin Gogan, whom he refers to as the ``King of Dirt.''
</P>
<P>
   Dolphins offensive line coach  &UR; Paul Boudreau doesn't expect
Ruegamer to be Mr. Clean.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough kid, a Gogan type,'' Boudreau said. ``He lacks
some things in terms of real athleticism, but every time you turn
on the film and watch him, he's knocking somebody on their
(butt).''
</P>
<P>
   Ruegamer maintains he learned to play offensive line in his
first ASU start three years ago. He was playing alongside lineman
 &UR; Pat Thompson against Washington in Seattle, when he felt a
pinching pain in his inner thigh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked, and it was Pat,'' Ruegamer said. ``I said, `Pat,
that's me.'
</P>
<P>
   ``He said, `Oh, sorry, dude.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson then grabbed Huskies linebacker  &UR; Steve Hoffman's groin.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was pretty cool,'' Ruegamer said. ``Hoffman was a good
player, but that took some steam out of him.'' &QL; 
Big shoes to fill
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City Chiefs have given first-round pick  &UR; John Tait,
the Brigham Young offensive tackle, jersey No. 76, last worn by
left tackle  &UR; John Alt, who retired in 1996 after a 13-year career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know all about John Alt,'' said Tait, the Tempe McClintock
High School product. ``He's a cornerstone of the history of the
Chiefs. Just to be mentioned in the same sentence as him is a
little bit unfair. I haven't proven anything to anyone. It shows a
lot of people think highly of me, and that just puts the pressure
on me to perform even better.'' &QL; 
Making history
</P>
<P>
   Green Bay Packers General Manager  &UR; Ron Wolf never had drafted a
punter in the first seven rounds before taking Oregon's  &UR; Josh
Bidwell in the fourth round last week.
</P>
<P>
   The pick of Bidwell came two years after the Packers took
place-kicker  &UR; Brett Conway in the third round.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what you're going to ask me: `Is this any different
than Brett Conway?''' Wolf said. ``I certainly hope so. This is a
second-day pick. You can do stuff like this in the second day.'' &QL; 
Scarlet and gray
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals would have taken linebacker  &UR; Andy Katzenmoyer with
21st pick overall had Eastern Michigan offensive tackle  &UR; L.J.
Shelton not been there. That would have given them an all-Ohio
State first round.
</P>
<P>
   They picked Buckeyes wide receiver  &UR; David Boston eighth overall.
</P>
<P>
   Cardinals officials also liked Ohio State quarterback  &UR; Joe
Germaine, the Mesa Mountain View product, but wouldn't have taken
him before the fifth round. Germaine went to the Rams in the fourth
round. &QL; 
Short shots
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised if the Redskins, who have three first-round
picks next year, use at least one on signing another team's
franchise player to an offer sheet.
</P>
<P>
   Jets Coach  &UR; Bill Parcells, on the Colts trading
 &UR; Marshall Faulk: ``To tell you the truth, we had a conga line in the
office when we found out he wasn't in (the division anymore). I
would always tell him, `You're a pain in the (butt),' and I meant
it as a compliment.'' &QL; 
Includes information from other media sources. Steve Schoenfeld can
be reached at 444-8334 or by e-mail at
steve.schoenfeld(at)PNI.com. &QL;
</P>
