<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-ARIZONA-BURKHART-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OVERPOPULATION OF BURROS DAMAGES WILD LIFE HABITAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BARRY BURKHART  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   This is no new problem. It's an ongoing saga.
</P>
<P>
   The latest chapter began last Saturday in Tucson, when the
Arizona Game and Fish Commission voted to ``strongly'' request that
the Bureau of Land Management initiate emergency burro removal in
various areas of the state.
</P>
<P>
   The BLM and the U.S. Forest Service, under the federal Wild,
Free-Roaming Horses and Burros Act of 1971, are in charge of
managing mustangs and burros. In Arizona, that means primarily
burros and the BLM. There are 11 herds in this state.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish biologists are concerned that burros are adversely
affecting public lands administered by the BLM as well as federal
wildlife refuges and state wildlife areas where BLM still is in
charge of managing burros, said  &UR; Dave Walker, head of the
department's Habitat Branch.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Bill Berlat of Tucson, the commission chairman, said burro
overpopulations and the resultant damage to wildlife habitat have
been going on far too long.
</P>
<P>
   In April of last year, the state sued Secretary of the Interior
 &UR; Bruce
 &UR; Babbitt, alleging that the BLM is violating the law by failing to
control burros on Game and Fish's Alamo Lake Wildlife Area. The
suit claims burros are having severe effects on wildlife, including
sensitive species. The suit hasn't been resolved.
</P>
<P>
   Game and Fish is requesting that BLM do its job and remove
burros that are having an impact on wildlife habitat, especially in
riparian areas and areas containing sensitive species. It also
wants burro population inventories and information on how much
damage burros are doing to wildlife habitat in the various herd
management areas.
</P>
<P>
   There's more, but it all will be tough to do.
</P>
<P>
   Everyone concerned knows that burro populations in Arizona are
out of control. These feral animals are growing in numbers and
damaging wildlife habitat. They don't belong in the wild. They have
domestic roots.
</P>
<P>
   The act should be called The Wild, Free-Roaming HORSES and
Sometimes Burros Act. Almost all the funding it provides is for
mustangs. Burros are an afterthought.
</P>
<P>
   The state can howl and threaten, but unless the BLM in this
state gets some money, nothing is going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it will take the courts to wrest money from the
Department of Interior to take care of the immense burro problem in
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   Move 'em out. &QL; 
More action &QL; 
The commission also voted to oppose the proposal to create a
Sonoran Desert National Park and Preserve in southwestern Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   The 3 million-acre park would combine the Barry Goldwater Range,
the Cabeza Prieta National Wildlife Refuge and the Organ Pipe
Cactus National Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The Interior Department said these lands are extremely important
for maintaining and improving native wildlife populations and
wildlife-related recreational opportunities.
</P>
<P>
   Walker said that giving control of the land to the National Park
Service has the potential to seriously reduce Game and Fish's
jurisdiction with fish and wildlife management on the Goldwater
Range and the Cabeza Prieta refuge. He also said it could conflict
with interagency management agreements, projects and land
management planning activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just want to continue our management activities there,''
Walker said.
</P>
<P>
   Currently there 75 wildlife water developments on the range and
the Cabeza Prieta. In addition, another 26 water developments are
scheduled for the eastern part of the range.
</P>
<P>
   Hunters are offered 13 desert bighorn sheep permits in the area,
100 javelina permits and 425 deer tags. Part of the range offers
quality quail hunting.
</P>
<P>
   A program also has been developed to help save the endangered
Sonoran pronghorn. &QL; 
Barry Burkhart can be reached at 444-8454 or at
barry.burkhart(at)pni.com via e-mail. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
