<HEADER>
A2396 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EZZARD-COLUMN26-COX     04-25 0663
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EZZARD-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Empty gestures won't create peace we're seeking
 &HT;    By Martha Ezzard
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Metal detectors of the mind. That's what we might wish
for, to prevent any more Littletons. We'd like a modern-day quick
fix. Whether it's Kosovo or Colorado, it's easier to deal at arm's
length. Modern-day examples abound.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians fight a sterile war.
</P>
<P>
   Parents outfit their kids, but don't make time to talk to them.
</P>
<P>
   Politicians lack the guts to take on the gun lobby.
</P>
<P>
   Educators don't teach the values that history, art, science and
literature offer.
</P>
<P>
   A nation goes to church but doesn't share spiritual
conversation.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, exceptions to those generalizations, all
around us and in Littleton. The young student who said she wished
she had given one of the killers a hug because she knew he was
hurting inside; the devoted teacher who was fatally wounded while
pushing his students away from a doorway; the solitary Republican
senator from Denver, Dottie Wham, who voted alone on her side of
the aisle against a National Rifle Association-sponsored bill to
eliminate gun restrictions in some Colorado towns, including the
barring of assault weapons; the black parent who advised his son
not to change schools, only to learn one youth apparently was
executed because he was black (the civil rights movement taught him
never to run from wrong, the father said).
</P>
<P>
   I try to put myself in the shoes of the parents who lost
children to the senseless horror. But it hurts too much.
</P>
<P>
   Our oldest daughter and her family are flying in from Colorado
to visit this week. They live a few miles from the site of the
tragedy, as did we for a long time. After the shootings, she wasn't
the only young mother who found it hard to let go of a 4-year-old's
hand at the preschool door. (I didn't tell her that I went to the
toy box I've replenished for the grandchildren and threw away the
water guns _ a silly but symbolic gesture.)
</P>
<P>
   There are no solutions, only remedies that play around the
edges. But open discussions between diverse groups of students, not
just best friends, and interactions with caring adults will do a
lot more lasting good than metal detectors.
</P>
<P>
   I liked two ideas I heard this week. In Colorado, one elementary
school assigns each student an adult other than a parent to mentor
the youngster all the way through school. A variation of that could
work for older kids, too, and could get parents more involved in
the larger school scene. In a Georgia school where fights were
breaking out in the school cafeteria, the principal called on
parents and other volunteers to come have lunch on a regular basis
and get to know different groups of students informally.
</P>
<P>
   I'm a believer that great good can come of great evil, that it's
a sign civilization has progressed when America fights in Kosovo,
not for oil or solely in the national interest, but for universal
human dignity. I believe many adults will decide they have time
after all to listen to young people because of the Columbine
tragedy.
</P>
<P>
   And since I once served in the Colorado Legislature and have
watched that body drift to the extreme right on the gun issue, I
have hope sanity will return to policymaking there. Three bad gun
bills have been postponed indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   The pastor at one of the Littleton memorial services conceded
that he could offer no answers to his tearful audience, just hope
that eternity will provide those answers. As another spring
snowstorm blows into Denver, as if in divine fury, the only words
about the loss I'd like to send to a community our family loved for
its vibrancy are these, by an anonymous writer:
</P>
<P>
   Do not stand now and weep/ I am not here/ I do not sleep/ I am a
thousand winds that blow/ I am the diamond glint on snow./ I am the
sunlight on ripened grain/ I am the rain.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
