<HEADER>
A2397 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YOUNG-COLUMN26-COX     04-25 0673
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YOUNG-COLUMN26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Stop fretting about fabric; fret about feelings
 &HT;    By John Young
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Whenever it is that the survivors of the Columbine
High massacre reunite as a student body, someone is going to have a
dilemma that needn't be.
</P>
<P>
   The quandary will be over fabric.
</P>
<P>
   Someone will be dressed in black. Someone else will be trying to
judge it.
</P>
<P>
   What will it mean _ black? Will it mean mourning fallen
classmates? Or will it mean solidarity with fallen shooters? Or
will it mean that the white T-shirt was in the wash and the black
one was at the top of the drawer?
</P>
<P>
   Which will it be?
</P>
<P>
   A futile exercise, yes, but someone will be trying to judge, as
will people in schools across the country. Step right up and make
your judgment. It's a game everyone can play. The Columbine gunners
played it. They based spot judgments on the color of classmates'
skin, on a ball cap. Hitler played such a game.
</P>
<P>
   I know. Let's ban black. That would be a typical exercise _
typically fruitless. Lest this be seen as a tome on student
uniforms and the folly of dress codes that historically stay one
step behind whatever is fashionable, relax. Not this time. I wish
for the dialogue not to be about fabric. Let's talk about what
happens below it.
</P>
<P>
   What's happening below this fabric is roughly what happens when
a chick sheds egg shell: a struggle, a strain, an imperative. Break
that shell or die, says nature. It's a good thing baby chicks don't
know the gravity of their challenge. It would scare them to death.
</P>
<P>
   I remember being scared as a teen _ not about carnage in the
school lobby or even the war that was raging on another continent
with my prospective draft number attached. No, I was scared,
simply, of the unknown _ the leap, the advance of time, the leaving
of the previous me behind.
</P>
<P>
   I had no idea that nature was going to provide in so many ways,
that I wasn't really leaving anything behind, that everything I
wished to keep near my heart I could keep simply by wanting to. It
would take letters and long-distance calls, and reasons to come
home often. It still does, and it's still life-sustaining.
Fortunately for me, there was always a lot at home to sustain.
</P>
<P>
   I can't imagine what fast-forwards through the minds of teens in
the late 1990s, in an era when anything longer than a music video
is of epic length.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, we ought to be thankful for music videos. Just look at what
else is on the TV: ``Crisis in (fill in blank)''; ``Showdown in
(fill in the blank)''; ``(Fill in the blank) Under Siege.''
</P>
<P>
   I'm often relieved to observe that in their baby-chick world,
teens generally just ignore these world crises and satellite-ready
tempests. They are worried about what's happening inside _ inside
them, inside a friend.
</P>
<P>
   That should be good news to people who worry about converting
teen-agers to paths of righteousness. Inside has their attention,
believe me. And I do believe that discussions about treating one
another other with respect and kindness can stick if we get the
conversation rolling. Of course, to get the children to listen we
need to treat them with respect and kindness we expect from them.
</P>
<P>
   Too touchy-feely? Well, we're talking about feelings. You'll fix
them with a meat mallet?
</P>
<P>
   This may sound like something from a long-broken 45 record, but
we need to recognize the natural process of emerging as a person
unto one's self, with fears and uncertainties, and fads as
transitory as amniotic fluid on the down of that chick.
</P>
<P>
   Here we have fundamental things to discuss: life incubating,
maturity in the making. Instead, someone wants to discuss the color
of fabric.
</P>
<P>
   So, what about that color? Is it in mourning? Is it in defiance?
Is it ``just me'' and not you? Yes.
</P>
<P>
   John Young is opinion page editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
His column appears Tuesday, Thursday and Sunday. E-mail:
jyoung(at)mail.wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
