<HEADER>
A2419 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHARP-DRIVING27-COX     04-25 0524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHARP-DRIVING27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Safety devices can't make trunk of cars childproof
 &HT;    By Linda Sharp
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ One of the challenges that face automakers is to
figure out how their customers think. They do this mostly so they
can entice people to buy their products. It can be difficult.
</P>
<P>
   General Motors found out there is a more complex and challenging
customer base _ children _ or their car-buying parents.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to solve the problem of children accidentally locking
themselves in car trucks, which has caused about 20 deaths since
1987, GM decided to use children as research agents. (Ford Motor
Co. also has developed a trunk-escape system.)
</P>
<P>
   Working with experimental psychologists and biomechanical
experts from Exponent/Failure Analysis Associates, GM began a
behavioral research program.
</P>
<P>
   Child physiologist and EFAA staffer Christine Wood, who worked
with 10 behavioral scientists, explains, ``We began by developing a
mechanism that we thought screamed out to the kids, `Use me to open
the trunk.' We quickly discovered that mechanisms that force
children to use only their fingers did not work as well as those
where children put their whole hand on it.''
</P>
<P>
   She said adults have a lifetime of experience opening things and
are aware of hazards. Young children have limited experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``The very youngest kids we tested (age 3) are still so
dependent on adults for being able to do all the basics like
getting dressed, doing buttons, zippers, etc. ... there are real
physical limitations on what kids can do,'' Wood said.
</P>
<P>
   About nine different devices were tested.
</P>
<P>
   A lighted overhead pull cord similar to those used on buses was
appealing to adults and engineers, Wood said. ``We adults were sure
it would work well, but we found that young children believe they
shouldn't touch things that looked electrical. They wouldn't even
try it.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods and her associates found there is seemingly nothing
``child-attractive.'' They settled on an ordinary-looking
lever-type handle because it had a high success rate among the
children tested.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Zarrella, executive vice president of General Motors, noted,
``We tested a number of designs, found that many that our research
team intuitively thought would be successful didn't work well at
all. And while the majority of the 100 children who ranged in age
from 3 to 7 we tested could operate the escape handle we ultimately
developed, we learned that not all _ especially the younger ones _
were successful. That is why GM quickly changed its focus from an
escape handle to a preventative measure.''
</P>
<P>
   Trunk kits are available at GM dealers for about $50 and can be
installed on most 1990 or later GM passenger cars.
</P>
<P>
   My view: Cars are not playthings, and children should be taught
that at an early age. They should never be allowed to play in or
around a parked vehicle. Nor should they ever be left alone in one.
</P>
<P>
   Lock your car even in your own driveway. Little ones have an
uncanny way of finding ways into curious places.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
