<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2420 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-THE-MECHANIC27-COX     04-25 0598
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THE-MECHANIC27-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Be leery of shops retrofitting A/C system
 &HT;    By Nora Carter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ah, spring! Open windows, chase out musty smells.
Winter's wool garments are replaced by cooler cotton fabrics, and
the temperature selector in the car is moved from the red to the
blue zone. Just push that A/C button and ... What? Oh-oh, no cold
air? Now what?
</P>
<P>
   Getting your car's air-conditioning system serviced has become
more complicated and expensive in the past few years for a number
of reasons. Primarily, the transition from environmentally
unfriendly R-12 to an ozone-safe refrigerant opened a Pandora's
box.
</P>
<P>
   All vehicle manufacturers have been using the newer R-134a in
their A/C systems since the mid-'90s, and it has become the
industry standard to retrofit replacement refrigerant for older
R-12 systems.
</P>
<P>
   However, the introduction and use of several other refrigerants,
both legal and illegal, has created A/C chaos for the auto repair
business. The culprit is contaminated refrigerant, which can only
be identified by using a special piece of equipment that ``sniffs''
it out.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the cost of this mess has fallen on the consumer.
</P>
<P>
   Both R-12 and R-134a are pure refrigerants and can be recovered
and recycled _ if they are not contaminated with any other
chemical. Hence the problem.
</P>
<P>
   If a vehicle's A/C system is identified as containing
contaminated refrigerant, it may be deemed unserviceable by a shop.
The recovery and disposal of contaminated refrigerant is a
time-consuming and expensive undertaking. Many shops just don't
want the headache.
</P>
<P>
   It is illegal to vent refrigerant to the air. The penalty is a
stiff fine or possible imprisonment. If a shop subscribes to this
practice, do you suppose they care what they put in your system?
</P>
<P>
   As the price of R-12 continues to escalate, owners of older
vehicles with A/C systems that use this refrigerant will become the
prime targets for the ``retrofit hawkers,'' or shops that encourage
you to switch your air-conditioning system to a money-saving,
alternative refrigerant.
</P>
<P>
   Beware! While there are legitimate circumstances where a system
should be retrofitted, there are many instances where minor repairs
and a recharge will suffice.
</P>
<P>
   In any case, steer clear of shops using refrigerants other than
R-12 or R-134a. Although the other accepted refrigerants may work
well and their price is attractive, it could prove to be a
nightmare when you need future service.
</P>
<P>
   Most reputable shops recommend retrofitting an A/C system only
when the situation is extreme, such as compressor failure or the
need to replace multiple components. Major repairs of this sort
require that the entire system be flushed out with a cleaning
chemical that removes all traces of debris, old refrigerant and
lubricating oils. This, in turn, provides the best possible
environment for the R-134a replacement along with the new oil,
neither of which is compatible with R-12.
</P>
<P>
   The end result is a system that is environmentally friendly,
less expensive to maintain (the cost of the refrigerant in the
event of future repair) and uncontaminated by residue from old
R-12.
</P>
<P>
   There are plenty of arguments throughout the industry that
ridding the system of the old chemical is unnecessary and that it
is acceptable simply evacuate and recharge using the replacement
refrigerant and oil. However, the use of refrigerant identifiers is
uncovering an epidemic of contamination.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
