<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 16:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2452 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES26-COX     04-25 1403
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-GRAVES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    KOSOVO REFUGEES TELL OF DIGGING MASS GRAVES
 &HT;    By MARCIA KUNSTEL and JOSEPH ALBRIGHT
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKAS, Albania _ The way Hasan Hyseni pieced together the story
of the carnage he found near Izbica, his Kosovo village, Serbian
forces pursued a simple tactic there: ``Every person they saw, they
killed. Five here. Ten there.''
</P>
<P>
   Hyseni said he is one of the Kosovar Albanians who discovered
the butchery. Then he helped gather the bodies and dig 151 shallow
graves.
</P>
<P>
   Bajram Hasani is another Kosovo refugee who described the
painful duty of examining the bullet-pocked, sometimes mutilated
remains of his compatriots. He, too, dug graves at Izbica
(pronounced Iz-BEET-sa), then carefully deposited the bodies of his
wife's father, her uncle and her cousin.
</P>
<P>
   ``We covered them with blankets. When we buried them we put them
in the right direction as our habits say,'' Hasani recalled.
</P>
<P>
   These Kosovo refugees talked of scores of graves near the
village Izbica. Shallow graves mounded with dirt. All lined up and
orderly.
</P>
<P>
   On April 17, NATO officials said at a briefing in Brussels that
a spy satellite had photographed what appeared to be scores of
graves, all pointing southeast toward Mecca out of respect for the
victims' Muslim religion.
</P>
<P>
   The officials cited the discovery as compelling evidence of
Serbian atrocities. The apparent graves had not appeared in a
satellite photo in March.
</P>
<P>
   But intelligence authorities had no way to penetrate the earth
thousands of feet below their cameras to learn what or who really
lay beneath it, no way to answer the questions of how and why and
when.
</P>
<P>
   These two refugees, who stay in tent camps here on opposite
edges of this city, seem to be answering at least some of those
questions. While their stories cannot be verified here, they
directly reflect the satellite findings and support NATO's
accusations of Serbian human rights abuses of an appalling
magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   The men's descriptions don't line up fact by fact, but on most
points their stories agree, and also match what human rights groups
have heard from other refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Here is how the two men recounted the chaos of Kosovo and the
human destruction they witnessed:
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of March, tales of killings flew through the
mountain villages that for months had been tormented by Serbian
Yugoslav police, army troops and paramilitary fighters.
</P>
<P>
   The area is home to a predominantly ethnic Albanian population
and a stronghold for guerrillas fighting for Kosovo's independence.
But it also holds a large Serb police presence and a smattering of
villages where ethnic Serbs dominate. The place is a lethal,
long-simmering stew.
</P>
<P>
   The people in this cluster of settlements centered between Pec
to the west and Pristina to the east had been on the run from
village to village, from village to mountains, from mountains to
home _ constantly moving to find a place that seemed momentarily
safer from the Serb forces they said had been mounting sporadic
attacks for nearly a year.
</P>
<P>
   In the last week of March, Hyseni's family had gone from their
home in Kastriot to Klodernice to Tushila, each of which is
separated by just a few miles.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani and his family of nine people also had ended up in
Tushila that day. Both families placed the date as March 27.
</P>
<P>
   Members of both families also said a large group of Kosovar
Albanians, mostly women and children, arrived in Tushila shortly
afterward. Serb forces had ordered them to leave the grounds of the
Izbica schoolhouse where they had been staying, but had not allowed
the older people and men to go along.
</P>
<P>
   There was fear and talk of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   Both families independently said they had been told that a
grenade or mortar had exploded in the middle of the column of women
and children, killing one mother and her two children.
</P>
<P>
   The Hasani and Hyseni families could not provide precise dates,
but both said that within a day or two the Serb authorities rounded
them up among the thousands of ethnic Albanians who had taken
refuge in Tushila. This group, too, was divided, and the males aged
15 to about 50 were not released.
</P>
<P>
   The rest were put on the march, heading south toward Albania
accompanied by Serb forces who periodically shot in the air to
hurry them along. But after about only 10 miles, the armed guards
left the convoy. The column dispersed, and many went home or to
other refuge.
</P>
<P>
   Within another day or two, village men ventured out in search of
lost friends and relatives whom they feared might have perished.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were lots of people looking,'' remembered Hyseni, a
52-year-old primary school teacher. ``We would ask each other, 'Did
you find anyone? How many have you found?' ``
</P>
<P>
   Hyseni said he walked less than a mile over the rough terrain in
a steady drizzle, following a path along a dried-up creek bed, when
he found the first cluster of three bodies.
</P>
<P>
   They were lying face down, hands behind their heads, shot full
of bullets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We turned them over to see their faces,'' he said, and he
realized he knew all three. One was his cousin Mustapha. One of the
bodies was missing a foot, which Hyseni and a friend found a few
yards away.
</P>
<P>
   A mile and a half farther he encountered two more bodies, he
said, an elderly man and his son, whose fingers had been nearly
hacked off one hand.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, there was a group of 10 bodies scattered along the
creek bed for about 50 yards, all of them shot but not mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew them all,'' Hyseni said.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers met at the Izbica schoolhouse around 4 p.m. They
determined to gather the bodies and bury them the next day as
properly as possible, about half a mile away from the school in a
plot of land that a local man donated.
</P>
<P>
   Hyseni said he believed few people had been killed there at the
white, three-room school, and that most were brought from nearby
sites such as those he had discovered.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani, who is 45 and a bricklayer, differs on this.
</P>
<P>
   He also said villagers had gathered at Izbica in the late
afternoon, but arrived to discover a line of scores of bodies on a
small field near the school.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of them had been killed from a very short distance,'' he
said. ``From five to ten meters, not more.'' Some had many wounds,
some only a shot in the head or the heart or the chest, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani said the villagers found three piles of shells in
different places, leading them to believe three people had carried
out the massacre.
</P>
<P>
   He discovered the bodies of the father, uncle and cousin of his
wife Sobrije. The villagers covered the bodies as best they could,
using a blanket for every three bodies.
</P>
<P>
   Sobrije Hasani whispered an added fact to a reporter out of her
husband's presence. When he came back home that night with her
brother, who had gone with him on the search, her husband was so
shaken that he was unable to tell her what had happened. Her
brother had to deliver the bleak news.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani did agree that not all the bodies buried the following
day had been found at the same site, and that some were brought
from elsewhere in the vicinity of Izbica. Some of those, he said,
were mutilated.
</P>
<P>
   He put the total dead at 145, while Hyseni said it was 151. Both
said smaller numbers of additional victims were found and buried in
different villages during these days.
</P>
<P>
   Hasani and Hyseni, who said they are acquainted but had not seen
each other since they left Kosovo as refugees, gave identical
accounts of what happened the day of the burial. They also gave the
same names of some of the deceased, including three fighters of the
Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The burials, they said, were simple. Men dug a yard or so deep,
placed a body, and covered it with dirt so that a mound was left
showing.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA helped dig the graves, but more important, stood guard
for Serb patrols, they said. They also videotaped the event to be
used as evidence in war crimes trials.
</P>
<P>
   The villagers said they did one other thing that may or may not
survive the brutality of ethnic cleansing in Kosovo. They put
numbered wooden markers at the head of each grave and made a
corresponding list of the names of the dead, so people will be able
to find their late loved ones if they and if peace ever return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
