<SLUG> BC-AAAA-ADCOL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD AGENCIES URGED TO LEAD  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Texas, Md., Fla., Calif.)  By STUART ELLIOTT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   AMELIA ISLAND, Fla. _ The 81st annual meeting of the American
Association of Advertising Agencies, which concluded here on
Saturday, closed with exhortations to the estimated 350 attendees
to enthusiastically tackle the challenges confronting the industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have serious issues; the world is changing,'' said Shelly
Lazarus, the chairwoman of the association for 1999-2000 who is
also chairwoman and chief executive of Ogilvy &AMP; Mather Worldwide in
New York, part of WPP Group PLC. ``Are we going to lead or are we
going to follow?
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to lead, we need to be active and we need to be
committed,'' not just ``sort of involved,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   Recounting the humorous definition of the difference between
``involvement'' and ``commitment'' _ in a ham-and-eggs breakfast,
``the chicken was involved but the pig was committed'' _ Ms.
Lazarus declared: ``We live and die by this industry. In this
instance, I align with the pig. So let's get on with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Lazarus, in her address as the incoming chairwoman, urged
members of the association, which is known as the Four As, to
celebrate the unconventional and the unexpected _ the better to
meet competition from the likes of management consultants, who are
threatening to usurp the traditional role agencies play in
marketing communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``My management consultant friends sometimes seem almost
offended by the irrational and illogical,'' Ms. Lazarus said.
``Have you noticed that?''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, she asserted, ``we thrive on that,'' because
``consumers are often irrational and illogical,'' influenced by
``intangible emotional values that often transcend logic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not a vendor arm of the clients we serve,'' Ms. Lazarus
said. ``We are not the tactical executor of our clients' will.''
</P>
<P>
   Rather, she added: ``We marry consumer insights in
brand-building communication. We find ideas. We produce the stimuli
that drive behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is not what consultants do,'' Ms. Lazarus declared.
``That is what we do.''
</P>
<P>
   In the text of her speech, Ms. Lazarus suggested that the
association ``pull a shocker'' and ``offer the consultants
membership in the Four As.'' Ms. Lazarus said later that the
passage was omitted for time reasons, adding with a smile that she
had ``meant it absolutely in jest.''
</P>
<P>
   Jest and the unexpected were prominent parts of a panel
discussion on how to operate an agency successfully.
</P>
<P>
   ``You need to embrace failure,'' said Donny Deutsch, chairman
and chief executive at Deutsch Inc. in New York. ``Learn from it,
grow from it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when you reach for the stars, you fall off your
chair,'' he added. ``We are so afraid of the myths, but that's only
where greatness comes from.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Deutsch advised, ``let's be proud'' and be
imbued with ``the arrogance the McKinseys have,'' a reference to
the McKinsey &AMP; Co. consultancy.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a tough business,'' he added, ``and you have to say to
yourself we are going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   A second panelist, Clifford J. Einstein, chairman and corporate
creative director at Dailey &AMP; Associates in West Hollywood, Calif.,
part of the Interpublic Group of Cos., told the audience that ``if
you want to be great, clients should think you're great.''
</P>
<P>
   That way, he explained, ``they will trust you and listen to you
and bring you into the business'' _ and those additional insights
will help you produce even better work.
</P>
<P>
   A third panelist, Ed Eskandarian, chairman and chief executive
at Arnold Communications in Boston, owned by Snyder Communications,
echoed Ms. Lazarus in proclaiming that success comes from ``taking
a different perspective, a different angle at the way you look at
things.''
</P>
<P>
   Unlike an executive who said at another panel discussion that
agency managers should ``set a goal to pay less than average
salaries,'' Eskandarian urged agency principals to ``pay more
competitively'' to attract talented employees and ``give them
opportunities for growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Because no advertising conference is complete without awards,
the association presented its 1999 honors on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In the O'Toole Creative Awards competition, for general
excellence during 1998, BBDO New York, part of the BBDO Worldwide
unit of Omnicom Group, won for agencies with billings of more than
$30 million. It was the second time in three years that BBDO New
York had won or tied for the award. Dweck Inc. in New York,
formerly Dweck &AMP; Campbell, won for agencies with billings of less
than $30 million.
</P>
<P>
   O'Toole Awards for multicultural advertising were presented to
four agencies. Vigilante in New York, part of the Leo Burnett Co.,
won for work aimed at black consumers. There was a tie for the
award for work aimed at Spanish-speaking consumers, which was
shared by Bromley, Aguilar &AMP; Associates in San Antonio, part of
MacManus Group, and Conill Advertising in New York, owned by
Saatchi &AMP; Saatchi PLC Pancom International in New York won for work
in the ``other multicultural'' category.
</P>
<P>
   The O'Toole Awards for public service advertising were presented
to Eisner &AMP; Associates in Baltimore, for television work, and Asher
&AMP; Partners in Los Angeles, for print work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
