<SLUG> BC-TALK-MEDIA-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEAR DREAMWORKS: YOUR LETTER WENT TOO FAR  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., Mass., Ore., Colo.)  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It sounded like a letter from a love-smitten stalker.
</P>
<P>
   The letter, which appeared to have been printed out from a home
computer, arrived in a plain envelope with no return address.
``Dearest,'' it began, ``Do you know how in love with you I am?''
It went on: ``I have fallen in love without taking a step ... When
I'm close to you, I feel your hair brush my cheek when it does not.
I look away from you sometimes, then I look back.''
</P>
<P>
   That letter arrived on Tuesday. On Friday, another arrived, in a
similar envelope, addressed in the same computer type. This one
read: ``Dearest, Hope you got my letter. `The Love Letter' will
open in the smaller theater next to `Star Wars' on May 21st. Hope
to see you there.''
</P>
<P>
   The two letters, which were received by many editors and
reporters around the country who cover the media industry, turned
out to be a publicity stunt by the Dreamworks SKG film studio.
</P>
<P>
   The letters frightened several recipients, and some said they
were annoyed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was creepy and disconcerting,'' said Jennifer Barr, a
senior editor at Elle magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Holly Millea, a senior editor at Premiere magazine, was equally
disdainful. ``It was utterly bad timing, in light of all the bad
things that happened this week in the world, and in the magazine
world,'' she said, referring to the school shootings in Colorado
and the death from cancer of Liz Tilberis, editor of Harper's
Bazaar.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a turn-off,'' Ms. Millea said. ``It's right up there with
sending a ticking clock for a terrorist film. Not funny.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Press, the director of marketing for Dreamworks, said that
she saw no need to offer any apologies. In fact, Ms. Press said,
that she had heard from women who were disappointed when they
discovered that they did not really have an anonymous admirer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hate to say it,'' she said, ``but lighten up.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Alex Kuczynski &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Barricade Guidelines
</P>
<P>
   Many people watching CNN's live coverage of the high school
shootings in Littleton, Colo., last week were shocked to hear the
voice of a student still inside Columbine High School, who spoke by
cell phone to the local television station, KUSA, and told where he
was hiding.
</P>
<P>
   No one knew at that point where the gunmen were, or whether they
had a TV set turned on during their siege. But KUSA's and CNN's
live broadcast could possibly have endangered more students.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patty Dennis at KUSA has said that in retrospect she might not
do that again,'' said Barbara Cochran, president of the
Radio-Television News Directors Association. Ms. Dennis, KUSA's
news director, did not return a call Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Cochran added: ``These things suddenly explode on you,
and a new technology enters the picture _ this is the first time I
know of where kids in school had cell phones and could call out _
and people haven't had a chance to think about it and establish a
rule.''
</P>
<P>
   CNN, which is owned by Time Warner, has rules, said the senior
vice president for domestic news, Earl Casey. ``Our primary
guideline,'' he said, ``is don't do anything that could endanger
human life or human safety, and don't endanger an ongoing law
enforcement effort.''
</P>
<P>
   To help journalists learn from one anothers' experience, the
Media Studies Center of the Freedom Forum in New York has started a
project to produce a handbook on fairness for broadcast
journalists. Av Westin, a former news executive for CBS and ABC, is
compiling the handbook, which will gather the ``best practices''
advice of journalists from the major networks and station groups.
</P>
<P>
   He found that stations in Portland, Ore.; Tampa, Fla., and
Boston already have agreements with their local police departments
setting rules for coverage of what they call ``barricaded assailant
situations.'' They set distances for how close news helicopters can
get to the scene, agreed to use pool cameras in some cases and
decided not to broadcast live footage of SWAT teams in action. In
exchange, the police agreed to allow pool cameras better locations.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not me on Mount Olympus pronouncing things. This is
fellow journalists saying how they handled it,'' Westin said of the
handbook. ``If guidelines become second nature, coverage will be
better.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Lawrie Mifflin.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
