<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-CITY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SPIFFED-UP CAPITAL IMPRESSES NATO VISITORS
 &HT;    With NATO-SUMMIT.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Secured and sanitized, the nation's capital has
impressed the thousands of journalists and diplomats who converged
for three days of NATO meetings, press conferences and dinners.
</P>
<P>
   With streets sealed and several blocks barricaded in the
downtown area where the conference was held, the scene was serene
and clean almost to a fault.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very different this time,'' Vlad Nistor, a member of the
Romanian delegation, marveled Sunday about his second visit to the
District of Columbia. ``Ordinary people are not around _ only
police cars and heads of state.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a very positive impression of the city, but I doubt
that this is the normal situation,'' said Paul Koopman, a newspaper
reporter from the Netherlands who was making his first visit to
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems suspiciously safe and clean,'' he said. ``It reminds
me of a story of our queen who thought something should be done
about the odd smell at all the hospitals that she visited. It was
fresh paint.''
</P>
<P>
   The District government has viewed NATO's 50th Anniversary
Summit and a gathering of the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council as
a chance to show that things are changing in a city long plagued by
images of crime, corruption and incompetence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opportunity is for the District to put a welcome mat out
to the world, not a trap door,'' new Mayor Anthony Williams told
the Washington Post last week. ``They will see that Washington,
D.C., is a city on a comeback.''
</P>
<P>
   The early reviews from the well-traveled European visitors were
glowing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been absolutely delighted with the city,'' said Lance
Prince, a member of the delegation from the United Kingdom.
``Everything looks fantastic.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, Saturday and Sunday provided glorious spring weather _
cool temperatures, bright sunshine and cloudless blue skies. White
dogwoods and red tulips are blooming, and trees are bursting with
young green leaves.
</P>
<P>
   While tourists abound in normal numbers, most local residents
have heeded warnings to stay away from the blocked streets, so
traffic has remained unusually light. Anti-NATO demonstrators were
kept well away from the meetings and motorcades that occupied
</P>
<P>
   the 3,400 journalists and 1,700 diplomats.
</P>
<P>
   But some visitors missed the expected bustle of a metropolis.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very beautiful city, but in comparison with New York,
it's much calmer,'' said Andre Rubbens, press spokesman for the
Belgian defense minister. ``Without being insulting, I would say
that it's a quite provincial city.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
