<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIVAL-MAGAZINES-MEDIA-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GQ AND ESQUIRE GRAPPLE FOR A MANLY MARKET 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Graphic is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Non-subscribers can make
individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By ALEX KUCZYNSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Esquire and GQ, nominees for National Magazine Awards
this week, are rival men's publications headed by two former
colleagues and sharing a demonstrated interest in what might
politely be called male anatomy. But they approach the subject _ as
they do many other things _ very differently.
</P>
<P>
   At the GQ Man of the Year Awards, a star-studded,
multimillion-dollar, black-tie affair held in October at Radio City
Music Hall, an audience of some 5,000 watched as the rock star
Sting accepted his award. He hoisted the statuette _ a muscular,
nude male torso sculpted in glass _ and then made a speech about
the energetic amorous life he shares with his wife, Trudie Styler.
The crowd roared with glee. The proceedings were, in a phrase,
testosterone-rich.
</P>
<P>
   In the pages of Esquire, however, the tone is a bit more quirky
and earnest, much like the magazine's editor in chief, David
Granger. In November, while the Man of the Year cover was GQ's
best-selling issue of the year, Esquire's cover (its worst seller
of 1998) featured a profile of Fred Rogers, the 70-year-old
children's television-show host.
</P>
<P>
   In the story, writer Tom Junod described his subject's daily
athletic-club swim. He observed Rogers' locker-room changing
session and described in jaw-dropping prose _ that is, for people
not accustomed to thinking about their childhood heroes in the buff
_ Rogers' nude body.
</P>
<P>
   GQ: Sting's virility. Esquire: naked septuagenarians.
</P>
<P>
   The difference speaks volumes about these magazines and their
editors, who were once mentor (Art Cooper) and protege (Granger).
They have been vaguely at odds since Granger left GQ in May 1997 _
pilfering several GQ staff members along the way, including one who
has the letters ``GQ'' tattooed on his arm _ to take the top
editing job at Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   GQ, put out by the Conde Nast unit of Advance Publications, is
aimed at men entranced by luxury, fashion, sports and the notion of
what some call ``the good life'' (a theme of the May issue). It has
been and remains the financially stronger of these two titles in
the men's general-interest magazine field.
</P>
<P>
   But Esquire, published by Hearst Corp., has under Granger aimed
for quirkier, more personal writing _ like one writer's essay about
his addiction to the painkiller Vicodin, or another's about his
heart surgery _ and is showing signs of a small but palpable
resurgence after a nearly two-decade decline.
</P>
<P>
   The two men couldn't be more different. Cooper is known for his
sartorial grandeur, his occasional bouts in the tabloid press with
celebrities like Sharon Stone _ there was that episode in 1998 when
he refused to let her pose for GQ's cover with live zebras _ and
his martini lunches with supermodels. The soft-spoken Granger, on
the other hand, lives in the suburbs with his family and has said
that he prefers never to see his name in boldface type.
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Cooper-Granger heat gets its most direct test
yet. After a lonely spell of five years, Esquire has been nominated
for not just one but three National Magazine Awards, in the coveted
categories of essays and criticism (for which it has two
nominations) and feature writing.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, GQ, which has been nominated for 21 awards since
1992, is a nominee in only one category, feature writing. The
winners of the awards, which are presented by the American Society
of Magazine Editors, are to be announced on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The disparity in nominations fuels a continuing contretemps
between GQ and Esquire. When his protege left for Esquire two years
ago, Cooper gibed to reporters that Granger had been ``burning to
be an editor in chief.'' Later, he called Granger's magazine
``unsubtle.''
</P>
<P>
   Now a seemingly benevolent and perhaps more publicity-conscious
Cooper says in a politely worded e-mail that Granger ``is a
talented editor and has done a nice job with the magazine.''
</P>
<P>
   Granger, meanwhile, will say nothing negative about his former
boss. ``My relationship with Art is complicated,'' he said. ``Art
has done a very good magazine for a long while, and I continue to
marvel at some of the good writing.''
</P>
<P>
   Solidly moribund for most of the 1990s, Esquire was mainly
overlooked by the American Society of Magazine Editors in those
years, and its annual ad pages hit an apocalyptic low of 608, to
GQ's 1,558, in 1996, according to the Publishers Information
Bureau. Its circulation slid from 747,000 in 1994 to 673,500 in
1998, according to the Audit Bureau of Circulations.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't that long ago that people had totally written
Esquire off,'' Granger said. ``When I took the job, people asked
me, `What are you thinking?' They assumed Esquire couldn't be a
vital magazine again. But all the signs point to a tremendous era
of vitality.''
</P>
<P>
   Feeding that vitality are not just the award nominations, but
also an intriguing literary find that Granger will publish this
summer _ three previously unpublished short stories by the
postmodern writer Raymond Carver _ and a minor burst in advertising
pages. For its issues of January through May, Esquire can count 348
ad pages, up 32 percent from the corresponding period last year,
according to the Publishers Information Bureau.
</P>
<P>
   GQ, by contrast, counts 586 pages from January through May,
which, while formidable, still represents a 24.8 percent decline
from the same months in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Valerie Salembier, the publisher of Esquire, attributed the
magazine's advertising growth to Granger's editorial vision,
adding, ``Give readers a product they want, and advertisers will
follow.''
</P>
<P>
   Esquire's successes have come in a less-than-perfect period for
GQ. There was a perilous 17.5 percent decline in GQ's newsstand
sales for the second half of 1998. Then its fourth publisher in
five years, Jack Laschever, resigned this month, citing medical
reasons. But Thomas Florio, his newly appointed successor, does not
seem worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just because they showed up at the race in their uniform,
doesn't mean they're going to win,'' Florio said of Esquire.
``They're just at the starting line.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared with GQ, in fact, Esquire hasn't even gone that far.
Since Hearst rescued the magazine by acquiring it from Esquire
Magazine Group in 1987, Esquire has never made a profit. Ms.
Salembier would not discuss specific losses, but she said there
might be a chance that Esquire would be in the black by the end of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   GQ, by contrast, is a moneymaker for Conde Nast, though the
company will not disclose how big the profits are. In 1997, the
last full year of Richard Beckman's tenure as publisher, the
magazine generated $75.8 million in advertising revenue, according
to the Publishers Information Bureau, up 17 percent from the
previous year.
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, revenue reached $88.6 million, and Beckman _ who had by
then earned the sobriquet ``Mad Dog'' for his aggressive sales
strategy _ moved to Conde Nast's Vogue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to admit,'' Ms. Salembier said, ``that after Richard
Beckman, no one scares me.'' She added, ``I heard they started
calling him `Mad Cow' Beckman around the office.'' Beckman
responded by saying of Ms. Salembier, ``We sort of internally
thought of her as one of the great marketing minds of the Dark
Ages.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1998, Esquire's advertising revenue was $42.6 million, less
than half GQ's. And advertisers still consider GQ the stronger buy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``GQ is huge,'' said Steve Greenberger, the director of print
media at Grey Mediacom, a unit of Grey Advertising. ``The question
is, in this more challenging share-of-market war that is going to
be witnessed not only between GQ and Esquire but among all the
men's magazines, it's whether GQ can still gain significant
growth.''
</P>
<P>
   Both publishers acknowledge that the men's magazine market is
changing. Reed Phillips, a managing partner at DeSilva &AMP; Phillips,
an investment banking firm that advises the media community, said
that fewer readers were interested in general-interest men's
magazines.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's happening with men's magazines like GQ and Esquire, in
the general-interest category, is that they are facing competition
from more niche-oriented magazines like Men's Health, Outside,
Details and Maxim,'' Phillips said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should be more concerned with who is chipping away at
their market rather than locking horns with one another,'' Phillips
said. But locking horns is what improves magazines, and it is the
identities of the two top men that inform the heart and soul of GQ
and Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   At a party celebrating Cooper's 15th anniversary as GQ editor,
held in September at the Four Seasons, guests received a booklet
with Cooper's devilish caricature on the cover. Inside, a
contributor to the magazine had written a list of qualities she
could ascribe to Cooper and those she could not.
</P>
<P>
   Under ``What's Art'' the following entries appeared: Florence,
Italy; Cole Porter; Dom Perignon; steak, and GQ. Under the heading
``What's Not'': Cleveland, Ohio; John Tesh; tofu burger, and
Esquire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, Art and I are very different people,'' Granger later
said of the unflattering comparison.
</P>
<P>
   Granger and Cooper do have a bet riding on this week's awards.
The winner has to take the loser to lunch at the Four Seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess that's OK,'' Granger said. ``Even if it is his
restaurant.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper, who answered by e-mail, offered his own salvo: ``If
neither of us wins, Valerie Salembier buys us lunch.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
