<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALBANIA-MILITARY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. BATTLE TANKS ARRIVING IN ALBANIA
 &HT;    410&AMP;add.
 &HT;    By JOSEPH ALBRIGHT
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   RINAS AIR FIELD, Albania _ Stepping up its psychological
pressure on Yugoslavia, NATO on Sunday began deploying limited
numbers of American heavy battle tanks into Albania.
</P>
<P>
   The tanks, arriving from the 1st Armored Division in Germany,
are intended to help protect U.S. Army troops on duty in Albania, a
U.S. military spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   But as Yugoslavian generals realize, the 1st Armored Division is
one that thrust deep into Kuwait on the first day of the Desert
Storm ground war against Iraq in 1991.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman said crew members of an MIA1 Abrams battle tank
would be made available for press interviews at this congested air
strip Monday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   There are also plans to allow the media to photograph at least
one Abrams tank on a runway, not far from the landing pads of the
Apache attack helicopters that made their highly publicized first
landing here Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   NATO commander Gen. Wesley Clark, visiting U.S. soldiers here
for the second time in about a week, said the helicopter gunships _
seven more of which arrived Sunday _ would be put into action soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have a specific date as of when the Apaches will be
operational, but we're on track and they won't be too long,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Correspondents in Belgrade, meanwhile, said a new wave of NATO
bombing raids Sunday temporarily knocked Serbian state TV off the
air for a second time since Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Also, NATO missiles hit the northeastern industrial area of Nis
early Sunday, causing extensive damage, according to the Yugoslav
news agency Tanjug. Five other missiles hit a chemical plant in
Lucani, about 60 miles south of Belgrade, Serb media said.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said at a Brussels news conference
that neighboring Macedonia had agreed to allow the deployment of
additional British and German troops on its territory.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the moment we have in Macedonia over 12,000'' troops, Shea
said. ``We are sending via Greece a second German battle group.
It's on its way. Also a second (British) battle group. This will
take the numbers up to something like 16,000'' in Macedonia.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been building an advance force in Macedonia for an
eventual peacekeeping operation in Kosovo where Serb forces have
driven out ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   Shea also announced that Romania and Slovenia had granted NATO
the use of air space for alliance military operations against
Yugoslavia. Bulgaria is expected to vote Monday to give similar
permission.
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of top-of-the-line battle tanks in Albania is likely
to excite speculation about whether the first few M1A1s are the
forward wedge of a future ground war.
</P>
<P>
   Because of Albania's high mountains and poor roads, it probably
would be impossible to move any significant number of tanks to the
Kosovo frontier by road or air, and they are too heavy to drop by
parachute.
</P>
<P>
   But it may be possible to use a ferryboat service that runs
across northern Albania to carry the heavy tanks most of the way to
the border.
</P>
<P>
   The ferry route follows the valley of the river Drin from the
northern city of Shkoder to the riverside of Fierze. From there it
might be possible to develop a further barge route across an
artificial lake called Lake Fierze eastward to the border of
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 1,600 years, generations of military planners have
considered the Drin valley a potential invasion route through the
Balkans. In the 4th century A.D., the Romans erected the citadel of
Vig along the river bank to prevent invasions from present-day
Kosovo by the Ostrogoths and Visigoths.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
