<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON, YELTSIN CONFER ON NEXT STEP TO END KOSOVO STANDOFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEWART M. POWELL  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and the NATO allies pressed a
carrot-and-stick campaign for ending the bloodbath in Kosovo
Sunday, encouraging intensified diplomatic intervention by Russia
while warning that the military alliance will now defend nations
bordering Yugoslavia from any Serbian attack.
</P>
<P>
   The punishing military offensive against Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic dominated the final day of the three-day summit
of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization, just as it had through a
gathering once planned to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the
Cold War-era alliance and map a new strategy for combating future
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, winding up the summit with a final statement,
emphasized that even amid fledgling diplomatic overtures, the
19-member NATO alliance will ``intensify our actions, military and
economic, until we achieve our objectives in Kosovo.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed that the alliance would protect Slovenia and six
non-NATO nations bordering Yugoslavia from any Yugoslav attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance ``will stand by the neighboring countries that have
accepted risks and hardship in support of this effort,'' Clinton
declared. ``If Mr. Milosevic threatens them for helping us, we will
respond.''
</P>
<P>
   National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said that
Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin agreed in an earlier
telephone call for the Kremlin leader to press ahead with
diplomatic efforts to press Milosevic to accept an armed occupation
force in Kosovo. Kosovo is a province of Serbia, the dominant state
in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin and the Russians are ``very serious about trying to find
a peaceful solution,'' Berger told the Cable News Network.
``President Clinton encouraged President Yeltsin to do so and I
think there will be continuing contacts over the days ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Yeltsin conversation, which lasted for nearly an
hour, triggered preparations for Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott, fluent in Russian, to travel to Europe to huddle with
Chernomyrdin in coming days.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana echoed U.S. support for
stepped-up Russian involvement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be positive to have the Russians on board,'' Solana
said. ``We want to recuperate the Russians.''
</P>
<P>
   Solana said keeping the Russians involved in the quest for a
diplomatic solution could help avoid a Russian veto in the
15-member U.N. Security Council when and if NATO seeks U.N.
participation in drafting a peace agreement acceptable to
Milosevic, or the supervision of a postwar occupation force in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``For that, Russia will be important,'' Solana explained.
</P>
<P>
   Berger said the ``biggest stumbling block'' for suspending the
allied air campaign that began on March 24 remains the disagreement
with Milosevic over ``the nature of an international presence that
would go into Kosovo'' to facilitate the return of 1.4 million
ethnic Albanians who have been uprooted by Milosevic's ``ethnic
cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   NATO allies favor a heavily armed international force, including
troops from NATO countries, Russia and Ukraine, to provide security
for frightened ethnic Albanians who have been driven from their
homes in Europe's most horrific campaign against civilians since
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Berger dismissed relying on unarmed international monitors with
``clipboards and pencils'' as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO has to play a significant role so that the Kosovars can
feel that they can come back in safety,'' Berger emphasized. ``That
is not something that Mr. Milosevic has yet agreed to but I believe
that the Russians will continue to work to try to move this towards
a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's conversation with Yeltsin followed up on a peace
mission to Belgrade on Thursday by former Russian Prime Minister
Viktor Chernomyrdin, who has close ties to Vice President Al Gore.
Chernomyrdin won Milosevic's acceptance of a U.N.-controlled
``international presence'' in Kosovo to guarantee the safe return
of refugees. NATO leaders rejected Milosevic's ill-defined
commitment as inadequate.
</P>
<P>
   NATO allies have been in touch with the Russians for nearly a
month to find an end to the Kosovo crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Russian Premier Yevgeny M. Primakov met with Milosevic in
Belgrade on March 30 to discuss a diplomatic compromise. But
Milosevic said he would not seek a political solution until the
NATO bombing campaign ended.
</P>
<P>
   NATO rejected suspension of the bombing campaign until Milosevic
accepted NATO's conditions. But on Friday, NATO leaders softened
their conditions, offering to suspend bombing if Milosevic began
withdrawing forces from Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pledged allied support to the leaders of Albania,
Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia, Romania and Slovenia during a
meeting with so-called ``front-line states.'' On Saturday, the
alliance extended comparable security guarantees to the democratic
government in Montenegro, which with Serbia forms Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Belgrade challenges its neighbors as a result of the
presence of NATO, we will respond,'' Clinton declared.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said the defense guarantees did not match iron-clad
guarantees protecting the NATO members. Under the NATO agreement,
an attack on one partner is deemed an attack on all.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we have given all the assurances that we will take with
the utmost concern any problem that they may have,'' Solana said,
adding: ``I think we have demonstrated that we are standing by
these countries and will not allow them to be destabilized as a
result of Milosevic's ethnic cleansing.''
</P>
<P>
   Albania and Macedonia are providing sites for camps for hundreds
of thousands of refugees from Kosovo as well as facilities for
thousands of allied troops.
</P>
<P>
   Romania and Slovenia have opened their air space to NATO war
planes and humanitarian flights _ a gesture expected by Bulgaria on
Monday. Croatia, Bulgaria and Bosnia are cooperating with
enforcement of an economic embargo against Yugoslavia. That
blockade is expected to tighten in the days ahead with NATO
enforcement of a ``visit and search regime'' on ships at sea.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea called the defense of Yugoslavia's
neighbors ``a direct and material interest of the alliance,''
adding: ``We will not tolerate threats against them or attacks on
them by Belgrade.''
</P>
<P>
   The meeting of Clinton, Solana and leaders from Yugoslavia's
neighbors underscored that ``in the region, Milosevic is all
alone,'' Shea emphasized. ``He is a pariah in his own back yard.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Berger, Clinton's top security adviser, said that Yeltsin
indicated in his telephone conversation with Clinton that Russia
would honor the oil embargo being imposed on Yugoslav oil imports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would expect all nations, including the Russians, would
abide by a regime to put a halt to oil shipments,'' Berger said,
adding that he had heard ``nothing in the conversation today with
President Yeltsin that was to the contrary.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton and alliance leaders said they were laying plans for a
comprehensive recovery plan for the Balkans akin to the post-World
War II Marshall Plan that helped rebuild Western Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The package includes security guarantees by NATO and assistance
from international financial institutions to help nations in the
Balkans build robust, free enterprise economies led by democratic
regimes that enjoy extensive trade ties with the West.
</P>
<P>
   Solana said the allies would launch ``a very important plan for
restabilization of the region'' in the days ahead, adding: ``We
really want to take as a priority the southeastern part of
Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   Shea added: ``This area has got to stop being the bleeding wound
of Europe.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
