<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2511 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZJOURNAL-MAKEOVER-M     04-25 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZJOURNAL-MAKEOVER-MEDIA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE STRUGGLING JOURNAL OF COMMERCE UPDATES ITS STRATEGY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By FELICITY BARRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Coverage, circulation and advertising have peeled
away from The Journal of Commerce for two generations. Stock and
bond tables disappeared two decades ago, commodities coverage was
hijacked by competitors and the advertising base eroded as large
shipping companies merged. But as the newspaper has sputtered
economically, it has continued to provide a mix of trade policy
analysis and coverage of the shipping industry.
</P>
<P>
   The recipe, however, is being changed. The newspaper _ which was
founded in 1827 by Samuel Morse, the inventor of the telegraph _ is
jettisoning most of its policy coverage, all of its commodity price
listings and 20 percent of its editorial staff _ four of 18 _ and
will devote itself to ``those who control the movement of goods,''
in the words of a recent Journal editorial. It will also convert
from a broadsheet to a tabloid format on June 1.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper plans to move from its broader perspective to
porthole-to-porthole coverage of an industry that has all the
glamour of the industrial age at a time when the financial world is
fixated on all things digital.
</P>
<P>
   Just as shipping companies' stock prices have been dwarfed by a
digitally charged Standard &AMP; Poor's index, the circulation figures
of The Journal of Commerce (18,290 at last count in September, half
its peak rate in the 1950s) have been dwarfed by those of snazzy
new business magazines like the two-year-old Fast Co. (256,000,
more than double its figure at the end of 1997). Advertising
revenues followed circulation down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had developed a kind of stodgy format that hadn't changed
for quite a while,'' said Roger Majak, the assistant secretary of
commerce for export administration and reader of The Journal of
Commerce for the last 10 years. He expressed the hope that in its
new incarnation the newspaper would concentrate on ``trade in all
its international implications.''
</P>
<P>
   Majak's vision, however, does not seem to mesh with that of
Willy Morgan, the publisher and executive vice president of the
Journal of Commerce Group, which is wholly owned by the Economist
Group. ``We've understood that we're in the business-to-business
business,'' he said, chuckling in mock despair at his own
description. Then he continued, ``we have, for the first time in
however old we are, a mission statement that says we aim to provide
actionable business information to help people get richer and more
profitable.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Morgan's strategy is to put all breaking news on the The
Journal's World Wide Web site (www.joc.com). ``We've done research
and we've found that something incredible, like 74 percent, of our
readers say they're connected to the Web,'' he said. ``We will be
marketing the paper and the Web holistically. Hideous word,
holistically.''
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to ``get actionable stuff to them faster on the Web,
along with a lot more of the breaking news,'' Morgan said. ``The
paper will be more of a how-to, news analysis, case-history
vehicle.''
</P>
<P>
   This approach will allow editors to enforce earlier production
deadlines, so that all articles are filed by 2 p.m. and the
Philadelphia printing plant can start to ship the newspaper off to
its nationwide destinations by early evening. It will also attract
a wider field of advertisers _ accounting firms that are branching
into the business of helping with shipping logistics, for instance,
or banks and financial services catering to shipping companies.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Tirschwell, the 37-year-old new editor of the newspaper,
said that until recently it had sought to provide in-depth coverage
of fields like energy, world trade, insurance, and air, rail and
truck transportation, as well as maritime issues. ``The information
needs of those separate areas have changed,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're making a very strong effort to try to consolidate what
we have,'' Tirschwell said. And while the paper will still do some
``broad-picture trade stories,'' he said, the coverage of how goods
get from one point to another, and how money can be made along the
way, matters most now.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
