u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-AHEAD26-COX     04-25 0594
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-AHEAD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO KEEPING OPEN THREE TRACKS TO VICTORY
 &HT;    With NATO-SUMMIT.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ After nearly five weeks of air strikes, NATO is
pressing the conflict against Yugoslavia on three separate tracks.
</P>
<P>
   The alliance's leaders are keeping the way clear for a swift
diplomatic end to the fighting on its own terms. At the same time,
it is escalating its bombing campaign and preparing for the
possibility of a prolonged war of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   Working closely with Moscow, the United States and other NATO
members are trying to formulate a plan that would save face for
President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia, yet still meet NATO's
bottom-line demands on Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   For NATO to halt the bombing, Milosevic must end his year-long
campaign of repression against the ethnic Albanian majority in
Kosovo, pull out his forces and allow armed peace-keepers led by
NATO to ensure the safe return of refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Those, at least, are the terms laid out in a Friday agreement
that set the tone for this weekend's summit marking the 50th
anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings last week with Foreign Minister Victor Chernomyrdin
of Russia, Milosevic signaled a willingness to go along with all
these conditions except the armed peace-keepers. Milosevic offered
to allow an unarmed United Nations monitoring team, but NATO
rejected the offer, saying it would not ensure the safe return of
the 1.5 million ethnic Albanians that Serbs have driven from their
homes in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott is to meet with
Chernomyrdin in the days ahead to try to build on the possibility
of a Russia-brokered plan.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon, meanwhile, is escalating the air war.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, has asked for
300 additional warplanes, and Hungary, one of NATO's three new
members, agreed Sunday to allow U.S. and allied pilots to fly out
of three of its airfields, a move expected to hasten the deployment
of the planes.
</P>
<P>
   Clark spent Sunday in Albania, where he said Apache attack
helicopters would soon be ready to strike inside Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   NATO also announced Sunday that 4,000 additional British and
German infantry troops are en route to Macedonia, where they will
joint 12,000 other NATO troops already there. The force is
providing humanitarian assistance to refugees at the moment, but
would form the vanguard of a larger NATO peacekeeping contingent,
should Milosevic capitulate.
</P>
<P>
   However, NATO appears to be bracing for the possibility that
Milosevic won't give in soon.
</P>
<P>
   As fears of a widening war have spread across the region, NATO
extended security guarantees to seven states along Yugoslavia's
borders _ Albania, Bosnia, Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia, Slovenia
and Romania.
</P>
<P>
   Security guarantees aren't taken on lightly. NATO wouldn't have
widened its defense obligations unless it were deemed essential to
carrying on a longer-term conflict with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The move fits, moreover, with NATO efforts to choke off
Yugoslavia's oil imports, with a naval blockade, if necessary.
</P>
<P>
   By placing efforts to starve Yugoslavia of oil alongside its
promise to widen its security umbrella to cover every state in the
Balkans except the one it's attacking, NATO has sent an
unmistakable signal: the alliance is hunkering down for the
possibility of weeks, if not months, of continuing war in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
