<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0092 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 17:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2521 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-INTELLECT-ART-     04-25 0974
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-INTELLECT-ART-910(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MACEDONIAN CITY IS HAVEN FOR KOSOVO INTELLECTUALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BARRY BEARAK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TETOVO, Macedonia _ Here they stroll, up Marshal Tito Street,
some of the most recognizable faces of Kosovo's diaspora. Their
lives are now scattered pieces, some parts irretrievable _ homes
lost, loved ones missing, work destroyed, faith worn down to the
nub.
</P>
<P>
   In the past month, hundreds of the uprooted intelligentsia of
Pristina, Kosovo's capital, have come to Tetovo, a Macedonian city
of 300,000 people, dozens of good coffee houses and a university.
In Tetovo, as in Pristina, most people are ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
   So who was strolling here on Sunday?
</P>
<P>
   Luan Jaha, the stage actor, came along. He made it across the
border three weeks weeks ago. His face was pale, his eyes tired. He
seemed like an old ball that had lost its bounce.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no mind any more with which to think,'' he said wanly
and apologetically. ``My wife asks me what am I going to do, and I
say what can I do but wait? But it is not even waiting that I do,
because waiting means I expect something. And what is there to
expect?''
</P>
<P>
   And there walked the young playwright Jeton Budima, wearing a
black leather jacket and biting the end of a toothpick. He and his
wife and daughter spent four nights sleeping in their car, stranded
in the awful traffic of so many people with vehicles trying to get
out.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly you are an animal on the run, a refugee, a number in
the world's book of statistics,'' he said. ``Suddenly, you feel
like human garbage.''
</P>
<P>
   They were here, but their talk was mostly of who was not. Had
there been word of so-and-so? Was she among the many still hiding
in Pristina? Had she gone to Albania? Was she dead?
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper editor Baton Haxhiu was almost dead. NATO
announced news of his murder on March 29. Haxhiu heard the live
broadcast, finding the information inaccurate but hardly
inconceivable. He surmised that he was on a Serbian hit list,
joining such authentically dead as the civil-rights lawyer Bajram
Kelmendi and the trade unionist Agim Hajrizi, both murdered by the
Serbs shortly after NATO bombing began on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   After a harrowing escape, Haxhiu set up shop here on Marshal
Tito Street. His newspaper, Koha Ditore, was the most respected
Albanian-language daily in Kosovo. Then, on March 24, its offices
in Pristina were ransacked and its night watchmen killed. The
daily's founder, Veton Surroi, a delegate to the failed peace talks
on Kosovo, went into hiding.
</P>
<P>
   The Serbs, said Haxhiu, ``want to cut all connections to
truth.''
</P>
<P>
   As he talked, he was standing outside the paper's new office, a
tiny space jammed with desktop computers but lacking even a single
phone line. The staff intends to end Koha Ditore's monthlong
silence on Monday, distributing free copies in refugee camps.
</P>
<P>
   Someday, Haxhiu said, the Serbs will awaken from their moral
slumber, but ``we Albanians will never forget what has happened to
us, and it will be very hard to forgive.''
</P>
<P>
   Across the street is the popular Restaurant Arbi, its espresso
machine ceaselessly exhaling steam and, at night, its bartenders
pouring stiff drinks. Life can be terribly painful and some believe
the best way to look at it is through the refracted light of a shot
glass.
</P>
<P>
   Only weeks ago, these same people would have been chatting in
Pristina's crowded cafes like Magic and Hani i 2 Roberteve. Both
places were attacked by the Serbian paramilitary. The young actress
Ardiana Abdullah was killed with a machine gun, said her friends,
now in exile here.
</P>
<P>
   Migjen Kelmendi lost a cousin in one attack and expected that he
would soon be among the slain. His face is well known, as are his
opinions. He is a writer. He once sang in a rock band.
</P>
<P>
   ``This phenomenon of emptying a city and pushing people out of
their lives _ this I had only seen in movies,'' said Kelmendi,
sipping coffee at Restaurant Arbi.
</P>
<P>
   He used the words ``holocaust'' and ``genocide'' in his
descriptions, but then regretted it and asked forgiveness. These
are terms others reserve for their own catastrophes and he worried
that the Kosovo Albanians' plight did not yet measure high enough
on the calibrations of human misery.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I feel I have had death as close to me as my skin or my
T-shirt,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the clatter of silverware and plates, he told his story,
and it was not an uncommon one. He went into hiding after the first
NATO airstrike. Six days later, the Serbian paramilitary came into
his Pristina neighborhood and ordered everyone to leave in three
minutes. Fear had been joined by chaos. The soldiers marched
thousands of people toward a train station. Kelmendi pulled a cap
low on his forehead, trying to conceal his familiar face.
</P>
<P>
   ``This scene was biblical, you could say,'' he continued. ``We
were marched at gunpoint through the center of town, and I will
especially remember that our Serbian neighbors who saw this were
indifferent. No one asked: What are you doing to these people?''
</P>
<P>
   He estimates that 7,000 ethnic Albanians were packed into the 20
cars of a passenger train. The border was only 50 miles away but
the journey took six hours. The train kept stopping, and when it
did, the air became as still as the locomotive. People gasped and
collapsed. Parents pleaded for water for their children. At least
two old men died.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want, I could also tell you about conditions at the
refugee camp at Blace,'' he said, referring to his first days in
Macedonia. ``But maybe this is enough horror for now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   A few tables away sat Vesel Nuhiu, dean of the philology
department at the ethnic Albanians' underground university in
Pristina, founded after the Serbs stripped Kosovo of broad autonomy
in 1989. He was immaculately dressed in the only shirt and sport
coat he left with. His family had five minutes to pack after the
paramilitary arrived with rifles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is hard to describe the madness of such a thing,'' he said.
``We were with a colleague of mine from the faculty and we agreed
to go to Tetovo together. But in the chaos we were separated almost
immediately. I was lucky to leave with my car, though at every
intersection, the police asked for 100 or 200 Deutschmarks (roughly
$55 or $110) or more.''
</P>
<P>
   The University of Tetovo has welcomed the exiled professors and
students, but the school was already overcrowded. Like the Serbs,
the Macedonians disapprove of colleges that teach in the Albanian
language. The university here is tolerated, if not officially
accredited, and its classes are held in basements, garages and
apartments.
</P>
<P>
   ``My department had 70 professors and associates, but I only
know what has happened to five or seven,'' said Nuhiu. ``I just met
one here at the restaurant. Others are a mystery.''
</P>
<P>
   People are caught up like corks in a swift current. They once
fit snugly into a bottle. Now the bottle is gone.
</P>
<P>
   Along Marshal Tito Street came Ardian Arifaj, youthful and
serious and angry, the managing editor of Koha Ditore. He had a
paper to put out. He had recovered purpose, but not the place or
the possessions or the people he needed. He felt incomplete.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is not only a biophysiological concept,'' he said. ``My
life is the place where I grew up, where I live, my desk, my books,
my music, my computer, the people I know and the places I go to
have fun. This is what I am and without it I do not exist. I am no
longer the same as I was. I have lost my personality. And now I am
merely surviving.''
</P>
<P>
   Much of Pristina has come to Tetovo, but Tetovo can never be
Pristina. Kosovo is home and the ethnic Albanians believe _ or
fervently hope _ that one day soon they will go back.
</P>
<P>
   Presumably, they will again share their cities with Serbs, the
neighbors who they say have been so lacking in conscience. Can such
a deep hurt ever heal?
</P>
<P>
   Arifaj pondered this and recounted a story that he heard as a
child:
</P>
<P>
   There was a naughty boy whose father would hammer a nail into a
piece of wood each time his son did something wrong. One day the
boy asked why, and when it was explained, the boy decided he would
behave better. Each time he did something good, he wanted his
father to remove a nail from the board. Eventually all the nails
came out.
</P>
<P>
   Arifaj let a few seconds pass, allowing suspense to precede the
story's moral.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, the nails were gone,'' he said. ``But the holes always
remained.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
