<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LEAH-PERSONALS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 By LEAH GARCHIK  
 c 1999, San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BATTENING DOWN THE HATCHES &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't avoid it!'' says the cover line for  &UR; Victor &LR; 
 &UR; Porlier &LR; 's scare-mongering book, ``Y2K, an Action Plan for January
1, 2000'' (HarperCollins; $10.95). This volume includes a
comprehensive series of checklists of items to store in preparation
for the turn of the century. Among them:
</P>
<P>
   Whistles (for communication, a la  &UR; Lauren Bacall &LR; ); 10 pounds of
beans (never mind your roommates); a flour sifter (to smooth the
roux); a hand pump (multipurpose); plunger (muting your brass
instrument is a secondary use); No-Doz (who wants to sleep through
the crisis?); candle molds (candle making is recommended as an
enjoyable project for children); nonelectric iron (you'll want your
clothes pressed); duct tape (for fixing ducts); and an array of
weapons (pesky neighbors).
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FLASH &LR;
</P>
<P>
   - Interview magazine to  &UR; Harvey Keitel &LR; : ``Many of the
characters you've portrayed over the years arrive on the screen
from a position of strength. You have a quality that gives them a
power that is very manly, both physically and psychologically. Yet
they're also able to exhibit deep pain. Does that ability come from
doing a whole lot of living?''
</P>
<P>
   Harvey Keitel to Interview magazine: ``Hmm. It probably comes
from a strong desire to suck my thumb.''
</P>
<P>
   - Gear magazine says that when  &UR; George Lucas  &LR; was writing the
original screenplay for ``Star Wars,'' he ``developed stomach and
chest pains and would compulsively cut off patches of his hair with
scissors.''
</P>
<P>
   -  &UR; Andrew Lloyd Webber &LR;  is planning to open a hotel-theater
complex in Las Vegas, reports the New York Post, where his musicals
will play 24 hours a day.
</P>
<P>
   - The Times of India _ in a story cited by Slate _ has
deconstructed  &UR; Madeleine Albright &LR; 's jewelry: When she wears an
American eagle brooch, she's being hawkish; her cherub brooch means
she's sweet and gentle; her balloon brooch means she's festive.
</P>
