<P>
   KOSOVO-GRAVES _ KUKES, Albania _ The way Hasan Hyseni pieced
together the story of the carnage he found near Izbica, his Kosovo
village, Serbian forces pursued a simple tactic there: ``Every
person they saw, they killed. Five here. Ten there.'' Hyseni said
he is one of the Kosovar Albanians who discovered the butchery.
Then he helped gather the bodies and dig 151 shallow graves. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WITH PHOTOS: mugs of the Hyseni and NATO aerial photo of the
grave site. (Kunstel, Cox News Service) 40.
</P>
<P>
   ALBANIA-MILITARY _ RINAS AIR BASE, Albania _ Stepping up its
psychological pressure on Slobodon Milosevic, the Western alliance
on Sunday began deploying limited numbers of American heavy battle
tanks into Albania. Story includes comments by NATO commander Gen.
Wesley Clark at a news conference here and roundup of day's bombing
raids. (Albright, Cox News Service) 15. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   NATO-SUMMIT _ WASHINGTON _ A NATO strategy for a long-term
conflict in Kosovo began taking shape here Sunday, as the alliance
extended formal security guarantees to seven bordering states,
ramped up troop deployments and firmed up plans to escalate the air
war using airports in Hungary. (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   NATO-CITY _ WASHINGTON _ Secured and sanitized, the nation's
capital duly impressed many of the journalists and diplomats who
converged for three days of NATO meetings, press conferences and
dinners. (Dart, Cox News Service). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATO-AHEAD _ WASHINGTON _ After nearly five weeks of air strikes
against Yugoslavia, NATO is moving on three separate tracks: hoping
for a swift yet honorable diplomatic end
</P>
<P>
   to the conflict, escalating its bombing campaign, and preparing
for the possibility of a prolonged war of attrition. (Deans, Cox
News Service) 30. MOVED
</P>
