<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Monday, April 26, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Polar air will surge into New England behind a strengthening
cold front. Brisk winds from the northwest will drive much cooler
weather back into the Northeast during the next 24 hours. Ahead of
the front, ample sunshine will combine with increasingly mild winds
to raise readings 10 degrees above seasonal levels from Cape Cod to
the middle Atlantic region.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore winds, circulating around high pressure off the Carolina
coast, will keep an abundance of clouds over Georgia and the
western Carolinas. Showers are likely near the southern
Appalachians.
</P>
<P>
   The air mass over the Gulf states will stay warm and very humid,
which will give rise to clusters of thundershowers. A cold front in
eastern Texas will be the triggering mechanism for strong to severe
thunderstorms near the Texas coast and over Louisiana and Arkansas.
Flooding rains and isolated tornadoes are possible.
</P>
<P>
   A wedge of dry and pleasant air is expected from the northern
Ohio Valley to the northeast Plains as high pressure slips
southward from Canada. Winds from the southeast will extend to
30,000 feet over the upper plains, and this will promote widespread
clouds and patches of showers, from the Dakotas to Kansas. Somewhat
drier air will be drawn northward from Mexico into western and
central Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Showers of rain and snow will linger over the eastern Rockies. A
new push of polar air should spread into the Pacific Northwest with
plenty of clouds and showers inland and a mixture of sun and clouds
at the coast. The Southwest will be brighter and warmer.
</P>
<P>
   Focus: Rochester Rains
</P>
<P>
   In March, southern Minnesota and Wisconsin enjoyed an unusual
two-week streak without a drop of rain. This has changed
dramatically as Rochester, Minn., is now on the verge of its
wettest April. As of Saturday evening, 6.39 inches of rain had
fallen, just .09 inches shy of the record set in 1990. Across the
Mississippi River, La Crosse, Wis., has now moved into ninth place
for April rainfall. Oddly, in Rochester, four of the five wettest
Aprils have occurred in this decade, leading to speculation about a
long-term shift in spring weather patterns over the Middle West.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
