<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 18:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDIA-POLITICS-650&AMP;AD     04-25 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIA WILL LIKELY HOLD ELECTIONS FOR THIRD TIME IN 3 YEARS 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ A week after the Hindu nationalist-led
government collapsed, India appeared to be headed for its third
general election in three years as the opposition's efforts to form
a new government disintegrated Sunday in acrimony and finger
pointing.
</P>
<P>
   Congress Party President Sonia Gandhi, the widowed heir to the
nation's political dynasty who actively campaigned to bring down
the government, admitted Sunday that her first attempt to lead the
party back to power had failed.
</P>
<P>
   She was unable to win enough support from other opposition
parties for Congress, which has only about a quarter of the votes
in Parliament, to form a government by itself. And she ruled out
supporting a coalition that would have necessarily included more
than 20 squabbling, demanding parties in the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not ready to bargain,'' Mrs. Gandhi said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi's reputation for calm, shrewd leadership was
tarnished in the past week as Congress helped shatter one
government but was unable to put together the shards of the
opposition to form a new one. In what now appears to have been a
bluff, she claimed on Wednesday that she had the 272 votes for a
majority, but confessed Sunday that she had come up with only 239.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Gandhi, who has never held elective office, informed
President K. R. Narayanan of the political stalemate. It is now up
to him to decide what to do.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said there was an outside chance the
president would give the coalition that narrowly lost a confidence
vote a week ago another chance. But so far, that coalition, led by
the Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, has claimed 270
supporters, still two votes short of a majority.
</P>
<P>
   The more likely option is to hold general elections since no
alliance of the more than 40 parties in Parliament has mustered a
majority.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, who resigned a week ago but
stayed on as a caretaker, announced Sunday evening after meeting
with Narayanan that he would call a Cabinet meeting on Monday
morning to discuss the political crisis. He did not say what action
they would take. Nor did he describe what the president had
recommended.
</P>
<P>
   But analysts said it is likely that the Cabinet will request
dissolution of the Lok Sabha, the lower house of parliament, and
call for new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Looking tired and dejected, Vajpayee, 72, pointedly noted that
some in the opposition had claimed a new government would be formed
in five minutes. If there are elections, leaders of the Bharatiya
Janata Party will undoubtedly portray their main rival, the
Congress Party, as a destructive force more interested in coming to
power than in the country's need for political stability.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee, a grandfatherly looking man with an understated
manner, is generally thought to be more popular than his party,
which has had trouble shaking its reputation for being anti-Muslim
and, more recently, anti-Christian, in its pursuit of an idea of
India as a nation united by a Hindu way of life.
</P>
<P>
   Vajpayee has said in the past that his current stint as prime
minister would be his last in government, but on Thursday, during a
somber dinner party at the home of a supporting member of
parliament, he chuckled mirthlessly when asked if he would run
again. Then he fell silent. Munching from a plate of sweets, he
drifted away to another conversation.
</P>
<P>
   If parliament is dissolved, elections must take place within six
months. Pulling off national elections in India _ the world's
largest democracy with more than 600 million voters _ is a costly,
gargantuan task. And because of the timing, voting would either
have to take place in the near future, during the scorching summer
when temperatures routinely top 105 degrees in some parts of the
country, or during monsoon rains that leave parts of the country
flooded, muddy and impassable.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The way the last week has played out seems likely to have
damaged the Congress Party politically and created sympathy for the
Bharatiya Janata Party, which lost a confidence vote by the
narrowest margin ever in independent India _ a single vote.
</P>
<P>
   The government's fall came after Jayalalitha Jayaram, head of an
18-member party from the southern state of Tamil Nadu, withdrew her
support, but Mrs. Gandhi is seen to have encouraged Jayalalitha, a
former actress who is known by her first name, to jump ship by
attending a tea party in her honor, a step that suggested Congress
might be a friendlier port of call.
</P>
<P>
   After Jayalalitha quit, Mrs. Gandhi personally lobbied many
party leaders to vote against the government.
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts say her advisers badly miscalculated the
degree of support Congress would get to run a government that left
all its allies on the outside looking in. Mulayam Singh Yadav,
leader of a party in India's most populous state, Uttar Pradesh,
that is a bitter rival of Congress, flatly refused to support any
government that excluded his party. Without his 20 votes, Mrs.
Gandhi's gambit was finished.
</P>
<P>
   Until the current debacle, Mrs. Gandhi had won plaudits for her
restraint in seeking power. Repeatedly, she had stressed that
Congress needed to rebuild its corroded foundations before it took
power.
</P>
<P>
   She had begun installing a younger generation of leaders at the
state level. Attempting to rebuild the party's fractured coalition,
she had pushed through a measure requiring that 53 percent of party
officials at all levels be women, Muslims or low-caste people.
</P>
<P>
   The strategy had seemed to be working. In November, Congress
clobbered the Bharatiya Janata Party in state elections, largely on
the issue of rising vegetable prices.
</P>
<P>
   But some Congress Party officials said that in recent months
party leaders had begun to worry that the Hindu nationalists were
consolidating their hold on power.
</P>
<P>
   Prices had come down. Attacks on Christian churches and schools,
which many believed were fomented by groups allied with the party,
had dwindled. The government had introduced a budget that was well
received. And after months of mixed signals, it had pressed forward
with a number of economic proposals to encourage investment and
foreign trade.
</P>
<P>
   When Jayalalitha's withdrawal deprived the government of a
majority, Congress went into action to insure that Vajpayee's
coalition lost the vote of confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Gandhi had played her hand very cooly and unhurriedly in
favor of waiting for a few more state assembly elections,'' said
Pran Chopra, a political analyst at the Center for Policy Research
in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   But this time she listened to advisers who told her that
Congress could win control of the government.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very bad advice,'' Chopra said. ``But the advisers were
appointed by her and the responsibility of that advice belongs to
her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
