<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-L </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`L.A. RIOTS REVISITED:' THE DAY VIOLENCE ECLIPSED THE SUNLIGHT 
</HEADLINE>
 . A . RIOTS-REVIEW-NYT   (Eds: Production notes appear at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
 &HT;    (DW) 
 By WALTER GOODMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Although ``L.A. Riots Revisited'' comes up with no revelations,
it does bring back the striking failure of the Los Angeles police
to contain, much less control, the April 1992 riots that left much
of the city ablaze. While mobs ran through South-Central Los
Angeles, looting and burning and attacking whites who found
themselves in the wrong place, the police dithered, retreated and
for a time surrendered to violence.
</P>
<P>
   The rioting, we are reminded Monday night at 9 on A&AMP;E, was set
off when a jury from Simi Valley, a mainly white town, returned a
not guilty verdict for four white officers who had been seen on
video beating a black man named Rodney King. Bill Kurtis,
narrating, suggests that the jury was reacting to a few seconds of
the tape that fuzzily caught King charging at the police officers,
images not widely included in the repeatedly broadcast pictures of
the King beating. Whether that explanation, advanced by someone
identified as ``a defense attorney,'' can mitigate the police
outburst, the viewer can decide.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, the suggestion that the officers were forced to club
King because they had been forbidden to use choke holds does not
explain the gratuitous quality of the beating revealed on the
video.
</P>
<P>
   In his search for explanations of the riots, Kurtis criticizes
television's treatment of the beating, with its heightened,
slow-motion effects, as well as the live coverage of the riots,
which may have further incited the crowd. He does not note that his
own series, ``Investigative Reports,'' is given to such techniques
of docudrama. Monday night's program, for example, opens with
re-enactments that have no other purpose than to add to the
emotional punch.
</P>
<P>
   The program also suggests that the efforts of individuals, black
and white, to calm rioters and help victims were insufficiently
reported. Perhaps, but no doubt is left that the basic failure was
the lack of leadership by the authorities. Once it became apparent
on the streets that the police could not or would not react
forcefully to the outbursts of violence in a neighborhood known for
the presence of youth gangs, the results were ordained. It was,
Kurtis says, ``a lesson in failure.''
</P>
<P>
   ``L.A. Riots Revisited'' ends on an optimistic if somewhat
wishful note, with reports on efforts by black churches to rebuild
burned-out areas of South-Central. But the pictures of
still-devastated areas are likely to leave viewers reflecting on
the job that a mob can do when the police fail to do their job.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `L.A. RIOTS REVISITED'
</P>
<P>
   At 9 p.m. Monday on A&AMP;E
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
