<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2542 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OSCAR-DOCUMENTARIES-N     04-25 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OSCAR-DOCUMENTARIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OSCAR BOARD RETHINKS FATE OF THE SHORT DOCUMENTARY  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By TERRY PRISTIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Margaret Lazarus had been making films about social issues for
17 years before she won an Academy Award in 1994 for ``Defending
Our Lives,'' a 30-minute documentary recording the experiences of
battered women who were convicted of killing their husbands.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination alone landed her $135,000 film a 10-city tour
along with other nominated short films. But the Oscar made the film
an instant classic with women's groups, giving Ms. Lazarus _ and
her cause _ enormous exposure and making it much easier for her to
raise money for subsequent work. ``I'd been making a lot of films,
but nothing else propelled to the heights this did,'' Ms. Lazarus
said, referring to her Academy Award. ``It made the film enter a
different dimension.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, however, the board of governors of the
Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences, which administers the
Oscars, voted to eliminate the separate award for short
documentaries (40 minutes or under), contending that there were no
longer enough entries to justify it. The decision meant that next
year, short and feature-length documentaries would compete in one
category.
</P>
<P>
   The Jan. 7 vote provoked an outcry from documentary filmmakers,
who say that short documentaries, which were first recognized by
the academy in 1943, are an art form in themselves, a vehicle for
provocative or challenging subjects and a path of entry for young
filmmakers with limited resources. Many suggested that the action
was taken to shorten the Oscars presentation, an accusation that
the Academy leadership vigorously denies.
</P>
<P>
   The protest led to a resolution seeking to restore the separate
award. It will be taken up by the board at a meeting Tuesday, said
Bruce Davis, the executive director of the Academy. Last week
Martin Scorsese, Robert Redford, the director Taylor Hackford,
Michael Eisner, the chairman of Disney, and 55 other prominent
members of the film industry joined the movement to overturn the
decision. In an ad running in trade papers, they said that ``Oscars
for short films provide inspiration to filmmakers and moviegoers
worldwide.''
</P>
<P>
   Defending the board's decision, Davis said that a separate
category for short documentaries was not warranted because most of
the 23 films that were entered for nomination this year were made
not for movie theaters but for television, which is outside the
purview of the Academy. ``We have to maintain that distinction,''
he said. ``It's not about snobbery.''
</P>
<P>
   Imax films, which are being shown at an increasing number of
theaters, are an exception, Davis acknowledged. ``But over the last
five years, there have been two and a half Imax documentaries a
year,'' he said. ``That's not enough to maintain a real category.''
</P>
<P>
   Filmmakers say the Academy's leadership is out of touch. Short
films are shown in a wide variety of places, including theme parks,
museums and film festivals, said Bob Rogers, a veteran film maker
who was nominated twice in the category for short live action
films.
</P>
<P>
   Rogers and other critics of the Academy's decision said the
academy would be better advised to delete some of the plodding
Oscar night production numbers rather than an award that often
produces some of the broadcast's freshest moments. Jessica Yu,
whose short film, ``Breathing Lessons: The Life and Work of Mark
O'Brien,'' was honored last year, is still remembered for saying
that her dress cost more than her film.
</P>
<P>
   This year Keiko Ibi, who won for her film ``The Personals:
Improvisations on Romance in the Golden Years,'' touched audiences
when she delivered a succinct speech thanking her ``mother for
letting me come to the United States so I can follow my dream to
become a filmmaker.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, the board of governors decided to eliminate the awards
for both short documentaries and short films using actors, which
are known as live action films. The move drew a similar protest
from some of the movie industry's biggest names, leading the board,
in what some people considered a face-saving effort, to shelve the
decision and commission a study. After examining the 88-page report
by a researcher, Heather Lindquist, the governors reversed
themselves and restored the categories.
</P>
<P>
   The issue came up again after Chuck Workman, a filmmaker whose
montages are seen during the awards presentation, observed at a
meeting of the Academy's executive committee that both the number
and the quality of short-documentary entrees had declined. But
Workman, who won an Oscar in 1986 for a short documentary,
``Precious Images,'' said he had never suggested that the category
be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   In a letter, Workman urged Davis and Robert Rehme, the president
of the academy, to retain the category and predicted that the
caliber would improve if short documentaries shown at film
festivals were allowed to compete.
</P>
<P>
   As several other filmmakers suggested, Hackford, the director of
``An Officer and a Gentleman,'' said he thought the consolidation
of short and long documentaries was a first step that would
eventually result in the elimination of short live action and short
animated films. He said that an Oscar he won for a live action
short, ``Teenage Father,'' in 1978 was pivotal in his career. ``It
gave me an entree that I didn't have before,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bill Guttentag, who won an Oscar in 1989 for the short
documentary ``You Don't Have to Die,'' about a young boy's triumph
over cancer, said that short films deserved to be honored for their
quality rather than the boost they give winners. ``Is a short story
by Philip Roth any less valid than one of his novels?'' he asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
