<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0108 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 18:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-INDONESIAN-WRITER-ART     04-25 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INDONESIAN-WRITER-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AN INDONESIAN WRITER AND SURVIVOR PREACHES COURAGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mich., Wis., Calif., Vt., Canada, Netherlands)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(lb) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ For three decades Pramoedya Ananta Toer, Indonesia's
greatest modern writer, felt the full force of President Suharto's
military state.
</P>
<P>
   Clubbed on the head when he was seized by the police in 1965 _
Indonesia's infamous ``year of living dangerously'' _ he lost much
of his hearing. Arrested without charge, he was imprisoned and
silenced for 14 years, confined for most of that time to a remote
island penal colony where he was forced into hard labor and had to
forage for food. More than a dozen years of closely monitored house
arrest followed.
</P>
<P>
   He is a free man now on his first visit to the United States,
his first trip abroad since 1959. At 74 he is small and frail and
speaks sparingly and quietly. But when he speaks, there is no
mistaking his strength, and no sign that his tormentors ever came
close to breaking his will.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't just seem strong; it takes more than strength to
survive,'' he said on a balmy afternoon in the garden outside the
United Nations, which he had just toured. ``It took resistance,
mental resistance as well as spiritual resistance. Strength was not
enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya's story of suffering and survival on the prison island
of Buru are the theme of a memoir, ``The Mute's Soliloquy,'' to be
published in the United States on Wednesday by Hyperion East.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Mute's Soliloquy'' is a collection of ruminations from the
Buru experience in the form of notes to himself and unsent letters
to his eight children, whose growing-up years he missed. The
letters are full of fatherly advice: don't swim carelessly in the
sea; take your vitamins; learn to relax before falling asleep at
night; study history.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in Indonesian through an interpreter, his American
editor and friend, John McGlynn, a co-founder of the Lontar
Foundation to promote Indonesian literature abroad, Pramoedya
(pronounced pram-OOH-dee-ah) is still pained by the damage his
ordeal caused his family. In an interview, he was acerbic about the
quality of Indonesian intellectual life and guarded in his
predictions about Indonesia's future.
</P>
<P>
   Last May the 30-year rule of Suharto came to an end amid street
protests against his corrupt and dictatorial military government.
At the same time an economic crisis gutted the currency and
Indonesian living standards, bringing the International Monetary
Fund into the management of the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Under an interim president, B.J. Habibie, elections are to be
held in June to elect a new parliament, which in turn is to choose
a new president this fall for Indonesia, the world's
fourth-most-populous nation.
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya seems to doubt that Indonesians, consumed now by the
settling of ethnic and political scores through violence on several
islands, have the courage to make a clean sweep of the old order.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a whole country of `yes' people,'' he remarked
dismissively.
</P>
<P>
   He never was one. A leftist and supporter of Indonesia's first
president, Sukarno, Pramoedya continues to hold some anti-Western
opinions and suspicions about the United States. He discourses
freely on the corruption of the Indonesian military and the
cowardice of the older generations, which are now closing ranks, he
says, against change and possible revelations about the past.
</P>
<P>
   He still has critics who suspect that he was closer than he
admits to a communist movement that was intent on controlling
intellectual life in the 1960s and might have been prepared to
seize political power in 1965, when Suharto stepped into a murky
coup and tens of thousands of suspected leftists and ethnic Chinese
were slaughtered.
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya says he cannot understand why anyone would be
interested in these old accusations. But he says that to get into
politics now would only revive old charges that he is a communist.
Sukarno's daughter, Megawati Sukarnoputri, is expected to be a
leading candidate for president in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya, who says he freed himself from house arrest in 1992
by simply walking out onto the street on Human Rights Day, has
picked up several international prizes in recent years, among them
the 1995 Magsaysay Award, Asia's top honor, and a UNESCO award in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   His newest book was the subject of an Asia Society program on
Thursday. Last week Fordham University, which arranged his trip to
the United States, held a three-day symposium on his work.
</P>
<P>
   He is to receive an honorary degree this week from the
University of Michigan and then plans to visit the University of
Wisconsin and Berkeley before touring Canada and finally the
Netherlands, the colonial power in Indonesia for 300 years. In 1947
Pramoedya was imprisoned by the Dutch.
</P>
<P>
   For Pramoedya, recognition late in life is no recompense for
``all the things that have been stolen from my life.'' Separation
for years from his wife, Maimoenah Thamrin, and children in the
1960s and '70s was a kind of torture in itself, because he had
vowed as a young man to be a better father than his own scholarly
but distant father had been.
</P>
<P>
   Postcards to his children were censored. ``But an even greater
tragedy than being unable to teach my own children was that the
atmosphere created by the New Order acted as a stronger teacher for
them,'' he said, using the Suharto regime's name for itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was extremely difficult for them. During the time I was
away, they had to bear the burden of curses, people looking down on
them, people exiling them within the community, so that they
themselves didn't grow up naturally. They didn't become the people
they should have been.''
</P>
<P>
   One of his daughters was barred from taking a final exam in
pharmacology, although she topped the class. Even after Pramoedya's
release from Buru in 1979, he said, his only son, then a young
teen-ager, was beaten by a gang of taunters, and then arrested and
tortured by the police officers who arrived to break up the brawl.
</P>
<P>
   If Pramoedya was deprived of a normal life, Indonesia was also
denied the work of many writers and thinkers who shared his
experience of harassment and years in prison. He does not hold the
government solely responsible for their isolation.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to look at the intellectuals themselves,'' he said.
``A good portion of the blame rests on the intellectuals. The
Indonesian intelligentsia has no tradition of speaking out. The
intelligentsia, for the most part, comes from the upper class. And
that particular group of people was raised to respect the status
quo. They listen to what their superiors say. This unfortunate
aspect of Indonesian culture came to the fore in the past 30 years,
where everyone from top to bottom had to listen to the top. The
only exceptions you might find were the intellectuals who lived
abroad.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But not many Indonesians lived and wrote abroad, being unable to
tear themselves away from the intense cultures of their
archipelago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the problem is that many Indonesians felt that they
could not survive abroad, not just in the intellectual sphere but
in the material sphere,'' he said. ``Indonesians seem to have a bit
of an inferiority complex presenting themselves to the foreign
world. Even when you talk about Indonesia itself, you don't find
many Indonesians who know their own history. A lot of them have to
read textbooks written by foreigners.''
</P>
<P>
   In Jakarta, where Pramoedya is still wary of leaving home alone
for fear of government spies or the police, his books of both
fiction and history remain officially banned, though they are now
widely available.
</P>
<P>
   His best-known novels form a four-part series, the Buru Quartet
_ ``This Earth of Mankind,'' ``Child of All Nations,''
``Footsteps'' and ``House of Glass'' _ built around the life of
Minke, a Javanese boy who comes of age in the waning years of Dutch
colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   The books were composed in his head on Buru, a mental exercise
that helped preserve his strength and sanity. They were written
down only late in his imprisonment, when he was allowed a
typewriter.
</P>
<P>
   Politically charged students now flock to Pramoedya to draw on
his wisdom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wave after wave of young people come to my house, and I keep
telling them, `Have the courage to stand up for your
convictions,''' he said. ``All that the younger generation needs is
capital, capital in the sense of bravery and courage. Bravery and
courage does not come down from the heavens. You have to create it
yourself. It's as much a part of fitness as a physical fitness
exercise.''
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya is impressed by the emergence of the student movement
that drove Suharto from power last May, especially since many of
the young people were drawn from comfortable families in which
challenging authority was not encouraged.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oddly enough, having been raised in deceit has also opened
their eyes to deceit and has brought them together as a class,'' he
said. ``They are without power. They had no weapons. They were
without hope of success. But they went after Suharto and they
brought him down.''
</P>
<P>
   The future ``is completely dependent upon the youth,'' he said.
``If they can pass the test of history itself, Indonesia will
survive and become stronger. But if they can't, I don't see much of
a future. I see only two choices ahead: One is that students
achieve their goal of complete reformation of the government or, if
that doesn't work, the consequence could well be social revolution.
If the latter were to happen, that would be the end of Indonesia as
we know it.''
</P>
<P>
   Pramoedya spends his days writing a diary and occasional
articles, while collecting histories of prisoners whom the Dutch
sent into exile in Irian Jaya, Indonesia's share of New Guinea. He
is keeping a journal about his current trip and his impressions of
the United States. For years he held this country responsible for
prolonging colonialism in Indonesia and interfering even after it
ended.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general my intellectual opinions about the United States
are pretty much what they once were,'' he said. ``But this trip has
given me the opportunity to balance my views, to fill out the
picture. I find it such a pleasure to see so many ethnic groups,
religions, people from all over the world being able to live here
in harmony and peace,'' he said, after stops in Washington,
Bennington, Vt., and Ithaca, before arriving in New York City on
Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am pleased to see police forces without the arrogance that
is apparent in my own country,'' he added. Not yet knowing about
the criticism of police violence in New York recently, his general
reaction to American police was positive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Indonesians seem to have a problem with power,'' he said.
``They get just a little bit of it, even an ounce, and they go
overboard.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
