<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2552 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONFED-DAY26-COX     04-25 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONFED-DAY26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Confederate Memorial Day forgotten by many
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Frank ``Skip'' Alcorn IV remembers as a kid scooping
minie balls ``by the bucketful'' out of Tanyard Creek in Collier
Hills. Once he ``scared my mother to death'' by lugging home a
cannon ball he'd found. And his mind's eye still sees the
``fantastic, deep trenches'' on the spot where Piedmont Hospital
now stands.
</P>
<P>
   Like many people, Alcorn, 51, laments that in a city long linked
to the Civil War by ``Gone With The Wind,'' so many remnants of
Atlanta's past have vanished like the trenches he remembers from
his adolescence. One exception is Confederate Memorial Day today,
but not many people other than state employees are even aware of
it.
</P>
<P>
   Its main impact today will be on traffic. For more than 81,000
state workers, including 30,000 in Atlanta, it's a paid day off.
</P>
<P>
   In Athens, the original Confederate Constitution will be hauled
out of storage and put on display at the University of Georgia's
library, as it is every year only on Confederate Memorial Day. Over
the weekend, groups like the Sons of Confederate Veterans and the
United Daughters of the Confederacy held wreath-laying ceremonies
at cemeteries across the city, state and South.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the South has changed so much since World War II that few
people seem to care about the day, or even know it exists, says
John Shelton Reed, a sociologist at the University of North
Carolina at Chapel Hill who specializes in Southern culture. Only
31 percent of Southerners had ancestors in the Confederate army,
according to a recent UNC poll. Eight percent had ancestors who
were Union soldiers, 8 percent had ancestors on both sides and 34
percent said they didn't know.
</P>
<P>
   For thousands of African-Americans, the day is a reminder, like
the Confederate battle emblem on Georgia's state flag, of ``a lost
and wrongful cause,'' said Rev. Joseph Lowery, former head of the
Southern Christian Leadership Conference.
</P>
<P>
   The state holiday hasn't attracted the protests that the battle
flag has, but there are many who would like to see it abolished.
Georgia legislators designed Confederate Memorial Day as a holiday
in 1874. Many states in the former Confederacy commemorate their
veterans, some with state holidays.
</P>
<P>
   But such days annoy many African-Americans, says historian Skip
Mason of Morris Brown College.
</P>
<P>
   ``It represents a horrific time to those who are descendants of
those African-Americans who were slaves,'' said Mason. ``That we
should still have it as a holiday I find absolutely unthinkable.''
</P>
<P>
   Proponents, including members of the Sons of Confederate
Veterans and United Daughters of the Confederacy, argue that men
who fought for a cause they thought just should be forever honored.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Dunaway, an official of the UDC, said it would be
unthinkable not to honor those who fought for the Confederacy, and
even Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important for us to preserve this period of history,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   And some African-Americans see a value in having a Confederate
Memorial Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that should be studied, not glamorized,'' said
Erwin Jordan, a University of Virginia historian, and an
African-American who authored a book about black men who supported
or fought for the Confederacy. ``It's an episode in history from
which we can learn, and by learning, perhaps not repeat some of the
same mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed contends both sides are right _ and wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not inappropriate for people to honor the Confederate war
dead,'' he said. ``These were honorable men who were doing their
duty as they saw it, and it seems to me that memorials are quite
appropriate. The problem comes when the state gets into the act and
basically says, 'This is everybody's holiday.'''
</P>
<P>
   Some state officials insist a day should be set aside to honor a
war that killed more than 618,000 Confederate and Union soldiers
because it serves as a reminder of a past that no one should want
to forget, however painful. More soldiers died in the Civil War
than any in other war where Americans have fought. In comparison,
405,000 Americans died in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
