<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 19:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-KLA-630&AMP;ADD-NY     04-25 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-KLA-630&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO REBELS SPEAK OUT IN ALBANIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ANTHONY DePALMA   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   KUKES, Albania _ For the first time since NATO began bombing
Yugoslavia, leaders of the rebel Kosovo Liberation Army in northern
Albania spoke openly on Sunday with Western reporters, detailing
what they said were crippling shortages of ammunition and food in
Kosovo, and confusion within the rebel force itself.
</P>
<P>
   Although the KLA openly has a base in this town, its
representatives have growled at reporters and refused all requests
for interviews or photographs for weeks.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, the rebels produced a military spokesman who calls
himself Leopard II, and a representative of the Kosovo Albanians'
underground government. Like rebels who have previously met
reporters in Albania's capital, Tirana, or commanders reached in
Kosovo by telephone from Macedonia, they described fierce fighting
between the rebel army and Serbian troops across many areas in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Gani Sylaj, who said he is a former schoolteacher who spent 11
years in Yugoslav jails for advocating freedom for Kosovo, also
accused the Serbian security forces in Kosovo of a list of
massacres and rapes. There was no way to confirm their accounts
independently.
</P>
<P>
   The sudden openness of the KLA in Kukes appears to represent a
new strategy that has the potential to stir up the already volatile
state of politics in Albania.
</P>
<P>
   Organizing a meeting with reporters may have been the rebels'
way of mitigating reports of thuggish acts by KLA adherents, who
had for a time appeared to take civil control of Kukes, pulling
people off the street for questioning, and enforcing order. Young
refugees here often voice the fear that they will be grabbed by KLA
soldiers and forced to enlist.
</P>
<P>
   The establishment of a KLA office here also raises questions
about what effect the rebels' activities will have on the political
landscape of Albania, whose northeast is the political stronghold
of former president Sali Berisha. His government lost control of
this rugged, mountainous country before he lost elections in June
1997.
</P>
<P>
   The current Albanian government openly backs the Albanian
rebels' aim of independence, but _ unlike Berisha, whose family
property in the northeastern Albanian town of Tropoja has served
the rebels as a weapons depot in the past _ says it does not back
the rebels militarily.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the government has ceded control of its air space and
military bases to the NATO allies for their war against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA representative would not confirm or deny that support
was coming from Berisha, or that he has any designs on using the
conflict to return to power. ``We are getting all the help which is
possible to get from all our friends around the world,'' said
Leopard II. ``I cannot say that it is coming from Mr. Berisha or
not.''
</P>
<P>
   The military spokesman, who said he had served in the Yugoslav
army until 1990 and attended the military academy in Zagreb, said
the rebels currently are strongest in northeastern Kosovo, where he
said civilians are unable to flee, because the region abuts Serbia
proper.
</P>
<P>
   The commander said the KLA controls about 70 percent of that
northeastern Kosovo area. He would not offer a similar assessment
for other parts of the province, but said the picture shifts in
accord with civilian and Serbian movements.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA leaders expressed unlimited support for continued NATO
bombings, a planned oil embargo of Yugoslavia and called for ground
troops which they said could be guided by rebel leaders past
mountains and valleys where Serbian armor and tanks are concealed,
thus reducing allied casualties.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has been reluctant to lend open support to the KLA, which
last winter was seen as violating the cease-fire in Kosovo almost
as often as the Serbs. Western diplomats view the still shadowy
group with suspicion.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Founded in the early 1990s, the rebel group developed slowly and
unsteadily, with not much support and little in the way of arms or
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   Then, in 1997, chaos in neighboring Albania provided a windfall.
Berisha's government fell after crooked pyramid schemes collapsed.
Armories were looted and the country was flooded with 1 million
cheap automatic rifles. Many were brought into Kosovo and got into
the hands of the Kosovo Liberation Army.
</P>
<P>
   The murder of a leading KLA organizer, Adem Jashari, and dozens
of members of his extended family in March 1998 encouraged many
Kosovo Albanians to switch support from the pacifist tactics of
their political leaders to the rebels, who were fighting for
independence but have appeared unprepared to assume political
leadership.
</P>
<P>
   Sylaj conceded Sunday that the KLA has yet to mature.
</P>
<P>
   Recruits and volunteers from the Albanian diaspora have been
streaming into Albania, the KLA says. It is unclear how many of
them have actually been sent to fight, or assigned to strengthen
the KLA's disorganized command structure. The KLA says volunteers
are only processed at its Kukes base, and are then sent to safe
areas in KLA-controlled parts of Kosovo for training.
</P>
<P>
   The KLA has been running a recruitment campaign on Albanian
television. In one spot, videotape of civilians wounded in a Serb
attack is shown over footage of rebel recruits being trained. At
the end of the spot a voice sings, in English, ``That's why we are
here.''
</P>
<P>
   The spokesmen insisted that all the recruits are volunteers,
denying that young men are being picked up off the streets and
forced to join. And they denied that the KLA received financial
support from drug trafficking or other illegal activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money laundering, no drug money, none at all,''
said Sylaj. He said the bulk of the army's funding comes from
contributions sent by more than 100,000 Kosovo Albanians living
abroad.
</P>
<P>
   There have been independent reports of more than 50 KLA soldiers
being brought to the Albanian hospital at Bajram Curri, near the
border north of here. The spokesman would not confirm the number of
casualties but he did say soldiers had been wounded in border
skirmishes and in fighting within Kosovo.
</P>
</TEXT>
