<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ASSESS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: NATO SUMMIT MEETING'S SUCCESS WAS IN ITS APPEARANCE  
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By R.W. APPLE Jr.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The timing could hardly have been worse as the
commemoration of the 50th anniversary of the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization was largely obscured by savagery in Kosovo and
Colorado.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the absence of the Russians sounded a foreboding
note, especially since many of the European diplomats who assembled
here over the weekend consider it a near certainty that they will
eventually have to call upon the Russians to help negotiate an
agreement in Kosovo or to help enforce one or both.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton did what he could to keep that possibility
open in a lengthy telephone conversation Sunday with the Russian
president, Boris Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   But the NATO summit meeting, which ended Sunday afternoon,
proved to have unanticipated uses, however inert the rhetoric and
however unconvincing the reports of steady, significant military
success may have been.
</P>
<P>
   On the most basic level, it gave Clinton a chance to dramatize
the fact that the air attacks on Kosovo are the attacks of a broad
international alliance, although most of the aircraft are flown and
most of the missiles are fired by Americans.
</P>
<P>
   For years, Americans have been arguing that the Balkans are a
European problem and asking why the Europeans were not stepping in
to handle it. On a number of occasions, the United States has
thrown up its hands entirely, in part because American politicians
considered the Balkans a quagmire where public support for any
American involvement would soon dissolve.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got no dog in this fight,'' said James Baker, then the
secretary of state, after a visit to Yugoslavia as it was beginning
to fly apart eight years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Over the weekend, in a nice piece of symbolism, briefers with
European accents _ an Englishman, an Italian, a German, a Spaniard
_ stood behind lecterns in Washington with their American
counterparts to discuss the war. The administration hopes some of
the American public was paying attention.
</P>
<P>
   Likewise, there was strength in visible numbers for the leaders
of countries where the military campaign against President Slobodan
Milosevic of Yugoslavia is unpopular and growing more so with each
night the bombs rain down.
</P>
<P>
   President Vaclav Havel of the Czech Republic, a country with
longstanding ties to Yugoslavia, could revel for a while in his
nation's new membership in the NATO ``club,'' rather than
confronting in Prague the reality of rapidly vanishing public
approval for NATO's Kosovo policy.
</P>
<P>
   The delegations from Greece and Italy played it both ways,
trumpeting their solidarity with NATO in their official statements
on the alliance stage Friday afternoon and speaking more critically
to reporters from their own countries for domestic consumption. The
longer the war, the more likely Greece will grow alienated from the
United States, said Prime Minister Costas Simitis of Greece.
Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini of Italy had harsh words for the
mounting air attacks on civilian targets, including Serbian
television.
</P>
<P>
   Those tensions were not resolved here, nor were others. Some are
long term, such as the question of further expansion of NATO _
backed by France, Italy and Spain as a means of avoiding a split
between western Europe and the Orthodox Christian and Muslim states
farther east that want in, resisted by Germany and Britain on the
ground that the alliance will be weakened by size.
</P>
<P>
   Other lingering questions relate to the conflict in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The French, though thoroughly committed to the bombing campaign,
care more about U.N. authorization for future NATO operations than
the other members, and they seemed more worried than their allies
about the possibility of armed confrontation in the effort to block
oil shipments to Yugoslavia. Both disagreements were finessed, for
the moment, with murky language.
</P>
<P>
   On the most fundamental question _ whether the alliance would
even contemplate the commitment of ground troops in the absence of
an agreement with Milosevic _ less happened than met the eye, or
for that matter, ear.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Tony Blair of Great Britain took the most hawkish
public line, and he pressed Clinton hard in public. His aides
insisted that he had won significant concessions from the
president, and one or two of them pictured him as stiffening
Clinton's resolve the way Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher claimed
to have stiffened the resolve of George Bush at the onset of the
crisis in Kuwait that eventually led to the war in the Persian
Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   But Clinton is well known for his capacity to leave visitors to
the Oval Office convinced that he agrees with them when in fact he
retains serious reservations. Clinton may have accepted the notion
that the ground troops issue needs to be restudied merely to keep
peace in the family or merely to give Milosevic something else to
worry about, without any real intention of moving beyond a study.
</P>
<P>
   Even if the whole thing is deadly earnest and not a stall or a
bluff, much would have to happen before ground troops could move
in, not least the assembly of sufficient equipment, supplies and
support troops, a process that would probably take months. And the
advocates of ground troops would very likely have to decide to go
ahead without a unified NATO behind them.
</P>
<P>
   ``The good thing about this war,'' as Sen. Joseph Biden, D-Del.,
put it, ``is that it's being fought by an alliance. The bad thing
about this war is that it's being fought by an alliance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
