<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2560 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-MEMORIAL26-COX     04-25 1049
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-MEMORIAL26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Columbine memorial: `The heart of America aches with your heart'
 &HT;    By Mike Williams
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ They came by the thousands, somber faces
under low gray skies, hands clasping bright spring flowers, lapels
pinned with blue and silver ribbons, eyes rimmed with tears.
</P>
<P>
   In the distance, Columbine High School stood silent, the echoes
of Tuesday's gunfire from the nation's worst school shooting
tragedy likely still echoing in the minds of hundreds of teachers
and students who ran for their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the past week is about as much suffering as any
community can bear,'' the Rev. Charles J. Chaput, Archbishop of
Denver, told the crowd gathered Sunday to mourn the 13 victims
killed by two boys who then took their own lives. ``But as
scripture says, love is stronger than death. I believe that. Love
is stronger than death.''
</P>
<P>
   The solemn gathering drew an estimated 70,000 people who braved
damp, chilly weather to pay their respects to the victims and their
families.
</P>
<P>
   A light rain began to fall as the service drew to a close,
dappling the wings of 13 white doves which were released and
flitted into the sky as Colorado Gov. Bill Owens read the names of
each victim.
</P>
<P>
   Joining Owens on the platform were Vice President Al Gore,
former Joint Chiefs Chairman Colin Powell and numerous other state
and local dignitaries.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are not alone,'' Gore told the crowd, which spilled across
a 20-acre movie theater parking lot and down Bowles Avenue toward
the nearby high school. ``The heart of America aches with your
heart ... To the families of the victims ... may you feel the
embrace of the literally hundreds of millions of Americans who
grieve with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many other leaders who have spoken out in the wake of the
tragedy, Gore issued a challenge not to allow the deaths to go in
vain.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us must change our lives to honor these children,'' he
said, his voice shaking. ``More than ever I realize that everyone
of us is responsible for all the children. Somewhere in the reach
of every adult in this country is a child to hold and teach ...
Parents, we can stop the violence and the hate. We can rise up and
we can say, no more.''
</P>
<P>
   The service was the largest of dozens of memorials, funerals and
other community gatherings held in the days since the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Police, who have worked nearly around the clock combing through
the devastated school in a painstaking search for evidence, scaled
back their work Sunday, but are expected to be back at full force
today.
</P>
<P>
   Officials have tightened security at area schools, although
there were no plans to cancel classes in the wake of a disturbing
note received Friday by a Denver newspaper that warned of more
violence to come today.
</P>
<P>
   Police believe the note was composed after the two teens, Eric
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, killed themselves at the end of
their deadly rampage.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold and Harris left a detailed diary, begun more than a year
before the shootings, which laid out in chilling detail how they
would carry out the crime. They apparently began building homemade
bombs and gathering weapons months in advance, and even studied
school schedules to determine when they could kill the most
students in one spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were going for a big kill,'' Jefferson County Sheriff
John Stone said.
</P>
<P>
   The boys were apparently motivated by rage ignited from the
taunting they got from more popular students, particularly
athletes. They also seemed fascinated with Nazism, posting
disturbing messages on a Web page created by Harris.
</P>
<P>
   They carried out their melee on the anniversary of Adolf
Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Police continue to suspect others may have helped them, either
in planning and preparation, or in transporting the numerous bombs
they brought into the school. As yet no other suspects have been
named.
</P>
<P>
   The memorial service brought Columbine's shell-shocked students
and teachers together again, a prelude to Thursday when they will
resume classes at Chatfield High School, where they will split the
day with the students who regularly attend that school.
</P>
<P>
   Many wore school jackets or sweatshirts, and nearly everyone
wore a ribbon of blue and silver, the school's colors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're sticking together,'' said Sarah Cain, 16, a Columbine
sophomore who fled the school cafeteria just before the shooters
came in. ``I've been going over to other kids' houses and talking.
I want to go back in our building, but I don't think I'll go back
in the library again.''
</P>
<P>
   Ten victims were found in the library, where witnesses said the
shooters casually strolled around the room, taunting their victims
before shooting many at point-blank range.
</P>
<P>
   Evangelist Franklin Graham, the Rev. Billy Graham's son, spoke
about one victim in the library, Cassie Bernall, who was confronted
by one of the shooters who asked her, ``Do you believe in God?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I believe in God,'' she replied, according to witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those were the last words she spoke,'' Graham said, calling on
others to be equally strong in their faith.
</P>
<P>
   The service was filled with many touching songs, including
performances by Christian singers Michael W. Smith, Amy Grant and
Phil Driscol.
</P>
<P>
   Two Columbine students, brothers John and Steve Cohen, opened
the memorial with a song they wrote with their pastor's help. The
song will be released on a CD, with proceeds going to the victims'
families, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine, friend of mine, peace will come to you in time,''
the boys sang, accompanied only by a guitar.
</P>
<P>
   After the white doves were released near the end of the service,
four Colorado Air National Guard jets thundered low over the
gathering, splitting the gray skies.
</P>
<P>
   Gore then led a solemn procession down Bowles Avenue to Clement
Park, where huge makeshift memorials filled with flowers, teddy
bears, cards and balloons now cover several acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just sorrow, a lot of sorrow,'' said Joanne Nelson, 60, a
resident of nearby Englewood who volunteered as an usher for the
service. ``It's horrible because there's no explanation. You search
and search but there are no answers.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
