<SLUG> BC-GEN-WALL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFF THE WALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TOM HOFFARTH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You're going to be reading more John Elway tributes this week as
the king of comebacks officially tells everyone there'll be no more
coming back, sending the entire state of Colorado into group
therapy.
</P>
<P>
   A testimonial we found to be most impressive came, from all
places, another journalist. The Boston Globe's Will McDonough ended
his Sunday column with:
</P>
<P>
   ``I said this a few years before he ever won a Super Bowl, John
Elway is the best quarterback I have ever seen and that covers
almost 40 years in this business. If you put Elway on the same team
with the others considered as the greatest, he would have had them
beat in size, arm strength, mobility, durability and courage. If
they were all young and in their prime, trying out for the same
team, Elway would be the starter.'' . .
</P>
<P>
   __ In the same column, McDonough quotes New York Giants coach
Jim Fassel, who recruited Elway out of Granada Hills High to go to
Stanford and coached him there all four years.
</P>
<P>
   His favorite Elway moment? It came in a baseball game.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was a sophomore playing right field against Arizona State.
They had a man on second and the batter hit a single down the
right-field line, just inches inside the line. John raced to the
line, gloved the ball, turned and threw a strike to home plate to
get the runner.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never seen anything thrown as hard as that ball was. It
was so stunning the players on both sides came out of the dugout,
and the fans came right out of their seats.'' . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Elway leaves football. Jordan left basketball. Gretzky left
hockey. And by the end of the year, after he plays DH long enough
to get his 3,000 knocks, Cal Ripken will leave baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Add Joe DiMaggio's death and fittingly, the last year of the
1900s will be remembered in sports as the year of the good-bye. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ It's already been see-ya-later Lavin-gator at UCLA, so why
does the coach, who broke down and cried while defending himself at
a team meeting when the season ended, seems to be the only one who
thinks Baron Davis will be back? . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Lavin's only hope is that no one else defects, because after
two great recruiting classes, his staff whiffed on every notable
prep senior it wanted, most notably JaRon Rush's little brother
Kareem. . . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Dave Taylor's short list for a Kings coach reminds us of what
Dodgers' GM Kevin Malone had to pick from last winter: Davey
Johnson, Kevin Kennedy or Mike Scioscia. Does Taylor go with a
proven winner but often-fired guy (Mike Keenan), someone who's been
there but isn't in the loop anymore (Ted Nolan) or a former team
star who might not be ready (Butch Goring or Dave Lewis)? If form
follows function, go with Keenan on Staples Center opening night. .
.
</P>
<P>
   __ If that great humanitarian who owns the Clips spent as much
on NBA talent as he has publicizing the latest Friars Club roast,
maybe his team wouldn't be the butt of another Dom Irerra guffaw.
As if DTS knows the difference between Cazzie Russell and Nipsy
Russell. He's still following up on a lead that Yakov Smirnoff,
knocking 'em dead in Branson, Mo., is the latest European power
forward lock as a lottery pick. . .
</P>
<P>
   __ Finally, if it were anyone but future Friars Clubber Tom
Arnold, we might care. But a star-struck reporter from the Arizona
Republic easily spotted him at Thursday's NHL playoff opener
between St. Louis and Phoenix _ because while all the Coyotes fans
were dressed in white, Arnold came in black.
</P>
<P>
   Not enough that Tombo achieved his purpose of being noticed. He
then said about the Phoenix faithful: ``The crowd is great. . . You
could never get fans to do this in L.A. One, they'd leave after the
first period. Two, they'd never all dress the same because they're
too conceited.''
</P>
<P>
   Yeah, so?
</P>
</TEXT>
