<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-OWEN-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LOVE OF PASTIES BRINGS OUT THE DEVOTED ONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN OWEN  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   You need only pronounce the words ``Cornish pasty'' and devotees
around the world begin to sniff, salivate and generally behave as
though they've been surviving on sunflower husks and vinegar water
since the last millennium.
</P>
<P>
   Matter of fact you can get the same effect merely by printing
the words on paper. That's exactly what I did in this column a
couple of months ago.
</P>
<P>
   Since then I've been invited to a spectacularly successful pasty
feed. I learned where to buy the best commercial pasties in greater
Seattle. I have come into possession of the Web site address of the
Pasty Capital of the World. And I learned that, with proper
planning, you can travel from West Seattle to Michigan's Upper
Peninsula fueled only by the contents and fumes of freshly baked
pasties.
</P>
<P>
   Teresa Holappa lives in West Seattle but was raised in the
copper mining region of Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a large English and Cornish population there and
everyone ate pasties. Besides our dads taking them down the mine
for their lunch, we took them to school in our lunch buckets and in
winter could sometimes heat them on the radiators,'' she reports.
</P>
<P>
   On frequent trips across the country the Holappas and their four
sons would load up on freshly baked pasties in West Seattle or
Michigan and try to survive until they reached the city limits of
Butte, the Pasty Capital of the Rockies. The trick was to avoid
eating up all the warm, fragrant pasties in the first half hour of
travel.
</P>
<P>
   A ``trip home'' for E. Donald Sutton involves traveling from
Bellevue, Wash., to Cornwall, where he was born and raised. The
retired Boeing engineer recently established contact with Hettie
Merrick (Pasty Queen of Cornwall) and with her daughter, Ann
Muller, who now operates the Lizard Pasty Shop at Beacon Terrace,
Helston, Cornwall. Sutton reports that the Web address is:
www.connexions.co.uk/lizardpasty/index.htm
</P>
<P>
   Sutton has determined the best pasties in this area are baked at
the British Pantry in Redmond, Wash., even though the cook is not
from Cornwall.
</P>
<P>
   The pasty cooks are also active in Poulsbo, Wash., and Walter
Williams, who was raised in Butte, sent along his grandmother's
recipe.
</P>
<P>
   And from Sequim, Wash., Jean Timmermeister reports that she is
president of the Pacific Northwest Cornish Society. She leaned
about pasty cookery from her grandmother who was also from Butte.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who maintain pasties are the only edible
products of British kitchens.
</P>
<P>
   Not true. Shortly after she turned out a batch of pasties, my
wife created a terrific Bubble and Squeak, although _ to tell the
truth _ it neither bubbled nor squeaked. She made it like this:
</P>
<P>
   Bubble and Squeak
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-sized onion
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   4 cups mashed potatoes
</P>
<P>
   one-half teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   one-half teaspoon black pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup chopped ham
</P>
<P>
   1 and a half cups Brussels sprouts or cabbage
</P>
<P>
   Cook and coarsely chop the sprouts or cabbage. Drain and
reserve.
</P>
<P>
   Heat the oil and butter in a large skillet. Mince the onion,
then saute until soft in the skillet. Add the diced ham and cook
another minute or two, then push the ham and onion to one side of
the pan.
</P>
<P>
   Add the mashed potatoes to the skillet. Spoon the onion and ham
over the top, then add the sprouts or cabbage. Add salt and pepper
to taste.
</P>
<P>
   With a wooden spoon moosh everything down in the pan and fry
until the underside of the potato cake is brown and crispy.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with the crispy side up. This makes four portions as a
side dish, two portions as the main dish.
</P>
<P>
   The Brits also specialize in Dover sole and I recently kitchen
tested this recipe with good results.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon Sole
</P>
<P>
   2 pounds sole filets
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   2 egg yolks plus 1 tablespoon water or one-fourth cup of egg
substitute
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon flour
</P>
<P>
   three-fourths cup chicken broth
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   one-eighth teaspoon cayenne pepper
</P>
<P>
   one-half cup (or more) of green stuffed olives, halved or sliced
</P>
<P>
   Heat 1 tablespoon of butter in a pan and stir in the flour. When
you have a smooth paste, stir in the broth and lemon juice. Let it
thicken, stirring, then keep warm.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out the sole filets in a single layer on a greased oven
dish. Sprinkle with salt and pepper then dot with the remaining
tablespoon of butter.
</P>
<P>
   Shove the fish dish into a 350-degree oven for 10 minutes, or
until the sole flakes when touched with a fork.
</P>
<P>
   Remove the fish to a warm platter.
</P>
<P>
   To the sauce in the pan stir in the egg substitute or the yolks,
which have been beaten with the tablespoon of water. Let thicken
over low heat (do not boil). Stir in the cayenne pepper.
</P>
<P>
   Spoon the sauce over the cooked fish and scatter the sliced
olives over the top. Serves four.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
