A2568 &Cx1f; tth-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-SUMMER-MOVIES-SP     04-25 0645
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-SUMMER-MOVIES-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER MOVIE SEASON IN TWO WORDS: `PHANTOM MENACE' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By WILLIAM ARNOLD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the history of the movie summer of 1999 is written, it will
be summed up in two words: ``Phantom Menace.'' It's a foregone
conclusion that George Lucas' long-delayed ``Star Wars'' prequel
will be the movie event of the year, probably the decade, possibly
the century.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, its box-office impact is expected to be so monumental
that no movie analyst seems confident about predicting how it will
affect the rest of the movie summer _ that crucial period between
Memorial Day and Labor Day when Hollywood traditionally does its
heaviest business of the year.
</P>
<P>
   One prevalent theory is that ``Episode I'' will create a bonanza
of a movie summer. After all, a monster hit _ especially when it
comes early in the season _ tends to generate a kind of moviegoing
momentum that benefits the entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   The other theory is the film will be so big, and everything else
will seem so small and ho-hum in comparison, that it will simply
gobble up the American moviegoing dollar for the entire summer.
People will see it not once, but endless times, and ignore
everything else.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the second theory seems to be holding sway, and the
competition is so afraid of the Force that Lucas is getting a clear
field in May. And, at this point, the rest of the summer looks as
unambitious and lacking in potential megahits as any summer of the
1990s.
</P>
<P>
   According to Variety editor Peter Bart's new book, ``The
Gross,'' which analyzes the movie summer of 1998, the reasons for
this may have less to do with ``Star Wars''-phobia than with the
culmination of several trends that have suddenly made Hollywood
surprisingly gun-shy of blockbusters.
</P>
<P>
   Bart points out the disappointment of ``Godzilla'' (especially
to its merchandising partners), the low profit margins of expensive
sequels such as ``Lethal Weapon IV,'' the trauma of ``problem
pictures'' such as ``Armageddon,'' and the flop of big-star
vehicles such as ``Meet Joe Black'' have made the studios
dramatically rethink their summer strategies.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Hollywood is curtailing the number of summer releases
(while demanding that producers ``supply co-financing from outside
sources'') and cutting back sharply on ``pricey event movies.'' All
in all, according to one distributor, it's ``a big trend away from
the expensive techno-movies.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the studios are stepping up the output of
low-budget, demographically targeted genre pictures _ especially
inexpensive comedies geared to teenagers, most of them modeled
after ``There's Something About Mary,'' last summer's most
profitable film.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not surprising,'' Bart writes, ``that Sony, the company
that gave us `Godzilla' in 1998 will focus summer '99 not on
big-effects movies, but on slasher sequels, an Adam Sandler comedy,
and a children's effects movie titled `Muppets in Space.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Significantly, Steven Spielberg, who had his name on no less
than four summer films in '98 as producer or director, is staying
out of summer '99, though his company, DreamWorks, has several
films, including Jan De Bont's remake of ``The Haunting.''
</P>
<P>
   There will be some big movies, including Disney's animated
version of ``Tarzan.'' But, beyond ``Phantom Menace,'' there is
only one $100 million-plus special-effects spectacular on the
boards: the big screen version of TV's ``The Wild, Wild West'' on
July 2.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, buoyed by the success of last summer's ``The
Truman Show,'' the studios will brave the summer market with a
number of serious, non-summer type films, including Stanley
Kubrick's ``Eyes Wide Shut'' on July 16, Spike Lee's ``Summer of
Sam'' on July 30 and John Sayles' ``Limbo'' on June 4.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
