<HEADER>
A2569 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WILDERNESS-ACCESS-ART     04-25 1100
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDERNESS-ACCESS-ART-740A&AMP;DD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RICH NEWCOMERS CLOSING THE WILDS OF MONTANA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mont. , Mo.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JIM ROBBINS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ENNIS, Mont. _ Since 1959, the Combs family has entertained
guests at their dude ranch in Jack Creek Canyon, taking a few at a
time by horseback into places with names like Cowboy Heaven and
Spanish Peaks, deep in the rugged wilderness of the Madison
Mountain Range in south central Montana.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, the nearly half-century tradition of leading
riders into the federally owned wilderness was in jeopardy, said
Bruce Combs, a Bozeman lawyer and a ranch owner.
</P>
<P>
   A new neighbor had threatened to block the family's access to
the government land, resulting in a lawsuit. It was the sort of
dispute that had become increasingly common in the West as wealthy
people from out of state buy land that includes roads and trails
long used by the natives.
</P>
<P>
   Originally the Combses' 159-acre ranch, tiny by Western
standards, was nearly surrounded by U.S. Forest Service land, which
the family members rode across freely to get to the Lee Metcalf
Wilderness Area, more than a quarter-million acres just north of
Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   The Forest Service land eventually was traded to a timber
company for land elsewhere, but the Combs family still had access
to the wilderness. Then the timber company sold about 10,000 acres
to Jon Fossel, the former chief executive of Oppenheimer Funds, one
of the nation's largest mutual funds companies, and his brother,
Scott, a retired venture capitalist. The Fossels' lawyer sent the
Combses a letter in 1996 saying that they could no longer use seven
of the the trails that crossed their land.
</P>
<P>
   The Combs family thought that three trails were not enough to
sustain the dude ranch. If someone comes for a week, ``they're done
with those by Tuesday,'' Combs said. ``Then you still have
Wednesday through Saturday.''
</P>
<P>
   Combs also says that Jon Fossel, an avid bow hunter, told him he
had plans to close all 10 trails and effectively lock the Combses
out of the wilderness, and out of a way to make a living. After a
court battle in early March, a settlement was reached.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of the case, the three trails the Combses had access
to remain open to all users; the other seven are open just to the
Combs family and their guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're thrilled with it because it assures our riding
program,'' Combs said.
</P>
<P>
   The case underlined a growing trend. Those who can afford a
slice of the Rockies often find a bonus: when they buy acreage that
borders government-owned wilderness areas, they gain access to
thousands more acres of public land.
</P>
<P>
   But many newcomers grow unhappy with the public's right of
access to public lands through their private ranches. Some realize
that they can have exclusive or near exclusive access to huge
chunks of taxpayer-owned ground by locking the public out.
Incidents in which private landowners close trails or roads are
growing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Access to public lands is one of the biggest issues in the
state right now,'' said Alan Charles, coordinator of
landowner-sportsman relations for the Montana Department of Fish,
Wildlife and Parks. ``These guys with the big ranches are getting
the press, but it is going on in the little, lesser-known valleys
throughout the state as well.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Fairhurst, a retired military pilot in Three Forks, is
finishing a term as volunteer president of Public Lands Access
Association, a group formed 15 years ago to battle the closings.
There is no question, he said, that the situation is getting worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``I get calls once or twice a week from people complaining they
are being locked out'' of Forest Service or Bureau of Land
Management land, Fairhurst said.
</P>
<P>
   About a third of the land in Montana is public. The only way for
the large and increasing number of hunters, fishermen, hikers,
mountain bikers and others to get to the wilderness, in most cases,
is to travel on private land.
</P>
<P>
   Some landowners say that public access leads to litter, cattle
killed by hunters and noxious weeds that grow from seeds that fall
from tires. Disputes about what trails are public are often
complicated, which is part of what led to the Combs case.
</P>
<P>
   Those who fight for public use say landowners often wage a war
of accelerating intimidation. The first salvos are ``no
trespassing'' signs on a public road, which most people obey. If
that does not work, the next step is a locked gate. Fairhurst said
he drove on a county road not far from his home recently and found
it blocked by a locked chain.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Things sometimes go further. Ted Turner, the founder of CNN and
Time-Warner vice president who owns tens of thousands of acres of
land in Montana, and Leon Hirsch, founder of U.S. Surgical Corp.,
who has a ranch near Dillon, have been the subjects of repeated
complaints to the state for using armed security officers to deny
people legal access to public streams and lands in their ranches.
</P>
<P>
   The first big fight by access advocates involved Robert M. Lee,
the owner of a chain of retail stores called Hunting World and a
big-game hunter. Lee bought the Windy River ranch near here and
closed a hiking trail. Lee lost a lawsuit in 1988 and the trail
remained open.
</P>
<P>
   Across the road from the Combses' Diamond J ranch is another
sprawling ranch, owned by Stan Kroenke, an apartment complex and
strip mall magnate from Missouri and minority owner of the St.
Louis Rams football team. Kroenke is married to Ann Walton, a niece
of the late Sam Walton, the founder of Wal-Mart and one of the
nation's wealthiest men. A local outfitter, Tim Beardsley, is suing
Kroenke for closing the Aspen Creek trail that goes through his
ranch and allows access to the government wilderness.
</P>
<P>
   The increasing value of wildlife has also contributed to
closures, and not just by recent arrivals. The public lands access
group has sued asserting that a longtime rancher near Avon, Earl
Stuky, placed locked gates on two public roads after leasing the
ranch to private outfitters.
</P>
<P>
   For many people in the West, the closures trend represents the
erosion not just of access but of an established way of life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taking people into the wilderness is how many people make
their living around here,'' Combs said. ``Montana is becoming
gated, exclusive and private, because that's what sells. It's
gut-wrenching.`
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 1932EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
