<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 19:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2570 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ATT-CABLETV-ANALYSIS-     04-25 1228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ATT-CABLETV-ANALYSIS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: TASTY MORSELS AND DIGESTIVE CHALLENGES FOR AT&AMP;T  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the AT&AMP;T Corp. under C. Michael Armstrong has become
an experience akin to watching one film sequel after another in the
``Jaws'' series.
</P>
<P>
   Just when you thought that Armstrong, AT&AMP;T's chairman of 18
months, could not possibly bite off another big deal, he does just
that, and the masses in the communications industry are sent
fleeing to find ways to cope.
</P>
<P>
   Last week's casualty may have been the Comcast Corp., the big
cable television operator. Just when it looked as if AT&AMP;T had
settled down to manage its own $31.8 billion acquisition of
Tele-Communications Inc., the No. 2 cable carrier, Armstrong swam
into the middle of Comcast's pending $53 billion deal for the
Mediaone Group and roiled the waters with an unsolicited bid for
AT&AMP;T to buy Mediaone for $58 billion.
</P>
<P>
   Mediaone executives have not yet publicly responded, but many
analysts say that AT&AMP;T, with its superior financial power, will
scare off Comcast and win Mediaone _ if regulators allow it. That
would make AT&AMP;T the nation's No. 1 cable television company, in
addition to the nation's No. 1 long-distance telephone carrier.
</P>
<P>
   But like a voracious shark that ends up with a bunch of old
license plates in its belly, AT&AMP;T may have a tough time digesting
everything it has tried to swallow. The main question for AT&AMP;T now
is whether its appetite has exceeded its ability to integrate its
businesses into the lean yet powerful communications machine that
Armstrong wants AT&AMP;T to become.
</P>
<P>
   As Armstrong propels AT&AMP;T headlong into the future he has
envisioned, the company faces mounting challenges _ not only of
management and strategy, but also of regulation and technology.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most daunting management challenge for AT&AMP;T is the
sheer breadth of Armstrong's strategic ambition. After John Zeglis,
AT&AMP;T's president, was conspicuously absent during the company's
Mediaone announcement last Thursday, several analysts wondered
where he was.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out he was in Japan. There, over the weekend, AT&AMP;T and
British Telecommunications, AT&AMP;T's new international partner,
announced a joint investment of more than $1.8 billion to acquire a
30 percent stake in Japan Telecom, a communications carrier backed
by the main Japanese railroad company.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T and British Telecommunications will also fold into Japan
Telecom two of their existing Japanese ventures, with combined
annual revenue of just more than $200 million.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement's near simultaneity with the Mediaone bid was
either impressive or unnerving, because it demonstrated Armstrong's
comfort with juggling multiple deals. In fact, the Japan Telecom
and Mediaone deals ``are part of the same strategy,'' Zeglis said
over the weekend. ``We want to go end-to-end delivering services
for our customers on our own architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite AT&AMP;T's common goal of controlling its own architecture,
or electronic infrastructure, there is a big difference between
these two deals. AT&AMP;T's overseas ventures are aimed at serving
big-ticket multinational corporate clients, while the company's
cable television expansion is aimed at serving everyday residential
consumers. It is the company's hunger for residential customers
that best explains AT&AMP;T's seeming feeding frenzy.
</P>
<P>
   It is clear by now that AT&AMP;T is terrified of the prospect of at
least one of the local Bell phone companies, probably Bell
Atlantic, being poised to win regulatory approval to enter AT&AMP;T's
core long-distance business this year.
</P>
<P>
   By way of a harbinger, AT&AMP;T is well aware of what happened in
Connecticut after the Southern New England Telecommunications
Corp., which did not need special approval, began offering
long-distance service to Southern New England's local phone
customers. Large numbers of Connecticut customers dropped
long-distance service from AT&AMP;T, among others, to take a single
package of local and long distance from SNET.
</P>
<P>
   AT&AMP;T's strategic planners hate to contemplate the millions of
local phone customers who might drop AT&AMP;T phone service once Bell
Atlantic is freed to offer long-distance service to customers along
the Eastern Seaboard, or even just in New York. It is a much bigger
worry for AT&AMP;T than for its principal long-distance rivals, MCI
Worldcom and Sprint, because AT&AMP;T derives a much higher proportion
of its long-distance revenue from residential consumers than do MCI
and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   Armstrong has decided that the solution is to counterattack the
Bells by taking the war to a new front _ off the conventional local
telephone network and onto cable TV systems. Through those cable
lines, AT&AMP;T intends to offer local and long-distance calling, as
well as Internet service.
</P>
<P>
   It will probably take a few years to determine whether that
strategy is visionary or foolhardy. AT&AMP;T would like to offer its
cable-based services using a variant of Internet technology.
Because this is a largely experimental approach, it poses large
technical challenges. It may, however, prove easier in Mediaone
territories than in TCI areas, because Mediaone's network is
generally more technically advanced. That is why AT&AMP;T is willing to
pay more for Mediaone than it did for TCI, even though TCI has more
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The cable strategy also raises management questions. AT&AMP;T is
well practiced in telephone-network technology, but linking so much
of its future to cable television networks means the company needs
to rely on experts from outside the AT&AMP;T tradition. Foremost among
them is Leo Hindery, the former No. 2 executive at TCI who now runs
AT&AMP;T's cable operation _ but who is still largely unfamiliar with
AT&AMP;T and its culture in offering telephone service. The same could
be said for the highly respected Amos B. Hostetter, Mediaone's
largest shareholder, who AT&AMP;T has said will become chairman of its
cable and Internet unit if its Mediaone bid succeeds.
</P>
<P>
   But before Hostetter can come aboard, AT&AMP;T must not only fend
off Comcast, but also convince Federal regulators that a combined
AT&AMP;T-TCI-Mediaone would not wield disproportionate power in the
cable television industry. Under Federal Communications Commission
ownership rules, no single entity can control cable systems that
together are available to more than 35 percent of the nation's
households. But those rules have been suspended pending a review by
the FCC.
</P>
<P>
   There are financial imponderables. AT&AMP;T _ with backing from
Chase Manhattan Bank and Goldman, Sachs &UR;  &LR; &AMP; Co. _ seems set to raise
$30 billion in cash to support its Mediaone bid. But Standard &AMP;
Poor's, the credit-rating agency, said on Friday that it was
considering downgrading AT&AMP;T's debt to reflect the big financial
burden the company will take on if it acquires Mediaone.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes for Armstrong, not to mention AT&AMP;T, are high. They
keep escalating. If the cable strategy works well, he will become
known as one of the most visionary and dynamic executives of his
day. If it does not, business history might one day recall him as a
former IBM executive who was passed over for the top job at that
company and who, later, when given the chance to run AT&AMP;T, tried to
prove too much.
</P>
<P>
   For now, at least, dynamic seems to be winning. Armstrong,
presumably, is looking for his next ``Jaws'' sequel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 1935EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
