<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-MILITARY-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SERB TV KNOCKED OFF THE AIR AGAIN AFTER NATO ATTACK 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By PHILIP SHENON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO warplanes knocked Serb television off the air
again Sunday for several hours when they attacked large television
transmission towers south of the Yugoslav capital of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   NATO officials said the attack, the second on Serb television
facilities in three days, should make clear to Serb television
employees that they risk their lives if they continue broadcasting
what NATO has described as hateful propaganda.
</P>
<P>
   The towers in the hills of Avala, about 10 miles from Belgrade,
were among 200 targets hit in what NATO spokesmen described as a
busy night in the month-old air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Also hit overnight in the raids were a chemical factory in the
central Serb town of Lucani _ NATO says the plant produces
explosives _ as well as an oil storage depot in Pristina, the
provincial capital of Kosovo, and several targets in the industrial
city of Nis, about 125 miles southeast of Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   At least six missiles were reported to have struck a bridge in
Nis, Yugoslavia's third largest city, which has faced heavy NATO
bombardment in the past week.
</P>
<P>
   Television transmissions in Belgrade resumed Sunday about 11
hours after the attack on the transmission towers, which took place
at about 3 a.m. as the network was showing a Russian romance film.
</P>
<P>
   But when Serb television returned to the air Sunday afternoon,
the image was fuzzy because the national network was forced to
borrow facilities from a private television station with limited
range. The extent of the damage to the transmission towers was not
reported by NATO, nor was it clear if anyone was killed in the
overnight strike on the facility.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, NATO attacked the building in Belgrade that housed
the headquarters and studios of Serb television, forcing it off the
air for about six hours. The Yugoslav state news agency Tanjug
reported Sunday that six more bodies were recovered from the
studios, bringing the death toll there to 20.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has defended the attacks on Serb television by describing
the network as a military propaganda tool for Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Only hours before the attack Sunday, President Clinton told
reporters at the NATO summit here that the alliance's military
commanders believe that ``Serb television is an essential
instrument of Mr. Milosevic's command and control _ he uses it to
spew hatred and to basically spread disinformation.'' He justified
the attacks by insisting that the television network is ``not in in
a conventional sense a media outlet.''
</P>
<P>
   A NATO spokesman, Col. Konrad Freytag, said at a news conference
Sunday that Serb television was included among the targets of the
American-led air raids because it ``helps create the political
environment of oppression.''
</P>
<P>
   Yugoslavia's ambassador to the United Nations, Vladislav
Jovanovic, condemned the airstrikes on the television facilities,
saying Sunday that they amounted to ``terrorist action against
civilians and against civilian targets'' and that NATO was
attempting ``to stifle the right to speech.''
</P>
<P>
   Air raid sirens sounded Sunday over Serbia's second-largest
city, Novi Sad, as Cornelio Sommaruga, head of the International
Committee of the Red Cross, toured wreckage there from earlier NATO
strikes, which destroyed all three of the city's bridges across the
Danube River.
</P>
<P>
   Sommaruga was scheduled to meet on Monday with Milosevic, hoping
to secure the return of Red Cross staff to Kosovo and access to
three American soldiers who were captured by the Yugoslav army on
March 31.
</P>
<P>
   The NATO supreme military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, traveled
to Albania Sunday to meet with about 3,300 American troops
stationed there. He said that the allied campaign against the Serbs
was ``right on schedule'' as seven more Apache attack helicopters
arrived to step up the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   The low-flying Apaches are designed to destroy tanks, and Clark
said it ``won't be too long'' before they are put into action
against Serb forces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
