<SLUG> BC-NATO-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WORLD VIRTUALLY REMOVED FROM THE REAL-LIFE NIGHTMARE 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NATO-RDP, NATO-ASSESS) 
(js) 
 By FRANCIS X. CLINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ It seemed a far lovelier war being waged Sunday in
the embattled nation of Azure.
</P>
<P>
   Computer mice, not swagger sticks, were in the hands of the
British air marshal and three-star Ukrainian general moving troops
and fighter planes about on the big-screen projection of Azure, a
place every bit as ravaged as Kosovo except for the one advantage _
it was a dream in a NATO war-game, not the real-life nightmare in
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's diplomats wended through their final bittersweet day
of commemorating and conferring on the alliance's 50th anniversary,
some of the cream of NATO's officer corps and allies worked quietly
on Azure at dozens of computer command screens.
</P>
<P>
   As a simulation of technological prowess, Azure proved a
blessedly fantasy-filled challenge in comparison with the harrowing
reality of Kosovo that haunted the diplomats through their final
ceremonies. Even with 100,000 simulated refugees on the run and a
rebel-held uranium mine in peril, Azure was only the stuff of
NATO's dreams.
</P>
<P>
   It was a high-tech war that could be believed. It was a
convincing theater of operations where provinces named Indigo and
Turquoise were yielding to the canniest war college strategems.
There were no sticky postmortems about collateral casualties and
overdue Apache gunships.
</P>
<P>
   Criss-crossed with high-tech command graphics and multicolored
force vectors, Azure proved an apt virtual-reality symbol for
NATO's weekend gathering. The summit conference, hermetically
isolated from the rest of the city by a formidable ring of
security, often seemed a dimension removed as well, as it wrestled
uncertainly with the air campaign against Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Only the more telegenic scraps of agenda talk were played out on
the countless television screens that dotted the cavernous Ronald
Reagan International Trade Center, an office citadel where more
than 2,000 global news workers were tagged and kept under close
watch. The three-day presentation of resolute speeches and
ceremonial comings and goings by NATO leaders played largely to
themselves on the summit's internal broadcast system.
</P>
<P>
   Out beyond the conference, on the screens of the surrounding
nation, viewers were more likely to be watching graphic
alternatives like the latest from the high school shooting rampage
in Colorado. Or even an interview with Slobodan Milosevic, the NATO
antagonist who dominated the summit by his absence. He spoke a
peacefully toned, articulate English in contending that Serbia
stood innocent before the forces of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday morning, the daily NATO briefing on Kosovo was followed
by more of the silent motion pictures of the latest Yugoslav
bombings: Mundane gray targets loomed upward in the now familiar
cross hairs, slowly rotating to sudden explosive blots on the giant
screen in the Reagan building lobby. Dozens of people moved past
the highlight film, heedless as commuters as they searched for
fresh briefings and food and hints of whatever was really
happening.
</P>
<P>
   The order of each summit day seemed rooted in tightly controlled
photo opportunities. ``Leaders Walk to Working Lunch,'' a typical
agenda highlight, was multiplied six-fold Sunday with farewell
lunches for the leaders, defense and foreign ministers and their
spouses separately sub-grouped. Closer mingling in search of the
nuances of statesmanship had to be sought by way of the summit's
truly teeming cell-phone culture; everyone seemed to have a cell
phone, even the army private polishing his general's NATO sedan as
he waited through the summit's final hours.
</P>
<P>
   Talking-head sound bites and video cameos from selected leaders
and briefers provided the raw material of each conference day. The
product was beamed up to the satellite-dish heavens from eddies of
on-camera reporters. They boomed forth with polyglot summit
authority, but no clear word on how NATO will ultimately manage
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   A few of NATO's natural politicians, chafing in the
ultra-isolation of the diplomats' bastion in Mellon Auditorium,
crossed through the security cordon to chat in the flesh with
reporters. Here came Alexander Kwasniewski, the president of Poland
who had charmed the summit in thanking NATO for its induction of
his resilient nation. He stood in the morning sunlight that beamed
down through the atrium of the Reagan building, personally exuding
in a brief encounter more plain hope than a full news cycle of NATO
bombing briefers.
</P>
<P>
   As the summit wound down, Kwasniewski talked with certainty of
the day when peace and reconstruction would come to Kosovo. ``This
peace should not be based on poverty,'' he emphasized. Then this
newest summiteer headed off to a plenary session of gray-suited
diplomats, taking an outdoor path under skies that were azure,
indisputably.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
