<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Italy, Britain, Germany, Va., Mass., Calif.)   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEUTSCHE TELEKOM SEEN AS A SUITOR FOR ONE 2 ONE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Deutsche Telekom, which is in the midst of an $80-billion-plus
attempted merger with Telecom Italia, may also have its sights on a
major mobile telephone acquisition in Britain.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Telekom said it was interested in acquiring One
2 One, a joint venture between Cable and Wireless and Mediaone
Group. One 2 One's parents put it up for sale last month, and the
company has drawn intense interest throughout the European
telecommunications industry. It is unclear whether Telekom has made
a firm offer.
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL CROSSING TO ACQUIRE GLOBAL MARINE
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, the owner and operator of a worldwide fiber
optic network designed for Internet transmissions, is expected to
announce the acquisition Monday of the Global Marine unit of Cable
and Wireless for $725 million in cash and $160 million in assumed
debt.
</P>
<P>
   SUN TO INTRODUCE NETWORK PRODUCT
</P>
<P>
   Sun Microsystems plans to introduce software Monday that is
designed for companies that want to let their employees use various
devices to connect to corporate computer networks, secure from
unauthorized access. With the system, workers could use desktop
computers, laptops or even hand-held personal digital assistants to
connect to the network.
</P>
<P>
   A NEW TACK ON THE SHIPPING NEWS
</P>
<P>
   The Journal of Commerce, which has provided a mix of trade
policy analysis and coverage of the shipping industry, is changing
its focus. It is jettisoning most of its policy coverage, all of
its commodity price listings and 20 percent of its editorial staff
and is devoting itself to ``those who control the movement of
goods,'' in the words of a recent editorial. It will also convert
from a broadsheet to a tabloid format on June 1. The newspaper, led
by its new editor, Peter Tirschwell, plans to move from its broader
perspective to porthole-to-porthole coverage of an industry that
has all the glamour of the industrial age at a time when the
financial world is fixated on all things digital.
</P>
<P>
   HARVARD ECONOMIST WINS
</P>
<P>
   Medal Andrei Shleifer, a Harvard University economist who
immigrated to the United States from Russia when he was a
teen-ager, has won the John Bates Clark Medal, the most prestigious
prize in economics short of the Nobel. The medal, awarded every two
years by the American Economic Association, goes to an outstanding
economist younger than 40.
</P>
<P>
   VIRGINIA GOVERNOR TAKES LEAD ON INTERNET
</P>
<P>
   As the worlds of politics and high technology increasingly come
together, Virginia Gov. James Gilmore would like to be at the
nexus. In recent years, Virginia's high-technology economy has
surged and Gilmore, a Republican, has made Internet policy central
to his 18-month stint in office.
</P>
<P>
   DOW JONES PLANS FREE BUSINESS SITE
</P>
<P>
   Dow Jones, which has attracted 283,000 paid subscribers to The
Wall Street Journal Interactive Edition, is introducing
dowjones.com, a free site for business users. The company is also
preparing a Sunday section devoted to careers and personal finance,
which will be offered to newspapers as a supplement to local
business sections.
</P>
<P>
   LINKING REAL AND PRETEND VIOLENCE
</P>
<P>
   Parents and consumer groups have sounded alarms for years about
the effects that violent films, television and video games like
Doom, left, are having on their children and society. The
industry's response consistently has been indignant shock that
anyone would think a movie or game could have a measurable effect
on anyone. But a growing body of evidence suggests a connection
between exposure to media violence, including video games, and
increased aggression.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
