<HEADLINE>
SUPPORTERS RALLY AROUND VIETNAM VET WHO MAY BE EXECUTED FOR
MURDER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass., R.I.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By   EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN QUENTIN, Calif. _ Little more than a week until his
appointment with the state executioner, Manny Babbitt has more
friends now than in all his nearly 50 miserable years.
</P>
<P>
   The list of those rallying to save his life is long and growing.
It includes at least two of the jurors who sentenced him to death,
his trial lawyer, who says his defense was inept, and a retired
police officer whom Babbitt saved as a Marine in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Among the others: more than 600 other fellow Marines who endured
the 1968 siege at Khe Sanh, when American troops were pinned down
for 77 days by the North Vietnamese, thousands of other veterans
and David Kaczynski _ the brother of Ted Kaczynski, the Unabomber _
who knows the anguish Babbitt's brother feels for turning Manny
over to the police.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in a visiting cell, Manny Babbitt, stocky and
open-faced, seemed perplexed at all the attention from all over the
country, after 18 years on death row. ``Children and women are on
death row, too,'' he said, his eyes moistening behind his bifocals.
``I hope some people try to save them.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the Board of Prison Terms scheduled to consider
Babbitt's plea for clemency on Monday, there are people equally
passionate about sending him to his death _ none more so than the
family of the 78-year-old woman whom he attacked in Sacramento the
night of Dec. 18, 1980.
</P>
<P>
   They have no use for the arguments that the victim was a war
casualty, that Vietnam had broken Babbitt's fragile mind. They know
all they need to know: Manuel Pena Babbitt broke into Leah
Schendel's apartment, beat her, grabbed a few trinkets and some
change, and caused the heart attack that killed her.
</P>
<P>
   For Gov. Gray Davis, who is waiting for the recommendation from
the Board of Prison Terms before deciding whether to commute
Babbitt's sentence to life in prison, the case poses a unique
dilemma. During his election campaign last year, Davis promised to
be a tough-on-crime, pro-death penalty governor. Shortly after he
took office in January, he turned down the clemency plea of Jaturun
Siripong, who was put to death by lethal injection a month later.
</P>
<P>
   But as an Army veteran, the governor has also pledged to give
veterans due respect. Babbitt, who was awarded the Purple Heart in
a rare prison ceremony last year, has become a rallying cry for
Vietnam veterans of all political stripes. They are convinced that
Babbitt _ who wrapped a leather strap around his victim's ankle,
reminiscent of the way soldiers tagged the dead _ attacked Leah
Schendel in a flashback caused by a textbook case of post-traumatic
stress disorder brought on by two tours of duty in the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe Manny when he tells me that he doesn't remember
anything about the crime,'' said Gary Dahlheimer of Fresno, who was
a mechanic in Babbitt's platoon at Khe Sanh and has collected 600
letters of support for him. ``I'm not an expert on PTSD, but I came
very close to killing my wife once,'' Dahlheimer said. ``I was
asleep and I was dreaming of killing a North Vietnamese and I had
him in a scissor lock. It was my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``So far I've gone to six of the Khe Sanh reunions and
everyone from private to general seems to suffer from some degree
of post-traumatic stress syndrome.''
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors call Babbitt a career criminal and a mean drunk who
hated women. Jan Scully, the Sacramento County district attorney,
said that the post-traumatic stress disorder defense had been
raised at the trial and the jury had rejected it. She also said
that a federal court had ruled two years ago that Babbitt had
received a ``very good defense _ a better one, in fact than the
defense argues in hindsight should have been presented.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the jury that convicted Babbitt and sentenced him to
death understood his offenses. ``It should go without saying that
members of the Marine Corps are neither trained nor permitted to
rape, rob or murder defenseless senior citizens,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Vietnam, in many ways, was the high point of Babbitt's life, his
lawyers said. Raised dirt-poor in Wareham, Mass., in a small
community of immigrants from the Cape Verde Islands, he and his
eight brothers and sisters were regularly beaten by their father,
Charles.
</P>
<P>
   Their mother, Josephine, suffered from bouts of mental illness
that worsened after Charles Babbitt died, when Manny was 14. She
would stand outside in her black mourning clothes, talking to a
pear tree, and wake the children in the middle of the night,
screaming at the top of her lungs.
</P>
<P>
   Manny dropped out of school when he was in the seventh-grade, at
age 17. After joining the Marines, he was sent to Vietnam, where he
became a highly regarded member of an anti-tank, anti-personnel
armored car unit.
</P>
<P>
   In March, 1968, Babbitt was wounded by shrapnel at Khe Sanh, and
flown to a medical unit atop a pile of dead bodies. He was back on
duty shortly afterward.
</P>
<P>
   After Khe Sanh, he fought another battle, went home, married,
and signed up for another tour. In the fall of 1969 he was
stationed at Quonset Point, R.I.. But something was going wrong.
</P>
<P>
   At night, while patrolling with his M-16 rifle, he would kill
and skin rabbits. He'd scream to his wife to grab the babies and
run for cover from the bombs. He took LSD, as he did in the war,
and went absent without leave. By the time he was given an
honorable discharge in 1971, he had been demoted from corporal to
private.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
