<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2589 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CALIF-DEATHROW-VET-AR     04-25 0739
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CALIF-DEATHROW-VET-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
 SAN QUENTIN, Calif.: to private.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Eventually he turned to crime. In 1973, he helped rob two gas
stations and was sentenced to eight years in state prison. He ended
up in a hospital for the criminally insane in Bridgewater, Mass.,
where he spent eight months before going back to prison. Two months
later, after numerous suicide attempts, he was returned to the
hospital. In 1975, as a diagnosed paranoid schizophrenic, he was
granted parole and freed.
</P>
<P>
   Single again, he moved near his half-brother Charles in
Providence, R.I., met a woman, and attempted to settle down.
Instead, he became the town crazy. For sport, according to defense
affidavits, some patrons of his brother's bar would ply Manny with
drugs and alcohol, knowing that would set him on a lunatic tear.
</P>
<P>
   James Schenk, Babbitt's court-appointed lawyer for his murder
trial, could have found dozens of witnesses willing to discuss his
client's mental condition to corroborate his psychiatric defense.
He did not seek them.
</P>
<P>
   Schenk, who resigned from the state bar last year after pleading
no contest to embezzling $50,000 from client trust funds, admitted
in court papers that he ``failed completely in the death penalty
phase'' of the trial.
</P>
<P>
   He never called witnesses who had served with Babbitt in
Vietnam, never documented his family history of mental illness, an
aggravating factor in the post-traumatic stress disorder, and never
sought Babbitt's Vietnam medical records. The records documented
that Babbitt had had ``dissociative reactions,'' or bouts of
amnesia, during particularly stressful events, during his two tours
of duty.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt says he does not remember attacking Ms. Schendel, or
another woman on the following night who was beaten but recovered.
On the afternoon before he attacked Ms. Schendel, he drank and took
drugs with an Asian-American man who was also a Vietnam veteran.
All he remembers of that night, Babbitt said, were lights in the
fog which reminded him of incoming aircraft in Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Babbitt's appeals lawyers, Jessica McGuire, a public defender,
and Charles Patterson, a private attorney who is a Khe Sanh
veteran, say that Babbitt saw the lights in the fog and
``dissociated.'' The sight of aircraft would always be followed by
fire from the enemy, and soldiers would duck for cover. Babbitt,
they say, ran for cover in Ms. Schendel's house and reacted as a
soldier _ brutally _ when she panicked at the sight of him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Schendel, whose forehead was split open to the bone, was
found with her dress pulled over her waist, a tea kettle on her
pubic area, a mattress over her and a cord around her ankle.
</P>
<P>
   The mattress, defense experts say, is significant because
soldiers covered the dead with anything available to protect them
until they could be recovered. And soldiers always wrapped dog tags
around a fallen comrade, to aid in identifying him.
</P>
<P>
   Schenk said he never explored the way Babbitt left Ms. Schendel.
He also said he failed to raise an objection when the prosecution
argued that Ms. Schendel was sexually assaulted, although its
expert could only say that it was ``possible.''
</P>
<P>
   William Babbitt, who had moved his younger brother Manny from
Providence to live with him in Sacramento shortly before the attack
on Ms. Schendel, said that his brother should have received help,
not a death sentence.
</P>
<P>
   He called the police after finding coins and a cigarette lighter
with the initials ``L.S.'' among his brother's belongings and said
the police assured him that his brother would ``not go to the gas
chamber.''
</P>
<P>
   He blames a justice system that most severely punishes blacks
when the victims are white, as in his brother's case.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Thompson, Mrs. Schendel's granddaughter, is angry at the
system too. For 18 years, she and her family have waited for
justice, she says, while Manny Babbitt's appeals wound their way
through the courts. (Babbitt was refused an evidentiary hearing at
every turn, and the Supreme Court declined to review the case.)
Now, Ms. Thompson fears that the campaign to spare the killer who
ruined her family will work.
</P>
<P>
   Manny Babbitt, who has taught himself to read and write, said he
would like to write Ms. Thompson a letter and tell her he is sorry,
and that if he is executed, he hopes it will bring her closure.
</P>
<P>
   His execution by lethal injection is set for May 4, one day
after his 50th birthday.
</P>
</TEXT>
