</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-SUMMIT26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NATO VOWS TO PROTECT YUGOSLAVIA'S NEIGHBORS
 &HT;    500&AMP;add.
 &HT;    With NATO-CITY, ALBANIA-MILITARY and KOSOVO-GRAVES.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO extended security guarantees Sunday to seven
countries rimming Yugoslavia, widening its defense obligations to
include non-alliance states for the first time in its 50-year
history.
</P>
<P>
   The move places the NATO security umbrella over Albania, Bosnia,
Bulgaria, Croatia, Macedonia, Romania and Slovenia _ every part of
the Balkans except Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   It comes as the seven states have agreed to play increasingly
larger, and potentially riskier, roles in NATO's escalating attacks
against the regime of President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will stand by the neighboring countries that have accepted
risks and hardship in support of this effort,'' President Clinton
said in closing a three-day summit that he said had left the
alliance more united than ever. ``If Mr. Milosevic threatens them
for helping us, we will respond.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton did confer with President Boris Yeltsin of Russia on
Sunday about prospects for negotiating an end to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, NATO announced that 4,000 additional
British and German troops were en route to Macedonia, while Hungary
and two other states extended air rights to allied warplanes on
missions to attack neighboring Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO pressed on with bombing strikes on bridges, broadcasting
stations, airfields, troops and tanks across Yugoslavia. The NATO
commander, U.S. Army Gen. Wesley Clark, visited Albania and said
Apache attack helicopters would soon be ready to fly missions into
the province of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's hour-long telephone conversation with Yeltsin came as
he dispatched Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott to Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Any Russian-brokered end to the conflict, officials said, would
be based on Milosevic accepting NATO's essential demands:
</P>
<P>
   _ An end to repression of ethnic Albanians in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   _ The withdrawal of Yugoslavian forces and the admittance of a
NATO-led peacekeeping force.
</P>
<P>
   _ Guarantees that the 1.5 million ethnic Albanians that have
fled Kosovo would be allowed to return and rebuild their homes in
safety.
</P>
<P>
   _ The return of political autonomy for the majority Albanians in
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly five weeks of inconclusive NATO air strikes against
Yugoslavia, Clinton and other allied leaders voiced their resolve
to prosecute a war of attrition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The alliance leaves Washington more united even than it was
when we came here,'' said Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As one example, White House aides said France had decided to
drop its objections to a NATO naval blockade aimed at choking off
Yugoslavia's oil imports.
</P>
<P>
   It later appeared, though, that France had simply agreed to set
aside its concerns until the details of how a blockade would be
enforced could be worked out.
</P>
<P>
   ``There may be a combination of mechanisms,'' said White House
national security adviser Samuel Berger, ``to achieve the goal of
inhibiting and stopping the flow of energy to (Milosevic's) war
machine.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   As NATO worked to tighten the military and economic noose, the
alliance took the unprecedented step of extending security
guarantees to the seven non-NATO members.
</P>
<P>
   Those states have already suffered economic damage, threats and,
in the case of Albania and Macedonia, military attacks and
overwhelming refugee flows, since NATO launched air strikes against
Yugoslavia on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   Two of those ``frontline'' states _ Slovenia and Romania _ have
agreed to let NATO warplanes fly over their airspace for bombing
runs targeting Yugoslavia and for reconnaissance flights and midair
refueling.
</P>
<P>
   A third, Bulgaria, is expected to grant its permission for such
activities on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   Two others, Macedonia and Albania, are playing host to a growing
NATO troop contingent.
</P>
<P>
   And NATO has already assumed a major security role in Bosnia,
where it has based peacekeepers.
</P>
<P>
   Separately, Hungary, which became a full NATO member last month,
said it would permit U.S. and allied warplanes to take off from its
airfields to bomb Yugoslav targets.
</P>
<P>
   NATO spokesman Jamie Shea said the alliance's security
assurances to these states are not as strong as the guarantees
provided by Article Five of the NATO charter. The heart of the
alliance structure, Article Five obligates all 19 NATO members to
regard an attack on any single member as an attack on all, and to
respond militarily.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are not the same as Article Five, but they are very
strong indeed,'' said Shea. ``They're much stronger than anything
that we've ever done before in making it clear that we would
consider
</P>
<P>
   an attack on any of these countries as something which would
obviously need to elicit a response from the allies.''
</P>
<P>
   The essence of the commitment, said Shea, is that ``we have a
direct material concern for the security of these countries.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's move marked the first time the alliance has extended
formal security guarantees beyond the borders of its members, said
NATO expert Ronald Spector, chairman of the history department at
George Washington University.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the past, they did not guarantee the security of non-NATO
states,'' said Spector. ``In fact, they went to some lengths to
avoid it, if you think about the 1968 Soviet invasion of
Czechoslovakia,'' which NATO treated as an issue to be contained
within the sphere of influence of the old Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
