Zimmerman won't start, other notes 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ Don't expect to see right-hander Jeff Zimmerman in
the Rangers' rotation during this or future seasons.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers have never discussed the possibility, assistant
general manager Dan O'Brien said yesterday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think that's something we have in mind,'' O'Brien
said.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman possesses two ``plus'' pitches _ fastball and slider _
and an improving changeup. He started as recently as 1997 while
pitching for Winnipeg of the independent Northern League.
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers, though, view Zimmerman as one of those
``maximum-effort pitchers,'' one who expends a great deal of energy
during his delivery to generate velocity. That does not make
Zimmerman an ideal candidate for the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman entered yesterday's games with a major league-best 11
scoreless innings and ranked fifth among American League relievers
in opponents' batting average at .086 (3-for-35).
</P>
<P>
   Manager Johnny Oates considers inserting Zimmerman into the
rotation an interesting idea, but added: ``He's doing great right
where he is.'' Pettitte scratched The New York Yankees scratched
left-hander Andy Pettitte from his scheduled start Thursday at The
Ballpark in Arlington.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte (0-0, 2.08 earned-run average) complained that his
``legs felt like sandbags'' after his start Saturday against the
Toronto Blue Jays. Pettitte, who made only his second start this
season after straining his left elbow during spring training,
allowed three earned runs on seven hits in the 108-pitch
appearance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would be a lot easier getting back,'' Pettitte
told reporters afterward. ``I thought my legs would have been under
me a lot quicker than they have been.''
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees plan to start right-hander Ramiro Mendoza (2-1, 2.05
ERA) on Thursday. That might not be a favorable tradeoff for the
Rangers.
</P>
<P>
   Pettitte is 5-3 with a 6.42 ERA during 542/3 innings against the
Rangers. Mendoza is 2-1 with a 3.86 ERA during 161/3 innings. No
interest in Nomo Right-hander Hideo Nomo, whom the Chicago Cubs
released Friday, does not interest the Rangers, O'Brien said. The
Rangers shared the assessment of Cubs general manager Ed Lynch.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just didn't see the command or stuff that we felt was good
enough to get major-league hitters out,'' Lynch said.
</P>
<P>
   The Cubs released the 30-year-old pitcher Friday after Nomo
declined to make two more starts at Triple-A Iowa. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
