<HEADLINE>
STANFORD TAKES PAC-10 WOMEN'S AND MEN'S SINGLES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By VINCENT BONSIGNORE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &LR; OJAI, Calif. _ Even though she dominated junior events at the
Ojai Valley tennis tournament over the years, Marissa Irvin was
never satisfied.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin won titles here as a 14- and 16-year old, then would watch
as the Pacific-10 Conference crowned its annual champions before
large crowds at Libbey Park. For a talented young player growing up
in Southern California, the Pac-10 represented prestige and
history, the conference championship tournament a destination to
one day reach.
</P>
<P>
   That's the way it's always been for Irvin, Stanford University's
freshman sensation: Dream about the future while dominating the
present.
</P>
<P>
   In both regards, nothing much has changed. On Sunday, Irvin
fulfilled a lifelong goal of winning the Pac-10 women's singles
title, beating USC's Ditta Huber 6-1, 7-6 (7-4) in the final of the
99th annual Ojai Valley Tournament. Soon after, she was asked what
her immediate plans were: Will she return to Stanford University
next fall or play professional tennis?
</P>
<P>
   Once again, it seems Irvin's present and future are intertwined.
</P>
<P>
   This time, Irvin decided to enjoy what !ital!was!off! instead of
considering what will be.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to base what I do on (college and amateur)
tournament results,'' Irvin said. ``I'll base it on how I feel.
(Pro tennis) is a goal of mine, obviously, but I'm just going to
wait and see how I feel.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the sort of thing that happens when a freshman explodes
onto the scene as Irvin has. She was regarded as one the top
recruits in Stanford history after leaving Harvard-Westlake and
she's done nothing this year to tarnish that belief.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin's impressive first season _ she captured the women's
singles championship at the Rolex National Indoor Title in February
and had a string of 23 consecutive wins at one point _ has only
fueled speculation that she might soon turn pro.
</P>
<P>
   Irvin, who said she won't make a decision on her future until
after the NCAA tournament in May, just wants to enjoy her latest
win. She ended the day by teaming with Teryn Ashley to help
Stanford win the women's doubles title 6-1, 6-2 over Cal's Claire
Curran and Anita Kurimay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being from Southern California, the Pac-10 always meant so
much,'' Irvin said. ``When I came here to play (as a youth), I'd
always watch the Pac-10 final and think about playing in it one
day. It's definitely been a dream of mine for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   In men's Pac-10 singles, Stanford's Ryan Wolters beat Arizona
State's Gustavo Marcaccio 6-4, 6-4. Wolters was making his third
straight appearance in the final, but for the first time he faced
someone other than a Stanford teammate.
</P>
<P>
   He noticed the difference early Sunday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a lot more nervous then I was the last two years,''
Wolters said. ``I definitely wanted to win more this year than the
two previous times.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolters kept Marcaccio off balance with solid serving and some
terrific passing shots. In some ways, he beat the clever Marcaccio
at his own game.
</P>
<P>
   Marcaccio, a 5-foot-7 senior, frustrated previous opponents with
his quickness and tenacity. That didn't work against Wolters, who
showed similar intensity and hustle.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to be in top shape to beat Ryan,'' Macaccio said.
``And today he was really tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Irvin slipped a little in April (she lost four of her
last seven matches heading into Ojai), she is obviously on top of
her game now. Irvin didn't drop a set here this week and was
cruising against Huber before wilting somewhat in the second set.
Serving for the match at 5-2, Irvin lost four of the next five
games to force a tiebreaker. She rallied at that point, winning the
tiebreaker 7-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I just got a little tight, I started having trouble
with my first serve and then I was tight on some of my shots,''
Irvin said. ``But fortunately I was able to pull it out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
