<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-IMPACT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COST OF WAR IN KOSOVO COULD COST BORDER COUNTRIES $2.5 BILLION  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   By PAUL LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The war in Kosovo will effectively cost the six
most affected Balkan countries bordering Serbia at least $2.4
billion this year if fighting is prolonged and no refugees return
home, Western analysts have estimated.
</P>
<P>
   Even that estimate may prove conservative, and the costs for
Albania, Bosnia, Romania, Bulgaria, Croatia and Macedonia are
likely to rise if the conflict continues into 2000, a study by the
International Monetary Fund and World Bank concludes.
</P>
<P>
   Finance ministers attending the spring sessions of the Bank and
the IMF will discuss the estimated costs and the study of the
economic consequences of the Kosovo crisis on Tuesday in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   The study concludes that _ if the Kosovo crisis persists all
year _ the six affected Balkan countries will need a total of
$1.826 billion in outside assistance. The money would cover
increased balance of payments deficits as a result of lost trade
and the cost of caring for refugees.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the study says, the governments of the six
countries are likely to see their budget deficits swell by another
$652 million as a result of lost customs revenues and the increased
costs of maintaining defense and law and order during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The study postulates what it calls pessimistic assumptions that
Albania will receive 417,000 Kosovo refugees this year, followed by
Macedonia with 182,000. The total number of refugees is estimated
to reach 925,000, including 276,000 in Montenegro, Serbia's junior
partner which is part of Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   This unfavorable scenario assumes these countries lose all their
official trade with the rump Yugoslavia this year, but that their
exports and imports across Yugoslav territory return to a quarter
of their precrisis levels in the second half.
</P>
<P>
   It also assumes the number of refugees they are sheltering peaks
at 750,000 in the second quarter of the year and ``declines only
modestly in the remainder of the year as a result of some
relocation of refugees to other countries.''
</P>
<P>
   On the more optimistic assumption that ``the crisis is resolved
quickly,'' the World Bank and the IMF say the six countries will
need some $807 million in external assistance to cover the costs of
lost trade and caring for refugees. In addition, their governments
will face additional budget deficits totaling $308 million.
</P>
<P>
   The assumption in this scenario is that their trade with
Yugoslavia returns to 75 per cent of precrisis level and transit
trade to 50 per cent during the second half of the year and that
all refugees have returned by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The Fund and the Bank say the Kosovo crisis will strain the
social and economic infrastructures of these largely impoverished
Balkan states. Trade _ particularly for Macedonia and Bosnia, which
export to Serbia _ will be disrupted, and the flow of commerce in
general slowed by NATO bombing damage to Yugoslav transport and
storage facilities, the study notes. Foreign investment is likely
to sink because of the general crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Croatia's lucrative adriatic tourist trade is expected to
suffer. Along with Bulgaria and Romania, it is likely to find
itself paying higher interest rates for borrowing on international
capital markets.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the study says the crisis may harm these countries by
postponing economic reforms they are planning. For example the
privatization of state-owned industries may be delayed by lack of
foreign investor interest and lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   Both the World Bank and the IMF say they will help these
countries meet the additional costs they face as a result of the
crisis. The World Bank says it will ``provide emergency financing
assistance to the affected countries to help close balance of
payments and budgetary gaps,'' noting that it has already given
Albania $2 million for refugee costs and is discussing aid with all
of them.
</P>
<P>
   The IMF, which by statute cannot assist governments cover
domestic budget deficits, says it will ``rephase and augment''
existing loans to help some countries finance their increased
payments deficits.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
