<SLUG> BC-CAR-NHRA-GWYNN-TEX </SLUG>
 
Darrell Gwynn pulls life together after paralyzing crash 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
ENNIS, Texas _ April 15 used to be the most taxing day of the year
for Darrell and Lisa Gwynn, but it snuck right past them this
month.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The only thing we think about now on April 15 is our taxes,''
Lisa Gwynn said from the couple's home in Fort Lauderdale, Fla.
``That's a good thing. It's a healing kind of process that we've
gone through. Because for the first couple of years after the
accident, it was like, `Oh gosh, it's here again.' ''
</P>
<P>
   The accident. It happened on April 15, 1990, Easter Sunday.
Darrell Gwynn was an always-smiling, borderline-cocky, rising star
in the National Hot Rod Association's Top Fuel ranks. And then an
exhibition run down a drag strip in England altered his destiny.
</P>
<P>
   The chassis on Gwynn's rear-engined car inexplicably snapped in
half while accelerating down the quarter-mile Santa Pod Raceway.
The tumbling wreckage struck the track's retaining wall, paralyzing
Gwynn from the chest down and eventually forcing doctors to
amputate his left arm at the elbow. In a matter of five or six or
seven horrifying seconds, the carefree driver known as ``The Kid''
_ winner of 18 NHRA races and the championship runner-up in 1986
and 1988 _ was launched into his second life at 28.
</P>
<P>
   ``You are a creature of your environment,'' said Gwynn, 37,
owner of the Team Mopar Dragster driven by Mike Dunn at the Castrol
Nationals this weekend at the Texas Motorplex. ``A lot of people
haven't been around me since the accident. I still have my bad
days, days when I don't feel like getting out of bed. But if you
own a Top Fuel team, you'd better get out of bed. Early.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also have a lot of good people and my family around me. A
lot of good things have happened to me since the accident.''
</P>
<P>
   To begin with, Darrell and Lisa, who were engaged at the time of
the accident, were married Jan. 9, 1993. Last June 26, Lisa gave
birth to the couple's first child, daughter Katie Brianne. She is
the first frozen embryo born through the Miami Project to Cure
Paralysis.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a little miracle child,'' said Darrell, proudly
sporting a plastic credential-holder around his neck featuring two
photographs of his daughter. ``She's 10-months-old and learning how
to say `da-da.' I've got more reasons than ever to stay home with
my wife and my baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Lisa Gwynn is completing the first year of a three-year
residency at Jackson Memorial Hospital at the University of Miami,
leading to board-certification as a pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm interning as a mother and a pediatrician,'' said Lisa, who
also has learned to rely on family and friends to make her and
Darrell's diverse schedules work. ``Living life with a spinal-cord
injury in the family is not without its complications. With the
baby, it makes it even harder. We've truly learned about the
goodness of people.''
</P>
<P>
   But Darrell also has more reasons than ever to guide his
motorized wheelchair into his specially equipped Winnebago
motorhome and spend the weekend at the track. Because four races
into the 22-event schedule, Gwynn's team is atop of drag racing's
premier division.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn ended a personal losing streak dating to June 23, 1996,
with a victory in the season-opening Winternationals on Feb. 8 at
Pomona (Calif.) Raceway, where Gwynn won his first Top Fuel race in
1986. Dunn also won the season's third race in Gainesville, Fla.,
on March 21. Dunn brought a 32-point lead over Doug Herbert into
this meet.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not by accident that this car is running this good,''
said Gwynn, whose team includes veteran tuner Ken Veney and team
manager Larry Meyer of Irving. ``We did a lot of problem
identifying in the off-season to find out how to make this team
better. Hiring Larry Meyer fixed about 90 percent of the
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   That could be bad news for the usual Top Fuel contenders. While
many have been hit-and-miss with their five-disc clutch and engine
combinations, Veney generally has been able to keep Dunn firing on
all eight cylinders.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ken has got the rip-your-throat-out attitude,'' said Gwynn, a
bulldog who posted a five-year won/loss record of 140-64 (.686
percentage) as a driver. ``As a car owner, I can't ask for anything
more.''
</P>
<P>
   In Dunn, Gwynn has a driver he truly can relate to. Gwynn's
father, Jerry, was an accomplished Sportsman drag racer whose
career included a victory in the World Finals at Dallas in 1969 in
an AA/Altered Roadster. Dunn is the son of Jim Dunn, a pioneer
Funny Car driver whose 1970s match-racing career was chronicled in
the movie ``Funny Car Summer.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Dunn, who drove Funny Cars from 1981-1991, has been Gwynn's
full-time Top Fuel shoe since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Dunn is a guy I don't have to babysit,'' said Gwynn,
whose team's best points finishes have been fourth-place runs in
1993 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Dunn's admiration for Gwynn and his commitment to the team is
unabashed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The competitive spirit has never died in Darrell,'' said Dunn,
42, of Wrightsville, Pa. ``And don't get me wrong, because we do
argue. I've often said that part of the reason we're still together
is that I live in Pennsylvania and Darrell lives in Florida. The
thing about Darrell is, since I've been with him, he has never
complained about the cards he's been dealt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrell wants us to get better. He's always said, `Let's
invest the money that will make the real estate \Rbodywork\S on the
side of this car more valuable.''
</P>
<P>
   Courting sponsors, in fact, occupies most of Gwynn's work day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm in contact with Mopar and Gates Rubber and Prolong and Mac
Tools and Winnebago, the people that have invested in us,'' Gwynn
said. ``It's a full-time job making sure those people are happy and
taking care of the business side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a schedule that, combined with his family life, allows
Gwynn little time to dwell upon ``one bad day'' nine years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of knew it was coming up last week,'' Darrell Gwynn
said of the anniversary, ``and it went by and I never thought about
it. It's not like we sit around the house all day, crying on April
15.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
