`Machines' threaten horse racing's image 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY MOSS 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
FORT WORTH, Texas _ Trainer Bob Baffert is going for a record third
consecutive Kentucky Derby victory. Sheikh Mohammed al Maktoum is
launching an invasion from Dubai. Answer Lively tries to become the
first juvenile champion since 1979 to win the country's most
prestigious horse race.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Interesting storylines for this Run for the Roses on Saturday
are everywhere. But instead, headlines are being dominated by the
saga of jockey Billy Patin, who is being investigated for possibly
carrying an illegal battery device that could keep Arkansas Derby
winner Valhol out of the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Horse people cringe at the adverse publicity the issue has
generated at a time when the sport is aggressively seeking a better
image. ``There is no place in this game for something like this,''
said trainer Nick Zito, who has three horses for Saturday's race.
</P>
<P>
   Crude electrical stimulation devices are as much a part of
racing folklore _ although an unseemly part _ as the Vanderbilts
and Whitneys.
</P>
<P>
   A computer check by Association of Racing Commissioners
International turned up 65 pages of stewards' rulings since 1974
for electrical devices, commonly known in the sport as
``machines.'' Such homemade devices typically consist of two AAA
batteries looped in wiring and covered with black electrical tape,
with two exposed prongs that provide a shock when pressed.
</P>
<P>
   Offending jockeys most often have carried the small devices in
their palms, surreptitiously rubbing them against horses' necks as
part of their natural riding motion in an attempt to shock horses
into running faster.
</P>
<P>
   Riders have been caught with machines hidden up their sleeves,
tucked into riding britches, and tied to the underside of horses'
manes. One jockey in Arizona was caught when a finish-line
photograph showed a device in his mouth.
</P>
<P>
   Oaklawn Park is alleging Patin carried a ``machine'' during the
April 10 Arkansas Derby, then dropped it to the track as 31-1
longshot Valhol was galloping out past the finish. At least one
eyewitness saw an object fall from the horse, and video from ESPN's
national telecast clearly shows an unidentified object falling from
the vicinity of Patin's left hand.
</P>
<P>
   Valhol faces possible exclusion from the Kentucky Derby due to a
lack of graded-stakes earnings. The Arkansas Racing Commission is
withholding the gelding's $300,000 Arkansas Derby winnings, pending
the outcome of its investigation, which will last at least another
eight days. James Jackson of Rockdale, who owns Valhol, says he
will take legal action if necessary to have those earnings credited
to Valhol until guilt or innocence is established.
</P>
<P>
   If Valhol makes it into the Kentucky Derby, he will be a
longshot, just as Hallieboy was a half-century ago.
</P>
<P>
   Hallieboy finished 10th at 69-1 odds in the 1950 running, and
track officials subsequently received a tip that jockey George
Atkins carried a ``machine'' during the race. When Hallieboy ran
two weeks later in another race at Churchill Downs and finished
sixth, Atkins was searched afterward and a device was found.
</P>
<P>
   Atkins wasn't permitted to ride again until 1959 and never had
another Derby mount. \Nsubheds:A Who's Who of culprits The ARCI's
list of stewards rulings associated with battery devices includes
well-known jockeys such as national superstar Shane Sellers, Lone
Star Park's own Marlon St. Julien, and top quarter horse jockey
Eddie Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Some, like Sellers, were unfairly accused and later exonerated.
Then only 20 years old, Sellers was ruled off in May 1986 by
stewards at Fairmount Park, a minor-league track in Collinsville,
Ill., for what they termed as ``participation'' in the possession
of an electrical device. Actually, the device was found on Lee
Felix, who had been aboard a pony that accompanied Sellers and his
mount to the starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   Fairmount stewards overturned the ruling nine months later and
restored Sellers to good standing.
</P>
<P>
   ``As God is my witness, I was nowhere near that thing,'' Sellers
recalled yesterday from Churchill Downs. ``It wasn't fair back
then, and I don't like being associated with that stuff now. I've
worked too hard to build my good name.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien was given a six-month suspension in 1995 by stewards
at Evangeline Downs in Lafayette, La., for an incident in which a
machine was found on the ground beneath one of his mounts.
</P>
<P>
   St. Julien, the leading Lone Star thoroughbred jockey in races
won in 1998, said he continued to ride on appeal, never served a
single suspension day, and now has a clean record. According to the
Louisiana Racing Commission, St. Julien was arrested for
``unnatural stimulation of a racehorse,'' but charges were dropped
and the incident removed from his record after he participated in a
four-month diversionary program as mandated by the Lafayette Parish
district attorney.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers and St. Julien are natives of south Louisiana. Many of
the country's most celebrated machine cases involved other riders
from that area, such as Lane Suire, Phil Rubbicco, L. J. Durousseau
and now Patin.
</P>
<P>
   That might not be coincidence.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers explained to Fairmount stewards in 1986 that although he
had never carried a device at a recognized track, they were
commonly used at the state's celebrated ``bush'' tracks where
quarter horses are matched against each other for side bets. Like
many Cajun kids, Sellers began riding in these races at a young
age.
</P>
<P>
   One trainer who asked not to be identified said that machines
are much more prevalent at smaller tracks, where scrutiny from the
public and officials is not as intense. At some small tracks, he
said, maintenance workers have been known to supplement their
income by retrieving discarded machines from track infields and
selling them back to jockeys.
</P>
<P>
   He said the devices tend to work best on older horses that have
become bored with the sport and don't try their hardest.
Inexperienced horses such as Valhol are considered poor candidates.
\Nsubheds:A matter of chance Former jockey and racing official Ted
Atkinson, now 83 and a member of the National Racing Hall of Hame,
said it is well-known that most racehorses don't respond positively
to such stimulation.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just a question of the horse,'' Atkinson said. ``He's got
to be scared to death of it, and a lot of horses won't run from it
at all. It's a matter of chance.''
</P>
<P>
   As a steward at Arlington Park, Atkinson participated in the
expulsion of Suire, whose creativity was surpassed only by his hard
luck.
</P>
<P>
   In the early 1970s, Suire was injured in a spill at Arlington
and was removed from the track by ambulance. A few minutes later, a
tractor driver harrowing the track found a whip on the track near
the spot of the accident. The whip was engraved with Suire's
initials and a battery device was found concealed inside its
hollowed-out handle, with two prongs sticking out of the bottom of
the handle.
</P>
<P>
   Suire was suspended from riding for five years.
</P>
<P>
   The most notorious of all jockeys associated with ``machines,''
however, hailed from Arkansas rather than Louisiana.
</P>
<P>
   The late Lonnie Joe Ray was a talented rider, but was better
known for his flamboyant and often erratic personality. Those who
knew him well said Ray would rather win one race dishonestly than
two by following the rules.
</P>
<P>
   Ray eluded discovery until a January 1973 race at Tropical Park
in Miami, now known as Calder Race Course. Security showed up
behind the starting gate to search Ray, who was ordered to
dismount. A body check turned up nothing. Ray climbed back into the
saddle, and as his horse was loaded into the gate, he verbally
abused the track starter, who presses the button to open the gates
and begin the races.
</P>
<P>
   The starter had heard rumors Ray had a special hiding spot for
his machine, and had kept quiet during the initial search. But when
he was cursed by Ray, he ordered the horse backed out of the
starting gate.
</P>
<P>
   He summoned security officers. ``Look in his knot,'' the starter
said.
</P>
<P>
   And there, tucked into a large knot Ray had tied in the reins
behind the horse's neck, was an electrical device.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, the authorities had their man. Ray was ruled off from
riding.
</P>
<P>
   If the frequency of stewards' rulings is any indication, the use
of electrical devices in racing is declining. Three cases were
reported to the ARCI in 1997, one in 1998, and none so far this
year.
</P>
<P>
   Lone Star Park executive vice president and general manager
Corey Johnsen said track management meets with riders before each
season to explain the hard line the track will take with offenders.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no place in horse racing for an electrical device,
and we feel strongly about that,'' Johnsen said. ``If anyone is
found with one on our grounds, they will be banned for life from
Lone Star.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson agrees with that stance.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it is proved beyond a shadow of a doubt that \RPatin\S
carried a device,'' said Jackson, ``then in the future they should
check riders before every race and at the gate. They should make
absolutely sure nothing like this ever happens to anyone else in
this game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm innocent in this, but yet I'm the one paying the price for
it.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
