<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-G8-MEET-785&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LITTLE URGENCY CLOUDS EVE OF WORLD BANKERS' MEETING 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Story includes material from previously skedded RUSSIA-IMF.) 
(mk) 
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ When the finance ministers and officials of the
world's biggest economic powers last met in Washington six months
ago, President Clinton declared that he and other leaders were
confronting ``the biggest financial challenge facing the world in a
half-century.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, on the eve of another such meeting, millions of people are
still suffering, national economies are still shrinking, but the
crisis seems oddly abated.
</P>
<P>
   The crisis preoccupying Clinton and other leaders is in Kosovo,
not the market. Fear of new forms of ``economic contagion'' has
been replaced with far older fears of military contagion. Asia's
slow recovery has moved it off the political radar screen.
</P>
<P>
   Without that sense of urgency, the chances of remaking the
``global financial architecture'' through fundamental changes _ the
rallying call of financial meetings last fall _ have diminished
considerably. But there have been some modest steps, including one
Sunday by the International Monetary Fund's executive board. As
part of the lending agency's efforts to offer some way to prevent
economic turbulence from spreading from country to country, the
board approved a program for contingency credit, Michel Camdessus,
its managing director, announced.
</P>
<P>
   The program, first called for by Clinton last September, will
allow the IMF to offer substantial credit to any country determined
to be following sound economic policies. The hope is that such
support will deter speculators from attacking a nation's currency
and will preserve investor confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin said that the IMF's action was a
victory for Clinton's financial stability agenda and that the
program would provide ``an expanded capacity to help maintain
confidence when countries face the threat of financial contagion.''
</P>
<P>
   An unresolved problem with the program is that the standard _
sound economic policies _ is likely to be hard for the most
vulnerable nations to meet, while many eligible countries are less
likely to be hit by contagion.
</P>
<P>
   As the leaders of the IMF and the World Bank, in Washington for
their spring meetings, start occupying the hotel rooms just
abandoned by NATO leaders who were here for NATO's 50th
anniversary, some officials insist that the biggest worry once
again is the absence of fear itself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a real danger, which I sense already, that the
pressure to reform is weakening around the world,'' James
Wolfensohn, the president of the World Bank, said in an interview
this weekend. ``There were a lot of powerful and wealthy interests
who opposed reform, and they have been able to reassert
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton warned last week against the dangers of ``complacency,''
endorsing an agenda of reforms spelled out the next day by Rubin.
Those proposals, however, turned out to be modest at best: more
disclosure rules to force countries, companies and hedge funds to
make information about their financial health public, and some
``voluntary guidelines'' to try to prevent countries from taking
huge financial risks.
</P>
<P>
   To many experts, the package looked more like interior
decorating than real architectural alterations. Rubin shied away,
for example, from any proposals to control the flow of capital into
or out of vulnerable countries, or to expand the powers of the IMF
to be a ``lender of last resort'' for stricken nations.
</P>
<P>
   For some of the countries hardest hit by the economic crisis,
notably Thailand and South Korea, a sense of optimism has replaced
gloom. Although their economies will still shrink this year, their
stock markets began rocketing back almost as soon as the last set
of meetings of the World Bank and the IMF ended in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   By some measures, South Korea's market has returned to where it
was before the crisis in Asia struck, and Hong Kong's has roared
back to life. Brazil, which in January appeared to be the next
domino to fall, has stumbled into unexpected stability.
</P>
<P>
   While the good news has buoyed investors, it has also emboldened
the leaders of huge businesses _ like South Korea's powerful
industrial groups, the chaebols, which came to symbolize crony
capitalism _ to resist real change.
</P>
<P>
   ``The crisis came about because of some misjudgments about the
fragility of the system,'' said Jeffrey Garten, the dean of the
Yale School of Management, who had called for some tough reforms,
including the creation of a global central bank, several months
ago. ``Now there is a feeling in the air that the system is more
resilient, more capable of bouncing back fast, than anyone thought.
When you put that together with vivid pictures out of Kosovo, you
can see how quickly the political attention span can be diverted.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Some other reforms are under way. Countries already publish far
more data than they did before the crisis first hit Thailand in
July 1997. The IMF posts some of its conclusions about member
nations' debt and economic strategies on the Internet
(http://www.imf.org).
</P>
<P>
   Armed with more information, investors are expected to be far
more cautious. But questions remain as to whether the new
disclosure policies have prompted the IMF to be less open. ``We are
clearly less willing to publish something that could trigger
investors to panic now that it's clear it may be immediately
published,'' one senior official said recently.
</P>
<P>
   Adding to the diminished sense of urgency is some new thinking
that has emerged about crisis-racked nations like Russia and
Indonesia: that after a while, their troubles pose less of a threat
to the rest of the world, not more.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, the Clinton administration scrambled to put
together a huge bailout package for Russia, fearing that an
economic meltdown would destabilize President Boris Yeltsin,
threaten economic reforms and perhaps lead to a national political
breakup.
</P>
<P>
   While the IMF is close to a new agreement to resume loans, it
will probably give Russia only enough to pay back major debtors and
avert the embarrassment of default.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would be surprised if Russia gets anything more than just a
chance to muddle through the year,'' said one international
official involved in the negotiations. ``There is a sense that if
you don't give them the money, it would be another sign of Russia's
severed linkage with the West, which would put them more and more
outside the system.'' Talk of resuming real economic reform,
though, has dissipated.
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, aid to Indonesia is on hold until after elections in
June. While its economic woes remain severe, and violence continues
around the country, American officials have concluded that the
chances are now small that Indonesia's troubles will infect the
rest of Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The new thinking is the old thinking,'' said Garten, who left
the Clinton administration for Yale after the president's first
term. ``And that is that since we still don't really understand
many of the forces at work, we should leave a lot of this to the
market.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2050EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
