<HEADLINE>
CATROL NATIONALS NOTES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHN STURBIN AND LEN HAYWARD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
Attendance up ENNIS, Texas _ Texas Motorplex owner Billy Meyer said
he is pleased with the growth rate of the Castrol Nationals, which
concluded its third edition yesterday with an announced four-day
attendance of 119,000, up from 112,200 last year.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Elon Werner, the track's director of media relations, said that
126,350 tickets were sold but that the threat of rain likely held
attendance down.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday's attendance was estimated at 36,000. Meyer said
Saturday's attendance was up 18.9 percent and Friday was up 10
percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``This race is the same size as the fall race was in its ninth
year,'' said Meyer, referring to the O'Reilly Fallnationals, which
has a 14th edition scheduled Oct. 21-24. Tough day for Prudhomme
Don Prudhomme's entries, driven by Ron Capps and Larry Dixon, both
lost in the first round.
</P>
<P>
   Capps' struggles continued in his Copenhagen Chevrolet Camaro
Funny Car, even after qualifying second behind John Force. Dale
Creasy Jr. beat Capps in their first-round run, keeping Capps
winless in elimination rounds this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were just too aggressive early in the run,'' said
Capps, who finished second to John Force in the 1998 Funny Car
point standings. ``It's not a front-end down-force problem; it's
the first 200 feet of the track, and it's just that you are trying
to run these cars so hard you lift the front end.''
</P>
<P>
   Dixon, driving the Prudhomme-owned Miller Lite Top Fuel
dragster, was the top qualifier in the class, but lost traction in
his first-round pass, losing to Allen Hartley. Dixon's loss was the
second time this season he has failed to advance out of the opening
round.
</P>
<P>
   Also losing in Top Fuel's first round were Doug Herbert, who was
coming off a $100,000 victory at Houston Raceway Park two weeks
ago, defending Castrol Nationals champion Joe Amato and
sixth-fastest qualifier Bob Vandergriff Jr. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
