</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEST-TEX </SLUG>
 EDITORS: This is a test from the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. nn
<TEXT>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2054EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0168 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2626 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EDIT-NURSING-HOMES-NY     04-25 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-NURSING-HOMES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: THEY DIDN'T LIVE SO LONG FOR THIS  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
   c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Monday, April 26:
</P>
<P>
   It is thought that as many as half of all women over 65 in the
United States and a third of all men will spend some of their
remaining time in a nursing home. The American population is aging,
and as new assisted living communities draw off the more able and
affluent retirees, and as increased federal funding allows others
to be supported by health care visits at home, nursing homes have
acquired the sickest and most dependent of the old.
</P>
<P>
   Of that concentration of 1.6 million people, less than 8 percent
can bathe, dress, go to the bathroom, move about and feed
themselves without help. Bedded down usually two to a room, they
are cared for at an average charge of about $50,000 per year _
$94,000 in New York City _ enough to impoverish most of them. About
two-thirds end up being welfare cases. The federal government
expects to pay $39 billion for nursing-home care this year. Yet as
every study for decades has shown, great numbers of the old, many
as helpless as babies, continue to be neglected and abused.
</P>
<P>
   Some die of accidents, malnutrition, dehydration, untreated
urinary infections and bedsores that turn into toxic, flesh-eating
wounds. In California, a lawyer who is an advocate for the elderly
charged that more than 3,000 people succumbed to unacceptable care
in 1993 alone. The General Accounting Office, investigating a
sample of those cases, found that in half of them that may have
been true. The majority of nursing homes seem to give good or
decent care. But just last month, the GAO pointed out that
government inspections of nursing homes across the country each
year show that more than one-fourth cause actual harm to their
residents, or place them at risk of serious injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   One problem, says Dwana Pinchock, of the National Citizens'
Coalition of Nursing Home Reform, is that for nurse's aides, who do
most of the bathing, dressing, turning and feeding of patients,
there is often less required training than for a manicurist at a
beauty parlor, and they may be paid less than a beginning caretaker
at the zoo. Another problem is that state and federal governments
have been too lax. Again and again, nursing homes found to mistreat
patients are given time to correct the problems, only to be found
in violation again.
</P>
<P>
   It is a disgraceful dose of misery and death for a generation
that did not survive the Great Depression and World War II to be
treated like this. There are, however, some reasons for hope.
</P>
<P>
   One is the baby-boom generation, whose members, in places like
California, Maryland and Michigan, have begun to complain about the
fate of their parents, aunts and uncles in nursing homes.
</P>
<P>
   Another is the Senate Special Committee on Aging chaired by Sen.
Charles Grassley of Iowa, which keeps prodding the GAO to
investigate, and the Clinton administration to get tougher under
present law. There are signs that the Medicaid and Medicare
authorities are beginning to clamp down on nursing home
performance. Michigan has an initiative of its own, making rules
that have allowed it to force plans of corrective action on homes,
and even impose professional managers on them until they improve.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome this sort of initiative,'' Grassley said recently,
``and I'm going to be watching this to see if that's something we
can build on.'' Toward a better end.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
