<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVO UPDATE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DIPLOMACY
</P>
<P>
   _ NATO ended its three-day summit meeting in Washington with the
alliance declaring that its military campaign against Belgrade
would succeed.
</P>
<P>
   _ President Clinton told Russian President Boris Yeltsin in a
telephone conversation that they should work together on a
diplomatic solution to the conflict.
</P>
<P>
   COMBAT
</P>
<P>
   _ In the 33rd night of strikes, NATO warplanes again knocked
Serbian television off the air for several hours. A factory in
Lucani, in central Serbia, that NATO said produced explosives was
attacked, as were an oil-storage depot in Pristina and several
targets in the industrial city of Nis.
</P>
<P>
   OTHER DEVELOPMENTS
</P>
<P>
   _ Representatives of the Kosovo Liberation Army in northern
Albania spoke openly with reporters for the first time, appealing
for NATO to supply them and to use Apache helicopters against the
Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB
</P>
<P>
   Continuous coverage of the conflict in Yugoslavia is available
from The New York Times on the Web: http://www.nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
