<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-RDP-ART-580(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO WORK WITH RUSSIA TO RESOLVE KOSOVO CONFLICT 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also NATO-ASSESS, NATO-SKETCH) 
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By JANE PERLEZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and Russian President Boris
Yeltsin agreed in a telephone conversation Sunday to continue
personal contacts in the search for a solution to the Kosovo
conflict. They spoke as leaders of NATO concluded a summit with
pledges to continue and intensify their air campaign against
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   White House officials said Yeltsin initiated the call and had
asked Clinton to place the next one after doing ``some thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian leader's thoughts were not fully clarified in the
90-minute conversation, the officials said. But after the call they
announced that Deputy Secretary of State Strobe Talbott would leave
for Moscow on Monday to consult with Victor S. Chernomyrdin,
Yeltsin's envoy to the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   The three-day NATO summit, originally called to celebrate the
50th anniversary of the alliance but largely overshadowed by
Kosovo, concluded with bold expressions of solidarity in the
struggle to halt Milosevic's assault on Albanians in Kosovo, and,
in so doing, build a united Europe.
</P>
<P>
   ``What NATO did here this weekend was to reaffirm our commitment
to a common future rooted in common humanity,'' Clinton said in his
closing statement. ``Standing against ethnic cleansing is both a
moral imperative and a practical necessity.''
</P>
<P>
   The leaders went away declaring that they would succeed against
Milosevic by sticking to their original strategy of an air
campaign. But they vowed to escalate the attacks and expand the
targets.
</P>
<P>
   They left open how long it would take for the air campaign to
achieve their goal of degrading Milosevic's military forces in
Kosovo and forcing him to capitulate. The British foreign
secretary, Robin Cook, declared that NATO would continue ``for as
long as it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   Talk at the beginning of the summit about when and how ground
troops might enter Kosovo faded, a casualty of opposition within
the Clinton administration and a recognition that the stability of
several European governments, especially Germany and Italy, would
be risked by open discussion of troops.
</P>
<P>
   Reaffirming the primacy of the air assaults, Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, said: ``What I think has really come out of
this session here at the summit is a really genuine support for an
intensified air campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   German Chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said, ``It's not going to be
easy. It's going to take longer than we would have originally hoped
for, but we shall win.''
</P>
<P>
   But behind the steely statements, aides to European leaders said
there was an acute awareness that the escalation of the air strikes
had to bring better results soon. Public support in NATO countries
could easily erode if the war dragged on, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Further, if the alliance wanted to get the more than 500,000
ethnic Albanian refugees now camped in Albania and Macedonia back
into Kosovo before the onset of winter, the military campaign
against the Serbs in Kosovo had to speed up, several European
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time that the alliance was stressing military
victory, NATO leaders were also trying to push a diplomatic track.
</P>
<P>
   The officials described Russia's efforts to deal with the Serbs
as being in ``good faith'' and that they were interested to know
more about what Chernomyrdin had accomplished in Belgrade during a
visit there last week with Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president made the point to Yeltsin strongly that he very
much wants to keep the lines of communication open at the highest
level,'' Joe Lockhart, the White House spokesman said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   During the phone conversation, the Russian president described
some of the elements of a possible peace deal that Chernomyrdin had
brought back from Belgrade, according to a White House official who
listened to the call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeltsin told us there was a commitment from the Serbs to allow
the return of the refugees and for the Serbs to withdraw their
forces from Kosovo,'' the official said.
</P>
<P>
   But there was ``not a great deal of clarity'' on what the
withdrawal of Serb forces meant. On another key point, Yeltsin said
that Milosevic had agreed to the deployment of an ``international
presence'' run by the United Nations with Russia as a key element.
It was also not clear whether the ``presence'' meant inclusion of
police, armed observers or soldiers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deal described by Yeltsin fell far short of the five
principles that NATO had laid down as the basis for an agreement,
the White House aide said. These include an international military
force, with NATO at its core, that would escort back the ethnic
Albanian refugees once the conflict was over.
</P>
<P>
   An important task for Talbott was to try to determine from
Chernomyrdin how much Milosevic ``was hurting'' from the air
strikes, the White House aide said. This was a key factor in
figuring out how far the Yugoslav leader is from accepting a
diplomatic solution on NATO's terms.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders stressed the need for Russia's help in finding a
solution.
</P>
<P>
   The German chancellor said he was meeting with the U.N.
secretary-general, Kofi Annan, in Berlin this week to talk about a
Kosovo solution and that he understood Annan would then fly on to
Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invite the Russians to resume their role in putting pressure
on the Serb side to come to a political solution of the conflict,''
Schroeder said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Annan was on the verge of appointing a personal envoy for the
Kosovo conflict, most probably former Austrian Chancellor Franz
Vranitsky, Austrian officials said Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Belgrade, a member of the Milosevic government, deputy prime
minister Vuk Draskovic, said that Russia and NATO could come to a
compromise agreement at the United Nations soon, and urged his
government to accept it.
</P>
<P>
   As it had during the first two days of the summit meeting, the
Kosovo conflict served as the constant current on the last day.
</P>
<P>
   At a special session devoted Sunday morning to the seven states
that surround Serbia, Clinton praised Albania and Macedonia for
bearing the burden of more than 500,000 ethnic Albanian refugees
expelled into their countries by Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``The people of Albania and Macedonia have welcomed almost a
half a million refugees to their countries _ often, literally, into
their homes,'' Clinton said. ``You have shared what you have,
though the strains are immense.''
</P>
<P>
   The well-being of all Europe, Clinton said, rested on the
ability of NATO and other Western organizations to rebuild
Southeastern Europe. When the Kosovo conflict ended, the region
should aim for similar democratic and economic standards as Western
Europe, he said.
</P>
<P>
   There were few specific details about how this would be
accomplished, although several countries in the region called on
Sunday for measures on the scale of the Marshall Plan. The German
chancellor reiterated Sunday that his government was interested in
initiating a ``stability pact for Southeastern Europe'' which would
involve an economic role in the region for the European Union, and
a security role for NATO.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Clinton made 11 statements during the three day summit
conference, including several toasts and a question and answer
session at a news conference Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing remarks Sunday afternoon, he tied together the
idea of a new Europe with the conflict in Kosovo and its refugees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our vision of a Europe undivided, democratic, free and at
peace depends upon our constructive commitment to the hundreds of
thousands of poor refugees, so many men, women and children with no
place else to turn, who have been made pawns in a power struggle,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   The delegations of all 19 countries included defense ministers.
In interviews Sunday, half a dozen of the ministers said an
important outcome of the summit meeting was the decision to step up
the air campaign with a goal of turning the Serbian people against
their leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are looking at how their positions will be after this
is all over,'' said Hans Haekkerup, the defense minister of
Denmark. ``People are not going to believe in this myth of
Milosevic much longer.''
</P>
<P>
   The summit's communique embraced the idea that NATO remained
open to new members but did not give a timetable for when they
could join.
</P>
<P>
   The communique listed groups of possible new members. In the
first group were Romania and Slovenia, which almost made it into
NATO in 1997 when Hungary, the Czech Republic and Poland were named
as new entrants.
</P>
<P>
   In the second group, the communique listed the Baltic states:
Estonia, Latvia and Lithuania. Bulgaria and Slovakia were both
noted for ``positive developments,'' a reference to their moves
toward democratic standards. And Albania and Macedonia, which are
bearing the burden of the ethnic Albanian refugees but have little
hope of meeting NATO's standards, were listed as long-shot
contenders.
</P>
<P>
   Macedonian President Kiro Gligorov criticized NATO for not
extending an invitation to his country to join NATO and showing
little appreciation for Macedonia's efforts to aid the refugees.
``Macedonia has been circumvented and has again been put in last
place,'' Gligorov said.
</P>
<P>
   The domestic political impact of the Kosovo air campaign
prompted Sen. Trent Lott, the majority leader, to say Sunday that
he would not allow a Senate vote on a resolution authorizing the
president to ``use all necessary force'' to accomplish NATO's
objectives in Kosovo. Lott said that he feared that passage of such
a resolution would give Clinton too free a hand without any input
from Congress, while defeat of the measure could signal a lack of
political support for the NATO effort.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's important that Congress do no harm, first,'' said
Lott, appearing on the ABC news program ``This Week,'' speaking of
the resolution sponsored by Republican Sens. John McCain of Arizona
and Richard Lugar of Indiana. ``We don't need a divisive debate
that could give aid and comfort to Mr. Milosevic.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
