</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAFIRE-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: DEFEAT'S 19 FATHERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By WILLIAM SAFIRE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Public statements conflicted with the private,
unattributable thoughts of celebrants at Washington's NATO golden
anniversary weekend.
</P>
<P>
   How come, I demanded of an armed forces pooh-bah, it has taken
more than a month to get Apache helicopters in position? Didn't
anybody know that only close-in, low-flying aircraft could hit the
Serb killers in Kosovo? What military dunce requested Stealth
strategic bombers to fly halfway round the world and back to carry
out a tactical mission?
</P>
<P>
   The pooh-bah replied: You seem to think the Apache was the
weapon that could have taken out tanks and saved refugee lives in
Kosovo. All wrong.
</P>
<P>
   The little choppers are designed for close support of ground
troops. Spotters give pilots their assignments, he explained; the
pilots dart behind enemy lines, fire their rockets at targets they
can eyeball, and then race back to safety. They are too vulnerable
to roam around looking for targets of opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   A NATO tank expert agreed. ``You don't need surface-to-air
missiles to defend against Apaches. ``A man with a good arm and a
rock,'' he added figuratively, ``can knock one of those babies
down. Apaches can be most effective against emplacements and small
units, but only as part of a coordinated ground attack. By
themselves, they're no salvation for the Kosovars.''
</P>
<P>
   Scratch one panacea; unless NATO ground troops are ready to move
in, tactical airstrikes will not trouble Serbs now in their second
month of burning villages and systematically expelling the
un-Serbian population.
</P>
<P>
   To the bigger picture: What about massing troops in Macedonia
and in Hungary, as well as in Albania, to threaten a three-front
attack before September's snows that would require Milosevic to
pull his 40,000 Kosovo marauders back to defend Belgrade?
</P>
<P>
   Now you're talking a strategy for victory, said the military
types, but have you checked with the Hungarians about Vojvodina?
</P>
<P>
   I did. Vojvodina, like Kosovo, is a province of Serbia, but on
the border of Hungary and filled with several hundred thousand
ethic Hungarians. If NATO should strike through Hungary, Milosevic
might put those civilian lives at risk.
</P>
<P>
   Although Hungary is overjoyed to be part of NATO, its diplomats
looked pained when asked about Vojvodina. They said that allied
forces would have to strike hard, fast and not only on that front
to reach Belgrade and win the NATO-Serb war.
</P>
<P>
   I just used the verb never uttered by the assembled
Atlanticists: win. Sorry, but winning is not on the table. Among
the NATO Nineteen, defeat may be a rhetorical orphan, but victory
has no father.
</P>
<P>
   The fervent desire is to find a compromise that ceases
expulsions and bombing, moves some displaced refugees back to
southern Kosovo and allows both NATO and Milosevic to claim
victory.
</P>
<P>
   The Big Lie undergirding the deal is already in place: that
ethnic-cleansing was caused by NATO bombing, not the other way
around, and that the creation of a million terrified refugees is no
worse than the NATO punishment intended to bring the expulsion to
an end.
</P>
<P>
   That repugnant rationale for a face-saver is what you hear from
the Russians, who were officially not here, and from the Ukrainian
observers who were. Here's what the code phrase ``diplomatically
involving Russia'' means:
</P>
<P>
   For Serbia, full sovereignty over Kosovo and repair of bombing
damages. For the raped and ruined Kosovars, the right (but not the
incentive) to return, unarmed, under the ostensible protection of
U.N. observers wearing only sidearms and led by Russians. For NATO,
the withdrawal of Serb regular forces but not ``police,'' War
crimes trials will be balanced between low-level Serb paramilitary
and KLA members.
</P>
<P>
   As this sellout was privately being dressed up as ``autonomy for
the Kosovars'' among diplomats, I dropped in on the ceremony that
provided stark contrast.
</P>
<P>
   The National Endowment for Democracy awarded its highest honors
to the AFL-CIO's Lane Kirkland and to Poland's Lech Walesa.
Together these two anti-Communist patriots fought the Soviet empire
when the weak-kneed were bleating ``convergence.'' Their refusal to
compromise with evil exemplified the leadership that helped win _
the word is win _ the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Will such necessary moral courage skip a generation?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
