<HEADER>
A2633 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LAD     04-25 1101
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXCOL-COLUMN-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EX-CON AYALA HOPES TO REBUILD CAREER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sixteen years ago Tony Ayala walked into prison as a rapist and
one of the most talented fighters in the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday he walked out a changed man, or so he says _ a
36-year-old who wonders if the magic of his youth will be just a
memory when he returns to the ring.
</P>
<P>
   To Ayala, the former is far more significant than the latter:
His principal concern is his performance as a person, not as an
athlete.
</P>
<P>
   And, indeed, it appears Ayala has come a long way since New
Year's Day of 1983, when he raped a female neighbor in Paterson,
N.J., while on heroin and alcohol, substances that ruled his life
at that time.
</P>
<P>
   Ayala, who was on probation at the time of the rape for beating
a woman and breaking into a San Antonio home, was sentenced to 35
years. He was released after 16 for good behavior.
</P>
<P>
   In that time, Ayala, with the help of therapist Brian Raditz,
tackled the horrors of his own troubled childhood _ he was sexually
molested by a male friend of the family _ and the despicable person
he had become.
</P>
<P>
   After an ongoing series of painful sessions with Raditz, Ayala
insists he has emerged a ``normal'' person.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early on, I knew I had to deal with the issue that was tearing
me apart, the issue that got me in prison,'' Ayala said. ``I had to
find out why I committed such a horrible crime, I had to find out
whether I was just an animal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had made a very clear decision that if I was just a mad dog,
just a sick individual, I didn't want to live. I didn't want to
feel the guilt of knowing I was hurting people. That's when I
sought help from Brian.''
</P>
<P>
   Raditz, a prison therapist who became a close friend and now
Ayala's manager, said Ayala worked as hard on dealing with his
demons as he once did in the gym and believes Ayala now has ``a
great handle on himself.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no doubts that his patient is ready to return to society.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had masked a lot of fears, a lot of pain,'' Raditz said.
``He's developed significant insights into who he is. And then he
took it a step further: He shared his insights. He became a peer
counselor in the prison system and, the last two years, they've
brought in students from the outside for his seminars.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should feel proud of himself. He's come a long way.''
</P>
<P>
   While Ayala doesn't see boxing as his essence, it is important
to him.
</P>
<P>
   When he went to prison he was 19 years old, the WBA's top-ranked
junior middleweight and 22-0 (with 19 knockouts). It appeared the
next step was superstardom and untold riches.
</P>
<P>
   And then it was gone and he was left to wonder how great he
might've been. Now, at an age when the careers of most fighters are
winding down, he wants to find out whether it's too late finish
what he started.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some unresolved issues . . . with boxing, that I want
to be done with,'' said Ayala, who also freely admitted that the
prospect of a few big paydays is another reason he wants to resume
his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``. . . A lot of dreams were dashed because of what happened.
This is a way of affirming what I've believed about myself. I was
compared to some great, great fighters, and I don't know if I
belong in that category.''
</P>
<P>
   How good Ayala might be is anyone's guess.
</P>
<P>
   He apparently remained in good shape in prison. He claims he can
do 300 pullups, 300 pushups, 300 dips and 2,000 crunches and run
eight miles. However, he weighs at least 20 pounds more than the
junior middleweight limit of 154, the weight he'd like to get down
to.
</P>
<P>
   The first significant test will be in the gym. Ayala, who will
be trained by his father, Tony Sr., as he was before his
incarceration, said he plans to begin training immediately and
fight this summer.
</P>
<P>
   If it doesn't work out, he won't be heartbroken.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal is to die a better person than I was,'' he said. ``. .
. . I know a lot of people will measure my success on whether or
not my comeback in boxing is a success. The fact is, I'm already
successful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I survived 16 years in prison, I'm not out of control, I've
gained insights of who I was, and I have no desire to go out and
drink or anything.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am, quote, unquote, normal.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Rabbit punches: Juan Carlos Ramirez will replace Wayne
McCullough as the opponent of WBC super bantamweight champion Erik
Morales on May 8.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough was injured during sparring.
</P>
<P>
   Ramirez is 17-1 but has only seven knockouts, which means he has
no power and will be overwhelmed by the unbeaten and immensely
talented Morales. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Former three-time flyweight champion Michael Carbajal continues
his comeback against former contender Oscar Andrade on May 8 in
Miami. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Don King has weighed in on the open-scoring issue, saying boxing
can't survive without it.
</P>
<P>
   Don King speaking on salvaging the integrity of the sport? Does
anyone have a problem with that? . . .
</P>
<P>
   The Sharmba Mitchell-Reggie Green fight on Saturday provided
evidence that open scoring is a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   Mitchell knew by the 11th round that he would win if he avoided
a knockout. Thus, he cruised the final two rounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The public was robbed of a good finish,'' said Harold Weston,
Green's promoter. ``Sharmba did nothing in the last two rounds.
Open scoring is just a bad situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Weston was biased but right. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Olympic teammates and world junior middleweight champions David
Reid and Fernando Vargas have initiated a war of words.
</P>
<P>
   Reid was quoted in a magazine as saying Vargas is ``making
little money, (and) fighting with nobody watching'' and that Vargas
``hasn't been in the ring with anyone as fast or hits as hard as
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Vargas response: ``I respected David Reid before, but now he
wants to open his mouth. Well, I'm going to shut it. I want Reid as
soon as possible. I want to unify the title. If he's any type of
man, he'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   It probably won't happen soon. That's the kind of matchup
promoters want to build over a few years to maximize return.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas, a resident of Oxnard, is expected to headline an HBO
``Boxing After Dark'' show on July 31. His opponent has not been
determined. . . .
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Pettway is in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   The over-the-hill former junior middleweight champion is
scheduled to fight unbeaten IBF welterweight titleholder Felix
Trinidad on May 29 in Trinidad's home country of Puerto Rico with a
possible shot at Oscar De La Hoya hanging in the balance.
</P>
<P>
   Do you think Trinidad will be motivated?
</P>
</TEXT>
