<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OPERA-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
`RESURRECTION' UNEVEN AT TIMES
<TEXT>
<P>
   By CHARLES WARD &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ From preparation to performance, Houston Grand Opera's
latest premiere seemed destined to succeed. In the end,
Resurrection by American Tod Machover foundered on its
sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   The opera seemed to have it all: A potent story of spiritual
rebirth from Leo Tolstoy's last novel. A first-class production
capped by a visually chilling evocation of an ice-bound Siberian
winter. Two fine young singers as the prince and the prostitute. A
performance with the sure imprint of Houston Grand Opera's new
music director.
</P>
<P>
   But, in the end, there was a treacly conclusion almost straight
from the 1960s peace movement and with no more depth than We Shall
Overcome.
</P>
<P>
   Resurrection is HGO's 24th world premiere and the 14th for the
main company, all since 1974. In intention, realized at many
moments Friday at the Wortham Theater Center, Resurrection
fulfilled the current aesthetic of HGO general director David
Gockley: producing works that potentially can have broad public
appeal and, therefore, justify presenting them again quickly.
</P>
<P>
   Machover has created a score driven by insistent, restless
rhythmic energy (an acquaintance likened the surging orchestral
opening to the beginning of Bach's St. Matthew Passion). Constantly
shifting meters created urgency while avoiding the monotony of a
Philip Glass work.
</P>
<P>
   The music was fundamentally tonal with dissonance used liberally
for mood and effect. For moments of quietude and reflection, mainly
arias and duets, Machover opted for an overpared harmonic language
almost nave in its simplicity.
</P>
<P>
   Being best known for his work in electronics (The Brain Opera
and hyperinstruments), Machover combined a traditional opera
orchestra with electronics. They enhanced the sound overall, added
color and occasionally created atmosphere by themselves. The
blending was effective and completely unself-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   A troubling note, however, was the periodic amplification of the
singers. The ``general vocal enhancement,'' as HGO described it,
was used when the orchestra was playing ``at its fullest.''
</P>
<P>
   Partial justification would be the awkward set that pushed
singers to the rear and sides of the stage, or in between two slabs
of ice. Still, with an orchestra of only 32 acoustic instruments
and three electronic keyboards, the choice must be questioned.
</P>
<P>
   Tolstoy told the story of a young Russian noble, Prince Dimitry
Nekhlyudov, who meets the orphan Katerina Maslova living with his
aunts. The two young people are initially attracted; later, when
the prince returns from army duty, he forces a sexual encounter
(vividly simulated in this production) and impregnates her.
</P>
<P>
   He goes on his libertine ways until he serves on a jury that by
chance is judging Maslova for her part in a murder-by-poison plot.
When the jury botches the verdict and Maslova is sentenced to eight
years in Siberia, Dimitry pledges to free Maslova and marry her. He
sells everything, dismisses marriage to Princess Sofia Korchagin
and sets out to gain Maslova a pardon.
</P>
<P>
   He does, but when he brings it to Maslova in Siberia, he finds
she has fallen in love with a political prisoner, Peter Simonson.
They want to marry but she will do so only with the Prince's
blessing. He gives it and, in doing so, finds himself freed to
pursue life anew.
</P>
<P>
   During the preparation of the two-act Resurrection, the
dramaturgy was put through several operatic wringers by HGO music
director Patrick Summers, seasoned theater director Braham Murray
of Manchester, England (in his professional opera directing debut),
and the rest of HGO's artistic staff.
</P>
<P>
   The story of how the bitter consequences of their one-time
sexual encounter eventually transforms both people became what
Murray calls ``the spine.'' The narrative was unveiled in a tightly
focused sequence of scenes, some with flashbacks (as in the novel).
</P>
<P>
   It all should have worked except for the tone of the libretto by
Laura Harrington, with extensive reworking by Murray. It had the
flatness of ``I'm OK, you're OK'' sentimentality.
</P>
<P>
   Left out was poetry. The opera Harvey Milk by Stewart Wallace
proved that political windbagging doesn't work in opera;
Resurrection shows that sentimental moralizing doesn't, either.
</P>
<P>
   The latter was fatal in the final scene when people chattered on
about how ``the world is changed by one man to another.''
</P>
<P>
   In carefully developing his work, Machover had pointed it deftly
toward the end. He created many fine moments, particularly the
humorous dinner scene when Princess Korchagin tries every which way
to seduce Dimitry. A finale of soaring lyricism enhancing words of
soaring idealism would have made for a triumphant evening. It
didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   Although there are a large number of secondary and tertiary
roles in Resurrection, there are only two principal ones, sung very
well by products of HGO's Houston Opera Studio.
</P>
<P>
   Baritone Scott Hendricks, a current studio member, moved from
his understudy position to the lead late in the rehearsal process.
As he did in a smaller role in the HOS's spring staging of
Monteverdi's Orfeo, he scored a big success.
</P>
<P>
   Handsome, with strands of hair falling down over the right side
of his face, Hendricks was preeningly good as the arrogant, lustful
prince. On the other hand, the earnestness of the transformed
prince was a little labored.
</P>
<P>
   He sang as a person with a future: a rich sound, even, unforced,
unstrained at its top, capable of an almost animal vocal intensity.
If carefully shepherded in the transition from the studio to the
real world, he could have a major career.
</P>
<P>
   Mezzo-soprano Joyce DiDonato, a studio graduate, equaled
Hendricks' challenge with ringing tone and great ease. The range of
her emotional expressiveness was somewhat constricted for a
character who turned to prostitution after the prince's rape, only
to be reawakened to true charity during the march.
</P>
<P>
   Among the many other singers and their multiple roles, Judith
Christin was humorously playful as Princess Sofia Korchagin. As
Peter Simonson, tenor Raymond Very, an opera studio alumnus, was
strongly impassioned as he implored Dimitry for Maslova's hand.
Mezzo-soprano Katherine Ciesinski was regally icy as Dmitry's aunt
Sofia Ivanovna.
</P>
<P>
   Summers, conducting his second opera as HGO's music director,
was at ease with the rhythmically complex score. (He did have to
restart the piece a few moments into the performance when a dimmer
switch failed to function, a company representative said.)
</P>
<P>
   The Houston Grand Opera Orchestra, which is replacing the
Houston Symphony as the opera's ensemble over several seasons,
played satisfactorily. A group with more experience playing
together and playing such complex music would have made the
complexities seem clearer. One of Summers' challenges is to create
such an orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's experience showed via deft touches and an easy fluidity
in the movement. The brutality during the march to Siberia was
particularly frightful.
</P>
<P>
   In the jury scene, however, he was hampered by the hulking
blocks of seats for judge, jury and prisoners (which moved away for
the flashbacks). They pushed the singers far enough back into the
rear and sides that only Hendricks, DiDonato and Dale Travis (the
court president) could be heard easily.
</P>
<P>
   The production itself was handsome but spare. When the curtain
went up for Act Two, the blinding whiteness of the Siberian winter
provoked instinctive applause. If only the entire work could have
engendered similar spontaneity at the end.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Charles Ward can receive electronic mail via the Internet.
Address comments to charles.wardchron.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2110EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
