<HEADER>
A2638 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-PRINCIPAL     04-25 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-PRINCIPAL-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COLUMBINE PRINCIPAL, A TIME OF FUNERALS, GUILT, HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to insert info about DeAngelis' family in 3rd-to-last graf.
Inserts ``on Saturday'' in 5th graf.) (mk) 
 By SARA RIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Four days before the shootings, the principal
of Columbine High School, Frank DeAngelis, told his students at an
emotional pep rally in the gym that he did not want to bury another
young person. With the prom set for the next night, Saturday, he
implored them not to drink, or drink and drive, or put themselves
at risk in any way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to attend another memorial service,'' he had
said, recalling students who had died in car accidents, including a
baseball player he had coached and two girlfriends of his teen-age
daughter. ``I do not want to put up another memorial plaque.''
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis said he told them, ``I want to see all your smiling
faces here on Monday morning.''
</P>
<P>
   And on Monday morning, after a weekend in which not so much as a
fender bender was reported, the principal said, ``One of the
students came up to me and said, `I think all our smiling faces are
here.' ''
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis was talking by telephone from his home on Saturday,
only hours after he had attended one funeral, and two days before
he would attend four more. All were for victims of the shootings at
Columbine on Tuesday that left a teacher _ DeAngelis' close friend
William David Sanders _ and 14 students, including the two teen-age
suspects, dead.
</P>
<P>
   In the days since the shootings, the visible presence of the
police investigation has taken center stage, with briefings by law
enforcement officials and news conferences with the governor, the
district attorney and the superintendent of Jefferson County
Schools.
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis, 44, has been meeting with his faculty and students,
paying his respects to the families of the victims and, in the few
private moments he has had, anguishing over the young people, and
the friend, he has lost.
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis said that he had asked two aides to handle the press.
``My first priority is my faculty and kids,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Like everyone else, DeAngelis has no explanation for the actions
of the two suspects, Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold. ``I'm still
baffled by it all,'' he said. ``I cannot explain what went wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   But unlike everyone else, DeAngelis was in charge. Columbine was
his school. He had started there as a social studies teacher in
1979, and worked his way up, first to dean of students, then to
assistant principal and, in 1996, to principal.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold were his students. ``I knew them
by name and by face,'' he said, but he could not remember any
dealings with them.
</P>
<P>
   After shepherding a group of students to safety outside the
school amid the gunfire on Tuesday, and then maintaining a vigil
into the night for those trapped inside when police would not let
him re-enter, DeAngelis faced his faculty the next morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I apologized,'' he said. ``I stated, `I'm so sorry for what
you are experiencing, for what you went through with this tragedy.'
I told them, `Right now I'm feeling guilty. I've asked myself I
don't know how many times in the last several hours if there was
anything I could have done to prevent this.' I said, `I'm sure some
of you are feeling that too.' ''
</P>
<P>
   They cried together, he said. ``I told them how proud I was of
each and every one of them for putting their lives on the line for
our students.''
</P>
<P>
   From that meeting, one of his assistant principals drove
DeAngelis to a nearby church to address the community, parents and
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't sure what to expect,'' he went on. ``I was concerned
that I had let them down. Here I am the leader of this high school,
with over 1,900 kids, this fantastic community, a leader in our
school district, and I just felt that I had let everyone down, and
I wasn't sure if I was going to be accepted. I was worried that I
had disappointed people.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he was encouraged when two seniors, Kelly Beers and
Kelly Dickson, ran up and hugged him when he walked up and took his
place in the group of administrators on the stage. He awaited his
turn to speak. ``They announced, `Here's the principal of Columbine
high school,' and they gave me a standing ovation,'' DeAngelis
said. ``I just broke down.'' He was so overwhelmed, DeAngelis said,
that he turned his back to the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just overtaken by emotion. I got rejuvenated,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In his remarks, DeAngelis focused on the students. ``I told them
how proud I was of them,'' he said. ``I told them that I've been
proud of Columbine for 20 years, that I have never been prouder of
these students than I am now for what they have done. We've heard
stories of students stopping to help other students, of two
students administering first aid to one of my teachers.''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, DeAngelis recalled how on Tuesday morning he
had walked out of a meeting in the school, and into an eerily quiet
north hallway. Suddenly, his secretary, Susan White, came running
out of the office.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``She said there was a shooting downstairs in the cafeteria. I
said, `I don't believe it. Call 911.' ''
</P>
<P>
   His secretary ran back into the office, leaving DeAngelis alone
in the hallway. ``Then I noticed the gunman coming down the hall,
firing his weapon,'' he said. ``I said, `I'm dead, my time is up.'
''
</P>
<P>
   In that same moment, DeAngelis said, he heard voices and
laughter around the corner. He ran down the hallway and found a
group of about 20 girls, oblivious to what was happening, heading
from the locker room to gym class. DeAngelis said he herded the
girls into a locked storage room in the gym, assuring them that
they were safe and that he would be back to get them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went outside to try to see what was happening,'' DeAngelis
said. ``It was then that I saw fire alarms had gone off, kids
exiting the building, teachers helping kids out of the building.
</P>
<P>
   ``Several of us went back in to get the girls out of the storage
room. We got the girls outside to the park'' across the street, he
said. At that point police warned everyone to stay out of the
building, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It was only when he got to the park, the principal said, and
possible suspects were named, that he realized the awful
possibility: The gunman he had seen might be one of his own
students.
</P>
<P>
   DeAngelis said he waited outside for the next nine hours,
drawing maps of the school for the SWAT teams, sharing information
with police.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a point when a tank is moving down Pearce Street
with the SWAT team,'' he said. ``I just looked up and there were
helicopters hovering around and ambulances. I just thought to
myself, `This is only the beginning of this nightmare.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In the interview, DeAngelis sounded exhausted and
grief-stricken, but determinedly hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe there's such a strong foundation, it will
continue to be a great high school,'' DeAngelis said. ``There's
just a lot of loving and caring.''
</P>
<P>
   He had 12 funerals before him, the friends and families of the
dead to console, the wounded to visit in the hospital,
investigators' questions to try to answer. He has a school to lead,
even if, with Columbine closed indefinitely, he will be doing it
out of a neighboring high school. And he has a family of his own.
In addition to his 15-year-old daughter, Hayley, DeAngelis, a
native Coloradan, has a wife, Cheryl, and a son, Bryant, 24.
</P>
<P>
   His teachers will return on Tuesday, his students on Thursday.
Together, DeAngelis said, they will figure out how to finish the
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are times I've said, why were the 15 killed?'' the
principal said. ``Why? Life is so unfair. But I've also felt that
tough times make us tougher people, tough times challenge us, tough
times teach us how to get it done. Somehow I'm getting it done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2111EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 21:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-DIEHARD500-HNS &LR;      04-25 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-DIEHARD500-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TERRY BLOUNT  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Only four days shy of his 48th birthday, Dale
Earnhardt may be past his prime at most NASCAR tracks. But he's
still ``The Intimidator'' when it comes to restrictor-plate racing
at the two superspeedways.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earnhardt was the dominant driver for most of Sunday's DieHard
500, guiding his Goodwrench Monte Carlo to victory in front of more
than 175,000 spectators at the Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my kind of racetrack,'' Earnhardt said. ``The crew
needed this win, and it's a special win for (crew chief) Kevin
Hamlin.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the 72nd Winston Cup victory for Earnhardt, a
seven-time series champion. But it was the first for Hamlin, who
took over as Earnhardt's crew chief midway through last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' Hamlin said. ``Dale is absolutely the greatest at
restrictor-plate racing. He drove the heck out of that car today.
He is unreal.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt led the most laps, but he fell back to 16th after a
pit stop under a caution with 40 laps to go. He quickly moved up
and took the lead for good with 14 laps left in the 188-lap event,
holding off Dale Jarrett and Mark Martin at the end.
</P>
<P>
   ``You didn't know who would work with who all day out there,''
Earnhardt said. ``I moved up and was going to stay in second
(behind Jarrett) until the last lap or two, but they all started
jockeying around behind me, and I got an opportunity to go to the
front.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, Jarrett and Martin pulled away from the pack during
the last two laps, but Earnhardt finished .137 seconds ahead of
Jarrett (about half a car length) when Jarrett tried to go inside
to pass him at the line. Martin finished right behind Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the master at restrictor-plate racing,'' Martin said of
Earnhardt. ``He's the best I've ever come up against.''
</P>
<P>
   But Martin felt he could have made a run at Earnhardt if the
drivers behind him _ teammates Bobby Labonte (who finished fourth)
and Tony Stewart (who was fifth) _ would have stayed in line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question we were catching the leaders,'' Martin
said. ``It was shaping up to be extremely exciting at the end, but
I lost my pushers when Bobby and Tony got hung up side by side.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, too, thought he might have won had more than one car
been behind him to help push him in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``With only Mark behind me, I knew my chances were slim, because
Earnhardt is so tough at this place,'' Jarrett said. ``You have to
have some help, especially against Dale. I don't care to have him
in front of me or behind me.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett said he tried to slow down to put some distance between
his Quality Care Ford and Earnhardt so he would have a chance to
get enough suction from the draft to shoot past Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``But Dale's hard to pass because he knows where to put that 3
car in the draft,'' Jarrett said. ``I would pedal back (let off the
throttle) to maybe get a push from Mark, but Dale was smart enough
to pedal back to me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a record ninth career victory for Earnhardt in
restrictor-plate races, which were instituted in 1988 at Talladega
and Daytona to try to slow the cars by limiting air flow into the
carburetors.
</P>
<P>
   It also was a record 12th victory at Talladega for Earnhardt _
eight Cup races, three IROC wins (including Saturday) and one Busch
Grand National victory. But he also has had his low moments at
NASCAR's fastest track.
</P>
<P>
   He was burned on the face last year when his car caught fire
after crashing with Bill Elliott's in a multiple-car accident. And
the worst injury of Earnhardt's career came in 1996 on the 2.6-mile
tri-oval when he suffered a fractured sternum and scapula because
of a crash.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a love-hate situation for me here,'' Earnhardt said. ``I
like going fast and using the draft, but I've had two serious
crashes here that broke me up pretty good and burnt me up pretty
good.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday was the first victory for Earnhardt since his dramatic
win in the Daytona 500 to start the 1998 season. He was second to
Jeff Gordon at Daytona this year, but he has struggled everywhere
except the two restrictor-plate tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Daytona last year and Talladega on Sunday are the only two
victories for Earnhardt in the last 101 Winston Cup races.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think things are going to turn around for us now,'' he said.
``We have a brand new car going to California (next weekend). If it
doesn't run well, it will be the driver's fault.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt managed to avoid the one major accident of the day
when eight cars were involved in a crash on lap 49 after Mike
Skinner and Tony Stewart bumped on the backstretch.
</P>
<P>
   Gordon was one of the cars involved when he was T-boned by Rusty
Wallace. Gordon finished 38th, and Wallace finished 41st.
</P>
<P>
   The victory moved Earnhardt from 15th to a tie for ninth, with
teammate Skinner, in the points standings. Earnhardt still hopes to
pass Richard Petty and become the first driver to win eight Winston
Cup championships.
</P>
<P>
   ``Racing for the points is what this is all about,'' Earnhardt
said. ``We have a lot of things going on now that will make us
better everywhere. We still have time to climb back in this thing
and make a run at that eighth championship.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
