<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-MARLINS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Smoltz overpowers Marlins in 5-1 win
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Strange things have been happening at night around here,
but by daylight on Sunday, Part III of the Braves-Marlins series
looked much more like you'd expect.
</P>
<P>
   The best the Braves starting staff has to offer this young
season in John Smoltz was significantly better than the best the
Florida staff had to offer in Brian Meadows, who has three of the
Marlins' five wins.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz pitched Atlanta to a 5-1 win, earning his third victory
and helping the Braves take a 2-1 lead in the series.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish it would have been a night game,'' Marlins manager John
Boles said. ``So maybe then Smoltz would have gone and played golf
and maybe that would have thrown off his game. He overmatched us,
pure and simple. But he does that to a lot of people.''
</P>
<P>
   After the Tom Glavine loss and the fluky win by Greg Maddux,
Smoltz left little to chance as he plowed through the Marlins
order. He scattered six hits and two walks while striking out seven
to move to 3-0 in four starts this season.
</P>
<P>
   He held the Marlins to one run in 7 2/3 innings to beat them for
the sixth consecutive time dating back to June 29, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're a team I can go after with my fastball,'' he said.
``There's no, like, setting them up. It's not like facing guys
you've faced for seven or eight years, where you pick up
tendencies. These guys all are hungry to play baseball, just
waiting for mistakes and drilling them. You've just got to make
good pitches to get them out.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz made his longest outing of the season, pitching into the
eighth inning with 118 pitches, 81 of which were strikes, before he
was replaced by John Rocker after three consecutive hard-hit balls.
</P>
<P>
   ``Smoltz pitched like every other game he's pitched this year,''
Braves manager Bobby Cox said. ``Right on. He was good, really good
today.''
</P>
<P>
   As for coming back to Rocker _ who retired all four hitters he
faced _ in that situation, Cox said: ``I wanted to get him going
again. He struggled (Saturday night) a little bit. He threw the
ball fine today.'' Brian Jordan hit his sixth home run of the year
on the first pitch he saw from Meadows in the first inning with
Chipper Jones on base for a 2-0 lead. That was enough for Smoltz.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
