<HEADER>
A2645 &Cx1f; tad-z
u r &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEAD26-COX     04-25 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-LEAD26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Earnhardt captures 2nd win in 101 races
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ The question dogged Dale Earnhardt for more
than a year. Was the seven-time Winston Cup champion washed up, or
would he win again in NASCAR's highest series?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Earnhardt, only four days shy of his 48th birthday,
proved that he still has some intimidation left, holding off Dale
Jarrett and Mark Martin to win the DieHard 500 at Talladega
Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   It was only Earnhardt's second victory in his last 101 Winston
Cup starts, and his first since winning last year's Daytona 500,
snapping a 40-race winless streak.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt won for a record eighth time on this 2.66-mile,
high-banked oval, giving him nine wins in 46 starts at Daytona and
Talladega, where restrictor plates have been required since 1988 to
curb speeds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dale Earnhardt is the best,'' said car owner Richard
Childress. ``If anyone has given up on him, I think they've
probably lost their minds. (Sunday) probably answered a lot of
questions. A lot of people question him and his ability and what
he's got going on. I feel like he can still win anywhere for four
or five years, it just depends how long he wants to go on.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who never led a race this season before Talladega,
led 70 of 188 laps on Sunday, including the final 14. He climbed
six spots in points to ninth place, 315 behind leader Jeff Burton.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to work on the points, and racing for the points
championship is what it's all about,'' Earnhardt said. ``That's why
you're here. We've had a real poor year so far, but I think it's
going to turn around for us. If the guys make some mistakes, we can
still get up there and race them. The top-five finishes and the
wins are going to win championships.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett was second and moved to within 40 points of Burton, who
finished 11th. Martin was third, followed by Joe Gibbs Racing
teammates Bobby Labonte and rookie Tony Stewart, who finished in
the top five for the first time in his Cup career.
</P>
<P>
   Two-time defending Winston Cup champion Jeff Gordon suffered
another disappointing setback when he was involved in an eight-car
pileup during the 49th lap. He finished 38th and endured his third
DNF in nine races this season, the most since he had five in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having one of those years that everybody has been
waiting for,'' Gordon said. ``It's not because we're not running
good. We're running really good. We're just not having the good
fortune that we've been having and that's what it takes to win a
championship and be consistent. ``
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who started 17th, led 56 of the first 150 laps. But
it seemed he wouldn't be a factor after the final pit stops during
lap 135. Earnhardt complained of mechanical problems on the left
side of his car. His crew also changed four tires, allowing several
drivers to beat him off pit road.
</P>
<P>
   ``We took a little extra time,'' Earnhardt said. ``Everything
looked good, so we came out a little further back than we wanted
to, but we had the race car to come back to the front.''
</P>
<P>
   John Andretti was one of several drivers who took only two
tires, enabling him to move from seventh to first after the pit
stop. Andretti led 13 laps laps, before Earnhardt rallied from the
middle of the pack to grab his sixth lead. Michael Waltrip took the
lead only three laps later, but lost it when he fell out of line
and the critical draft.
</P>
<P>
   Labonte and Jarrett combined to lead 23 of the final 37 laps,
but Earnhardt clearly had the faster car down the stretch.
Earnhardt passed Jarrett for the final time on the backstetch of
lap 175, and Jarrett couldn't get enough drafting help from Martin
to mount a serious challenge the rest of the race.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jarrett) kept jockeying around and jumped out of line and
jumped in line,'' Earnhardt said. ``Finally, I got the opportunity
to go to the front. I didn't know if it was the right thing to do.
I was going to settle in there with Jarrett, but they kept racing
behind me and I figured maybe I'd like to be in front and maybe
they'd get to racing each other and help me win.''
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt and Jarrett pulled away from a pack of cars, but
Martin eventually caught Jarrett's bumper. When Labonte and Stewart
fell out of line, Martin says he knew he couldn't muster enough
power to push Jarrett past Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was shaping up to be extremely exciting there at the end,
but I lost my pushers and wasn't able to help Dale any by myself at
the end,'' Martin said. ``We would have been able to (pass
Earnhardt) if I wouldn't have lost my partners.''
</P>
<P>
   Martin said help from the two Pontiacs might not have been
enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Earnhardt's) sort of the master at restrictor-plate racing,''
he said. ``He's the best I've ever come up against.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
