<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-NASCAR-NOTES26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McReynolds puts blame on Skinner
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLADEGA, Ala. _ Larry McReynolds, crew chief for Mike Skinner
and the No. 31 Chevrolet, said he was upset at his driver for
causing an eight-car pileup only 49 laps into Sunday's DieHard 500
at Talladega Superspeedway.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds took out his frustration on a tow-truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   When Skinner tried to push rookie Tony Stewart's No. 20 Pontiac
into the grass on the backstretch of the 2.66-mile oval, the cars
made contact. The bump sent Skinner's car sideways across the
infield grass, before it caromed back on the track, collecting the
cars of Jeff Gordon and Rusty Wallace.
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds says his driver made the mistake.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll walk off the side of a mountain for the driver I work
for,'' McReynolds said, shortly after the accident. ``But I'll also
put him in his place when he's wrong. He's like the kid that's in
trouble. He better hope this race lasts a long time, because I'm
gonna get him when it's over with.''
</P>
<P>
   McReynolds got to a tow-truck driver first. When the truck
pulled into Skinner's pit stall to tow the car to the garage area
for repairs, the driver jumped on Skinner's car. McReynolds angrily
pulled him off and pushed him away.
</P>
<P>
   When Skinner returned to the race 29 laps later, he received a
two-lap penalty from NASCAR officials for ``abuse of a tow-truck
driver,'' according to team owner Richard Childress.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just trying to get us (to the garage) quick,'' Skinner
said. ``He was just trying to help. He didn't do anything on
purpose. He was excited and stopping and going, and he tore the
nose of the car off worse than it already was. It wasn't his fault.
The guy jumped on the nose of the car and upset some of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   What about teamwork?
</P>
<P>
   Shortly after the finish of Sunday's race, John Andretti
screamed at fellow Pontiac driver Stewart for leaving him out to
dry late in the race. When Andretti made a move to challenge the
leaders with less than five laps left, Stewart didn't follow him,
instead hooking up with Ford driver Mark Martin for drafting help.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart finished fifth for his first career top-five, while
Andretti slipped to ninth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a lot of fun, other than John Andretti coming over
yelling at me and asking me what make of car I drive,'' Stewart
said. ``The last time I checked it was a Pontiac. The last time I
checked, Pontiac didn't pay me to run behind their drivers,
either.''
</P>
<P>
   Burton bounces back
</P>
<P>
   Winston Cup points leader Jeff Burton was 11th, finishing
outside the top 10 for only the second time this season. But Burton
knows it could have been much worse.
</P>
<P>
   In the pace laps before the start of Sunday's race, Burton's No.
99 Ford started smoking badly. Burton, who qualified third, pulled
onto pit road to check the problem, so he was bumped to 43rd to
start after the unscheduled pit stop.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, crew chief Frankie Stoddard told his crew to
``round up some spare parts.'' The car continued to smoke, but
somehow lasted 188 laps. NASCAR officials inspected the car after
the race to determine what was causing the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
