<HEADLINE>
 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 
The Arizona Republic plans to move the following stories for use by
clients of the NYTimes News Service for Monday, April 26. If you
have any questions, please call the Republic News Desk at (602)
444-8286.
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
CANTTEST (UNDATED) It's an increasingly popular excuse among
today's AIMS-anxious. At the mere mention of the looming state
graduation test, students shriek, ``But I'm a bad test taker!''
Symptoms include blurred vision, stomach pains, sometimes loss of
sleep and bad dreams, and, of course, a bad test grade. And today,
when high school sophomores take the first of the controversial
AIMS tests, some of these symptoms will reach their peaks. BY
MELISSA JONES. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
TESTPREP (UNDATED) The ink is barely dry on the AIMS forms.
Students who take the test this year are exempt from having to pass
it to graduate. Yet the phone has been ringing for weeks at the
Sylvan Learning Center in the Ahwatukee Foothills. `Parents are
calling and saying, `The AIMS is coming up . . . do you have
something that will help my kid pass the math?' '' said Pat
Cunningham, director of the private tutoring firm in southeast
Phoenix. By CATHRYN CRENO. STORY WIll move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
COPSHOOT (PHOENIX) The post-prom party broke up when police knocked
on the hotel room door, but as one student tried to scramble out
the window to avoid being caught past curfew with beer, an
officer's bullet struck his head. Justin Franco, 18, a junior at
Barry Goldwater High School, is miraculously expected to recover
fully from the wound _ the bullet entered his cheek and lodged near
his spinal cord, his father said Sunday. By RICHARD RUELAS. Story
will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
BWAY (NEW YORK) David Ira Goldstein is putting on weight. Not
physically. The artistic director of Arizona Theatre Company is
swelling with pride as he stands in front of the Longacre Theatre,
a landmark of Manhattan's theater district since 1913. On the
stucco wall in front of him is a poster for The Gershwins'
Fascinating Rhythm. Its flashy graphics haven't caught Goldstein's
eye. He's wrapped up in the fine print. One incomplete sentence in
particular has set his pulse racing: ``Subsequent development
production at Arizona Theatre Company.'' It's the first time the
theater company's name has appeared on a Broadway poster. Every
troupe dreams of transferring a show from its stage to New York,
the center of the theater world. Goldstein's company has done it.
By KYLE LAWSON. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
QUAYLE (WASHINGTON) Former Vice President Dan Quayle drew heavily
from his Indiana roots, including the business community, to raise
funds for his 2000 White House bid, according to a list of his
contributors. The list, filed last week with the Federal Election
Commission, shows the former GOP senator from Indiana receiving
abundant support from those who know him best. The list of 35,251
contributors is dotted with numerous Indiana residents. Retirees
and executives are especially well represented; there is also a
sprinkling of contributions from ministers and others with stated
religious affiliations. By JEFF BARKER. Story will move in the A
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
ICEHOUSE (PHOENIX) When Maricopa County planners look along West
Jackson Street, they see a desolate corner of downtown that could
be improved by a new 10-story jail, parking garage and morgue. But
artists and historic preservationists see warehouses ripe for
renovation into shops, galleries, lofts and cafes. The two visions
collide at Jackson Street and Fourth Avenue in downtown Phoenix. By
Peter CORBETT. Story will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAMPUS (PHOENIX) A group of Phoenix players _ people with clout and
access to plenty of money _ is proposing a new, four-acre, downtown
campus to house a shelter and services for homeless people. These
services now work out of crumbling buildings, mostly along Madison
Street, where the new campus would be built between 12th and 13th
avenues. The proposed site is a mostly empty, city-owned lot except
for an emergency shelter still operated by Central Arizona Shelter
Services 14 years after it was officially designated `'temporary.''
It remains the largest emergency shelter in the Valley. Members of
the Phoenix Community Alliance board, which is chaired by Jerry
Colangelo, were once set on moving the shelter and surrounding
services, such as the St. Vincent de Paul Society dining hall, the
homeless post office and medical clinic. By PAT KOSSAN. Story will
move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
CAMPUSSIDE (Phoenix) Members of the Phoenix Community Alliance were
looking for a humane solution to the problem posed by homeless
people who stood in the way of their latest redevelopment project.
As part of their research, some members visited San Diego's St.
Vincent de Paul Village. The Village is run by a private,
non-profit organization, no longer connected with the St. Vincent
de Paul Society, the familiar charitable arm of the Catholic
Church, spokesman Brian Hom said. Hom describes the Village as a
one-stop campus of homeless services with eight separate centers
covering two square city blocks. Phoenix Community Alliance members
came back convinced a smaller version could work in Phoenix. By PAT
KOSSAN. STORY will move in the A category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
RAGE (undated) Robert Zabriskic, who's been driving _ and surviving
_ in the Valley since before the freeways, adheres to a simple
credo whenever he gets behind the wheel. ``You have to operate
under the assumption everyone on the road is a total idiot,'' the
north Phoenix resident said. It's Zabriskic's way of dealing with
aggressive driving, a phenomenon that quickly can ratchet up to
road rage, something police believe led to the fatal shooting April
17 of a Phoenix youth. By BOB PETRIE. Story will move in the A
category. &QL; 
 &QL; 
VIGIL (PHOENIX) Live coverage of a Mothers of Murdered Children
vigil tonight in Phoenix. By LAURA TRUJILLO. Story will move in the
A category. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
