<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 21:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2655 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-FLOWERS26-COX     04-25 0401
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-FLOWERS26-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Flowers serve as lovely, living memorial
 &HT;    Rachel Sauer
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ The first person in line had daisies, a great
white bunch of them that grew gradually smaller as each person
passing by took one or several.
</P>
<P>
   The next person had snapdragons, an armful of red and purple
blooms that loked saucy and vibrant against a backdrop of dark
winter clothes, a hovering layer of clouds and immeasurable
sadness.
</P>
<P>
   On down the line, people entering the memorial service for the
12 students and one teacher slain at Columbine High School on
Tuesday gathered one flower, then two, then four, until tens of
thousands of people carried vivid bouquets of life affirmation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think having these flowers is so important to helping people
heal,'' said Bic Nguyen, owner of Jade's Floral in Littleton, as
she handed out individual lilies. ``They're beautiful and alive and
help people think about the families and friends who are still
living.''
</P>
<P>
   The Santa Barbara (Calif.) Flower Growers' Association donated
20,000 individual flower stems for the memorial service and the
Colorado Flower Growers' Association donated 5,000 more, so the
first ones who got to Sunday's memorial service walked through a
canopy of flowers as they entered the parking lot at Mann Theaters,
where the service was held.
</P>
<P>
   Dozens of volunteers handed out the flowers, often giving
comforting words to those already crying.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just an incredibly sad situation,'' said Sherie
Johnson, owner of Cobblestone Gardens in Littleton, as she handed
out white carnations. ``These flowers give people joy.''
</P>
<P>
   As people wandered closer to the theater, they often clutched
flowers in one hand and the hand of a loved one in the other. The
flowers were a connection to life, a reminder of growth and
rebirth.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, many people raised their bouquets over their
heads, perhaps to show the fuchsia and yellow and purple blooms
that beauty can conquer ugliness.
</P>
<P>
   And when the service was over, thousands walked down Bowles
Avenue to the memorials in Clement Park and laid their flowers next
the ones already there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think,'' said Justin Rousselot, 18, who helped hand out
flowers, ``that people need to remember that life can be
beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2124EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0188 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 21:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2657 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WARNINGS-     04-25 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-WARNINGS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEEN-AGE SUSPECTS SIGNALED VIOLENCE TO COME
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: 2nd take is expected to move by 9:45 p.m., ET) 
(ATTN: Mich.)  (nk) 
 By DIRK JOHNSON and JODI WILGOREN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Something in Dylan Klebold's voice had
spooked his mother that morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``The goodbye had an edge to it,'' the mother, Susan Klebold,
told a family pastor, describing her son's tone last Tuesday
morning as ``almost fatalistic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``She thought, maybe he's in a bad mood,'' the Rev. Don
Marxhausen said. ``Maybe he's got a test today or something.''
</P>
<P>
   Later that morning, Klebold, 17, and his best friend, Eric
Harris, 18, ambushed their classmates and teachers at Columbine
High School with a storm of gunfire and pipebombs, taking 13 lives
before fatally shooting themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Dylan's father, Thomas Klebold, 52, a former geophysicist who
runs a mortgage business from his house, told the pastor he had
detected ``this slight tension'' in his son a few days before the
attack. Klebold made a mental note of it and thought he would get
back to it, the pastor said.
</P>
<P>
   These were not the only possible signs of the violence to come.
As new details of the young men's behavior comes to light, a
portrait is emerging of their friendship and of their relationship
with their families. It is a portrait littered with contradictions.
</P>
<P>
   Many students in the school have described the young men as
being obsessed with Nazi history, and the police now say that the
suspects planned the attack for Adolf Hitler's birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold is the great-grandson of a prominent Jewish
philanthropist. His father is Lutheran, and for a time the family
attended a church. At Passover this year, the Klebolds had a seder,
Marxhausen said, and Dylan asked the traditional four questions at
the table.
</P>
<P>
   Acquaintances of the suspects have said that they detested
athletes because of the way they were treated by them. But Klebold
participated in a baseball fantasy league.
</P>
<P>
   A fan of the Boston Red Sox, he was one of a dozen students who
took part in a fantasy baseball draft party recently, said one of
the participants, who did not want to be identified. In an apparent
display of his penchant for slurs, Klebold called his team the
Border Hoppers, and chose the Taco Bell logo as his team symbol.
</P>
<P>
   They affected the trappings of Goth culture, wearing black
clothing, spouting German phrases, and listening to German
techno-pop. But they were also good students and like hundreds of
other Columbine youths, held after-school jobs.
</P>
<P>
   While Klebold, 6-foot-4 and lanky, was often outgoing, Harris
was much quieter. Other students say Harris often scowled in return
to a greeting.
</P>
<P>
   A former teammate of Harris' in youth baseball in Plattsburgh,
N.Y., said that young Eric had lacked self-confidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He didn't really like baseball a lot, but said that his dad
pushed him to play Little League because every kid in Plattsburgh
played it,'' said the former teammate, Brendon LaPier. ``He was the
kind of kid who didn't mind being alone and he spent a lot of time
in the dugout.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harris family also lived for a time in Oscada, Mich. The
Rev. William Stone, a neighbor there, said he recalled Harris
putting up a basketball backboard in the driveway and playing ball
with Eric and his brother, Kevin, who is two years older. Kevin
would go on to play football for the Rebels of Columbine High. He
was seen as popular, ``just the kind of guy his brother was gunning
for,'' said Steve Berg, a classmate of Eric Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said that the Harris family ``cared for each other,'' and
that the parents ``seemed to enjoy their children.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   In Littleton, Harris lived in a new two-story house at the end
of a cul-de-sac. The Klebold home was much grander, a sleek
glass-and-cedar house that backed up to the spectacular redstone of
Dear Creek Canyon. The Klebolds also had a carriage house that they
rented out.
</P>
<P>
   The parents of both boys, described by friends as decent and
caring people from stable homes, have issued statements of sympathy
over the attack. But the authorities have come to the conclusion
that the parents should have had some idea of what was going on
inside their homes.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson County Sheriff John Stone said on Saturday that the
sawed-off barrel of a shotgun and bomb-making materials were
``clearly visible'' in the bedroom of one of the gunmen.
</P>
<P>
   The sheriff said the weapons were in places where stuffed
animals might be found in the bedrooms of other teen-agers. ``The
parents should have known,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Marxhausen, one of the clergymen who conducted a private funeral
service for Klebold on Saturday, said the young man's father told
him he ``felt Dylan was his soulmate, and felt that he knew what
was going on all the time.'' The pastor said the elder Klebold had
told him, `` `I thought I was ready to let him go _ he was a
finished product.'''
</P>
<P>
   The day before the shootings, Mrs. Klebold sent off a deposit
for their son's dormitory room at the University of Arizona, where
they believed he had planned to enroll in the fall.
</P>
<P>
   But the diary found by the police shows that the two young men
expected to die in the attack they had been plotting for a year, an
act of revenge on the popular crowd they blamed for making them
feel like outcasts.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the young people who knew Klebold and Harris were
shocked at the shootings. Some friends, however, say they had heard
Klebold and Harris make comments about blowing up the school.
</P>
<P>
   And the two young men, members of a disaffected clique known as
the trench coat mafia, produced a video in school that simulates an
armed attack on athletes. They had a well-known fascination for
death, gore, and Nazis.
</P>
<P>
   Harris even maintained a Web site that advertised his
machinations of murder.
</P>
<P>
   ``You start to wonder, how could people not have known what was
happening?'' said Debbie Wilder, 38, who lives a few doors from the
Harrises.
</P>
<P>
   On the weekend before the shootings, neighbors said the two
young men had made such a ruckus smashing glass in the Harris
garage _ making shrapnel for bombs, residents now suspect _ that
the noise disturbed children playing in the nearby cul-de-sac.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd like to think you'd be aware that kids are building
bombs in your house,'' Mrs. Wilder said.
</P>
<P>
   On his Web site, Harris posted violent threats. He had also
mused about killing large numbers of people in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the law, if you don't like it, you die,'' he had written.
``If I don't like you or I don't like what you want me to do, you
die.''
</P>
<P>
   Randy Brown, who said his son, Brooks, a fellow student, had
been threatened by Harris with menacing messages on the Internet,
says he took a 14-page printout of the rantings to the police. The
sheriff's department acknowledged receiving a report about Harris'
writings, but said that no action was taken.
</P>
<P>
   Harris and Klebold had a fondness for role-playing games and the
violent computer games Doom and Quake. They listened to the
sado-masochistic tinged music of German techno-rock. They were
arrested last year for breaking into a car to steal tools, and were
placed in a diversion program for juveniles, where they earned high
marks in an evaluation for being bright and cooperative.
</P>
<P>
   They were also good students who held jobs and caused no grief
to school officials.
</P>
<P>
   Christopher Lau, who owns Blackjack Pizza, where the two young
men worked three to five nights a week, said they always showed up
on time and worked hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's looking for answers and looking for answers,'' Lau
said. ``There's no clear answers. It's going to haunt us _ it's
going to haunt me for the rest of my life.''
</P>
<P>
   Joe Valentine, who runs a computer store in Littleton, said
Klebold had applied for a job, sending a resume that claimed he
``built my personal computer and helped build those of friends and
family.'' He said he offered the young man a job _ ``He has all the
right stuff to be a technician'' _ but that Klebold failed to show
up on his first day.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Stair, who was a member of the trench coat mafia before
graduating from high school last year, said he chatted with Klebold
and Harris last fall in a car outside the school, as they smoked
cigarettes during lunch period.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were talking about being hassled by the jocks,'' Stair
said, saying that athletes in the school often picked on Klebold
and Harris, among other students deemed unpopular.
</P>
<P>
   A photograph of the Class of '99 at Columbine High School
appears to be a striking example of the marginalized status of
these two young men. In a sea of mostly smiling faces, Klebold and
Harris, heads bent and eyes a bit downcast, are as far toward a
corner as they can be _ quite literally on the fringes of the
crowd.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2135EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0190 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 21:37 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2664 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLA     04-25 0494
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKENOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS IN MUST-WIN BATTLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Out of psychological necessity as much as anything,
the Lakers have dismissed the importance of wins and losses in
favor of accentuating simple progress. But now comes the brutal
reality. Tonight's game against the Rockets is an indisputable
must-win.
</P>
<P>
   For the hope of home-court comfort in the playoffs. For what's
left of their confidence. For their sanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you what, we need every win, man,'' Derek Harper
said. ``It's not one particular win. We need a win, period. You
start losing, it snatches the air out of you. Winning sort of fills
you up a little bit, makes you feel better about your team and
yourself. You gain confidence from winning.''
</P>
<P>
   If nothing else, the Lakers need to reassert their ability to
beat quality opponents. Losers of five of their last seven, the
Lakers have beaten just two teams with winning records in the last
five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   But this game has much more at stake. The Rockets and Lakers are
almost assured of meeting in the first round of the playoffs as the
fourth and fifth seeds in the West, and Houston has a tenuous hold
on the higher seed.
</P>
<P>
   A win, and the Lakers put themselves in control of home-court
advantage. A loss would be their third straight, and that streak
could easily reach five with games against Portland and Seattle
coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to go in there and play well,'' Shaquille O'Neal said.
``We match up pretty well with those guys. We're a similar team.''
</P>
<P>
   More similar than either would care to admit. As are the Lakers,
the Rockets are a mess. They've lost three straight, including
losses to two of the league's worst teams _ Dallas and the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   These are two desperate teams meeting in a playoff prelude with
playoff implications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very big. I don't think we can really understate how
important this game is,'' Derek Fisher said.
</P>
<P>
   But a must-win? He wouldn't go that far, at least not out loud.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not really all about wins and losses at this point,''
Fisher said. ``We've pretty much solidified a fourth or fifth
(seeding). It's about how we're playing.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is, horribly. And with just five games left to reverse the
trend.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to find ourselves as a basketball team,'' Harper
said. ``I don't think the cohesiveness is where it needs to be for
us to be successful. Say what you want, you don't have to sleep
with each other, go to bed with each other, but you need to be tied
together as a group. So where it is, I'm not sure. All of that
aside, we've got to find a way to get things turned around, find a
way to get back on track and win some games.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Ouch report: Reserve swingman Ruben Patterson skipped
Sunday's practice because of an upset stomach and possible flu
symptoms. His status for tonight's game is uncertain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2137EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0191 </DOCNO>
