<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2678 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-COLO-SCHOOL-RDP-ART-8     04-25 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COLO-SCHOOL-RDP-ART-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEARLY DOUBLE THE POPULATION OF LITTLETON MOURNS VICTIMS AT
MEMORIAL SERVICE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: In 5th grad corrects figure to 70,000) 
(ATTN: Calif.) (ART ADV: Photos are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
212-556-4204.) 
(rk) 
 By JAMES BROOKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Jonathan Cohen, a slender 17-year-old lost in
an oversized sweatshirt, stood Sunday before a sea of silent faces,
closed his eyes, and sang in a clear tenor, ``Do you still hear
raging guns, ending dreams of precious ones?''
</P>
<P>
   In this community torn by violence, many students who heard
Jonathan at the memorial service for the victims of the Columbine
High School shootings knew that he wrote the words from the heart.
</P>
<P>
   Last Tuesday, Jonathan, a junior, was trapped in the school
choir room when the shooting started. His older brother, Stephen,
who accompanied him Sunday on the guitar, had been in the
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine, rose blood red, heartbreak overflows my head,''
Jonathan sang to the still audience. ``Columbine, friend of mine,
peace will come to you in time.''
</P>
<P>
   As clouds and a cold rain shrouded the nearby Rocky Mountains,
the outdoor memorial service drew 70,000 _ nearly double the
population of the suburban neighborhood served by the high school.
</P>
<P>
   ``To the families of all those who died here, I say: You are not
alone,'' Vice President Al Gore said from a makeshift stage erected
in a movie theater parking lot. ``May you feel the embrace of
literally hundreds of millions who weep with you.''
</P>
<P>
   On a Sunday when religious leaders across the nation tried to
find meaning in a massacre that left 15 people dead, including the
two gunmen, many speakers at the service here cited the example of
Cassie Bernall, a 17-year-old junior. Asked by one of the gunmen if
she believed in God, she answered, ``Yes'' and was shot to death.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Franklin Graham, citing her final words, compared her
death to the suffering he had seen among Kosovo refugees on a
recent visit to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The forces of hatred and violence must not be allowed to
gain,'' exclaimed the son of the Rev. Billy Graham.
</P>
<P>
   Although bagpipes played, a religious singer played the trumpet,
and four F-16s scraped overhead in a ``missing-man formation'', the
most remarkable aspect of the huge gathering was the silence. With
ribbons on their lapels in the school colors, blue and white,
mourners wiped tears and bowed heads, holding hands or simply
embracing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it really puts any peace to it, because it's
still so fresh,'' said Taylor Brown, a 19-year-old who graduated
from Columbine last year. ``I'm still in shock.''
</P>
<P>
   Many clutched flowers, lilies or purple and white sprays, some
of 25,000 flowers donated by Colorado and California flower
growers. When the Cohen brothers opened the service with a simple
``Hi,'' mourners spontaneously released blue and white balloons
they had been holding. One hour into the service, when a light rain
began to fall, people quietly popped open umbrellas.
</P>
<P>
   At the end, as Gov. Bill Owens read the roll call of victims, he
released a white dove into the air for each of the victims. For a
few moments, the doves wheeled overhead, then flew away. Columbine,
Colorado's state flower, derives its name from a Latin word meaning
``like a dove.''
</P>
<P>
   Owens read only 13 names, omitting those of the two dead gunmen,
Eric Harris and Dylan Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, they took far too many precious lives,'' the governor
told the somber crowd. ``But they failed in their goal to kill
hundreds more, and to burn the school to the ground. Behind you
stands the charred remains of Columbine High School. This community
will not be beaten.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night at the park across from the school that has
been filled with makeshift memorials, a man brought a sign reading,
``We miss you Eric and Dylan.'' Someone seized the sign from him
and burned it on the spot.
</P>
<P>
   ``The young killers of Columbine High School do not stand for
the spirit of America,'' Gore said Sunday in a rare reference to
the gunmen. ``America is a good and decent place, and our goodness
is a light to all the nations of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   Several political leaders, including retired Gen. Colin Powell
and most of Colorado's congressional delegation, were on the stage
but did not speak. Those politicians who spoke urged Americans to
spend more time with their children and to purge popular culture of
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No more raising of children who do not value human life,''
appealed Owens, a Republican. ``No more children forced to grow up
in a culture of death and destruction.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, a Democrat, sounded a similar note, urging as he
gesticulated with his right forefinger, ``All of us must change our
lives to honor these children.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you are a parent, they need your attention, if you are a
grandparent, they need your time,'' he said. ``We must teach them
right from wrong. We must teach them about violence in popular
culture.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Saturday, President Clinton appealed to parents, the media,
and the entertainment industry to ``pledge ourselves to the task of
putting an end to the culture of violence.''
</P>
<P>
   Parents, Clinton said in his weekly radio address, ``should turn
off the television, pay attention to what's on the computer screen,
refuse to buy products that glorify violence.''
</P>
<P>
   To entertainment industry workers, he said, ``I ask you to make
every video game and movie as if your own children were watching
it.''
</P>
<P>
   Sunday, the Roman Catholic archbishop of Denver, Charles Chaput,
led the gathering in prayer, asking God to ``help us to turn away
from violence and selfishness.''
</P>
<P>
   A few hours after the memorial service, funerals were held for
two slain students, Kelly Fleming and Daniel Mauser. The funerals
were at the St. Francis Cabrini Roman Catholic Church, across the
street from the house of Eric Harris.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 23 wounded in the high school attack, 11 remained
hospitalized Sunday. Of the injured, one was in critical condition,
six in serious condition and four in fair condition.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, the day of the last scheduled funeral, Columbine
students are to return to school, attending classes at Chatfield
High School, a few miles south of here.
</P>
<P>
   Police investigators, who have already catalogued 2,000 pieces
of evidence, do not expect to release the crime scene until early
May.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
