<HEADER>
A2681 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-BLOCKADE-1STLD     04-25 1197
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-BLOCKADE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-730&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ENFORCEMENT OF OIL BLOCKADE PRESENTS POLITICAL, DIPLOMATIC RISKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS 2nd graf to change 1995 to 1996; 6th graf to describe how
embargo would increase tensions between Serbia and Montenegro.) (js) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The mechanics of imposing an oil embargo against
Yugoslavia enforced by NATO warships plying the Adriatic Sea should
be fairly simple, military officials said Sunday. The legal,
political and diplomatic risks are far greater, particularly with
Russia, which has furiously denounced the plan and thus raised the
specter of clashes at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Between 1992 and 1996, allied warships enforced such a ban on
arms to all six republics of the old Yugoslavia in the same
Adriatic waters. Some 6,000 ships were boarded and inspected, and
only six were caught trying to smuggle weapons. Arms shipments
overland still found their way into the hands of the warring
factions _ as did oil shipments to Serbia and Montenegro, despite
comprehensive U.N. sanctions that virtually barred all foreign
trade with the oil-starved republics.
</P>
<P>
   But the ban on oil shipments to Yugoslavia that NATO has now
authorized is trickier to enforce. And stopping oil tankers from
countries not party to the agreement, like Russia, is an expansion
of the month-long war with Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   NATO Secretary-General Javier Solana on Sunday sought to dismiss
the Russian threats of war with a verbal wave: ``The Russians,
every now and then, they make phrases which go a little bit beyond
where they should go.''
</P>
<P>
   Just as forcefully, Solana said on the ABC news program ``This
Week'' that Gen. Wesley K. Clark, NATO's military commander, was
writing a draft plan that considers ``all the possibilities so that
the embargo can be guaranteed not only by NATO and NATO-friendly
countries, but also for others. If it's an embargo, it will apply
to everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   The goal of the embargo is dry up the flow of oil into ports on
the coast of Montenegro, the small republic which supplies its far
larger partner in Yugoslavia, Serbia. The blockade could further
undermine the democratic government in Montenegro by introducing
more tensions into its relations with Serbia. NATO has also ordered
heavier air strikes against overland roads, pipelines and railroads
that carry the fuel to Serbia. ``Without oil, the Yugoslav military
machine will come to a halt and very quickly,'' said NATO spokesman
Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, NATO officials say that with Serbia's two main
refineries knocked out of operation, Yugoslav military officials
are so desperate for fuel that they are siphoning fuel out of the
abandoned cars belonging to refugees, and using it for tanks and
other vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   American intelligence analysts estimate that Montenegrin ports
have unloaded 40,000 to 45,000 metric tons, or about 300,000
barrels, of oil in the past month, undercutting the air campaign's
goal to dry up Belgrade's ability to resupply the 40,000 Yugoslav
troops in Kosovo who are expelling ethnic Albanians and destroying
their villages.
</P>
<P>
   France and Italy, in particular, have raised questions about the
legal justification for mounting a blockade against third-party
countries, as distinct from an embargo restricting only shipments
from cooperating nations. Solana's scenario would cover countries
that do not belong to NATO or the European Union, such as Russia or
Ukraine, whose tankers have unloaded oil in Montenegrin ports since
the air war started on March 24.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we make the choice of a blockade, then we have to recognize
we risk war with a third party who hasn't agreed to the blockade,''
said one French diplomat. ``For that you need a U.N. mandate.''
</P>
<P>
   Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema explained to Italian
journalists Sunday that the embargo by NATO and European Union
countries can be carried out with on-board searches and
inspections. But a blockade, as such, does not exist, he said.
</P>
<P>
   And Norway's foreign minister, Knut Vollebaek, said in an
interview, ``As for third parties, we would like to see a U.N.
Security Council resolution in order to make this binding.''
</P>
<P>
   But a senior Pentagon official said that while there may not be
a specific Security Council resolution authorizing the ban, ``the
laws of armed conflict'' justify such an embargo.
</P>
<P>
   Shea acknowledges that ``there would have to be a political
discussion as to who is covered by such a regime.'' And Solana, in
his closing briefing Sunday, made light of objections to the
embargo, asserting that all 19 members would be in agreement on
Clark's draft plan. The North Atlantic Council, NATO's political
arm, is expected to review that plan this week, military officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   As outlined now, American and other NATO officials said, the
embargo would not try to exclude all ships from Yugoslav ports.
Instead, NATO would create a kind of seaborne police force to check
manifests and board selected ships to investigate cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Ships caught carrying contraband oil would be turned back or
diverted to other ports, but NATO military officials said the legal
consequences of interdictions have not been worked out. ``There are
some legal questions that have to be answered,'' the Dutch defense
minister, Frank de Grave, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   Other military experts said the issue could be rendered moot
simply by the stated purpose of the naval armada. ``The very
presence of NATO ships would be a deterrent, and would induce ships
to go back,'' Sen. John W. Warner, R-Va., who heads the Armed
Services Committee, said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot tell our pilots to fly high-risk missions against
petroleum storage facilities in Yugoslavia, and then let this other
oil creep in through the back door,'' said Warner, a former
secretary of the Navy.
</P>
<P>
   At Clark's headquarters outside of Brussels, top aides are
pouring over the details of the operation. Military officials said
they must define where the NATO maritime interdiction force will
operate in the Adriatic and Ionian seas.
</P>
<P>
   Clark must also determine how many ships, helicopters and
surveillance planes, like U.S. Navy P-3s, the operation will need.
Navy officers said that a dozen ships, rotating duty, would likely
be sufficient. Eight NATO ships are assigned to the region now.
</P>
<P>
   A delicate part of the mission would be the actual rules of
engagement. Once NATO affirms a specific plan, a notice would go
out to all international mariners with the rules. NATO warships
would likely establish checkpoints off the Montenegrin coast for
checking vessels.
</P>
<P>
   If ships were suspected of carrying contraband, they would be
boarded and inspected. Allied ships could fire on any vessels that
refused to comply, first as a warning, and then to disable,
violators. Navy officers say there are also nonlethal means of
stopping a rogue tanker dead in its tracks, including devices that
would entangle a ship's screw or rudder.
</P>
<P>
   ``In a tactical sense,'' Adm. Luc Kroon, the Dutch chief of
defense staff, said in interview, ``it's no problem to execute
this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
