<HEADLINE>
IN NEW YORK SURVIVAL IS STILL HINDERED BY SLOW EMS RESPONSE  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds.: This story originally moved 4-18 and was held. It has been
re-edited and is now released) 
(ATTN: Wash.)   By ALAN FINDER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three years after the Fire Department took over New
York City's Emergency Medical Service, fire officials have begun to
make good on some of the bold promises made during their aggressive
campaign to seize control of the beleaguered public ambulance
system.
</P>
<P>
   But there is no hard evidence to show that more New Yorkers who
suffer cardiac arrest _ the most dire and the most easily measured
medical emergency _ are being saved.
</P>
<P>
   When lobbying in 1995 to take the Emergency Medical Service from
the city's Health and Hospitals Corp., fire officials had said they
would apply their management know-how and expertise in maintaining
vehicles to make the emergency service better, faster and more
efficient. They suggested that many more lives would be saved.
</P>
<P>
   Once they took control in March 1996, fire officials bought new
ambulances, moved dozens of paramedics and emergency medical
technicians out of administrative jobs and back into ambulances,
and trained thousands of firefighters to respond to medical
emergencies. The result: the average response time for
life-threatening situations has been cut by more than two minutes,
from eight minutes 58 seconds in 1996 to six minutes 43 seconds
last year.
</P>
<P>
   But it is uncertain whether this swifter response has produced
clear-cut medical benefits.
</P>
<P>
   By one measure, it has not. In 1996, 13.4 percent of people
whose hearts stopped beating reached an emergency room alive, EMS
officials said. In 1997, the rate was 13.6 percent and last year it
was 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Fire and EMS officials contend, though, that earlier responses
to life-threatening emergencies may be helping cardiac patients.
They noted that the annual number of cardiac arrests in New York
had declined, to 6,030 in 1998 from 6,969 in 1996. They theorize
that emergency crews now arrive so quickly that they prevent some
patients from ever going into cardiac arrest, when the heart stops
beating properly, usually due to an abnormal rhythm, which can be
caused by a heart attack or underlying heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Bolstering their theory, EMS officials said, is a sharp increase
in the number of respiratory arrests they treat each year; by
arriving quickly, emergency crews may be preventing some
respiratory arrests from developing into more serious cardiac
arrests, they said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think we're doing very, very well and we're going to
continue to improve,'' Thomas Von Essen, the fire commissioner,
told a City Council committee last month.
</P>
<P>
   Many independent medical experts said, though, that more must be
done to produce a significant increase in the number of New Yorkers
who survive cardiac arrest _ and that some important factors may be
beyond the control of city government.
</P>
<P>
   Response times might have to be pushed much lower before medical
benefits become obvious, many doctors said. People who go into
cardiac arrest must receive medical care within four to six minutes
to have a good chance of surviving, emergency physicians said. That
usually involves cardio-pulmonary resuscitation and, most
importantly, an electric shock from a machine called a
defibrillator to jolt the heart back into a normal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Alexander E. Kuehl, who was medical director of EMS in the
1980s and is a proponent of the Fire Department's takeover, said
that average response times would have to go below five minutes for
many cardiac patients to be resuscitated successfully. ``By the
time you get out to six minutes, you're not saving any lives,''
said Kuehl, who is now director of emergency care at the Champlain
Valley Physicians and Hospital Medical Center in Plattsburgh, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Only in the last few years have defibrillators become portable
and easy to use, and their use has become the key element to
survival. ``If somebody is standing by with a defibrillator when
someone goes into cardiac arrest and the patient is instantly
defibrillated, you can have a survival rate of as much as 70
percent,'' said Dr. Lynne D. Richardson, vice chair of emergency
medicine at the Mount Sinai School of Medicine. ``But it drops off
quickly. Once you get over five minutes, it is in single digits.''
</P>
<P>
   Many factors can prevent emergency workers from reaching
life-and-death emergencies quickly enough to apply defibrillation
in time. New York's persistent traffic and its high-rise buildings
add critical minutes to the race to reach people in cardiac arrest.
It is not surprising, medical researchers say, that medium-size
cities and suburban areas produce the best emergency response
times.
</P>
<P>
   In the suburbs of Seattle, a region noted for advanced emergency
care, firefighters and ambulances get to life-threatening
emergencies within four to six minutes, on average, said Thomas R.
Hearne, director of the King County Emergency Medical Services
Division.
</P>
<P>
   In Phoenix, where every firefighter is also a trained emergency
medical technician, the average is 4 minutes, 12 seconds, said Bob
Khan, a battalion chief in the Phoenix Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   In Seattle and King County, a vast suburb of 1.7 million people,
about one-third of the population has been trained in
cardio-pulmonary resuscitation, Hearne said. Through CPR,
bystanders can buy precious time for cardiac patients by
artificially propelling blood to vital organs until a normal heart
rhythm is restored by a defibrillator.
</P>
<P>
   Survival rates from cardiac arrest vary widely, with different
standards and competing claims. Even so, survival rates in King
County are impressive: More than 30 percent of patients in cardiac
arrest are resuscitated and ultimately go home from the hospital,
Hearne said.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, a 1994 study by three emergency doctors from
hospitals in the Bronx found the rate in New York is only 1.4
percent. The doctors used the same rigorous standard now used by
most medical researchers: A survivor is defined as someone who,
after undergoing cardiac arrest, eventually is discharged, healthy,
from a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Another factor that may be inhibiting survival rates in New
York, according to many paramedics, is that they are still not
getting to cardiac arrests quickly enough.
</P>
<P>
   In taking over EMS, fire officials promised, in writing, to
achieve a number of statistical goals. Among them was that
paramedics _ the most highly trained emergency workers _ would
arrive at life-threatening emergencies within eight to 10 minutes
90 percent of the time. Last year, they reached such scenes within
10 minutes only 45 percent of the time, according to the Mayor's
Management Report.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters or emergency medical technicians can reach a
cardiac patient quickly and use a defibrillator, but that only
stabilizes a patient temporarily, many paramedics said. Because
paramedics can administer medicines that stabilize the heart more
permanently, they must also arrive promptly, paramedics said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Among the problems has been high turnover among paramedics, many
of whom have left EMS for higher paying jobs with private
hospitals. ``We want to continue to work on that,'' said Von Essen,
who was not yet commissioner when the department lobbied to get EMS
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   In persuading the City Council to approve the takeover, fire
officials said they would reconfigure the agency, in part by
building as many as 60 ambulance battalion stations around the
city. That plan, and others, have been either scaled back or
dropped.
</P>
<P>
   Fire officials promised the Council that ambulances or
fire-engine companies would reach patients in life-threatening
situations within six minutes 90 percent of the time. They have
come close.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulance crews with emergency medical technicians _ who operate
basic life support units but who cannot administer most medicines _
reached patients in life-threatening situations within six minutes
59 percent of the time last year, according to the mayor's
Management Report. When trained firefighters were included,
emergency crews reached critical cases within six minutes 80
percent of the time.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have not met the goals that we reached together in our
memorandum of understanding,'' said Councilman Sheldon S. Leffler,
who is chairman of the Public Safety Committee. ``Response time has
improved significantly, and that's important and that's good. But
in terms of achieving the other goals _ to provide basic life
support 90 percent of the time under six minutes and advanced life
support 90 percent of the time under 10 minutes _ that they have
not done.''
</P>
<P>
   Leffler said he was disappointed that neither EMS nor
independent researchers had rigorously studied whether the Fire
Department's management had caused more lives to be saved. ``That
was their main selling point when they sought to get the merger
through, that there would be a major reduction in the number of
people who died,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
