u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-BOS &LR;      04-25 1191
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCHOOL-SHOOTINGS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TENS OF THOUSANDS ATTEND VIGIL FOR VICTIMS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN O'BRIEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ Tens of thousands journeyed for miles Sunday
in a search for solace at the first formal vigil held for the 13
victims of the Columbine High School shootings.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 70,000, twice as many as expected, came to hear
Vice President Al Gore and popular Christian rock singer Amy Grant.
</P>
<P>
   They were beckoned by the bittersweet sound of bagpipes and the
promise that they might someday return to the lives they knew
before Tuesday. But the people of Littleton, whose initial shock
has given way to a lingering pain, also know they will have to
change.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us must change our lives to honor these children,''
Gore told the overflow crowd at a movie theater parking lot a few
blocks from where two presumed killers, Columbine students Eric
Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, went on a rampage, killing 13
and wounding more than 20 before taking their own lives. ``More
than ever, I realize every one of us is responsible for all of the
children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We must have the courage not to look away from those who feel
despised and rejected,'' Gore said. ``If you are a parent, they
need your attention. If you are a grandparent, they need your
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Jonathan and Stephen Cohen opened the service with a
simple ``Hi,'' and sang a song they wrote in tribute to the
massacre's victims.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Cohen, a junior at Columbine, was trapped in the choir
room when gunfire erupted. Stephen, a senior, was in the cafeteria
where many students were shot or hit by shrapnel from pipe bombs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Can you still hear raging guns ending dreams of precious
ones?'' they sang. ``In God's son, hope will come, his red stain
will take our pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and retired General Colin Powell led an array of
dignitaries. Afterward, they walked slowly to nearby Clement Park
to place more flowers at an impromptu memorial that has been
growing daily since the shootings.
</P>
<P>
   Nick Foss, 18, who was grazed by a bullet while helping teachers
and students hide in a closet and overhead air ducts, limped in the
processional behind Gore and Powell. He was supported by Columbine
High School Principal Frank DeAngelis, and mourners applauded as
they passed.
</P>
<P>
   Four F-16 fighter jets from the Colorado National Guard soared
overhead, led by Columbine graduate Captain Scott VanBek. A private
plane trailed a banner overhead reading: ``Our love and prayers are
with you.''
</P>
<P>
   From her vantage point at the edge of the crowd, 17-year-old
Sarah Dix said she felt like an outcast, as she always has in this
city. While she cannot comprehend why Harris and Klebold seemed
determined to kill so many, she said she believed she knew why her
two friends felt so hopeless.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt the way Dylan and Eric felt,'' she said. ``Everyone is
so judgmental. They look at me, and they call me a junkie just
because I dress different from them. The people here are scared of
me; they think I represent all this evilness.''
</P>
<P>
   Dix said she left Columbine High School last year because of
what she felt was an enormous pressure to conform.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Dix and her friends were eyed warily by adults who
have reason to remain fearful, with investigators apparently
convinced that the two presumed killers had help carrying out their
well-planned attack.
</P>
<P>
   Two passersby told 25-year-old Columbine High School dropout
Robert Hopkins, who was wearing his usual wardrobe of oversized
hooded sweatshirt and baggy pants, that he should have dressed more
appropriately for the memorial service.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to go right back to the same scene,'' Hopkins said.
He said that high school athletes have tossed glass bottles at him
as he waited at a bus stop. Just two days ago, Hopkins said, a
group of football players challenged him and his friends at the
mall.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of them who don't act like that,'' Hopkins
said. ``But there are plenty who pick on everyone. I guess it's
about their egos.''
</P>
<P>
   Though these so-called outcasts say they have little hope that
this community of grieving parents and children will embrace
alternative groups, others are urging Columbine High to set a
nationwide example.
</P>
<P>
   Posted on the doors of the city's largest movie theater and
printed on pamphlets handed out by volunteers, are messages of
hope. ``Turn to that person who doesn't look like you. Turn to that
person who looks strange to you. Stop by their table in the
cafeteria, and extend your hand. Together we can make a
difference,'' reads a sign posted at the popular FunPlex, one of
the city's entertainment complexes.
</P>
<P>
   But with so many people alternating between sorrow and outrage
here, it is clear that tensions among teenagers will not disappear
soon.
</P>
<P>
   At Clement Park this week, high school athletes said they were
sure their school was no different from any other in the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, kids get picked on,'' said Brandon Jones, a 17-year-old
football player. ``But it's just like anywhere. They want to stand
out as being different, and they don't like us, and I guess we
don't like them.''
</P>
<P>
   Klebold was buried Saturday at a private service. Neither his
name not Harris's was mentioned by speakers during Sunday's outdoor
memorial.
</P>
<P>
   Klebold's parents released a short statement, saying they loved
their son as best they knew how, and extended their sympathy to
other parents who lost children this week.
</P>
<P>
   Because Klebold and Harris are believed to have spent hours
building bombs and accumulating weapons at their homes, their
parents have been targets of criticism, with local talk radio shows
filled with callers expressing incredulity that they could not have
known what their sons were doing.
</P>
<P>
   While scores turned out for Sunday's service, investigators
continued their probe into the shootings, questioning other members
of the ``Trenchcoat Mafia'' _ the name of Harris and Klebold's
group. Police have said the number of explosives found in the
hallways and the number of weapons recovered from the school
indicate the pair must have had help. During the hourlong shooting
rampage, 15 died, including one teacher, 12 students, Harris, and
Klebold.
</P>
<P>
   Several students who escaped the school as shots rang out have
told police they recognized a third teenager wielding a gun.
Jefferson County officials say they are hopeful that a diary found
in the home of one of the gunmen will help them in their
investigation.
</P>
<P>
   For now, mourners are being asked to hold fast to their faith
and work toward a time of greater understanding and less pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Surely the past week is about as much suffering as any
community can bear,'' said Roman Catholic Archbishop Charles Chaput
of Denver, who opened the service with a prayer. ``Love is stronger
than death. I believe that. Perhaps beyond all this suffering,
something good can be achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   Above him, the voices of a church choir floated skyward, along
with hundreds of blue and white balloons and 13 doves, released in
memory of the 13 who were slain.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
