<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2697 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS &LR;      04-25 1008
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-UPDATE-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
SECURITY VOWED FOR 7 NEIGHBORS OF YUGOSLAVIA: NATO ENDS SUMMIT WITH
CALL FOR TALKS WITH RUSSIA
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By DAVID IVANOVICH &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ NATO extended security guarantees to seven
countries bordering Yugoslavia Sunday, prompting a number of the
front-line nations to fuller cooperation with the allies' monthlong
Balkans war.
</P>
<P>
   As NATO's 50th anniversary summit ended, a German official
called for foreign ministers of the seven leading industrialized
democracies to confer with Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin this
week in hopes of finding a diplomatic end to the bloodshed.
</P>
<P>
   NATO military chiefs continued to work on how to implement a
planned oil embargo against Yugoslavia as NATO announced additional
attacks on a refinery in Novi Sad. Bad weather hampered weekend
bombing runs.
</P>
<P>
   NATO leaders promised the former Yugoslav republics of
Macedonia, Bosnia-Herzegovina, Croatia and Slovenia, as well as
Albania, Bulgaria and Romania protection from any encroachment or
attack by Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   ``NATO made its position very clear,'' President Clinton said.
``We said unambiguously, `If Belgrade challenges its neighbors as a
result of the presence of NATO, we will respond.'''
</P>
<P>
   The assurances gave Macedonia a strong enough sense of security
to accept up to 16,000 new British and German troops to augment the
12,000 allied soldiers already stationed there, NATO officials
said. The original troops were sent to Macedonia to serve as the
vanguard for a peacekeeping force NATO wants installed in Kosovo
after a cease-fire and withdrawal of Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have taken the decision to deploy those units now because
obviously we want to be ready for all contingencies,'' said NATO
spokesman Jamie Shea.
</P>
<P>
   Romania and Slovenia have agreed to give NATO aircraft access to
their air space. Bulgaria is expected to follow suit today.
</P>
<P>
   Hungary, despite joining NATO last month, has been reluctant to
play host to troops from the other alliance countries. Hungarian
officials fear Belgrade will retaliate against ethnic Hungarians
living in Vojvodina. It is a province of Serbia and, like Kosovo,
was an autonomous region until 1989.
</P>
<P>
   Five of the front-line countries _ all but Bosnia and Croatia _
are on a list of nine candidates for admission to NATO. The allies
are considering expanding again within the next three years, and
the conflict in Kosovo has heightened interest in the protective
umbrella of NATO.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair said he was struck by the
earnestness of countries wanting to emulate NATO's democratic
ideals.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was something quite humbling about their desire to be
part of our family,'' Blair said.
</P>
<P>
   The seven front-line countries and representatives from another
17 countries represented in the Euro-Atlantic Partnership Council
sat in with the full NATO members for the final summit session in
the sprawling, new Ronald Reagan Building two blocks from the White
House.
</P>
<P>
   Russia was the only member of the expanded group to boycott the
summit. With its religious and ethnic ties to Serbia, Russia has
adamantly opposed the air attacks on Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Russian President Boris Yeltsin phoned President Clinton on
Sunday to brief him on Chernomyrdin's recent meeting with Milosevic
in Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
   The White House dispatched Deputy Secretary of State Strobe
Talbott to Moscow to discuss the situation further. Canadian and
Swedish officials also planned consultations in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   German Foreign Minister Joschka Fischer said he is trying to
organize a meeting this week in Bonn between Chernomyrdin, a former
Russian prime minister, and foreign ministers from the major
industrial powers to seek a solution to the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   Germany is the current chair of the so-called Group of Eight as
well as president of the European Union for the first six months of
the year.
</P>
<P>
   The allies have been concerned about Russia's unwillingness to
abide by a planned, NATO-imposed oil embargo on Yugoslavia. Despite
the fighting, Russia has continued to ship petroleum products to
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. National Security Adviser Samuel ``Sandy'' Berger said that
the embargo did not come up during the Clinton-Yeltsin conversation
which lasted 1{ hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Yeltsin is well aware of the decisions that have
been taken here including the decision with respect to stopping
resupply,'' Berger said. ``President Yeltsin did not raise the
question of this issue, gave no indication that they would not
comply.''
</P>
<P>
   Just how the NATO countries will implement an oil embargo has
yet to be decided. ``All 19 countries agree that it is important to
cut down the supply of fuel going into fuel his war machine,'' said
U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen.
</P>
<P>
   The alliances is contemplating some kind of naval blockade,
which officials described as a ``visit and search'' operation.
</P>
<P>
   Serbia's two oil refineries, in the cities of Novi Sad and
Pancevo, have been frequent targets of NATO bombing raids. Other
recent targets included an ammunition storage depot in northern
Kosovo and a highway bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Since the air campaign began, the allies have flown more than
9,000 sorties and have lost one aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   The United States has already spent more than a $1 billion on
the effort, with some projecting the U.S. share of the campaign to
cost $6 billion or more.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans on Capitol Hill argue that Congress must go beyond
just paying for the war and increase military spending overall.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we should take this opportunity to look at
adding every military need we may have been aware of,'' Senate
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., said on ABC-TV's This Week.
</P>
<P>
   However, Lott said that he favors increasing troops' pay and
improving their retirement systems to ``give the troops the
assurances that we know they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Lott said total cost of such a bill would be at least $11
billion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
