<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-ANDERSON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: LEMIEUX'S NEXT GOAL: SAVE PENGUINS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ In gold, black and white with the Penguins' logo,
the ``Lemieux 66 1984-1997'' banner hangs high in the Civic Arena,
while the franchise's future hangs in bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Millionaire former superstars in every sport are supposed to
fade away into the sun and fun of celebrity golf tournaments, but
Mario Lemieux, who led the Penguins to the Stanley Cup in both 1991
and 1992, is trying to buy the Penguins franchise in order to keep
it alive and well in Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   This isn't the usual story of a franchise about to move. This
isn't the Dodgers leaving Brooklyn, or the Raiders leaving Oakland,
or the Browns leaving Cleveland. Those franchises were not only
solvent, but also profitable.
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins are bankrupt. The Penguins are $120 million in
debt, and co-owners Howard W. Baldwin and Roger M. Marino are now
seldom in sight. Zillionaires who might ordinarily want to buy a
National Hockey League franchise as a toy have shied away from the
Penguins as a bad investment.
</P>
<P>
   But the most famous player in Penguins history, Mario Lemieux,
along with the food-chain multimillionaire Ron Burkle, have joined
in a bid for this small-market franchise in the NHL, where
revenue-sharing doesn't exist. If the bid is successful, Lemieux
will be the principal owner.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux isn't just putting up his name; he's putting up $10
million of his reported $20 million in deferred income. If he
succeeds, it will be more important to the Penguins' future than
any, or all, of his goals as a center.
</P>
<P>
   In earlier eras, players didn't make enough money to even think
about being a club owner. It's different now. Michael Jordan wants
to be an owner of the Charlotte Hornets and Lemieux is hoping to
take over the Penguins, whom he watched take a two-games-to-one
lead on the New Jersey Devils in their opening-round
four-of-seven-game Stanley Cup playoff series with Sunday's 4-2
victory.
</P>
<P>
   Without hockey's best player, Jaromir Jagr, who was benched by a
groin injury for the second straight game, and in the confusion
over the bankruptcy situation, the eighth-seeded Penguins weren't
supposed to challenge the Devils, the Eastern Conference champions,
but the Devils are in jeopardy of being eliminated in the first
round for the second straight year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have any control of it, so we don't worry about it,''
Penguins Coach Kevin Constantine said of the bankruptcy. ``And it'd
be a lame excuse if we did.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe they don't worry about it, but the Penguin players surely
are aware that the franchise is awaiting its real playoffs _
discussions on Wednesday about the arena lease and a hearing on
Friday in U.S. Bankruptcy Court.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux will meet Wednesday with Wes Westley Jr., the president
and chief executive of Spectacor Management Group, which operates
the Civic Arena for the city.
</P>
<P>
   Lemieux will try to reduce the lease that costs the Penguins $7
million a year. In contrast, the Steelers and the Pirates will each
pay $350,000 in their lease arrangements with the city for the
approved new separate football and baseball stadiums. Lemieux
reportedly wants a $500,000 lease.
</P>
<P>
   And on Friday in bankruptcy court, Judge Bernard Markovitz will
conduct a hearing on the Lemieux group's bid.
</P>
<P>
   NHL Commissioner Gary Bettman has supported Lemieux's bid, so
much so that he has threatened to dissolve the franchise, or sell
it to another local ownership group or to an owner in another city
if the judge doesn't approve of Lemieux's bid, hopefully by June 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're running out of time,'' Bettman said at Saturday's game.
``We have a schedule to do for next season. It's virtually done,
but if we have to redo it, we have to know soon.''
</P>
<P>
   The NHL could also liquidate the franchise's assets and conduct
a dispersal draft of its players, notably Jagr, the NHL's leading
scorer this season, whose contract calls for a $9 million salary
next season. Should that happen, the Rangers would presumably be
the franchise best able to afford him.
</P>
<P>
   But that's not what all those Penguins fans want. And it's not
what Jagr wants.
</P>
<P>
   When the Penguins were in Madison Square Garden last Sunday for
Wayne Gretzky's going-away party, Lemieux, who was there as what
Gretzky described as ``the best player I ever played against,''
happened to walk by the Penguins' dressing room.
</P>
<P>
   ``Howya doin', boss,'' Jagr said wishfully.
</P>
<P>
   From his lips to the bankruptcy judge's ears.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2224EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
