<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 22:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2704 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLERGY-DISABILITIES-N     04-25 0710
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLERGY-DISABILITIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SEMINARIANS SEEK TO TEACH THROUGH THEIR DISABILITIES
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By NADINE BROZAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When four students from Union Theological Seminary
held a worship service in November, each one talked about her
disability or emotional impairment and how it related to her
spirituality.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the end of the service, dozens of people came up to us
individually and collectively, many in tears,'' said Jennifer
Pader, one of the organizers. ``We realized right away something
really special had happened and saw that there was a need not being
filled.''
</P>
<P>
   The four now call themselves ``By Our Wounds, We Are Healed,''
and their mission is to awaken churches to the struggles faced by
clergy members with disabilities. In addition to Ms. Pader, a
Unitarian Universalist, the group includes Mary Ramsay, who belongs
to the United Church of Christ; Barbara Rasero, a Roman Catholic,
and Elizabeth Schell, a Methodist.
</P>
<P>
   They have joined to create and lead worship services, conduct
workshops and do counseling in an effort to demolish barriers that
limit what disabled clerics can do and alter the perception that an
impairment is retribution for sin or moral failing.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the four conducted their second noontime
community service at the seminary's James Memorial Chapel, on its
campus in Morningside Heights. They recalled their unexpectedly
successful debut in November.
</P>
<P>
   ``We embarked on a journey out of the safety zone of the
seminary,'' Ms. Pader told the congregation. `` In this very
worship community, we outed ourselves as women living with physical
and psychiatric disabilities that had shaped our lives in some very
fundamental ways.
</P>
<P>
   `` These disabilities that make us uncomfortable and wanting to
avert our eyes from those who are different, can lead us toward a
new theology of liberation,'' she continued. ``This refusal to
accept the limited space that society has made for us and we have
made for ourselves, will make us better church members and more
insightful pastors.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Pader suffers from spasmodic dysphonia, a neurological
condition that causes involuntary movement of the vocal muscles in
the larynx that lead the voice to tremble and crack. Though there
is no cure, it can be treated with injections of a toxin known as
Botox that temporarily paralyzes the muscles to control the spasms.
</P>
<P>
   Last fall, Ms. Pader, who is also a freelance copywriter,
approached Karen Wood, associate dean for student life at the
seminary, with the idea of conducting a service focused on issues
of disability. Wood put her in contact with Ms. Ramsay, who was
newly diagnosed with fibromyalgia, a painful muscle disorder that
has no cure. ``Together we decided we wanted to lead a service that
would move away from the idea of victimization, and toward the
liberation of people with disabilities,'' Ms. Pader said.
</P>
<P>
   They were joined by two other seminarians who broadened the
group's definition of disability to encompass emotional problems as
well. Ms. Schell, who was raised by a schizophrenic mother, twice
attempted suicide during adolescence. Barbara Rasero, in her 20s,
has a social phobia so severe that she fainted the first time she
had to speak at a service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all had great chemistry,'' Ms. Pader said. ``I like to
think of us as the Spice Girls, although the rest of them really
hate that.''
</P>
<P>
   They intend to continue pursuing their cause after they
graduate, Ms. Pader in May, the three others next year, and after
their ordinations.
</P>
<P>
   They have engagements to preach at the Union Methodist Church in
the Park Slope section of Brooklyn and at the Fourth Universalist
Society on Central Park West. They also plan to conduct workshops
and offer counseling.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the advice they offer about surmounting limits imposed
on the disabled and combating prejudice, they also question the
meaning of disability in God's plan for humanity.
</P>
<P>
   ``My illness is not unrelated to my life and my call,'' Ms.
Ramsay said of her fibromyalgia at the November service. ``It is an
essential characteristic of the fullness of a life called to God's
service. For each of us, ministry comes through the truth of who we
actually are.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
