<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAMS' HIT GIVES DIMAGGIO A FITTING TRIBUTE AS YANKS SWEEP
</HEADLINE>
  (With BBA-ARATON-COLUMN) 
 (nk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In his day, Joe DiMaggio liked to lounge at his
locker, drinking coffee and smoking cigarettes. On Joe DiMaggio Day
at Yankee Stadium, Bernie Williams lounged at his locker and played
guitar with Paul Simon, royalty in these parts because of the
lyrics he wrote about Joltin' Joe.
</P>
<P>
   Oblique and direct lines bind DiMaggio to Williams, Yankee
center fielders and cleanup hitters from different generations, and
those ties extended all the way into the 11th inning Sunday, when a
single by Williams scored Chuck Knoblauch with the decisive run in
the Yankees' 4-3 victory over Toronto. Jason Grimsley (1-0) threw
two perfect innings of relief for his first victory as a Yankee.
</P>
<P>
   The win gave the Yankees a three-game sweep of the Blue Jays
(12-7), extended their winning streak to five and improved their
record to 12-5.
</P>
<P>
   DiMaggio and Williams have their differences, of course: At the
moment Knoblauch slid home ahead of the throw from right fielder
Shawn Green, Williams reacted in a manner that was mostly foreign
to DiMaggio. Williams, who has been overeager at the plate and
struggling to drive in runs, turned and fired his helmet to the
ground, ripped apart the Velcro binding of his batting glove and
stalked to the dugout, outwardly elated he had succeeded, and
disgusted it had taken him so long to do so.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just happy to get a base hit and produce in the clutch,''
said Williams, who has just four extra-base hits and seven runs
batted in over his first 68 at-bats this season.
</P>
<P>
   Like DiMaggio's Yankees, these Yankees have come to expect the
best from themselves, and only because of their own late-inning
struggles were they playing so late into Joe DiMaggio Day. David
Cone pitched well, allowing just six base runners in six and
two-thirds innings and turning over a 3-1 lead to the bullpen in
the seventh, but the Yankees' lack of left-handed relief hurt them
in the eighth and ninth innings.
</P>
<P>
   Because Mike Stanton, the only lefty in the Yankees' bullpen,
pitched out of trouble in the seventh and Jeff Nelson followed
Stanton, Don Zimmer, the Yankees' interim manager, had to turn to
the closer Mariano Rivera in the eighth when Nelson ran into
trouble _ the third appearance in three days for Rivera.
</P>
<P>
   He pitched out of a jam in the eighth, his fastball appearing
unhittable in the shadows that reached for home plate in the late
afternoon. But with Toronto trailing, 3-2, Carlos Delgado blooped a
single to short center leading off the ninth, and took second and
then third when catcher Jorge Posada was charged with two passed
balls; he just could not see the ball in the shadows, Posada
explained.
</P>
<P>
   With Rivera tired, the tying run scored, and only a perfect
relay from right fielder Paul O'Neill to second baseman Chuck
Knoblauch to Posada prevented the Blue Jays' Willie Greene from
scoring the go-ahead run in the ninth.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch walked to open the bottom of the ninth for the Yankees
and moved into scoring position, but Williams struck out and Tino
Martinez grounded out. The Yankees' leadoff hitter reached scoring
position again in the 10th, and again they could not capitalize.
Zimmer would muse later how the Yankees really have not played that
well, how their big hitters have not really started mashing the
ball. He did not use names, but he could have been talking about
Martinez, batting .220 with four RBIs in 17 games, and Williams,
whose .324 batting average is deceiving.
</P>
<P>
   Williams mashed the ball in spring training, batting .397 with
11 extra-base hits in 78 at-bats, but once the season began,
Williams seemingly lost his patience at the plate, swinging at the
first pitch in most of his at-bats and hacking with reckless
aggressiveness. Williams averaged 3.75 pitches a plate appearance
last year, and as Sunday's game began, he had averaged only 2.83
pitches a plate appearance this year _ the fewest in the American
League. Williams went on to swing at the first pitch in four of his
first five plate appearances Sunday. ``Maybe I've been trying too
hard, instead of just letting things happen and trusting my
ability,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Knoblauch was first to bat for the Yankees in the 11th, and he
turned away from an inside fastball from Toronto's Robert Person
and then immediately began moving toward first base, pointing at
his left hip, claiming he had been hit by the pitch; Mike Reilly,
the plate umpire, agreed. The Blue Jays argued angrily and
futilely; later, Knoblauch showed off a small mark on his hip to
reporters, promising he had not pinched himself.
</P>
<P>
   Derek Jeter struck out, but O'Neill walked, advancing Knoblauch
into scoring position and bringing Williams to the plate. This had
been a good day for Williams, before the game started: He had
chatted in the outfield with Simon while the singer was doing a
sound check, and before the game, Simon sat with him and Grimsley
with guitars, ``and we just jammed,'' Williams said. ``It was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   With each failure at the plate, however, Williams appeared even
more frustrated, lingering between pitches, concentrating so
intently that a thought balloon might have appeared above his head.
</P>
<P>
   But Person (0-1) threw a fastball on the inner half of the
plate, and Williams, batting left-handed, turned on it, lacing the
single between first and second; Knoblauch churned around third and
easily beat the throw from the outfield, jumping into the rush of
teammates.
</P>
<P>
   Williams purposefully high-fived other Yankees on his way back
to the dugout, saluted loudly by the crowd of 51,903, and suddenly
and finally, this was his day, no matter how obliquely, on Joe
DiMaggio Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
