<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 22:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2709 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SHOOTING-RDP-HNS &LR;      04-25 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOOTING-RDP-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
70,000 SALUTE LITTLETON'S FALLEN 13; WE MUST CHANGE, GORE SAYS AT
MEMORIAL
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By LISA TEACHEY &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   LITTLETON, Colo. _ For years the small community of students and
alumni of Columbine High School have used three words to show their
school pride.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the mantra became a chant of support and sorrow for
tens of thousands of people _ including Vice President Al Gore _
attending an open-air memorial service for the 12 students and
coach who were gunned down in the halls of the school Tuesday. Two
gunmen, students at the school, committed suicide after the attack,
which wounded 23.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, in a voice at times thunderous, told the crowd that
Americans should ``change our lives to honor these children.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a culture rife with violence where too many young people
place too little value on a human life, we can rise up and we can
say 'No more,''' Gore said to applause. ``We have seen enough of
violence in our schools. We must replace the culture of violence
and mayhem with one of values and meaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At such a time we need each other,'' Gore said. ``To the
families of all those who died here I say 'You are not alone.'''
</P>
<P>
   Joining Gore, his wife Tipper and community leaders on a
makeshift stage in the parking lot of a movie theater near the
school were the former head of the Joint Chiefs of Staff, Gen.
Colin Powell; Sen. Richard Gephardt, D-Mo.; Colorado Gov. Bill
Owens and singers Amy Grant, Michael W. Smith and Phil Driscoll.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 70,000 people, some who knew the victims, many who
did not, stood shoulder-to-shoulder in the parking lot and lined
the sidewalks across the boulevard. They carried flowers and wore
blue ribbons as they hugged and wept.
</P>
<P>
   More than 300 volunteers greeted people as they arrived, handing
out flowers, ribbons, programs and tissue.
</P>
<P>
   During the service, Columbine student body president Amber
Burgess told the crowd that the memories of her classmates and
beloved coach would not be lost. Then she shouted ``We are'' and
the crowd responded ``Columbine.''
</P>
<P>
   Although some of the speakers offered condolences to the
families of Eric Harris, 18, and Dylan Klebold, 17, the names of
the two killers were not mentioned. Officials said the gunmen had
plotted the massacre for a year.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities put their investigation at the high school on hold
Sunday to give officers and their families a chance to attend the
service. Steve Davis, Jefferson County Sheriff's spokesman, said
the investigation will resume today with continued processing of
evidence and interviews with witnesses.
</P>
<P>
   About 200 Colorado Army National Guardsmen, including 111 from
the 220th Military Police from Golden, Colo., were posted around
the campus for security.
</P>
<P>
   The service Sunday opened with a song written by brothers
Jonathan and Stephen Cohen. The two were trapped in different areas
of the school during the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   ``Columbine flower blue, Columbine there's hope for you,'' they
sang. ``Can you still hear raging guns ending dreams of precious
ones. Columbine, friend of mine, peace will come to you in time.''
</P>
<P>
   As the brothers sang, people in the crowd released hundreds of
blue and white balloons.
</P>
<P>
   The archbishop of Denver, the mayor of Littleton and other local
dignitaries then praised the heroism of the students and faculty of
Columbine and thanked the community and people across the country
who offered support after the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   Performers Grant, Smith and Driscoll sang emotional tributes.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Gore implored the country to become more active
in children's lives, saying ``the young killers of Columbine High
School'' were not what America stood for.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen in this community so much goodness, so much
healing, so much of what is best in our country,'' Gore said. ``You
have shown us that even in this ashen moment there is a spark that
lights our way forward.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we are brought to our knees in the shock of this moment,
what say we, what say we into the open muzzle of this tragedy,
cocked and armed at our hearts. All of us must change our lives to
honor these children.''
</P>
<P>
   Applause erupted from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president asked parents to pay more attention to their
children, grandparents to spend more time with their grandchildren
and childless adults to set a good example.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we as a people can work our way to that place where caring
and compassion open us to the lives of all our children, then those
children who died here will not have died in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   After the speeches and songs, the Colorado Air National Guard _
led by pilot Scott VanBek, a 1986 Columbine graduate _ flew over
the service in what is called the missing man formation.
</P>
<P>
   And white doves were released as the governor read off the names
of the dead.
</P>
<P>
   Bagpipers then led the dignitaries on a procession to Clement
Park, next to Columbine High, where memorials of flowers, notes and
stuffed animals have been set up.
</P>
<P>
   Gore laid flowers at a wreath in the park, then consoled family
members of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the public attending the ceremony had to walk by
protesters holding the American flag upside down and carrying signs
that read ``God Hates America.'' The protesters, a religious group
from Kansas, said they blame society for the shooting.
</P>
<P>
   As Don and Connie Baker arrived, Connie began weeping,
remembering Dave Sanders, the coach who was killed trying to
protect students.
</P>
<P>
   ``He coached our daughter-in-law,'' Don Baker said. ``We came
out mainly for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Laura Baker, a sophomore at neighboring Chatfield High School,
attended to show support for the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great way of really showing how the community has
come together,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Columbine High School principal Frank DeAngelis said the
ceremony was ``the end of a nightmare'' for him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm proud of Columbine High School,'' he said. ``Columbine
High School, because of its strong tradition, will continue on.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2230EDT &QL; 
