</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASKETBALL COLUMN: ONE HUGE COMEBACK FOR CHECKETTS' TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ There were lots of hugs to go around on Sunday
afternoon. With six-tenths of a second left and the New York Knicks
on the verge of stealing a game from the despised Miami Heat, Larry
Johnson hugged Kurt Thomas and Patrick Ewing hugged Charlie Ward.
Herb Williams was hugging everyone he saw on the bench. This was
like a giddy college team on the verge of winning a tournament
game, or a team of Davids who had just defeated Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   When Chris Dudley finally punched the ball away and the buzzer
sounded, the Knicks' bench emptied to celebrate their 82-80
victory. The players were as unrestrained as they had been composed
a few moments earlier during a fracas between Thomas and the Heat's
Jamal Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   Ward, Chris Childs and Marcus Camby hugged. In the stands, Dave
Checketts, the president of Madison Square Garden, Ed Tapscott, a
Knicks vice president, and Barry Watkins, a Garden spokesman,
looking as if they had been dragged through a wringer, shook hands
and accepted congratulations as they went to greet the team.
Checketts' team.
</P>
<P>
   His presence in Miami and the demotion of Ernie Grunfeld as
general manager last week served notice that Checketts, who used to
be the Knicks' president, is out of the ivory tower and back in the
trenches, taking the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``What was encouraging about today,'' Checketts said, ``was the
effort and the mental toughness to never, ever give up. Never get
out of the game. Don't let it sleep. Keep at it.''
</P>
<P>
   This was not simply a victory over a hated rival. This was the
second consecutive victory for a beleaguered team that was supposed
to challenge for a championship and finds itself struggling to make
the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   This is a team of severe peaks and valleys. On Friday they were
up by 17 points and needed a last-second shot by Ewing to beat
Charlotte. On Sunday, Ewing wasn't even playing, hobbled by
tendinitis, which will keep him in and out of the lineup from here
on out.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks were down by as many as 20 points. As the turnovers
mounted and the bad shooting continued, I kept looking over at
Checketts, Tapscott and Watkins, eight rows up behind the Knicks
bench. How would they ever recover from such a loss?
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday the Knicks staged the comeback of all comebacks, and
I'm still not convinced they know how they did it. All they know is
that Johnson capped the comeback by hitting a 3-pointer with 56.1
seconds left that tied the game at 77-77. Tim Hardaway came right
back with a 3. In days of old they most likely would have folded.
This time Childs drove, and then dished to Camby, who dunked with
verve, drew the foul and converted the free throw.
</P>
<P>
   ``He earned his stripes today'' Allan Houston said of Camby.
``We all earned our stripes today. This was special because of the
history we have with them. But it's only big until Monday.''
</P>
<P>
   There were two final pieces to put in place. Hardaway put up a 3
that missed and bounced long. In the past _ indeed, in the first
half _ the Heat simply would have beaten the Knicks to the loose
ball and run down the clock. This time Childs beat P.J. Brown to
the spot and sealed off the ball. Brown shoved him and was called
for the foul, and Childs gave the Knicks an 82-80 lead with 20.1
seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've lost a lot of games this year on last possessions, on
rebounds,'' coach Jeff Van Gundy said. ``That loose ball was
great.''
</P>
<P>
   There was one more drama to play out, indicating that this
patchwork team might be grafting.
</P>
<P>
   With 20.1 seconds left, Van Gundy took out the slender Camby and
inserted the heftier Dudley.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing, the Knicks' captain, who is alternately accused of being
the savior and a burden, met Camby as he came off the court. Ewing
grabbed Camby, who was traded for Ewing's friend Charles Oakley,
and looked him in the eye as if to say: Hey, you played a great
game; you played your role.
</P>
<P>
   Now let Dudley play his. The Knicks needed Dudley to use his
bulk and muscle to bump Alonzo Mourning, keep him just out of his
comfort zone. On this day the Knicks didn't need overtime. They
needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   The locker room was empty. In the corridor, Checketts nodded at
players as they passed by, and said he would see them on the team
bus.
</P>
<P>
   Checketts has been pressed back into service at the grass-roots
level to save the bottom line: For the first time since 1977,
Madison Square Garden is threatened with being dark during both the
National Basketball Association and the National Hockey League
playoffs, because the Knicks, expected to be a legitimate contender
in this first season of the post-Jordan era, have been
inconsistent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I care very much about this team, this organization,''
Checketts said. ``This is where I first got started in New York. It
feels good to be in the trenches, but when you're responsible for
so much more, it's very hard to stay here.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I got back involved was I was convinced for
eight games in the playoffs the organization had to put all the
distractions, divisions, whatever, had to put them all aside and
focus on making the playoffs, focus on effort. Talent alone is not
going to win for you. What will win for you is great effort. That's
what you saw today.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
