<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-CUBS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA BACK WITH A HIT, BUT SOSA GETS THE HIT THAT COUNTS
</HEADLINE>
   (nk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ It was supposed to be a day for celebration. Instead,
the Mets' 8-4 loss to the Chicago Cubs left Mike Piazza feeling
only frustration Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   In Piazza's first game back from a 15-day stay on the disabled
list, the Mets gave up the 3-0 lead they took into the bottom of
the fifth inning, built on solo home runs by Edgardo Alfonzo, Robin
Ventura and Rickey Henderson. The loss was their second straight at
Wrigley Field.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza was one for five with a run batted in during the ninth
inning in his first appearance since April 9, when he sprained a
ligament in his right knee in Montreal. But Piazza hit the ball
hard. And he said he did not feel anything wrong in his knee.
</P>
<P>
   ``It definitely feels strong,'' Piazza said. ``But after the way
we lost today, it doesn't feel much better.''
</P>
<P>
   Piazza's bad feelings had nothing to do with his health. He said
he was even going to switch from wearing a cumbersome knee sleeve
with hinges to one without hinges.
</P>
<P>
   That was the good news. The bad news was that the Mets (11-8)
finished a six-game road trip at 3-3 after dropping two of three to
the struggling Cubs (7-9).
</P>
<P>
   Six of Chicago's runs Sunday afternoon came in a fifth-inning
outburst that began against Orel Hershiser (1-2) with a bloop
single, a walk, a bunt single that died near the third-base line, a
two-run double off John Olerud's glove and a hit batsman that the
Mets thought did not hit anything, much less the bill of Mickey
Morandini's helmet.
</P>
<P>
   That was it for Hershiser, who had somehow tossed four shutout
innings even though, as he said, he did not know where each pitch
was going. On came Turk Wendell, the quirky former Cub, to face the
reigning National League most valuable player, Sammy Sosa, with the
bases loaded and the Mets clinging to a 3-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Even though Wendell had not allowed a run in his last nine
outings, it was hard to imagine a more difficult situation. To
compound matters, the crowd of 39,265 on a Sammy the Bear Beanie
Baby giveaway day was not only the largest of the season at Wrigley
this year, but the throng also greeted its favorite player by
chanting ``Sam-my! Sam-my!'' as he strode to the plate.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's good baseball,'' Wendell said. ``I'd like to come into
the same situation when I had good stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Wendell described the two-ball, two-strike pitch he
threw Sosa as ``a slider that didn't slide.'' Sosa belted the
hanger into the left-field corner for a double. Three runs scored,
and the Cubs had a 5-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm not going to hit a home run every time up,'' Sosa
said. It only seemed that way last season, when Sosa hit 66 of
them. Still, Sosa said he was upset with himself for swinging for
the fences with two strikes. ``I said to myself I needed to calm
down and relax,'' said Sosa, who hit another double in the seventh.
``I just wanted to hit it hard and bring in some runs.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the runners Sosa brought in was Morandini. But the Mets
thought he should not have been on base in the first place.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys in here said it didn't hit him,'' Hershiser said of
his up-and-in 1-2 pitch to Morandini. Bruce Dreckman, the plate
umpire, said it did, however. ``Maybe the umpire heard his bat hit
his helmet,'' said Hershiser, who yelled over to Morandini after
the pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Where did it hit you?''' Hershiser said. ``He said,
`Right here,' and pointed at his helmet.''
</P>
<P>
   Morandini said: ``I thought it hit the bill of my helmet. I
heard something nick. I was trying to get out of the way. Piazza
didn't catch it, so it obviously hit something.''
</P>
<P>
   Just not what Hershiser wanted to hit, which was pretty much his
story for the day.
</P>
<P>
   ``You won't see that very often,'' said Hershiser, who allowed
five runs on four hits and five walks in four-plus innings. ``I had
great movement, just no location.''
</P>
<P>
   Hershiser had thrown only 56 pitches heading into the fifth, but
for the afternoon, 36 of his 69 pitches were balls. ``That's not
Orel,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said.
</P>
<P>
   Then the Mets' bullpen, which led the league with a 2.11 earned
run average going into the game, had one of its worst showings of
the season. Even Armando Benitez, who had previously allowed only
two hits in eight and two-thirds innings, had a rocky outing,
allowing Tyler Houston's two-run triple in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where we were making that critical pitch, we didn't make it
today,'' the Mets' pitching coach, Bob Apodaca, said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had so many missed opportunities,'' Piazza said. ``I just
want to try to forget this game.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
