<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOCCER COLUMN: NOW THERE ARE TWO GREAT RIVALRIES 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ This summer's Women's World Cup gained
instant credibility on Sunday. This was apparent from the steamed
looks on the faces of the American players, who discovered that
they can, in fact, lose on the green, green grass of home.
</P>
<P>
   They had not lost in the United States in 50 games, but lose
they did, 2-1, to China in a highly competitive exhibition that
reminded everybody there are no Dream Teams this summer, no Charles
Barkley whupping on the Angolans.
</P>
<P>
   The American public and also the news media have not yet come to
grips with this event _ 16 national teams coming to the United
States in what will be the best-attended sports event held only for
female athletes. The third Women's World Cup, from June 19 through
July 10, gained a huge amount of respectability Sunday if only
because it showed the United States is vulnerable, at least in the
medal round.
</P>
<P>
   The promoters have sold 325,000 tickets, aiming toward 475,000,
and they can probably sell more tickets from bone-rattling hits
like the ones that leveled Mia Hamm and Michelle Akers on Sunday
than from potential double-digit romps.
</P>
<P>
   ``China is the favorite right now,'' said Dr. Robert
Contiguglia, the president of the U.S. Soccer Federation, shortly
after China won the game three minutes into injury time.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday's crowd of 23,765 might have been bigger if prospective
fans had not feared they had to watch the MetroStars first, like
taking your medicine before a tasty dinner. The locals lost to
Tampa Bay, 1-0, probably not setting back major-league soccer more
than six or eight years.
</P>
<P>
   The women promptly aired out the joint. China against the United
States would be the best women's team rivalry in the world, except
that Norway-United States got there first, and besides that, the
Norwegians all speak English, so little gibes have built up, along
with the bruises. China-United States, however, is getting there.
</P>
<P>
   The Chinese were stunned at losing early in the first Women's
World Cup, which was in their country in 1991, but time, as
somebody once said, is on their side. They studied and traveled and
trained, and now they can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are so fast and so technical,'' said Hamm, who now has
gone seven straight games without scoring. ``That gave them the
opportunity to win on a random clear.''
</P>
<P>
   The United States has still won 11, lost five and tied five
against China, with significant victories for the Summer Games gold
medal in Georgia in 1996, and for the Goodwill Games title last
summer. Then in March, China upended the Americans, 2-1, in the
final of the prestigious Algarve tournament in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   There was another sign that the Yanks are not going to dominate
their festival this summer. In February, just after the draw for
the World Cup, the United States lost, 2-1, to a group of world
all-stars who had literally held one workout together the day
before. It wasn't only feisty Linda Medalen of Norway playing
traffic cop in the back four; it was emerging players from Japan
and Nigeria and Canada giving what-for to the Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Dynasties do wear out, like the Boston Celtics of the Bill
Russell-K.C. Jones era, or the Islanders of the early '80s, the
games and the miles adding up like dog years. But this is more a
case of other nations catching up.
</P>
<P>
   When the United States beat China, 2-1, last Thursday in
Hershey, Pa., the Chinese played without their star goalkeeper, Gao
Hong, who was said to be injured. Late in the game, the Yanks
forced the play for a goal in the 92nd minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the way we are,'' said their coach, Tony DiCicco, on
Sunday. ``They treat a tie as a loss.''
</P>
<P>
   They faced a loss Sunday when China's top scorer, Sun Wen,
hammered a goal past Briana Scurry in the 14th minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``At halftime, Julie Foudy said: `This is a test for us. It will
show how we handle adversity,''' Hamm said later. ``It didn't turn
out the way we wanted, but we did come back.''
</P>
<P>
   They tied the game in the 58th minute when Cindy Parlow crossed
the ball to Foudy, who made an intricate fake to her left, and then
waited for traffic to clear and smacked the ball past Gao, who
played a terrific game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I only have short-term memory,'' Foudy said, still steamed
after the game. ``I can't remember the goal.''
</P>
<P>
   They could only remember how, on home turf, the Chinese swarmed
around Hamm in extra time and then whacked the ball downfield,
where a speedy Zhang Ouying burst past Carla Overbeck and Christie
Pearce and put the ball under Scurry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we just lose that game?'' Foudy blurted into a television
microphone a few seconds after the final whistle.
</P>
<P>
   They did indeed lose. But the 1999 Women's World Cup was the
biggest winner. Patriotism sells tickets, but parity sells even
more.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
