u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT &LR;      04-25 0955
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS USE THEIR ANGER AND LOATHING TO BEAT THE HEAT  
(DW)
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Fla., N.C., Ohio, Canada)   By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Marcus Camby and Kurt Thomas passed an initiation Sunday
and found themselves in a club reserved for those whose animosity
for the Miami Heat obliterates common logic.
</P>
<P>
   Logically, the New York Knicks had no chance to win. Not inside
a simmering Miami Arena, where a crowd was taunting and teasing
them as they trailed by 20 points near the end of the third quarter
and by 15 points with seven minutes left in the game. Not with the
injured Patrick Ewing in a suit and helpless to counter Alonzo
Mourning, who was smiling devilishly each time he touched the ball
for three quarters.
</P>
<P>
   While Larry Johnson's bile for Mourning likely stirred him into
his best performance of the season, and Allan Houston's recall of
Miami moments lifted him from his funk, it was two newcomers to
this kind of loathing, Camby and Thomas, who delivered in an
improbable finish that left the Knicks with an 82-80 victory
against the mightiest team in the Eastern Conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't compare regular season and playoffs,'' Coach Jeff
Van Gundy said, pondering last year's Game 5 playoff victory in
Miami without Ewing. ``But certainly, this year, without a doubt,
this is the biggest win.''
</P>
<P>
   It came when the spindly Camby fearlessly ducked inside for
dunks, produced a cool free throw with 33 seconds left and scored 9
of his 15 points in a rousing 34-point fourth quarter for the
Knicks. It also came when the immovable Thomas sneered right back
at Mourning as he denied him the ball and helped keep the most
valuable player candidate to 2 points in final eight minutes.
</P>
<P>
   The two of them fit right into the hostile nature of this
rivalry and revealed how a fight for survival and a sense of pride
can revive a hopeless situation. The Knicks had done so much to
come back in this game, and still topped it off with a big stop in
the last eight seconds.
</P>
<P>
   Thomas had fouled out, so it was up to Chris Dudley to produce
in his only cameo of the fourth quarter. Mourning backed into the
paint, and with no shot, wheeled the ball to Jamal Mashburn with
four seconds on the clock. Mashburn lost the ball off his leg and,
it rolled down the baseline, where Chris Childs grabbed it and
wrapped it up to seal the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're down like we were, it's give-up time for a lot of
teams,'' said Johnson, who scored a season-high 23 points. ``But we
didn't care how bad it looked, we weren't going to get down.''
</P>
<P>
   So perhaps logic is for losers. The Knicks (23-21) provided the
first evidence of the season that they could not only land a
playoff spot but also prosper once the post-season began. If they
are the eighth seed and meet Miami as the first _ which is how the
two stand with six games left in the Knicks' season _ Sunday's
outcome must fortify the Knicks' faith and unsettle the nerves of
the Heat.
</P>
<P>
   That's how quickly things can change. With seven minutes left,
the Knicks looked like a team headed for the kind of blowout loss
that could have sapped their confidence and nudged them toward a
tailspin to end the season. But then Thomas found Camby darting
toward the basket for a dunk, and Houston shrugged off his 2-for-10
start and hit two jumpers in a row to begin a 17-4 run that ended
with a 3-pointer from Johnson to tie the game at 77-77 with 56
seconds left. All Miami Coach Pat Riley could do was watch how his
team failed to respond.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't recognize when another team is desperate,'' Riley
said. ``They were down and desperate.''
</P>
<P>
   The Heat seemed afraid to shoot the ball. Mourning _ who had
collected 27 points in three quarters _ failed to score a field
goal against the very player Riley traded to Dallas three years
ago, Thomas.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't score a field goal, did I?'' said Thomas, who was 0
for 4 for the game. ``That's OK I just wanted to defend and defend
hard. I wouldn't say I got in Zo's head. I just wanted to give him
a different look and keep coming. When you get traded from a place,
you're really up to play.''
</P>
<P>
   But all of the Knicks' emotion _ which included technical fouls
called on Childs and Thomas in separate skirmishes _ it could have
been misplaced had they failed to finish off this game in the last
56 seconds. After a Tim Hardaway 3-pointer, they shrugged off the
ghosts of all those failed fourth quarters of the past this season
and grabbed the victory. After turning the ball over five times in
his chaotic drives to the basket, Houston barged into the paint and
flipped the ball to Camby for a dunk with 33 seconds left. On the
play, Mashburn fouled him.
</P>
<P>
   Camby was on his way to shedding his image of a flimsy player,
but his mentality would have been thrown into question again if he
had missed the free throw. He nailed it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last time I came down here, I didn't break a sweat,'' said
Camby who did not play because of Van Gundy's reticence to toss him
into the physical fray. ``I got my chance and was feeling pretty
good. I had my confidence and stepped to the line.''
</P>
<P>
   They all produced when everything was on the line. And when it
was over. Childs jumped in Johnson's arms as a beer bottle was
tossed onto the floor by a Heat fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was huge, incredibly big,'' Childs said. ``It's always
sweeter to come down here and win one, especially one that meant as
much as this one did. Every time we leave here with a loss, it zaps
us.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't losing this game. It didn't look good for a while.
But with everything between these two teams, there was plenty to
feed off of. Everyone was apart of this.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone joined the club.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
