<SLUG> BC-BROADCOM-EPIGRAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BROADCOM TO ACQUIRE EPIGRAM IN A DEAL WORTH $316 MILLION
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif.)  (nk) 
 By SETH SCHIESEL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Seeking to offer high-speed Internet links within homes, the
Broadcom Corp. said Sunday that it had agreed to acquire Epigram
Inc., a private maker of microchips for data communications, for
$316 million in stock.
</P>
<P>
   Epigram, based in Sunnyvale, Calif., is a leading developer of
chip sets for offering office-caliber data links within homes,
using the telephone wiring that is already in place. Though Epigram
does not expect to have significant revenue until the third
quarter, the company already counts the 3Com Corp., Northern
Telecom of Canada and Matsushita of Japan among its customers.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcom, based in Irvine, Calif., is a big maker of chips for
cable modems and digital set-top boxes. Broadcom executives are
among many in the data communications and personal computer
industries who contend that as high-speed Internet connections
become available to more people, more families will want to link
multiple devices within their homes at similar speeds.
</P>
<P>
   That would allow multiple people in one home to share a single
Internet connection or to share such peripherals as printers or
scanners. Epigram, which was advised by Hambrecht &AMP; Quist in the
transaction, is developing technology to allow those in-home
connections while not interfering with normal telephone use.
</P>
<P>
   ``This will create a dynamism where we will incorporate this
technology into every cable modem and set-top box we sell,'' said
Henry T. Nicholas, Broadcom's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey L. Thermond, Epigram's chief executive, said, ``The
bottom line for all of us is that this accelerates our ability to
bring our product to market.''
</P>
<P>
   He added: ``Broadcom's got a very entrepreneurial culture. When
we started these conversations three or four weeks ago, we were
struck with how similar the cultures were.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-25-99 2237EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990425.0216 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2718 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-N     04-25 0620
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-PENGUINS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
QUICK STRIKES LEAVE THE DEVILS LOOKING UP 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PITTSBURGH _ Some members of the Devils called the mental lapse
that led to two quick Pittsburgh goals a brain cramp. Whatever the
choice of words, the New Jersey Devils, the top-seeded team in the
Eastern Conference, now find themselves trailing the eighth-seeded
team, just as they did last season in their first-round elimination
by the Ottawa Senators.
</P>
<P>
   Two Pittsburgh goals 27 seconds apart in the first 40 seconds of
the third period Sunday led the Penguins to a 4-2 triumph and a
two-games-to-one lead in the first-round series.
</P>
<P>
   Some Devils players attributed their collapse to a lack of
concentration. All the Devils appeared shocked and stunned by the
two quick scores.
</P>
<P>
   The game had started well for the Devils. Pittsburgh's Jaromir
Jagr was sitting out his second game because of a groin injury, and
the Devils appeared to be the better team for the first two
periods. They went into the dressing room for the second
intermission leading by 2-1 on power-play goals by Sergei Brylin in
the first and Jason Arnott in the second.
</P>
<P>
   After two periods, the Devils had outshot Pittsburgh by 25-13,
and had had numerous chances to score more than the two goals. They
failed to convert their chances, which has been a problem the
Devils have had almost all season.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you have opportunities, you want to put them in,
especially when you have so many shots,'' said coach Robbie Ftorek,
who made four lineup changes from Saturday's second game, a 4-1
Pittsburgh victory. ``We played real well in the first two periods,
and maybe we should have had a bigger lead.''
</P>
<P>
   The Penguins came out on fire in the third and tied the score at
2-2 on Martin Straka's second goal of the game, just 13 seconds
into the period. Aleksei Kovalev's second goal in two days, just 27
seconds later, put the Penguins ahead by 3-2. An empty-net goal
with 17 seconds left gave Straka his hat trick and sealed the
victory for the financially troubled Penguins.
</P>
<P>
   ``We went into brain cramp for a couple of minutes there in the
third,'' Devils defenseman Brad Bombardir said. ``But we brought it
back for the next 13 minutes and we had our chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Bombardir echoed several of his teammates, who said that last
season's first-round loss to Ottawa had been erased from their
memories. All the players who made such a claim, however, seemed to
be looking the other way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year we didn't feel good about ourselves,'' Bombardir
said. ``This time we feel good. We're angry at ourselves, but we're
not frustrated.''
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Holik was upset that the Devils had dropped a game behind
the Penguins entering Tuesday night's game here. The series will
return to New Jersey on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had strictly a lack of concentration,'' Holik said. ``We
made some mistakes, and we should be harder on ourselves for making
such mistakes. It's a matter of focus. We played well for the most
part, but not at the start of the third.''
</P>
<P>
   Defenseman Ken Daneyko, standing across from Holik in a quiet
dressing room, was already talking about what the Devils would have
to do in the next game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Game 4 is vital to us,'' Daneyko said. ``We were shocked and
stunned.''
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Constantine, the Pittsburgh coach, said he didn't say
anything special to his players during the second intermission that
sparked them to come out with such enthusiasm in the third period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mike Eaves is the guy who talks to the team between periods,''
Constantine said, referring to one of his assistant coaches.
``Whatever he said worked out. They just played a great period.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
