<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-LONGSHOREMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AS GOVERNORS FEUD, DOCKWORKERS FEAR FOR THEIR JOBS 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ In the 29 years since James Stolpinski arrived on the
finger piers of Staten Island as an 18-year-old with a broad back
and a longshoreman's union card, he has unhappily watched New
Jersey supplant New York as the region's cargo hub. He blames New
York governors for being ``asleep at the wheel'' for decades as New
Jersey ports ascended at the expense of those in Brooklyn and on
Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Then, George Pataki became New York's governor, and Stolpinski
and many other longshoremen decided he might be a stand-up guy.
</P>
<P>
   Pataki gave voice to the accumulated resentments of New York
dockworkers when he criticized the Port Authority of New York and
New Jersey, the transportation agency that controls the region's
ports, railroads and airports. He also won points after helping to
prod the authority into a planned expansion of the Howland Hook
Marine Terminal on Staten Island.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Stolpinski and other New York longshoremen find
themselves in an awkward position. Pataki may be their champion,
but as they watch him battle his cross-harbor counterpart, New
Jersey Gov. Christie Whitman, over revenue from the Port Authority,
many worry that he is playing politics with the jobs of all
longshoremen.
</P>
<P>
   Claiming that New York deserves a larger cut, Pataki has
threatened to block a deal by Whitman to keep her state's two
largest shipping lines, Sea-Land Service and Maersk Line, from
moving to Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bylaws of the Port Authority, the governors of New
Jersey and New York both have veto power over the agency's
administration.
</P>
<P>
   To Stolpinski, who heads Staten Island Local 920 of the
International Longshoreman's Association, the choice is painfully
clear: Even though he agrees that New York deserves more from the
Port Authority, he cannot back his governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sign the deal,'' he said. ``Make the Sea-Land thing happen.
Then do what you've got to do with Whitman to get a fair share for
New York.''
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the shipping leases is really a proxy battle in a
larger war over control of the authority, and the longshoremen on
both sides of the water say they are unfairly caught in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Whom do they blame? It depends mostly on where they work. At
Howland Hook on Staten Island, there is plenty of sympathy for
Pataki's argument, if not his tactics. But at the Sea-Land terminal
in Elizabeth, N.J., Pataki is regarded as a political meddler.
</P>
<P>
   The two carriers employ 1,000 people in New Jersey with a $100
million payroll, including benefits. Many of the employees live in
New York. Others may work at Howland Hook or other New York docks,
but they also work overtime in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   ``The worst part of it is I'm a political pawn because of two
governors,'' said Lee Sobieck, 53, a mechanic, who was checking
trucks recently at the Sea-Land terminal in Elizabeth.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieck has worked at Sea-Land for 20 years and is paid about
$60,000 a year. ``It's hard to imagine looking for a job at 53,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sobieck joined the ILA at the age of 27, when the job entailed
little more than heavy lifting. Now, dockworkers operate
computerized cranes, forklifts, transfer trucks and other pieces of
heavy equipment. Depending on seniority and the amount of overtime
worked, a longshoreman can be paid between $30,000 and $110,000 a
year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a good job,'' Sobieck said. ``It had a future. I figured
I could work here until I'm 65.''
</P>
<P>
   Within the region's $20 billion shipping industry, Sea-Land and
Maersk account for about a quarter of the cargo moving annually
through the harbor. An original offer made to the companies by the
Port Authority included a host of subsidies, and Whitman sweetened
the deal two weeks ago by also offering $120 million in state
funds.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in New Jersey, as well as union officials, fear that
if the two carriers move to Baltimore, others may follow, hurting
not only longshoremen, but also myriad related businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Jim McNamara, spokesman for the ILA headquarters in Manhattan,
said the rank and file in New Jersey did have some protections if
the two lines do leave. Under the current regional contract,
McNamara said the 1,000 workers laid off in New Jersey would
probably qualify for the $36,000-a-year salary guarantee in the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   But the contract expires Sept. 30, 2001, and McNamara said union
officials worry that other carriers might follow Sea-Land and
Maersk to Baltimore rather than pay out the benefits of the
contract.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Sullivan, the union foreman at Sea-Land, said the critical
point overlooked by the politicians is that the boundaries between
New York and New Jersey are artificial where shipping is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the New York area,'' he said. ``It's the region we're
worried about. We're not New York and New Jersey. Pataki is worried
about New York. Christine Todd Whitman is worried about New Jersey.
As far as politics is concerned, I would like the two governors to
get together to preserve these jobs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
