<SLUG> BC-RAC-CHURCHILL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUBAI CONNECTION AND FILLIES SPICE DERBY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By JOSEPH DURSO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ Michael Osborne, manager of the racing stable
that sent two colts halfway round the world to the Kentucky Derby,
put it bluntly: ``We are going into the unknown.''
</P>
<P>
   What was unknown was this: Could you take two colts, keep them
in Dubai on the Persian Gulf all winter with no formal races, work
them in a couple of trial races that resemble scrimmages, then fly
them to Louisville and run them at a mile and a quarter in the
Kentucky Derby against the best colts in America?
</P>
<P>
   Some of the mystery came unwrapped at 6:30 Sunday morning when
the two colts, Worldly Manner and Aljabr, went to the track at
Churchill Downs and held their first formal workouts on American
soil since their arrival last Monday. They drew a large and curious
crowd along the backstretch as each worked seven furlongs in rather
slow time with reasonably fast finishes, which was what their
trainer had prescribed.
</P>
<P>
   Worldly Manner, with Jerry Bailey riding, as he will be on
Saturday in the Derby, languished through the first quarter-mile in
28 2/5 seconds, worked half a mile in 54 seconds and turned it up a
notch to complete the seven furlongs in 1:29 4/5. He finished up a
mile in 1:43 4/5.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Albertrani, assistant trainer to Sheik Mohammed bin Rashid
al-Maktoum and his Godolphin Stables, said: ``I thought it was a
good work. He started off a bit steady, and picked it up well and
finished strong. Jerry said he always felt there was something
there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, all his works are fairly consistent. They are slow
and steady the first part, and then finish up. He usually goes in
1:27 and change to 1:29.''
</P>
<P>
   Bailey then drove to Cincinnati to fly to New York, and Worldly
Manner was led back to his stall in Barn 45. Meanwhile, it was
Aljabr's turn on the track. And with Brian Procter riding, the colt
ran a quarter-mile in 28 2/5 seconds and seven-eighths in 1:31.
Hewing to the party line, Albertrani said, ``I thought he went
well, and finished up good.''
</P>
<P>
   But the sheik's horses weren't the only ones going into the
unknown.
</P>
<P>
   Menifee, who became one of the favorites by winning four of his
five starts, including the Blue Grass Stakes, turned in a snappy
five-furlong workout later in the morning in a minute flat. Both
his owner, Arthur Hancock, and his trainer, Elliott Walden,
expressed pleasure.
</P>
<P>
   ``I look for a good sharp workout over the track,'' said
Hancock, who won the Derby in 1982 with Gato del Sol and in 1989
with Sunday Silence. ``It tells me whether they like the track.
This horse had it this morning.''
</P>
<P>
   Walden, who trained Victory Gallop last year when the colt ran
second in the Derby and Preakness and first in the Belmont, said:
``He worked super. He had running on his mind.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the other unknowns in the Derby was whether fillies would
challenge the colts or stick to the Kentucky Oaks the day before.
So far, only Three Ring was an announced candidate for the Derby.
But Bob Baffert has two exceptional fillies in his barn,
Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting, who breezed five furlongs
Sunday morning in 59 1/5 seconds and finished out six furlongs in
1:12 flat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think both fillies will run in the Oaks,'' Baffert said
afterward. ``But we may cross-enter Excellent Meeting in the Derby.
Both of them have been so impressive in their works here. The key
at Churchill Downs is the turns, and both fillies just smoke around
the turns.''
</P>
</TEXT>
