<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CT-YALE-NEWHAVEN-645&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YALE PROPERTY LINE EXPANDS AGAIN, TO NEIGHBORS' IRE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Residents' anger over expansion by Yale
University, the city's largest employer and landowner, goes back
decades.
</P>
<P>
   When the university wanted to build two new dormitories in the
early 1970s, the Board of Aldermen rejected the plan, which Yale
eventually dropped.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s and early 1990s, Yale added three buildings to its
central campus as total enrollment grew by more than 950 by the
fall of 1993, to 10,975, a number it has hovered around since.
</P>
<P>
   Then Richard Levin became Yale's president. As a New Haven
resident for 23 years, he was well aware of the town-vs.-gown
hostility, but he stepped up the pace of property acquisition: Over
$20 million has been spent for at least 19 New Haven properties
since he took office in July 1993, according to city records and
Yale officials. And more acquisitions have been announced,
including a $5 million purchase of 10 properties on College and
Chapel streets.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents worry about the extent to which the university is
shaping the city. ``There is a concern that Yale is a little like a
conquering army, cleaning out the culture of what they conquer and
replacing it with their own,'' said Anstress Farwell, a founder of
a New Haven preservation group that is suing Yale to prevent it
from demolishing a 19th-century cottage.
</P>
<P>
   Yale officials like Bruce Alexander, the university's vice
president and director of New Haven and state affairs, disagree
with that characterization. Alexander, a former executive with
Rouse Corp., the developer of the South Street Seaport in New York,
said, ``This is not Yale's imprint on planning and development;
this is a partnership between Yale and the city.''
</P>
<P>
   While many New Haven residents have mixed feelings about Yale's
efforts _ they like seeing buildings spruced up but hate seeing
longtime businesses evicted _ some people are furious about the
university's plans to demolish the cottage at 85 Trumbull St. as
part of its plan to build a formal entrance to the campus.
</P>
<P>
   A group of preservationists called Friends of Hillhouse Avenue
is suing the university to save the building, known as Maple
Cottage, which is in a district listed on the National Register of
Historic Places.
</P>
<P>
   And an even wider circle of historians and preservationists
objected to a bill introduced in the state's General Assembly at
Yale's request that would have made it harder to sue educational
institutions over the destruction of historic buildings. The bill
died in committee in early April, and legislators say it is
unlikely to be reintroduced.
</P>
<P>
   Yale is also managing its retail properties more aggressively.
In a retail strip near campus that stretches from Mory's restaurant
on York Street around the corner to the new Barnes &AMP; Noble Yale
Bookstore on Broadway, Alexander would eventually like to carve
room for a student clothing store and a large restaurant, plans
that would shuffle existing tenants.
</P>
<P>
   Yale already owns most of the retail properties here, and many
of the tenants are mom-and-pop stores that say they depend on the
university for 80 percent of their customers. Alexander insists the
university wants a balance of chain stores and independents. But
its reputation among the family-owned businesses sank when the
university removed the 111-year-old Yale Co-op bookstore in favor
of Barnes &AMP; Noble in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Store owners acknowledge that Yale's involvement in the area has
been beneficial. The area was ``a dump'' before Yale got involved,
said George Koutroumanis, a co-owner of Yorkside Pizza and
Restaurant, which is in one of the few buildings on York Street
that the university does not own.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, Yale ``has to take into consideration not just
the students' needs, the needs of the school, but the people who
have been the stronghold of this area for years.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Tony Mongillo, who runs Y Haircutting on York Street, said Yale
wants his business to move upstairs from the Yale-owned
street-level space because the university sees it as a
``destination'' business, meaning customers would come no matter
where it is. But he disagrees. ``It's a walk-in business; we don't
have appointments,'' he said. ``We move upstairs, we're going to
lose the walk-in business.''
</P>
<P>
   Elliot Brause, the owner of the Quality Wine Shop, which has
been on Broadway since 1934, would also have to move a short
distance. Yale will cover the costs of new lighting, heating and
air conditioning, Brause said, but he estimates that the move will
cost him $25,000 to $30,000 for shelving, computer-system wiring,
custom lighting, and a new walk-in refrigerator. ``It's not
cheap,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Yale is also increasingly moving into residential neighborhoods.
In the Dixwell neighborhood north of campus, for example, Yale
hopes to acquire a two-acre plot on Lock Street, the site of an old
laundry-company building. To the west of the site lies the
university gym and a new residence hall; to the north are housing
projects. A Yale police substation is a possibility.
</P>
<P>
   Some in the neighborhood have embraced Yale's desire to buy the
land, preferring the university to an asbestos company that had
also considered the property. But others are wary.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like sleeping with an elephant,'' said Jerry Tureck, head
of a Dixwell community group. ``It can be the friendliest elephant
in the world, but every time it turns over you worry you might get
in the way.''
</P>
<P>
   Yale officials say they have made big strides in bettering
town-gown relations. Alexander, for instance, spends much of his
time at community events, speaking at neighborhood association
meetings and dining regularly with Mayor John DeStefano Jr.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor said one thing that has reduced tensions is a state
law that gives local governments partial reimbursements for the
revenue they lose on tax-exempt property owned by colleges and
hospitals. This year New Haven will receive $19.5 million for taxes
lost on land owned by Yale, a city spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   Levin, Yale's president, said better relations with the city are
crucial to Yale's success.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a tremendous historical suspicion of the university's
motives in the city,'' he said. ``In earlier years, Yale would try
to accomplish things without truly having laid the groundwork,
without having a strong relationship with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   But now, he said, ``our effectiveness depends on being taken
seriously as a partner by the community.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
