<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 22:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2724 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NATO-ANALYSIS-HNS &LR;      04-25 0847
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NATO-ANALYSIS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
EUROPEANS COUNT ON U.S. TO CARRY OUT KEY NATO ROLE
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
By CRAGG HINES &QL;
</P>
<P>
   c. 1999 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States leads in NATO because if there is
to be such a grand Euro-Atlantic alliance the United States must
lead it.
</P>
<P>
   Britain or France could lead, but no one would pay much
attention for long. Germany could lead, but everyone would pay too
much attention and quickly start talking about 1870, 1914 and 1939.
</P>
<P>
   For thin-skinned Europeans, the only thing worse than the United
States leading is the United States not leading.
</P>
<P>
   So, from the alliance's founding until its 50th anniversary
summit that concluded Sunday, U.S. leadership has been a
cornerstone of NATO and its success.
</P>
<P>
   NATO has brought Europe closer than ever to a wholly free,
democratic continent, what the State Department's John Holum called
``one of history's most elusive dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that strategic American role is to continue or how it
will be changed was a subtext to the summit proceedings, just as it
has been on both sides of the Atlantic since the end of the Cold
War.
</P>
<P>
   For most, it's not much of a debate.
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States is going to remain the key European power
for a long time to come,'' Dominique Moisi, deputy director of the
French Institute of Foreign Relations, said recently.
</P>
<P>
   That ``may not be good news'' for Americans, Moisi conceded,
because it will not be an inexpensive project _ most often the
point raised by U.S. politicians who take any exception to
Washington's dominating role in the defense alliance.
</P>
<P>
   The key U.S. position in the alliance is especially visible
during a conflict such as the Balkans _ ``the kind of war we cannot
wage without you,'' Moisi said.
</P>
<P>
   The United States is providing and delivering the vast majority
of the missiles and bombs against the forces of Yugoslav President
Slobodan Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   The centrality of the United States to the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization is why the Clinton administration's reticence on even
planning for a ground invasion of Yugoslavia was troubling to many
policy-makers, analysts and ordinary citizens. It was a strange
display of U.S. reluctance in the lead-up to the summit.
</P>
<P>
   It was such an unusual vacuum that British Prime Minister Tony
Blair rushed to fill it. He pressed until the leaders of other NATO
member nations at least consented to telling the allied military
planners to dust off some six-month old blueprints for ground
troops in Kosovo and to update them.
</P>
<P>
   Blair's move excited the neo-isolationist right in the United
States, with Republican presidential contender Pat Buchanan on
Sunday calling the British leader ``the mouse that roared.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is not going to be British troops hopping up that road to
Belgrade, but American kids, U.S. Marines, airborne divisions, and
that is not a vital interest of this country,'' Buchanan said on
NBC's Meet the Press.
</P>
<P>
   On the same program, Sen. Joseph Lieberman, D-Conn., argued the
importance _ for the United States, Europe and the world beyond _
of succeeding against Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Without a NATO victory, Lieberman said, ``there will be no fear.
Tyrants in Europe and Asia and the Middle East will run wild,
because there's no one on the block to speak for the values and the
security that we hold dear.''
</P>
<P>
   In that context, some analysts argue, the United States is
better off with a fight in Europe. For the United States, ``Europe
is still the best available and reliable partner,'' said Margarita
Mathiopoulos, a senior adviser at British Aerospace.
</P>
<P>
   But there are still questions about sharing the financial and
personnel burdens of such an alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Europeans have to do more than talk'' about their own security
arrangements, said retired Gen. George Joulwan, the former NATO
commander. For one thing, he said, they must begin to pay more of
the cost.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in NATO's history, costs were not as difficult for some
Americans to swallow as the mutual-security concept itself.
</P>
<P>
   In his toast at a White House dinner on Friday night for the
leader of NATO nations, Clinton pointed out that forming the
alliance was ``a radical departure'' for the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had been warned from the time of our first president,
George Washington, against entangling alliances with other
nations,'' Clinton recalled. ``But we learned the hard way, after
World War I, that the warning was no longer valid in the 20th
century.''
</P>
<P>
   And since World War II, the United States has been firmly
anchored in Europe.
</P>
<P>
   At some times, as Czech Ambassador Alexander Vondra pointed out
recently, a U.S.-led NATO serves to ``keep one European power from
taking over.'' And even that can lead to continental grumbling.
</P>
<P>
   But Prime Minister Blair, on Meet the Press, urged Americans not
to take the frequent criticism to heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you may read and hear about Europeans and what they
think and say about America, I tell you people are truly
grateful,'' Blair said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
