<SLUG> BC-TV-HOMEMOVIES-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TV REVIEW: MEET THE SMALL FAMILY, AFTER THE DIVORCE
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: Production notes are at end of review. Time, channel are
for New York area. Check local listings.) 
(nk) 
 By RON WERTHEIMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   It must take a great deal of effort to turn out an animated show
that looks and sounds like a clever rough draft. The producers of
``Home Movies,'' which starts its run Monday night on the UPN
network, are clearly proud of their techniques, which they also use
in their Comedy Central hit, ``Dr. Katz: Professional Therapist.''
They have aptly named their sketchy, jumpy visual style
Squigglevision. And if the dialogue seems hastily ad-libbed and out
of sync with the animation, that's on purpose, too. The dubbing
technique had been dubbed Retroscripting.
</P>
<P>
   The central character in ``Home Movies'' is an odd but bright
8-year-old who makes precocious videos with titles like ``The Dark
Side of the Law'' (followed by the sequel, ``The Dark Side of the
Law II''). The boy's name is Brendon Small, which is also the name
of the man who provides his voice. Brendon's newly single mother,
played by the comic Paula Poundstone, is called Paula. His best
friend, Melissa, has the voice of Melissa Bardin Galsky. And
Brendon's fool of a soccer coach, McGuirk (``rhymes with jerk''),
is H. Jon Benjamin, who also plays Ben on ``Dr. Katz.'' Benjamin
does double duty here, also playing Brendon's friend Snot-Nosed
Jason. Don't ask.
</P>
<P>
   The entire cast shares writing credit. That's Retroscripting for
you.
</P>
<P>
   In Monday night's episode, the only sample of the series
provided for review, McGuirk takes Paula on a date. Brendon is
understandably traumatized. Paula, who keeps her expectations as
low as possible, wears her sweat suit and red baseball cap to the
restaurant, where McGuirk says, ``I don't want to get into a whole
conversation about anything.'' (None of these characters,
apparently, ever changes clothes.)
</P>
<P>
   Paula turns down McGuirk's invitation for another date,
prompting him to declare to Brendon, ``Women are like men, but men
are not like women.'' If you're the least bit tempted to wonder if
that means something, this show is definitely not for you.
</P>
<P>
   The dry dialogue is mumbled in an odd singsong cadence
reminiscent of a Woody Allen film or an old Nichols and May
routine. But while this improv team may have the rhythm, that's not
enough to sustain interest between the sprigs of wit that pop up
organically during Retroscripting.
</P>
<P>
   Now if the producers could only invent Retrovision, you could
come back later and see this show when it's finished.
</P>
<P>
   PRODUCTION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `HOME MOVIES'
</P>
<P>
   UPN, Monday at 8:30 p.m. ET
</P>
<P>
   Created by Loren Bouchard and Brendon Small; Tom Snyder, Loren
Bouchard, Bonnie Burns and Mary Catherine Tucker, executive
producers. A production of Tom Snyder Productions in association
with Burns &AMP; Burns Productions. Premiere directed by Loren Bouchard
and written by Small, H. Jon Benjamin, Loren Bouchard, Paula
Poundstone and Melissa Bardin Galsky.
</P>
<P>
   WITH THE VOICES OF: Ms. Poundstone (Paula Small), Small (Brendon
Small), Benjamin (Coach McGuirk/Jason) and Ms. Galsky (Melissa).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
