<DATE_TIME> 1999-04-25 23:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2854 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BAFFERT-PROFILE-2TAKE     04-25 1013
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAFFERT-PROFILE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOKER IS WILD: BAFFERT BIDS FOR HIS THIRD KENTUCKY DERBY VICTORY
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ariz, Calif., Ore.)  (rk) 
 By JOE DRAPE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOUISVILLE, Ky. _ The camera crews hustled to get out of his way
and their subject was uncharacteristically oblivious to them. Bob
Baffert was working. He had a two-way radio in one hand, a
stopwatch in the other, and a chestnut gelding barreling around the
turn beneath those twin spires that make Churchill Downs horse
racing's signature postcard.
</P>
<P>
   He paced. He stood on tiptoes to get a better view. He cooed
instructions in the two-way to his horse, first through his
exercise rider's headset who relayed them to General Challenge
through her hands. When the likely Kentucky Derby favorite
blistered six furlongs in 1 minute 12 seconds, Baffert asked for
more. ``Let him gallop out strong,'' he barked. ``Keep going.''
</P>
<P>
   That worked for him and his horse.
</P>
<P>
   When General Challenge pounded out a mile in 1:38 3/5, Baffert
popped both arms in the air and shouted, ``Goooooaaaal!'' in the
exaggerated manner of soccer announcers.
</P>
<P>
   That worked for the cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Without dead-fit horses and telegenic exuberance, Baffert
wouldn't be in the position he is in now: with the chance to win an
unprecedented third consecutive Kentucky Derby.
</P>
<P>
   Strict preparation and high spirits have always coexisted within
Baffert. His acumen as a horseman has taken him from small-time
Arizona quarter-horse trainer to thoroughbred racing's most
successful conditioner. His manic charisma has brought
deep-pocketed owners to his stable and celebrity beyond his sport.
</P>
<P>
   He has won the last two national training titles, leads the
current earnings standing with more than $4.5 million and, in
General Challenge and Prime Timber, will saddle two top threats for
the Derby _ maybe four if he enters the fillies Excellent Meeting
and Silverbulletday, the only two horses among the Derby's current
candidates to have earned more than $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   ``People expect me to win this year; I'm not going to be able to
sneak up on anybody this time,'' Baffert said, sounding sorry about
it. ``But none of this happened overnight. I've been a student of
this game for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Baffert, 46, says he is different than the funny guy who, at his
first Derby in 1996, cut a startlingly fresh figure with his white
hair, shades like John Lennonuse to wear, pressed jeans and
starched shirts. He was here with a horse named Cavonnier, a single
groom and a pocketful of witty just-happy-to-be-here observations.
</P>
<P>
   When Cavonnier lost by a nose to Grindstone, it was nearly a
dream come true.
</P>
<P>
   The dream did come true in 1997 with a victory by Silver Charm,
a gray purchased for $85,000. And what was it like last year, when
Real Quiet, a $17,000 purchase, won for Baffert's friend, Mike
Pegram, who prodded and then bankrolled Baffert's switch from
quarter horses to thoroughbreds?
</P>
<P>
   ``Well,'' Baffert said, ``it was a rush, a sense of overwhelming
gratitude, and it made me want to keep coming back.''
</P>
<P>
   Team Baffert is not only back, but also has become a vivid
illustration of how big-time racing outfits are born in a sport in
which the stars are four-legged and the average trainer is a hybrid
of coach, general manager and ticket seller. The compact Baffert
outfit that accompanied Cavonnier has been replaced by 15 stable
hands, two assistant trainers and 32 horses _ double last year's
string _ all of whom will remain stabled at Churchill Downs.
</P>
<P>
   The modestly priced Silver Charm and Real Quiet have been
replaced by the $375,000 Prime Timber and the $175,000
Silverbulletday.
</P>
<P>
   Prime Timber is owned by the Oregon timber magnate Aaron Jones,
a longtime horse owner who had scaled back his involvement in the
late 1980s, when Baffert got his attention. Jones didn't know
Baffert, but he was impressed by his eye for talent. Silver Charm.
Real Quiet. Jones contacted him and told him to buy him a Kentucky
Derby horse.
</P>
<P>
   Silverbulletday is a Pegram splurge made affordable by his and
Baffert's successes.
</P>
<P>
   A fellow trainer, Eddie Plesa, said: ``The No. 1 thing we do is
recruit, recruit, recruit. We got to find the horses. We got to
find the owners to buy the horses. The bottom line is to win, then
you need national exposure.''
</P>
<P>
   Plesa, whose small Derby contingent with the filly Three Ring
brings back memories of Baffert's Cavonnier days, said: ``I was the
under bidder for Prime Timber. I saw Bob buy him and I knew why.
We're all working to afford those kind of horses.''
</P>
<P>
   While Baffert's shades and western wear remain in place and he
continues to entertain the growing news media throng outside his
barn, he operates now with a more sober perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe it or not, I don't make that much money,'' he said.
``I've got a huge overhead. I have 90 horses in training I'm
responsible for. I'm working on next year's Derby. I'm looking for
horses to buy for the Derbies down the road. The part I like best
is actually training the horse, and that's just a small part of my
day.''
</P>
<P>
   Long before two-way radios and television cameras were a staple
of Baffert's workouts, he had a knack for making horses run.
</P>
<P>
   It was hard-learned. He grew up on a farm in Nogales, Ariz., and
learned to train horses from his father. He rode briefly as a
quarter-horse jockey and then, in 1976, showed up at California's
Los Alamitos race track with four horses and a goat that he says
was ``worth more than all of them.''
</P>
<P>
   He became a proficient trainer, but couldn't break through with
a victory in the lucrative Futurity races. In the late 1970s, after
his father took a horse away from him to train himself, he quit. He
worked as a substitute teacher for $20 a day. When he was assigned
a junior-high history class for the remainder of the year, he was
the one that got the best education.
</P>
<P>
   ``I stayed up the night before and read the history book before
each class,'' he said. ``It taught me there was plenty I could
still learn.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He returned to quarter horse racing and by 1990 was a two-time
winner of one of the sport's showcase races, Champion of Champions,
at Los Alamitos, and saddled 90 winners that year.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, Pegram, who owns McDonald's franchises in the
Northwest, had chipped in $1 million and told Baffert to train
thoroughbreds. He scratched out just 9 victories in 69 starts.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, though, he won the Breeders' Cup sprint with Thirty
Slews. It was around then that Bob Lewis introduced himself to
Baffert at the so-called Clocker's Corner on the Santa Anita back
stretch. Lewis had overheard the animated Baffert commiserating
about his luck in a fashion that had a cluster of horsemen
rollicking, but immediately discovered the qualities that have
Baffert on the verge of making Derby history.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was looking for compatibility, chemistry, and here was this
guy willing to have some fun,'' said Lewis, who with his wife,
Beverly, owns Silver Charm and 22 other horses in Baffert's stable.
``But he had this humility. One of the first things he told me was:
`I do pretty good with sprints. I don't know nothing about going
long and I need to take some lessons.'''
</P>
<P>
   He took them by watching a trainer in the barn across from him:
the legendary Charlie Whittingham, who died last week at 86. As
Whittingham did, Baffert works his horses hard and fast. He decides
what is best for them by feel, not program. The two-way radio
allows him to dictate workouts as he sees them. Baffert is the rare
trainer who can successfully guide horses through the grueling
Triple Crown series and on to successful careers as older horses,
as he has done with Silver Charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want my horses dead fit,'' Baffert said. ``I don't believe
in racing them into shape. If they aren't ready they don't go.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the cameras, Baffert concedes he feels the pressure
and is braced for a backlash _ hinted at by some recently
publicized piques. One was an argument with the agent for jockey
Chris McCarron after he named Gary Stevens to ride General
Challenge in the Santa Anita Derby. The McCarron camp thought they
had the ride; Baffert thought he made it clear that Stevens, his
No. 1 rider, would be up if available.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert apologized, but the incident, along with some words
exchanged with writers over their coverage of the recent losing
efforts of Silver Charm and Real Quiet, have injected a little
heartbreak in what had been a long-running romance.
</P>
<P>
   Baffert still insists that he wants his Derby week to be the
mini-vacation it has been the past three years _ a time to
celebrate accomplishing his stable's real goal no matter how large
the operation has grown.
</P>
<P>
   Just getting here. Horse racing's ultimate joker knows too well
his sport can't be all fun and games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still have humbling times,'' he said. ``Nobody is bigger
than this game. It can kill you at any time. Charlie's best quote
of all time was `Horses are like strawberries _ they can go bad on
you at anytime.'''  &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
