<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKNOT-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KARIYA LEADING BUT NOT ON SCOREBOARD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 c.1999 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Paul Kariya was held scoreless in Sunday's
Game 3 loss to Detroit, but don't try to convince Anaheim Mighty
Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg that Kariya wasn't effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``One thing I've learned in the playoffs is how competitive and
how much of a leader Paul Kariya is. That's why he's our captain,''
Hartsburg said. ``He has been unbelievable. If anybody needs to
look somewhere (for inspiration), Paul is where they should start
looking.''
</P>
<P>
   Kariya, who has a goal and four points in the series, was
credited with three shots, not including the one that rang off the
left post in the second period. But it was his physical play that
really stood out. He had three hits, including one that nearly
knocked Chris Chelios' helmet off in the first period. He also put
a big hit on veteran Larry Murphy in the opening period.
</P>
<P>
   __ Them's the breaks:Detroit certainly got its share of good
breaks on Sunday. Tomas Holmstrom's deflection was ruled a goal on
a play that even Detroit coach Scotty Bowman admitted ``had to be
close, since they (the video goal judge and referee) took so much
time.'' The Wings also watched Kariya's bid to tie the game bounce
off the post in the second.
</P>
<P>
   But Teemu Selanne said Detroit is far from lucky.
</P>
<P>
   ``They got breaks, but they earned them more,'' said Selanne.
``Good teams seem to get those breaks.
</P>
<P>
   __ More bad breaks:Kris Draper of the Red Wings had his jaw
broken by Claude Lemieux in the 1996 Western Conference finals, but
the gritty winger still knows how to use his jaws.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of hard to talk with a stick in the mouth,'' said
Draper, who was cross checked by Stu Grimson in the second period.
``But we were able to put the puck in the net (on the ensuing power
play).
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not going to shut me up. . . . I'm going to keep
talking.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Worth every million:Bowman got more than his money's worth
from defensemen Nicklas Lidstrom and Chelios. They were matched
against Kariya and Teemu Selanne almost the whole game, limiting
the Ducks duo to one point (a power play assist by Selanne).
</P>
<P>
   Bowman thought the Red Wings were aided by the long television
timeouts; as a result, Lidstrom played 34:37 and Chelios 33:52. The
Detroit coach also said Chelios is benefiting from playing
alongside the underrated Lidstrom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chris hasn't had a partner like this since (Gary) Suter left
Chicago,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   __ Defenders down: The Ducks were down to five defensemen most
of the game. Ruslan Salei suffered a right shoulder injury in the
first period and played less than six minutes. Hartsburg refused to
elaborate on the injury, but did say that Salei ``is questionable
for Tuesday's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Salei's injury put most of the load on Fredrik Olausson, Kevin
Haller, Jason Marshall, Pavel Trnka and Kevin Haller.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall and Haller have been steady all series long, but the
Ducks needed better play from youngsters Pushor and Trnka, and
Sunday they got that.
</P>
<P>
   Trnka was especially impressive; he played nearly 23 minutes and
was credited with six hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought he played very well,'' said Hartsburg.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
