<HEADER>
A2863 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1ST     04-25 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ARATON-COLUMN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL COLUMN: BEHIND MEMORY'S VEIL, STILL LARGER THAN LIFE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (SUBS to delete the term ``a man's man'' from last sentence of 8th
graf, beginning ``He was blessed ...'')  (lb) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Through smooth, singular voices Joe DiMaggio was most
artfully remembered on Sunday. Bob Sheppard recited the last
lineup. Paul Simon sang a fond farewell. The grainy black-and-white
video-screen images paled in competition with recollections of the
way things were, or we wished them to be.
</P>
<P>
   They didn't have blooper videos when DiMaggio played, or 24-hour
cable sports news. They didn't have cameras trained on the dugout
to record for posterity every eruption of ire. The images are
spare, the memories select. Yogi Berra said he couldn't recall the
Yankee Clipper having ever made a mistake. Jerry Coleman thought of
one that DiMaggio had made, quickly realized and corrected, in two
simple steps.
</P>
<P>
   ``He caught a fly ball and thought there were three outs,''
Coleman said Sunday before DiMaggio's monument was unveiled, and
the Yankees' center fielder, Bernie Williams, took his mystical cue
and drove in the winning run in a 4-3 victory over Toronto at
Yankee Stadium. ``He took two steps with his head down and then
reacted immediately.''
</P>
<P>
   For the record, Coleman said, DiMaggio threw to the right base,
a perfect strike.
</P>
<P>
   Joe DiMaggio was the last of his kind, a gifted American
original who was mostly filtered through radio, immortalized in
print, perfected by memory. Long into retirement, right to his
death, he worked obsessively at insulating himself from the
double-edged sword that often accompanies contemporary fame.
</P>
<P>
   The closer the camera, the bigger the blemish. When DiMaggio
played, there were a dozen newspapers in New York City, but there
were also private places where the public eye could not go. Hank
Bauer stood in the clubhouse Sunday and pointed to where DiMaggio
had once sat, in the vicinity where Tino Martinez now sits. He
recalled how DiMaggio used to spit between closed teeth on the post
that is no longer there.
</P>
<P>
   It is one thing to say it, another thing to show it. Beyond his
indisputable grace and greatness on God's green grass, DiMaggio
might not have argued with a modern marketing slogan, Image Is
Everything. People who knew him always said that what DiMaggio
feared most was looking bad. He was no child of the television age,
but he married the most famous actress of his time. He learned from
her that the stars of most moving pictures play to mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   So, what the heck. Most of the men who played with DiMaggio
didn't understand him or were completely in awe of him. They are
not about to start an argument with Americana. Nobody could seem to
recall on Sunday one time that DiMaggio got picked off first, or
broke in on the ball when he should have broke back. He was blessed
by New York's cardinal and sainted by several former teammates as
gracious and selfless, the ultimate teammate, even though the
whispers have always suggested something else.
</P>
<P>
   Simon slipped into a Yankees cap, lugged his acoustic guitar out
to shallow center field and sang his famous verse about lost
innocence, soundtrack for cinematic drama. For only those touching
moments when the voices of Simon and Sheppard turned a grand old
ball park into a Bronx time machine was it possible to forget that
innocence was lost last week not in song but within the supposed
sanctity of a school.
</P>
<P>
   Those Stadium flags were not flying half-staff Sunday for Joe D.
These are harsher, less private times, when power is visual and
images are unforgiving. It is fair to wonder: If DiMaggio played
under today's ``Truman Show'' conditions, would he have come across
more as Michael Jordan or as Albert Belle?
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, who has been calling games on the tube since he laid
down his glove, said he believed that DiMaggio, cranky as he was
with the concept of up-close, would have survived quite well under
the microscope.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you can transfer people decade to decade,'' he said.
``The great stars could handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Coleman, a Yankees second baseman for DiMaggio's last three
years, joined the team in 1949, a season in which an injured heel
limited DiMaggio to 76 games. There was a weekend in Boston,
though, when DiMaggio dusted off the cobwebs and hit four home runs
that empowered a Yankee sweep.
</P>
<P>
   ``And that was the difference that year,'' Coleman said, his
point being that the great ones rise to the moment and transcend
their time, and that is why they could operate in any time.
</P>
<P>
   ``Today you have Jordan, Gretzky in hockey, and now you have a
quarterback going out,'' Coleman said. ``These people are giants.''
</P>
<P>
   When the venerable Sheppard enunciated the lineups from Game 6
of the 1951 World Series against the New York Giants, all it took
was closing one's eyes to feel as if 48 years had been erased. When
he announced DiMaggio, No. 5, batting fourth, playing center field,
who would have wanted to remember that DiMaggio had even made an
out in his life, much less a mistake?
</P>
<P>
   Jordan went out to global tributes a few months ago. Wayne
Gretzky made Canada cry and the rest of the hockey world sigh when
he quit last week. John Elway will get the forever treatment this
week when he announces he's through. We make the best players
bigger than the game, but Joe DiMaggio, with some stretching of the
truth, has for decades been made to be larger than life.
</P>
<P>
   Now he's left and gone away and, in all likelihood, taken the
concept with him.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
