<SLUG> BC-OBIT-COLE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIAN COLE, 74, RENOWNED MATHEMATICIAN WHO SPECIALIZED IN
PERTURBATION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif)  (rk) 
 By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Julian David Cole, a professor at Rensselaer Polytechnic
Institute in Troy, N.Y., and an internationally acknowledged expert
on the applied-mathematics technique known as perturbation, died
April 17 at Albany Medical Center Hospital. He was 74 and lived in
Loudonville, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was multiple myeloma, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   Perturbation is a powerful and widely used tool of applied
mathematics that has practical applications in heat flow,
elasticity, wave propagation and problems with solidification in
materials processing. Cole was an originator of singular
perturbation techniques, which involve solving problems dealing
with two or more scales of measurement. He also wrote
``Perturbation Methods in Applied Mathematics,'' a classic textbook
first published in 1968 and translated into many languages.
</P>
<P>
   The National Academy of Science recognized his accomplishments
with its Award in Applied Mathematics and Numerical Analysis in
1995. It cited his ``fundamental contributions'' in those
categories, adding, ``His work is characterized by its deep
physical and mathematical insights.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole's research encompassed basic theories of aerodynamics and
fluid mechanics, particularly in transonic flow, which is
fundamentally important in airplane and turbine design.
</P>
<P>
   Julian Cole was born in Brooklyn and graduated with a degree in
mechanical engineering from Cornell University in 1944. He earned a
Ph.D. in aeronautics and mathematics in 1949 at the California
Institute of Technology, where he was on the faculty until 1969,
rising to professor.
</P>
<P>
   Before he joined Rensselaer Polytechnic in 1982, he was chairman
of the department of applied science and engineering and a
professor of mathematics at the University of California at Los
Angeles. At Rensselaer, he was the Margaret Darrin distinguished
professor of applied mathematics.
</P>
<P>
   Survivors include his wife, Susan Cole, a professor of
mathematics at Rensselaer; four sons, David, Benjamin, Thomas and
Brenden; three daughters, Jennifer, Melody and Amy Rose, and a
brother, Gerald Cole.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
