Pramoedya Ananta Toer, 74, Indonesia's greatest modern writer. For
three decades Pramoedya felt the full force of President Suharto's
military state. His story of suffering and survival on the prison
island of Buru are the theme of a memoir, ``The Mute's Soliloquy,''
to be published in the U.S. by Hyperion East. ``You can't just seem
strong; it takes more than strength to survive,'' said Pramoedya
through an interpreter. ``It took resistance, mental resistance as
well as spiritual. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times Photo)
