<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving 04/25/99. Photo clients will
automatically receive these photos via AP's PhotoExpress or may
download them from either the Wieck Photo Database in Dallas at
972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at 305-448-8411.
Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling (888) 603-1036
or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) LOS ANGELES -- April 25, 1999 -- INTERNET-SPEEDUP, 4-25
-- Leo S. Spiegel was recruited to head Sandpiper Networks, a Web
services provider. Sandpiper and a rival start-up company, Akamai
Technologies Inc., are pioneering a way to distribute material over
the Internet that avoids much of the congestion that can turn the
World Wide Web into the World Wide Wait. (Ed Carreon/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) CARMEL VALLEY, Calif. -- April 25, 1999 --
SMILEY-COLUMN, 4-25 -- Jane Smiley, the author of ``A Thousand
Acres'' and ``Moo,'' with her dog, Sterling, at her home in Carmel
Valley. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) NEW YORK -- April 25, 1999 -- INDONESIAN-WRITER, 4-25 --
Pramoedya Ananta Toer, 74, Indonesia's greatest modern writer. For
three decades Pramoedya felt the full force of President Suharto's
military state. His story of suffering and survival on the prison
island of Buru are the theme of a memoir, ``The Mute's Soliloquy,''
to be published in the U.S. by Hyperion East. ``You can't just seem
strong; it takes more than strength to survive,'' said Pramoedya
through an interpreter. ``It took resistance, mental resistance as
well as spiritual. (Fred R. Conrad/The New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) WASHINGTON -- April 25, 1999 -- NATO-RDP-2, 4-25 --
President Clinton, followed by Defense Secretary William S. Cohen,
left, Secretary of State Madeleine K. Albright and Samuel R.
Berger, national security adviser, in rear, closed the NATO
celebration on Sunday with a news briefing. The three-day NATO
summit, originally called to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the
alliance was largely overshadowed by the crisis in Kosovo. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) WASHINGTON -- April 25, 1999 -- NATO-RDP-1, 4-25 -- The
NATO leaders ended their summit meeting on Sunday with expressions
of solidarity in prevailing over President Slobodan Milosevic of
Yugoslavia and a group portrait. The three-day NATO summit,
originally called to celebrate the 50th anniversary of the alliance
was largely overshadowed by the crisis in Kosovo. (Stephen
Crowley/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 25, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-RDP-1,
4-25 --Christine Reich, 17, a Columbine High School student, and
Erik Pedersen, an alumnus, watch balloons rise at a memorial
service on Sunday for the victims of the shootings at Columbine
High School in Littleton. About 70,000 people, including national
figures, attended the service. (Kevin Moloney/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 25, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-RDP-2,
4-25 --Parents and students grieve during a memorial service on
Sunday for the victims of the shootings at Columbine High School in
Littleton. As clouds and a cold rain shrouded the nearby Rocky
Mountains, the outdoor memorial service drew 70,000 -- nearly
double the population of the suburban neighborhood served by the
high school. (Andrea Mohin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) LITTLETON, Colo. -- April 25, 1999 -- COLO-SCHOOL-RDP-3,
4-25 --A sign outside the Klebold home in Littleton, left,
expressed support on Sunday for Susan and Thomas Klebold, whose
son, Dylan, killed himself after he and Eric Harris, who also
committed suicide, killed 13 people at Columbine High School. A
similar show of support, at right, along with some flowers was
posted in front of the Harris' home in Littleton. (Andrea Mohin/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) LANGHORNE, Pa. -- April 25, 1999 -- POKEMON-CRAZE-2,
4-25 -- Marie Summa, 12, of Beverly, N.J., went to the Pokemon
Trading Card Game Tour at the Oxford Valley Mall in Langhorne,
wearing a hat with horns and a T-shirt covered with her favorite
Pokemon characters. Pokemon which is actually a video game, has
grown into an international industry that includes comic books,
virtual pets, trading cards, T-shirts, and a television cartoon
show, with sales so far of nearly $5 billion. ``Marie has been
wearing that hat for three days,'' said her father, Thomas. (Jeff
Zelevansky/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) LANGHORNE, Pa. -- April 25, 1999 -- POKEMON-CRAZE-1, 4-25
-- Trading cards are among the Pokemon merchandise spinoffs that
were traded at the Pokemon Trading Card Game Tour at the Oxford
Valley Mall in Langhorne. More than a billion of the cards have
been sold in Japan, and they are catching on rapidly in the United
States. Pokemon which is actually a video game, started in
Nintendo's home market three years ago and has grown into an
international industry that includes comic books, virtual pets and
even a television cartoon show. (Jeff Zelevansky/New York Times
Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) TETOVO, Macedonia -- April 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-INTELLECT,
4-25 -- Baton Haxhiu, in rear, the editor of the Albanian language
newspaper Koha Dittore, which has just restarted publication in
Macedonia after being forced into exile from Pristina in Kosovo.
The staff intends to end Koha Ditore's monthlong silence on Monday,
distributing free copies in refugee camps. Someday, Haxhiu says,
the Serbs will awaken from their moral slumber, but ``we Albanians
will never forget what has happened to us, and it will be very hard
to forgive.'' (Alan Chin/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) KUKES, Albania -- April 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-IMPACT, 4-25
-- Refugees from Kosovo took a moment of quiet by a lake on Sunday
in Kukes. The United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees
estimates that there are about 363,100 in Albania, 135,200 in
Macedonia, 65,700 in Montenegro, and 32,500 in Bosnia and
Herzegovina. More than 15,000 have been evacuated from Macedonia to
13 countries, the agency said, including nearly 10,000 to Germany.
(Edward Keating/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) SPRINGFIELD, Va. -- April 25, 1999 -- , 4-25 --
GUN-GROUP-PRATT, 4-25 -- Larry Pratt, the executive director of the
Gun Owners of America, an advocacy group situated in Springfield,
Va. Pratt believes there should be absolutely no regulations
governing the sale or purchase of handguns and automatic weapons.
In this more perfect world, Pratt says, many of the deaths in
Colorado might have been prevented. ``We're saddened that there
were not teachers and principals who had access to a gun, who might
have been able to stop the mayhem,'' says Pratt. (Scott
Robinson/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) ENNIS, Mont. -- April 25, 1999 -- WILDERNESS-ACCESS, 4-25
-- Bruce Combs and his family nearly lost access to government land
from their Montana dude ranch. A new neighbor had threatened to
block the family's access to the land, resulting in a lawsuit. It
is the sort of dispute that has become increasingly common in the
West as wealthy people from out of state buy land that includes
roads and trails long used by the natives. The Combses have been
entertaining guests in and around their dude ranch in Jack Creek
Canyon since 1959. (Jim Robbins/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) TIRANA, Albania -- April 25, 1999 --
SUB-KOSOVO-MILITARY-2, 4-24 -- The NATO supreme military commander,
Gen. Wesley Clark, in soft cap, arriving at the Tirana airport on
Sunday to meet with American troops supporting the Albanian base to
be used by Apache gunships against Serbian forces. Clark says that
the allied campaign against the Serbs is ``right on schedule'' as
seven more Apache attack helicopters arrived Sunday to step up the
attacks. (James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) SACRAMENTO, Calif. -- April 25, 1999 --
CALIF-DEATHROW-VET, 4-25 -- Donna Kendricks watching a videotape of
her brother Manny Babbitt, a condemned killer seeking clemency. The
list of those rallying to save Babbit's life is growing and
includes at least two of the jurors who sentenced him to death and
a retired police officer whom Babbitt saved as a Marine in Vietnam.
Babbitt who has been on death row for 18 years, is convicted of
killing a 78-year-old woman in Sacramento the night of Dec. 18,
1980. (Monica Almeida/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) TIRANA, Albania -- April 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MILITARY-2,
4-24 -- The NATO supreme military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
arriving in Tirana, Albania on Sunday to meet with about 3,300
American troops stationed there. Clark says that the allied
campaign against the Serbs is ``right on schedule'' as seven more
Apache attack helicopters arrived Sunday to step up the attacks.
(James Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) TIRANA, Albania -- April 25, 1999 -- KOSOVO-MILITARY-1,
4-24 -- Apache attack helicopters arriving in Albania on Sunday.
While denying plans for ground troops, NATO intends to strike more
closely at Serb units on the ground with the low-flying Apaches,
now deployed in Albania and being prepared for use. The NATO
supreme military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark, says that the allied
campaign against the Serbs is ``right on schedule.'' (James
Hill/New York Times Photo)
</P>
